{"title_page": "Gurdwara Gobind Ghat", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Copy edit|date=April 2020}}\n{{More footnotes|date=April 2020}}\n{{More citations needed|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox religious building\n| name                  = Gurudwara Gobind Ghat\n| image                 =  \n| alt                   = \n| caption               = \n| map_type              = India Bihar#India\n| map_caption           = Location in [[Bihar]]##Location in [[India]]\n| religious_affiliation = [[Sikhism]]\n| coordinates           = {{coord|25|36|28.77|N|85|10|3.06|E|region:IN}}\n| other_names           = \n| devanagari            = \n| sanskrit_translit     = \n| tamil                 = \n| marathi               = \n| bengali               = \n| country               = [[India]]\n| state                 = [[Bihar]]\n| district              = \n| location              = [[Patna]]\n| elevation_m           = \n| deity                 = [[Guru]]\n| important_festivals   = \n| architecture          = [[Gurdwara]]\n| number_of_temples     = \n| number_of_monuments   = \n| inscriptions          = \n| date_built            = \n| creator               = unknown\n| website               = unknown\n}}'''Gurdwara Sri Guru Gobind Singh Ghat''', also known as Gurudwara Kangan Ghat<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sikhiwiki.org/index.php/Gurdwara_Kangan_Ghat|title=Gurdwara Kangan Ghat - SikhiWiki, free Sikh encyclopedia.|website=www.sikhiwiki.org|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>, is a [[Gurdwara|Sikh place of worship]] located on the bank of the river [[Ganges]] about {{convert|650|meter|yards|abbr=on}} away from [[Takht Sri Patna Sahib]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://takhatpatnasahib.in/|title=Takhat Sri Harimandir Ji Patna Sahib|website=takhatpatnasahib.in|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>. It is the place where [[Guru Gobind Singh]] threw his gold bangle ([[bangle|kangan]]) and passed on the knowledge of [[Sri Guru Granth Sahib Ji]] to [[Pandit]] Shiv Dutt, a devotee of Sri Ram Chandra.<ref>{{Cite\nweb|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151212051909/http://archimedespress.co.uk/books|title=Archimedespress {{!}} Books|date=2015-12-12|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> People believe that [[Sri Guru Granth Sahib Ji]] has taught them the preaching of the nine [[Sikh gurus]], giving them psychological peace.\n\nThe [[ghat]] is located near [[Patna Sahib Station]] in the state of Bihar. It is a sacred landmark marked by a gateway with the [[Gurudwara]] on top of it. Guru Gobind Singh Ji immortalized certain places in Patna Saheb. Subsequently, Patna Saheb became known as Gurudwaras, a point less than 200 yards from Harimandir Saheb. Gurdwara Sri Guru Gobind Singh Ghat is where the child Gobind used to play with his playmates on the bank of the Ganges. A ghat is a place on the riverbank, usually paved, used for bathing, drawing water, or landing and harboring boats. The river has, however, receded since away to the north.\n\n=== See also ===\n\n*[[Akal Takht]]\n*[[Takht Sri Keshgarh Sahib]]\n*[[Takht Sri Damdama Sahib]]\n*[[Hazur Sahib Nanded]]\n*[[Sri Guru Granth Sahib Ji]]\n\n==Notes==\n* Gurudwara Gobind Ghat is also known as Gurudwara Kangan Ghat.\n* It is located on the banks of the river Ganga.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Sikhism}}\n\n[[Category:Religious buildings and structures in Patna]]\n[[Category:Ghats of India]]\n[[Category:Memorials to Guru Gobind Singh]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Copy edit|date=April 2020}}\n{{More footnotes|date=April 2020}}\n{{More citations needed|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox religious building\n| name                  = Gurudwara Gobind Ghat\n| image                 =  \n| alt                   = \n| caption               = \n| map_type              = India Bihar#India\n| map_caption           = Location in [[Bihar]]##Location in [[India]]\n| religious_affiliation = [[Sikhism]]\n| coordinates           = {{coord|25|36|28.77|N|85|10|3.06|E|region:IN}}\n| other_names           = \n| devanagari            = \n| sanskrit_translit     = \n| tamil                 = \n| marathi               = \n| bengali               = \n| country               = [[India]]\n| state                 = [[Bihar]]\n| district              = \n| location              = [[Patna]]\n| elevation_m           = \n| deity                 = [[Guru]]\n| important_festivals   = \n| architecture          = [[Gurdwara]]\n| number_of_temples     = \n| number_of_monuments   = \n| inscriptions          = \n| date_built            = \n| creator               = unknown\n| website               = unknown\n}}'''Gurdwara Sri Guru Gobind Singh Ghat''', also known as Gurudwara Kangan Ghat<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sikhiwiki.org/index.php/Gurdwara_Kangan_Ghat|title=Gurdwara Kangan Ghat - SikhiWiki, free Sikh encyclopedia.|website=www.sikhiwiki.org|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>, is a [[Gurdwara|Sikh place of worship]] located on the bank of the river [[Ganges]] about {{convert|650|meter|yards|abbr=on}} away from [[Takht Sri Patna Sahib]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://takhatpatnasahib.in/|title=Takhat Sri Harimandir Ji Patna Sahib|website=takhatpatnasahib.in|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>. It is the place where [[Guru Gobind Singh]] threw his gold bangle ([[bangle|kangan]]) and passed on the knowledge of [[Sri Guru Granth Sahib Ji]] to [[Pandit]] Shiv Dutt, a devotee of Sri Ram Chandra.<ref>{{Cite\nweb|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151212051909/http://archimedespress.co.uk/books|title=Archimedespress {{!}} Books|date=2015-12-12|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> Many believe that the [[Sri Guru Granth Sahib Ji]] have taught him the preaching of the nine [[Sikh gurus]], giving him psychological peace.\n\nThe [[ghat]] is located near [[Patna Sahib Station]] in the state of Bihar. It is a sacred landmark marked by a gateway with the [[Gurudwara]] on top of it. Guru Gobind Singh Ji immortalized certain places in Patna Saheb. Subsequently, Patna Saheb became known as Gurudwaras, a point less than 200 yards from Harimandir Saheb. Gurdwara Sri Guru Gobind Singh Ghat is where the child Gobind used to play with his playmates on the bank of the Ganges. A ghat is a place on the riverbank, usually paved, used for bathing, drawing water, or landing and harboring boats. The river has, however, receded since away to the north.\n\n=== See also ===\n\n*[[Akal Takht]]\n*[[Takht Sri Keshgarh Sahib]]\n*[[Takht Sri Damdama Sahib]]\n*[[Hazur Sahib Nanded]]\n*[[Sri Guru Granth Sahib Ji]]\n\n==Notes==\n* Gurudwara Gobind Ghat is also known as Gurudwara Kangan Ghat.\n* It is located on the banks of the river Ganga.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Sikhism}}\n\n[[Category:Religious buildings and structures in Patna]]\n[[Category:Ghats of India]]\n[[Category:Memorials to Guru Gobind Singh]]\n", "name_user": "Dyakobovitch", "label": "safe", "comment": "Updated grammar to third party", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gurdwara_Gobind_Ghat"}
{"title_page": "Gordon Michael Woolvett", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n | name             = Gordon Michael Woolvett\n | birth_date       = {{Birth year and age|1970}}\n | birth_place      = [[Hamilton, Ontario]], Canada\n | other_names      = Gordon M. Woolvett <br> Gordon Woolvett\n | occupation       = Actor\n | years_active     = 1984\u2013present\n | spouse           = {{marriage|Michele Morand|January 15, 2000}}\n | relatives        = [[Jaimz Woolvett]] (brother)\n | children         = 3\n | website          = {{URL|https://www.gordonwoolvett.com}}\n | geminiawards     = \n}}\n\n'''Gordon Michael Woolvett''' (born 1970) is a Canadian actor from [[Hamilton, Ontario]].\n\n==Career==\nWoolvett's most enduring role was as [[Seamus Zelazny Harper]] on the television series ''[[Andromeda (TV series)|Andromeda]]'' (2000\u20132005). Prior to ''Andromeda'' he starred in another science fiction television series, ''[[Deepwater Black]]''. He was also credited as playing Mitch in the \"Pariah\" episode of the short-lived 1980s science-fiction/action series ''[[Captain Power and the Soldiers of the Future]]''. He also was in two episodes of ''[[Psi Factor|Psi Factor: Chronicles of the Paranormal]]''.<ref name=edotc>{{cite encyclopedia |url=https://www.encyclopedia.com/education/news-wires-white-papers-and-books/woolvett-gordon-michael-1970-gordon-woolvett-gordon-m-woolvett |title=Woolvett, Gordon Michael 1970- (Gordon Woolvett, Gordon M. Woolvett) |website=encyclopedia.com |access-date=23 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\nWoolvett was also one of the first program jockeys for [[YTV (Canadian television)|YTV]]'s ''[[The Zone (YTV)|The Zone]]'' (then called ''The After-School Zone'')<ref>{{cite news |url=https://torontoist.com/2015/12/the-oral-history-of-1990s-ytv/ |title=The Oral History of 1990s YTV |date=22 December 2015 |department=Culture |first=Will |last=Sloan |website=[[Torontoist]] |access-date=25 April 2020 }}</ref> and the original main host for a program called ''[[Video & Arcade Top 10]]'' which also aired on YTV.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.vice.com/en_ca/article/xdmpjk/why-people-on-twitter-are-still-asking-this-90s-ytv-host-for-video-game-help |title=Why People on Twitter Are Still Asking This 90s YTV Host for Video Game Help |magazine=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]] |date=15 October 2016 |first=Gregory |last=Adams |access-date=25 April 2020 }}</ref> He acted in the 1999 [[television film|made-for-TV film]] ''[[Ultimate Deception]]'' with [[Yasmine Bleeth]].<ref name=\"edotc\" /> More recently, Woolvett could be seen on the Canadian television series ''[[The Guard (Canadian TV series)|The Guard]]'', which aired from 2008 to 2009 on [[Global Television Network]].<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.halifaxfilm.com/files/images/The_Guard_II_Final_Press_Kit.pdf |title=The Guard II |website=Halifax Film |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724160743/http://www.halifaxfilm.com/files/images/The_Guard_II_Final_Press_Kit.pdf |archive-date=July 24, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1992, Woolvett was nominated for the [[Gemini Awards|Gemini Award]] for Best Performance by a Supporting Actor for his role in ''[[Princes in Exile]]'' (1990).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://film.athabascau.ca/commentary/princes-exile-commentary |title=Princes in Exile Commentary |website=Canadian Film Online |publisher=[[Athabasca University]] |first=Evelyn |last=Ellerman |access-date=25 April 2020 }}</ref> He directed the documentary ''Around the World in 80 Anthems'', which won Best Documentary at the seventh International Film Festival Manhattan in 2017.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Manuel |first1=Felix |title=Phl wins at Int'l Film Festival Manhattan (IFFM) |url=https://www.philstar.com/entertainment/2017/10/22/1751440/phl-wins-intl-film-festival-manhattan-iffm |website=philstar.com |accessdate=20 December 2018 |date=22 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nWoolvett was born in 1970 in Hamilton, Ontario, Canada. He married Michele Morand on January 15, 2000. His brother is actor [[Jaimz Woolvett]].<ref name=\"edotc\" />\n\n== Filmography ==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|1985\n|''[[Joshua Then and Now (film)|Joshua Now and Then]]''\n|Teddy Shapiro\n|\n|-\n|1990\n|''[[Princes in Exile (film)|Princes in Exile]]''\n|Louis\n|\n|-\n|1992\n|''[[Bordertown Caf\u00e9]]''\n|Jimmy\n|\n|-\n|1995\n|''[[Rude (film)|Rude]]''\n|Ricky\n|\n|-\n|1996\n|''{{sortname|The|Legend of Gator Face}}''\n|Chip\n|\n|-\n|1998\n|''[[Shadow Builder]]''\n|Larry Eggers\n|\n|-\n|1998\n|''Clutch''\n|Spit\n|\n|-\n|1998\n|''[[Bride of Chucky]]''\n|David Collins\n|<ref>{{cite web |last1=Donato |first1=Matt |title=Bride of Chucky 20 years later: Don Mancini looks back at one of horror's boldest sequels |url=https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/bride-of-chucky-20th-anniversary-don-mancini-childs-play |website=SYFY WIRE |accessdate=20 December 2018 |language=en |date=30 October 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|2000\n|''{{sortname|The|Highwayman|nolink=1}}''\n|Walter\n|\n|-\n|2006\n|''[[Everything's Gone Green (film)|Everything's Gone Green]]''\n|Spike\n|\n|-\n|2014\n|''Down Here''\n|Coach Randall\n|\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|1984\n|''{{sortname|The|Edison Twins}}''\n|Dave\n|\"Diamonds\"\n|-\n|1986\n|''[[Act of Vengeance]]''\n|Bobby\n|TV film\n|-\n|1986\n|''[[9B (TV series)|9B]]''\n|Kevin\n|TV film\n|-\n|1987\n|''Air Waves''\n|Greg\n|\"Happy 16th\", \"A Second Look\"\n|-\n|1987\n|''[[Captain Power and the Soldiers of the Future]]''\n|Mitch\n|\"Pariah\"\n|-\n|1988\n|''[[Learning the Ropes]]''\n|Brad\n|Recurring role\n|-\n|1988\n|''[[My Secret Identity]]''\n|Tim\n|\"It Only Hurts for a Little While\"\n|-\n|1989\n|''[[T. and T.]]''\n|Steve\n|\"Thicker Than Water\"\n|-\n|1990\n|''{{sortname|The|Campbells}}''\n|Henry Clay\n|\"A Proposal of Marriage\"\n|-\n|1990\n|''{{sortname|The|World's Oldest Living Bridesmaid|nolink=1}}''\n|Rodney\n|TV film\n|-\n|1992\n|''[[E.N.G.]]''\n|Nick\n|\"To Kill with Kindness\"\n|-\n|1992\n|''[[Road to Avonlea]]''\n|Rat\n|\"When She Was Bad, She Was Horrid: Part 2\"\n|-\n|1992\n|''[[Maniac Mansion]]''\n|John Cody\n|\"Ike's New Buddy\"\n|-\n|1993\n|''[[Family Pictures]]''\n|Soletski\n|TV film\n|-\n|1993\n|''[[Liberty Street (TV series)|X-Rated]]''\n|Tony Foster\n|TV film\n|-\n|1993\n|''Nickelodeon Wildside Show''\n|Host\n|Season 2 \"13 episodes\"\n|-\n|1994\n|''{{sortname|The|Mighty Jungle}}''\n|Peter\n|\"Allison's Restaurant\"\n|-\n|1994\n|''[[Side Effects (TV series)|Side Effects]]''\n|Chris Stokes\n|\"House of Caduceus\"\n|-\n|1994\n|''[[Forever Knight]]''\n|Kyle\n|\"Can't Run, Can't Hide\"\n|-\n|1995\n|''[[Mysterious Island (TV series)|Mysterious Island]]''\n|Herbert Pencroft\n|Main role\n|-\n|1995\n|''[[Heritage Minutes]]''\n|Young\n|\"The Paris Crew\"\n|-\n|1996\n|''[[Sliders]]''\n|Judge\n|\"The Young and the Relentless\"\n|-\n|1996\n|''Gone in a Heartbeat''\n|Paul Hackett\n|TV film\n|-\n|1997\n|''[[F/X: The Series]]''\n|Jules\n|\"Bad Influence\"\n|-\n|1997\n|''[[Deepwater_Black#TV_series|Mission Genesis]]''\n|Reb Andersen\n|Main role\n|-\n|1997\n|''[[Promise the Moon]]''\n|Little Jay\n|TV film\n|-\n|1997\n|''Peacekeepers''\n|Pte. Daryl Huddy\n|TV film\n|-\n|1998\n|''[[Psi Factor]]''\n|Gary\n|\"The Labyrinth\"\n|-\n|1998\n|''[[My Date with the President's Daughter]]''\n|Clyde\n|TV film\n|-\n|1999\n|''[[Ultimate Deception]]''\n|Andy McThomas\n|TV film\n|-\n|2000\n|''{{sortname|The|7th Portal|nolink=1}}''\n|Thunderer / Peter Littlecloud (voice)\n|TV series\n|-\n|2000\u20132005\n|''[[Andromeda (TV series)|Andromeda]]''\n|[[List_of_Andromeda_characters#Seamus_Harper|Seamus Harper]]\n|Main role\n|-\n|2003\n|''[[Shattered City: The Halifax Explosion]]''\n|Sergeant Sam Barlow\n|TV miniseries\n|-\n|2003\n|''{{sortname|The|Twilight Zone|The Twilight Zone (2002 TV series)}}''\n|Gordon\n|\"Cold Fusion\"\n|-\n|2007\n|''Secrets of an Undercover Wife''\n|Clayton\n|TV film\n|-\n|2007\n|''[[Blood Ties (TV series)|Blood Ties]]''\n|Steve Jeffries\n|\"Gifted\"\n|-\n|2008\u201309\n|''{{sortname|The|Guard|The Guard (TV series)}}''\n|Barry Winter\n|Main role\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[Supernatural (U.S. TV series)|Supernatural]]''\n|Ezra\n|\"King of the Damned\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Foster |first1=Tom |title=Whatever Happened to the Cast of Andromeda? |url=https://www.tvovermind.com/whatever-happened-cast-andromeda/ |website=TVOvermind |accessdate=20 December 2018 |date=10 July 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|2015\n|''[[Girlfriends' Guide to Divorce]]''\n|Ferret Guy\n|\"Rule #32\"\n|-\n|2017\n|''[[iZombie (TV series)|iZombie]]''\n|James Weckler\n|\"Spanking the Zombie\", \"Dirt Nap Time\", \"Conspiracy Weary\"\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[The Arrangement (2017 TV series)|The Arrangement]]''\n|Director (Frankie)\n|\"Truth\"\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.gordonwoolvett.com}}\n* {{IMDb name|id=0941315|name=Gordon Michael Woolvett}}\n* [https://www.facebook.com/gordon.m.woolvett/ Woolvett's Facebook site]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Woolvett, Gordon Michael}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Canadian male film actors]]\n[[Category:Canadian male television actors]]\n[[Category:Global Television Network people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Hamilton, Ontario]]\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove BLP|date=December 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n | name             = Gordon Michael Woolvett\n | birth_date       = {{Birth year and age|1970}}\n | birth_place      = [[Hamilton, Ontario]], Canada\n | other_names      = Gordon M. Woolvett <br> Gordon Woolvett\n | occupation       = Actor\n | years_active     = 1984\u2013present\n | spouse           = {{marriage|Michele Morand|January 15, 2000}}\n | relatives        = [[Jaimz Woolvett]] (brother)\n | children         = 3\n | website          = {{URL|https://www.gordonwoolvett.com}}\n | geminiawards     = \n}}\n\n'''Gordon Michael Woolvett''' (born 1970) is a Canadian actor from [[Hamilton, Ontario]].\n\n==Career==\nWoolvett's most enduring role was as [[Seamus Zelazny Harper]] on the television series ''[[Andromeda (TV series)|Andromeda]]'' (2000\u20132005). Prior to ''Andromeda'' he starred in another science fiction television series, ''[[Deepwater Black]]''. He was also credited as playing Mitch in the \"Pariah\" episode of the short-lived 1980s science-fiction/action series ''[[Captain Power and the Soldiers of the Future]]''. He also was in two episodes of ''[[Psi Factor|Psi Factor: Chronicles of the Paranormal]]''.<ref name=edotc>{{cite encyclopedia |url=https://www.encyclopedia.com/education/news-wires-white-papers-and-books/woolvett-gordon-michael-1970-gordon-woolvett-gordon-m-woolvett |title=Woolvett, Gordon Michael 1970- (Gordon Woolvett, Gordon M. Woolvett) |website=encyclopedia.com |access-date=23 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\nWoolvett was also one of the first program jockeys for [[YTV (Canadian television)|YTV]]'s ''[[The Zone (YTV)|The Zone]]'' (then called ''The After-School Zone'')<ref>{{cite news |url=https://torontoist.com/2015/12/the-oral-history-of-1990s-ytv/ |title=The Oral History of 1990s YTV |date=22 December 2015 |department=Culture |first=Will |last=Sloan |website=[[Torontoist]] |access-date=25 April 2020 }}</ref> and the original main host for a program called ''[[Video & Arcade Top 10]]'' which also aired on YTV.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.vice.com/en_ca/article/xdmpjk/why-people-on-twitter-are-still-asking-this-90s-ytv-host-for-video-game-help |title=Why People on Twitter Are Still Asking This 90s YTV Host for Video Game Help |magazine=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]] |date=15 October 2016 |first=Gregory |last=Adams |access-date=25 April 2020 }}</ref> He acted in the 1999 [[television film|made-for-TV film]] ''[[Ultimate Deception]]'' with [[Yasmine Bleeth]].<ref name=\"edotc\" /> More recently, Woolvett could be seen on the Canadian television series ''[[The Guard (Canadian TV series)|The Guard]]'', which aired from 2008 to 2009 on [[Global Television Network]].<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.halifaxfilm.com/files/images/The_Guard_II_Final_Press_Kit.pdf |title=The Guard II |website=Halifax Film |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724160743/http://www.halifaxfilm.com/files/images/The_Guard_II_Final_Press_Kit.pdf |archive-date=July 24, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1992, Woolvett was nominated for the [[Gemini Awards|Gemini Award]] for Best Performance by a Supporting Actor for his role in ''[[Princes in Exile]]'' (1990).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://film.athabascau.ca/commentary/princes-exile-commentary |title=Princes in Exile Commentary |website=Canadian Film Online |publisher=[[Athabasca University]] |first=Evelyn |last=Ellerman |access-date=25 April 2020 }}</ref> He directed the documentary ''Around the World in 80 Anthems'', which won Best Documentary at the seventh International Film Festival Manhattan in 2017.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Manuel |first1=Felix |title=Phl wins at Int'l Film Festival Manhattan (IFFM) |url=https://www.philstar.com/entertainment/2017/10/22/1751440/phl-wins-intl-film-festival-manhattan-iffm |website=philstar.com |accessdate=20 December 2018 |date=22 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nWoolvett was born in 1970 in Hamilton, Ontario, Canada. He married Michele Morand on January 15, 2000. His brother is actor [[Jaimz Woolvett]].<ref name=\"edotc\" />\n\n== Filmography ==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|1985\n|''[[Joshua Then and Now (film)|Joshua Now and Then]]''\n|Teddy Shapiro\n|\n|-\n|1990\n|''[[Princes in Exile (film)|Princes in Exile]]''\n|Louis\n|\n|-\n|1992\n|''[[Bordertown Caf\u00e9]]''\n|Jimmy\n|\n|-\n|1995\n|''[[Rude (film)|Rude]]''\n|Ricky\n|\n|-\n|1996\n|''{{sortname|The|Legend of Gator Face}}''\n|Chip\n|\n|-\n|1998\n|''[[Shadow Builder]]''\n|Larry Eggers\n|\n|-\n|1998\n|''Clutch''\n|Spit\n|\n|-\n|1998\n|''[[Bride of Chucky]]''\n|David Collins\n|<ref>{{cite web |last1=Donato |first1=Matt |title=Bride of Chucky 20 years later: Don Mancini looks back at one of horror's boldest sequels |url=https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/bride-of-chucky-20th-anniversary-don-mancini-childs-play |website=SYFY WIRE |accessdate=20 December 2018 |language=en |date=30 October 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|2000\n|''{{sortname|The|Highwayman|nolink=1}}''\n|Walter\n|\n|-\n|2006\n|''[[Everything's Gone Green (film)|Everything's Gone Green]]''\n|Spike\n|\n|-\n|2014\n|''Down Here''\n|Coach Randall\n|\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|1984\n|''{{sortname|The|Edison Twins}}''\n|Dave\n|\"Diamonds\"\n|-\n|1986\n|''[[Act of Vengeance]]''\n|Bobby\n|TV film\n|-\n|1986\n|''[[9B (TV series)|9B]]''\n|Kevin\n|TV film\n|-\n|1987\n|''Air Waves''\n|Greg\n|\"Happy 16th\", \"A Second Look\"\n|-\n|1987\n|''[[Captain Power and the Soldiers of the Future]]''\n|Mitch\n|\"Pariah\"\n|-\n|1988\n|''[[Learning the Ropes]]''\n|Brad\n|Recurring role\n|-\n|1988\n|''[[My Secret Identity]]''\n|Tim\n|\"It Only Hurts for a Little While\"\n|-\n|1989\n|''[[T. and T.]]''\n|Steve\n|\"Thicker Than Water\"\n|-\n|1990\n|''{{sortname|The|Campbells}}''\n|Henry Clay\n|\"A Proposal of Marriage\"\n|-\n|1990\n|''{{sortname|The|World's Oldest Living Bridesmaid|nolink=1}}''\n|Rodney\n|TV film\n|-\n|1992\n|''[[E.N.G.]]''\n|Nick\n|\"To Kill with Kindness\"\n|-\n|1992\n|''[[Road to Avonlea]]''\n|Rat\n|\"When She Was Bad, She Was Horrid: Part 2\"\n|-\n|1992\n|''[[Maniac Mansion]]''\n|John Cody\n|\"Ike's New Buddy\"\n|-\n|1993\n|''[[Family Pictures]]''\n|Soletski\n|TV film\n|-\n|1993\n|''[[Liberty Street (TV series)|X-Rated]]''\n|Tony Foster\n|TV film\n|-\n|1993\n|''Nickelodeon Wildside Show''\n|Host\n|Season 2 \"13 episodes\"\n|-\n|1994\n|''{{sortname|The|Mighty Jungle}}''\n|Peter\n|\"Allison's Restaurant\"\n|-\n|1994\n|''[[Side Effects (TV series)|Side Effects]]''\n|Chris Stokes\n|\"House of Caduceus\"\n|-\n|1994\n|''[[Forever Knight]]''\n|Kyle\n|\"Can't Run, Can't Hide\"\n|-\n|1995\n|''[[Mysterious Island (TV series)|Mysterious Island]]''\n|Herbert Pencroft\n|Main role\n|-\n|1995\n|''[[Heritage Minutes]]''\n|Young\n|\"The Paris Crew\"\n|-\n|1996\n|''[[Sliders]]''\n|Judge\n|\"The Young and the Relentless\"\n|-\n|1996\n|''Gone in a Heartbeat''\n|Paul Hackett\n|TV film\n|-\n|1997\n|''[[F/X: The Series]]''\n|Jules\n|\"Bad Influence\"\n|-\n|1997\n|''[[Deepwater_Black#TV_series|Mission Genesis]]''\n|Reb Andersen\n|Main role\n|-\n|1997\n|''[[Promise the Moon]]''\n|Little Jay\n|TV film\n|-\n|1997\n|''Peacekeepers''\n|Pte. Daryl Huddy\n|TV film\n|-\n|1998\n|''[[Psi Factor]]''\n|Gary\n|\"The Labyrinth\"\n|-\n|1998\n|''[[My Date with the President's Daughter]]''\n|Clyde\n|TV film\n|-\n|1999\n|''[[Ultimate Deception]]''\n|Andy McThomas\n|TV film\n|-\n|2000\n|''{{sortname|The|7th Portal|nolink=1}}''\n|Thunderer / Peter Littlecloud (voice)\n|TV series\n|-\n|2000\u20132005\n|''[[Andromeda (TV series)|Andromeda]]''\n|[[List_of_Andromeda_characters#Seamus_Harper|Seamus Harper]]\n|Main role\n|-\n|2003\n|''[[Shattered City: The Halifax Explosion]]''\n|Sergeant Sam Barlow\n|TV miniseries\n|-\n|2003\n|''{{sortname|The|Twilight Zone|The Twilight Zone (2002 TV series)}}''\n|Gordon\n|\"Cold Fusion\"\n|-\n|2007\n|''Secrets of an Undercover Wife''\n|Clayton\n|TV film\n|-\n|2007\n|''[[Blood Ties (TV series)|Blood Ties]]''\n|Steve Jeffries\n|\"Gifted\"\n|-\n|2008\u201309\n|''{{sortname|The|Guard|The Guard (TV series)}}''\n|Barry Winter\n|Main role\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[Supernatural (U.S. TV series)|Supernatural]]''\n|Ezra\n|\"King of the Damned\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Foster |first1=Tom |title=Whatever Happened to the Cast of Andromeda? |url=https://www.tvovermind.com/whatever-happened-cast-andromeda/ |website=TVOvermind |accessdate=20 December 2018 |date=10 July 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|2015\n|''[[Girlfriends' Guide to Divorce]]''\n|Ferret Guy\n|\"Rule #32\"\n|-\n|2017\n|''[[iZombie (TV series)|iZombie]]''\n|James Weckler\n|\"Spanking the Zombie\", \"Dirt Nap Time\", \"Conspiracy Weary\"\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[The Arrangement (2017 TV series)|The Arrangement]]''\n|Director (Frankie)\n|\"Truth\"\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.gordonwoolvett.com}}\n* {{IMDb name|id=0941315|name=Gordon Michael Woolvett}}\n* [https://www.facebook.com/gordon.m.woolvett/ Woolvett's Facebook site]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Woolvett, Gordon Michael}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Canadian male film actors]]\n[[Category:Canadian male television actors]]\n[[Category:Global Television Network people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Hamilton, Ontario]]\n", "name_user": "Adavidb", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:removed banner; everything has source citations", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gordon_Michael_Woolvett"}
{"title_page": "Serbs in Italy", "text_new": "{{short description|Ethnic group}}\n{{Infobox ethnic group\n|group    = Serbs in Italy<br>Serbi in Italia<br>\u0421\u0440\u0431\u0438 \u0443 \u0418\u0442\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0458\u0438<br>Srbi u Italiji\n|image    = [[File:Trieste Serb-orthodox church of San-Spiridione3.jpg|230px]]<br>[[Saint Spyridon Church, Trieste]]\n|population  = '''46,958'''<ref name=\"istat\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dossierimmigrazione.it/docnews/file/2014_La%20collettivit\u00e0%20serba_Scheda.pdf |title=Statistiche demografiche ISTAT |publisher=Demo.istat.it |date= |accessdate=2014-10-03}}</ref>\n|popplace = [[Trieste]], [[Rome]], [[Arzignano]]\n|rels     = [[Serbian Orthodox Church]]\n|related  = [[South Slavs]] \n}}\n{{Serbs}}\n'''Serbs in Italy''' ({{lang-it|Serbi in Italia}}; {{lang-sr|\u0421\u0440\u0431\u0438 \u0443 \u0418\u0442\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0458\u0438|translit=Srbi u Italiji}}) or '''Italian Serbs''' ({{lang-sr|\u0418\u0442\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0458\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438 \u0421\u0440\u0431\u0438|translit=Italijanski Srbi}}), number 46,958 in [[Italy]].<ref name=\"istat\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dossierimmigrazione.it/docnews/file/2014_La%20collettivit\u00e0%20serba_Scheda.pdf |title=Statistiche demografiche ISTAT |publisher=Demo.istat.it |date= |accessdate=2014-10-03}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nAccording to [[Graziadio Isaia Ascoli]], the 19th century writer [[Giovanni de Rubertis]] considered the [[Molise Slavs|''Schiavoni'' (Slavs) or ''Dalmati'' (Dalmatians) of Molise]] in Italy to be Serbs that were brought there by [[Skanderbeg]] during his [[Skanderbeg's Italian expedition|Italian expedition]] in 1460-1462 along with the [[Albanians]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Kova\u010di\u0107|first=Risto|authorlink=Risto Kova\u010di\u0107|title=Glasnik Srpskoga u\u010denog dru\u0161tva, Volume 62|year=1885|publisher=Serbian Learned Society|url=https://books.google.com/books?ei=pmQnTrvbIo6UOqalvK8K&ct=result&id=cQQbAAAAMAAJ&dq=%D1%81%D0%BA%D0%B5%D0%BD%D0%B4%D0%B5%D1%80%D0%B1%D0%B5%D0%B3+%D1%81%D1%80%D0%B1%D0%B8%D0%BD&q=%D0%BF%D1%80%D0%B2%D0%B8+%D0%A1%D1%80%D0%B1%D0%B8#search_anchor|accessdate=21 July 2011|pages=273\u2013340 [281] |chapter=Srpske Naseobine u Ju\u017enoj Italiji |chapterurl=https://books.google.rs/books?ei=pmQnTrvbIo6UOqalvK8K&ct=result&id=cQQbAAAAMAAJ&dq=%D1%81%D0%BA%D0%B5%D0%BD%D0%B4%D0%B5%D1%80%D0%B1%D0%B5%D0%B3+%D1%81%D1%80%D0%B1%D0%B8%D0%BD&q=%D0%BF%D1%80%D0%B2%D0%B8+%D0%A1%D1%80%D0%B1%D0%B8&redir_esc=y#search_anchor |quote=\u041f\u043e \u0433\u043e\u0441\u043f\u043e\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0443 \u0434\u0435 \u0420\u0443\u0431\u0435\u0440\u0442\u0438\u0441\u0443, \u0432\u0435\u043b\u0438 \u0433\u043e\u0441\u043f. \u0410\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0438 \u043e\u043d\u0434\u0458\u0435, \u043f\u0440\u0432\u0438 \u0421\u0440\u0431\u0438 \u2014 \u0438\u043b\u0438 \u043a\u0430\u043a\u043e \u0438\u0445 \u043e\u043d\u0430\u043c\u043e \u043e\u0431\u0438\u0447\u043d\u0438\u0458\u0435 \u0437\u043e\u0432\u0443 Schiavoni  \u0438\u043b\u0438 Dalmati \u2014 \u0434\u043e\u0448\u043b\u0438 \u0441\u0443 \u0443 \u041c\u043e\u043b\u0438\u0437\u0435 \u0437\u0430\u0435\u0434\u043d\u043e \u0441 \u0410\u0440\u0431\u0430\u043d\u0430\u0441\u0438\u043c\u0430 (\u0410\u043b\u0431\u0430\u043d\u0435\u0437\u0438) \u0448\u0442\u043e \u0438\u0445 \u0458\u0435 \u043e\u043d\u0430\u043c\u043e \u0434\u043e\u0432\u0435\u043e \u0421\u043a\u0435\u043d\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0435\u0433.}}</ref>\n\nIn 1497 Italian court poet Rogeri de Pacienza di Nardo wrote about a group of Serbian refugees who left the Despotate of [[\u0110ura\u0111 Brankovi\u0107]] to settle in the village of [[Gioia del Colle]] near [[Bari]], Italy. He describes how they sang and danced the [[kolo (dance)]] in honour of the Queen of Naples, [[Isabella del Balzo]]. The names of the singers that Pacienza wrote down are common Serbian names.<ref>{{cite book | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=dPBPHVf3kdoC&pg=PA98 | page = 98 | title = Oral Art Forms and Their Passage Into Writing | editor1-first = Else | editor1-last = Mundal | editor2-first = Jonas | editor2-last = Wellendorf | publisher = Museum Tusculanum Press | year = 2008 | isbn = 9788763505048}}</ref>\n\nIn 1782 the first Serbian school opened in [[Trieste]], and in the 19th century the Serbian Orthodox \"Saint Spyridon church\" in Trieste was built near the Ponte Rosso square.<ref name=NSK1>Sve Vesti, [http://www.svevesti.com/a199267-udru%C5%BEenje-srba-vuk-karad%C5%BEic-najstarije-u-italiji ''Udruzenje Srba \"Vuk Karadzic\" najstarija u Italiji'']</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\nSome 40,000 Serbs live in northern Italy. In [[Arzignano]] there are thousands of Serbs from all over former Yugoslavia.<ref>RTS.rs, [http://www.rts.rs/page/tv/sr/story/22/RTS+Satelit/645881/Srbi+u+severnoj+Italiji ''Srbi u severnoj Italiji'']</ref> In [[Trieste]], 10,000-15,000 Serbs live in the city.<ref name=Trieste>{{cite web |url=http://www.retecivica.trieste.it/new/default.asp?pagina=-&ids=51&id_sx=79&tipo=monoblocchi&tabella_padre=dx&id_padre=800  |title=Rete Civica Trieste |author= |date= |work= |accessdate=12 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n*{{nts|46,958}} (2013 census), \"Foreign citizens\" from Serbia (excl. Kosovo) <ref>{{cite web|title=Cittadini Stranieri|date=December 31, 2013|url=http://demo.istat.it/str2013/index.html|quote=Cittadini Stranieri. Popolazione residente per sesso e cittadinanza al 31 dicembre 2013 Italia - Europa}}</ref>\n\n==Triestine Serbs==\n\n'''Triestine Serbs''' ({{lang-sr-cyr|\u0422\u0440\u0448\u045b\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438 \u0421\u0440\u0431\u0438 /Tr\u0161\u0107anski Srbi}}; {{lang-it|Serbi Triestini}}) are the ethnic [[Serbs]] of [[Trieste]], present in the city since the 18th century.<ref name=\"Medakovic 1987\">{{cite book |last=Medakovic |first=Dejan |authorlink=Dejan Medakovic |year=1987 |title=Serbs in the history of Trieste}}</ref> \n\n===History===\nSerb merchants and ship-owners established a community in Trieste at the start of the 18th century, most primarily originating from [[Sarajevo]], [[Trebinje]], and the [[Bay of Kotor]].<ref name=\"Gorup 2006\">{{cite journal |last=Gorup |first=Radmila |date=Spring 2006 |title=Marija Mitrovi\u0107. Sul mare brillavano vasti silenzi: Imagini di Trieste nella letteratura Serba |journal=Serbian Studies |volume=20 |page=203}}</ref> In 1751 [[Maria Theresa]] of the Austro-Hungarian Empire proclaimed religious freedom in the city, and the Serbs and Greeks of Trieste built the [[Saint Spyridon Church, Trieste|Saint Spyridon church]] that same year.<ref name=\"peoplesaint\">{{cite web|url=http://www.culturaitalia.it/opencms/en/contenuti/eventi/event_1320.html?language=en|title=People of Saint Spiridione: the cultural and religious legacy of the Serbians of Trieste|accessdate=2014-06-11}}</ref> The most influential of the wealthy Serbian merchants of the time were<ref>{{Cite book|title=Kultura Srba u Trstu|last=Peri\u0161i\u0107|first=Miroslav|last2=Relji\u0107|first2=Jelica|publisher=Arhiv Srbije|year=2016|isbn=|location=Belgrade|pages=}}</ref> the Kurtovi\u0107, Gop\u010devi\u0107, Vojnovi\u0107, Vu\u010deti\u0107, Popovi\u0107, Nikoli\u0107 and Mileti\u0107 families, who owned most the structures and dock area of the \"Porto Vecchio\" (Old Port).<ref name=\"Medakovi\u0107 1987\">{{cite book |last=Medakovi\u0107 |first=Dejan |authorlink=Dejan Medakovi\u0107 |year=1987 |title=Serbs in the history of Trieste}}</ref> In 1766 Trieste's Serbs numbered 50, by 1780 they grew to 200.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Pavlowitch |first=Stevan K. |date=June 1961 |title= History of the Serbian Orthodox Church community of Trieste |journal=The Slavonic and East European Review |volume=39 |pages=541\u2013544}}</ref>\n\n===Serbian School===\nIn 1782 the Serbian community of Trieste began expressing its desire for a [[Serbian language|Serbian]]-language day school, a place for their children to be passed down Serbian culture and language. Jovan Miletic, a wealthy Serb merchant in Trieste, donated 24,000 florins to build a Serbian Elementary School in 1787. On July 1, 1792, the local government approved its opening and the \"Jovan Mileti\u0107\" private school began official operation, located in the city center, right beside the Saint Spyridon Church. A night school and reading room were opened in 1911.<ref name=\"Medakovic 1987\"/> In 1911 an asylum was added to the school, for Serbian political refugees, due to the constant warfare and bloodshed occurring between the [[Austro-Hungarian]] and [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] empires on the [[Balkan Peninsula]]. The school represented a pillar of the Serbian community of Trieste, where the children of the wealthy Serbian merchants went to school and integrated into the city's community. In 1973 the school was shut down due to lack of student enrollment and became a Sunday school for Serbian language and culture. Velimir Djerasimovi\u0107, the school's principal and teacher since 1927, retired in 1973. Djerasimovi\u0107 is the father of Italian film actors [[Ivan Rassimov]] and [[Rada Rassimov]].\n\n===Saint Spyridon Church===\n{{main|Saint Spyridon Church, Trieste}}\n[[File:Trieste Serb-orthodox church of San-Spiridione3.jpg|300px|thumbnail|right|The [[Saint Spyridon Church, Trieste|St. Spyridon Serbian Orthodox Church]]]]\nIn 1782 the [[Serbian Orthodox]] and [[Greek Orthodox]] communities of Trieste split due to major disagreements concerning church rituals and language-usage, at which point the Greek community built its own church, dedicated to [[Saint Nicholas]] in the [[Neoclassical architecture|neoclassical]] style, and the Serbs continued to use the original church of [[Saint Spyridon]]. In 1861 the Serb community demolished the original church, and rebuilt it in [[Serbo-Byzantine Revival]] style, in order to \"stamp their identity architecturally in the midst of a baroque Austro-Italian city\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neomagazine.com/2010_11_november/_hellenes.html|title=The Greeks of Trieste &#124; Neo Magazine|author=Alexander Billinis|accessdate=2014-06-11}}</ref> {{irrelevant citation|reason= Trieste is not a baroque city; article's author cites an unnamed person. |date=December 2014}} The church's construction was completed seven years later, in 1868. With the added capacity for 1600 worshippers, it was for a long time the second largest Serbian church in the world. {{citation needed|reason= This claim needs a reliable source by a historian of architecture.|date=December 2014}} The church is filled with liturgical masterpieces of the time, works in gold from the 17th and 18th centuries, antique Orthodox icons and handmade books, making it an important monument to Serbian history and culture.<ref name=\"peoplesaint\"/> The church was designed by Italian architect [[Carlo Maciachini]], featuring four cupolas and one large main dome adorned in an off-blue color. In the 1800s the Serbian population in Trieste numbered around 200 people.<ref name=\"Catalan 2011\">{{cite journal |last=Catalan |first=Tullia |date=October 2011 |title=The Ambivalence of a Port City: The Jews of Trieste from the 19th to the 20th century |journal=Quest. Issues in Contemporary Jewish History |url=http://www.quest-cdecjournal.it/focus.php?id=232}}</ref>\n\n===Under Fascist Rule===\nIn 1918, at the end of [[World War I]], Trieste became part of Italy and social life drastically changed for the Serbs and other minorities of Trieste. Due to the contentious national border with [[Slovenia]], Italian society became increasingly hostile towards all [[Slavs]] in Trieste including the Serbs, and anti-Slavic racism began to flourish in Italy.<ref name=\"Catalan 2011\"/> The anti-Slavic feelings in Trieste were present already before the War, embodied by the local Liberal-National Party, led by Giuseppe Cuzzi, whose aim was to make Trieste completely [[Catholic]] and Italian. The anti-Slavic propaganda focused on the idea that Slavic people were barbaric and could not integrate properly into a civilized society.<ref name=\"Catalan 2011\"/> Tensions came to a hilt in [[World War Two]], when the Germans, who had occupied Northern Italy in September 1943, built the only Nazi Extermination Camp in Italy, \"[[Risiera di San Sabba]]\", on the outskirts of Trieste. Three thousand Jews, Serbs and other Slavs were executed here in 1944 while thousands more were imprisoned awaiting transfer to other extermination camps.<ref>{{cite book |last=Poprzeczny|first=Joseph |authorlink=Joseph Poprzeczny|year=2004 |title=Odilo Globocnik Hitler's Man in the East}}</ref>\n\n===Monuments===\n[[File:Trieste-Canal Grande-DSCF1420.JPG|300px|thumbnail|right|The Palazzo Gopcevich]]\nBesides the Saint Spyridon Church and the Jovan Mileti\u0107 Serbian School, the Serbs of Trieste contributed to several other important landmarks of the city. The Gop\u010devi\u0107 family built the \"Palazzo Gopcevich\" on the Canal Grande, near the Serbian Church, in 1850 in commemoration to the heroes who fought for the [[Second Serbian Uprising|independence of Serbia from the Ottoman Empire]] (1814). Cristoforo Popovich owned many famous merchant ships in Trieste, some of the largest in the Adriatic: the \"Tartana\", \"Il Feroce Dalmata\", \"La Forza\" and the \"Ripatriato\", and was instrumental to the Russian-side in the Crimean War (1853-1856). Cristoforo Scuglievich (Skuljevic) built the Palazzo Scuglievich in the mid-1800s along the banks of the city, and donated the palace in his will to the Serbian community of Trieste; today it is owned by the Serb community.<ref name=\"Medakovi\u0107 1987\"/>\n\n===Serbian Writers===\nThe Serbian community of Trieste had a deep and long-lasting relationship with Serbian writers from the 18th century to today. Iconic [[Serbian literature|Serbian writers]] and linguists such as [[Vuk Karad\u017ei\u0107]], [[Dositej Obradovi\u0107]], [[Petar II Petrovi\u0107-Njego\u0161]], [[Zaharije Orfelin]] and [[Pavle Solari\u0107]] were inspired by Trieste and its developed Serbian community.<ref name=\"Gorup 2006\"/>  They wrote many works on Trieste's influence on Serbian \"pre-Romanticism\" and cultural development during a time when the Serbs lacked statehood and cultural expression. Serbian linguist and creator of the standardized Serbian language, [[Vuk Karad\u017ei\u0107]], kept in constant contact with Trieste's Serb community from his home in [[Vienna]]. In 1813 Vuk called upon the Triestan Serbs to subscribe to the Serbian-language newspaper, \"Novine Serbske\" promoting the newly standardized Serbian language, and more than sixty copies of the standard Serbian dictionary were bought in 1814.<ref name=\"Gorup 2006\"/> [[Lukijan Mu\u0161icki]] wrote an ode to Serbian merchants of Trieste in 1835, and revolutionary writer Dositej Obradovi\u0107 tutored the children of the wealthy Serb merchants.<ref name=\"Gorup 2006\"/> Many [[Serbian epic poetry|Serbian poets]] and folklorists {{Who|date=December 2014}} even worked in the Saint Spyridon Church for a time. An almost universal feeling of inspiration and admiration of Trieste's wealthy Serb community was shared by their Balkan-Serb contemporaries.{{Who|date=December 2014}}\n\n=== Modern Day ===\nToday, Serbian-born Serbs represent the largest foreign-born community in Trieste, numbering around 10,000, although some figures state anywhere up to 18,000.<ref name=\"ISTAT 2010\">http://www.demo.istat.it/str2010/index03_e.html</ref> The overwhelming majority of Serbs in Trieste today descend from the immigration wave following the [[Yugoslav Wars]] of the 90s. Recently the Serbian Orthodox Society in Trieste led by Bogoljub Stoji\u010devi\u0107 has called on the local government to grant the Serb Community of Trieste cultural autonomy and reinstate the [[Jovan Mileti\u0107]] Serbian school as a full-time school since it downgraded to a Sunday school due to inactivity in 1973.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.novosti.rs/vesti/planeta.301.html:312440-Trst-Srbi-traze-svoju-skolu|title=Serbs want their own school (In Serbian) |publisher=novosti.rs|accessdate=2014-06-10}}</ref> Since 2009 the Serbian community of Trieste, namely the Serbian Association \"Vuk Karadzic\", has been organizing an annual Balkan-style trumpet festival on the outskirts of Trieste called \"Guca na Krasu\" (Guca in [[Karst Plateau|Karst]]), modeled after the famous [[Gu\u010da Trumpet Festival]] in Serbia. Since its beginnings, the festival has managed to gain recognition and popularity, succeeding in getting famous musicians like [[Goran Bregovi\u0107]] and [[Boban Markovi\u0107]], as well as many popular Italian acts.<ref>{{cite book |last=Kunej |first=Drago |authorlink=Drago Kunej |year=2013 |title=Trapped in Folklore: Studies in Music and Dance Tradition and Their Contemporary Transformations|publisher=LIT Verlag}}</ref> The oldest active Serbian organization in Trieste is the soccer club \"Serbia Sport\",{{Dubious|reason= presumably, the oldest should be the Serbian Orthodox Community or Parish, not a football club from 1992|date=December 2014}} started in 1992, and since then has won a multitude of championships in the local Trieste soccer league, making it today one of the top soccer teams in the [[Province of Trieste]]. Together with the Serbian Association \"Vuk Karadzic\", Serbia Sport organizes an annual Serbian-Diaspora Soccer Tournament in Trieste on the Serbian holiday Spasovdan, which occurs 40 days after Easter.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radiobravo.net/home/42-vesti-radio-bravo/696-gua-na-krasu.html|title=Guca in Krast - Serbs, Slovenians and Italians in a Trance|author=Vasic, Slobodan|accessdate=2014-06-10}}</ref>\n\n==Organizations==\nThere are several community organizations of Serbs in Italy. The Association of Serbs of Italy was established in April 2015 by the combined organizations meeting in Trieste.<ref>{{cite web|title=Formiran Savez Srba Italije|work=Dijaspora|date=27 April 2015|publisher=Uprava za saradnju sa dijasporom i Srbima u regionu|url=http://www.dijaspora.gov.rs/lat/formiran-savez-srba-italije-2/}}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n\n; Nobility\n* [[Elena of Montenegro]], Queen consort of Italy\n* [[Princess Yolanda of Savoy]]\n* [[Darinka Kveki\u0107]], wife of [[Danilo I, Prince of Montenegro]]\n* [[Natalija Konstantinovi\u0107]], wife of [[Prince Mirko of Montenegro]]\n* [[Carlo III Tocco]]\n* [[Maria of Serbia, Marchioness of Montferrat]]\n* [[William IX, Marquess of Montferrat]]\n\n;Artists\n*[[Marcello Dudovich]], one of the most acclaimed commercial artists of art, prints, and posters during his time.\n*[[Milan Zlokovi\u0107]], an architect born in Trieste\n\n;Writers\n*[[Ljudevit Vuli\u010devi\u0107]]\n*[[Dositej Obradovi\u0107]]\n*[[Aleksa \u0160anti\u0107]]\n*[[Petar II Petrovi\u0107-Njego\u0161]]\n*[[Stefano Zannowich]]\n*[[Tomo Medin]] \n\n;Printers\n*[[Bo\u017eidar Vukovi\u0107]]\n*[[Vi\u0107enco Vukovi\u0107]]\n\n;Business people\n*[[Spiridione Gopcevich]], a shipowner from Trieste\n*[[Jovo Kurtovi\u0107]], a shipowner from Trieste\n\n;Singers\n*[[Sara Jovanovi\u0107]] (born 1993), Serbian singer born in Rome that represented Serbia at Eurovision Song Contest 2008\n\n;Doctors\n*[[Dimitrije Fru\u0161i\u0107]]\n\n;Teachers\n*[[Dositej Obradovi\u0107]]\n\n;Scientists\n* [[Spiridon Gop\u010devi\u0107]]\n\n;TV and cinema\n*[[Nina Seni\u010dar]] (born 1985), model and actress, lives in Italy since 2006\n*[[Sasha Montenegro]] (born 1945), actress born in Bari as Aleksandra Acimovi\u0107 Popovi\u0107\n*[[Ivan Rassimov]] (1938\u20132003), late actor born in Trieste to Serbian parents as Ivan Djerasimovi\u0107; brother of [[Rada Rassimov]]. \n*[[Rada Rassimov]] (born 1941), actress born in Trieste to Serbian parents as Rada Djerasimovi\u0107; sister of [[Ivan Rassimov]].\n*[[Olga Bisera]], actress born Bisera [[Vukoti\u0107]]. \n\n;Sportspeople\n*[[Giovanni Raicevich]] was a famous Italian wrestler in the early 20th century. \n*[[Milo\u0161 Malivojevi\u0107]] (born 1993), active footballer born in Scandiano, [[Reggio Emilia]] \n*[[Marino Nicolich]] (born 1910), late footballer born in Monfalcone, whose name was italianized in \"Marino Nicoli\" by the Italian Fascist government.\n*[[Dragan Travica]] (born 1986), volleyball player born in Croatia, son of the Serbian coach [[Ljubomir Travica]]; plays for the Italian national team \n*[[Ljubomir Travica]] (born 1954), volleyball coach and retired player; has residence in Italy since he played for [[Modena]] in 1983. He is the father of [[Dragan Travica]]\n*[[Marko Stanojevic]] (born 1979), rugby union player born in Birmingham to a Serbian father and an Italian mother. He played for the Italian national team.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Serbian diaspora]]\n*[[Serbs]]\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite web|title=Svetionik (Srbi u Italiji)|url=http://www.svetionik.it/}} (Community page) {{in lang|sr|it}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110303004647/http://www.europeandevelopmentcentre.eu/ European Development centre] (Serbian Diaspora in Italy)\n*{{Citation |last=Mihajlovi\u0107 |first=Miodrag |script-title=sr:\u0421\u0440\u043f\u0441\u043a\u0430 \u043d\u0430\u0441\u0435\u0459\u0430 \u043d\u0430 \u0458\u0443\u0433\u0443 \u0418\u0442\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0458\u0435 \u2014 \u0421\u043a\u0430\u0432\u0443\u043d\u0438 \u0438 \u045a\u0438\u0445\u043e\u0432\u0435 \u0438\u0437\u0432\u043e\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0435 \u0432\u0438\u043b\u0435 |trans-title=Serbian settlements in Southern Italy \u2014 Schiavoni and their spring fairies |url= http://www.srpsko-nasledje.rs/sr-c/1998/03/article-17.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.srpsko-nasledje.rs%2Fsr-c%2F1998%2F03%2Farticle-17.html&date=2012-09-10 |archivedate= 10 September 2012 |accessdate= |edition= |series= Srpsko Nasle\u0111e, Istorijske sveske |volume=3 |date= March 1998|origyear= |publisher= Preduze\u0107e za novinsko izdava\u010dku delatnost glas |location= Belgrade |language= Serbian |isbn= |oclc=40132319 }}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{in lang|sr}} [http://www.svetionik.it/ Northern Italy's Serbian community website]\n* {{in lang|sr}} [http://italia.rastko.net/ Historical documents on the Serbs of Italy]\n\n{{Serbian diaspora}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Serbs In Italy}}\n[[Category:Italian people of Serbian descent]]\n[[Category:Serbian diaspora in Europe]]\n[[Category:Serbian Orthodox Church in Italy]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Italy]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Ethnic group}}\n{{Infobox ethnic group\n|group    = Serbs in Italy<br>Serbi in Italia<br>\u0421\u0440\u0431\u0438 \u0443 \u0418\u0442\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0458\u0438<br>Srbi u Italiji\n|image    = [[File:Trieste Serb-orthodox church of San-Spiridione3.jpg|230px]]<br>[[Saint Spyridon Church, Trieste]]\n|population  = '''46,958'''<ref name=\"istat\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dossierimmigrazione.it/docnews/file/2014_La%20collettivit\u00e0%20serba_Scheda.pdf |title=Statistiche demografiche ISTAT |publisher=Demo.istat.it |date= |accessdate=2014-10-03}}</ref>\n|popplace = [[Trieste]], [[Rome]], [[Arzignano]]\n|rels     = [[Serbian Orthodox Church]]\n|related  = [[South Slavs]] \n}}\n{{Serbs}}\n'''Serbs in Italy''' ({{lang-it|Serbi in Italia}}; {{lang-sr|\u0421\u0440\u0431\u0438 \u0443 \u0418\u0442\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0458\u0438|translit=Srbi u Italiji}}) or '''Italian Serbs''' ({{lang-sr|\u0418\u0442\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0458\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438 \u0421\u0440\u0431\u0438|translit=Italijanski Srbi}}), number 46,958 in [[Italy]].<ref name=\"istat\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dossierimmigrazione.it/docnews/file/2014_La%20collettivit\u00e0%20serba_Scheda.pdf |title=Statistiche demografiche ISTAT |publisher=Demo.istat.it |date= |accessdate=2014-10-03}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nAccording to [[Graziadio Isaia Ascoli]], the 19th century writer [[Giovanni de Rubertis]] considered the [[Molise Slavs|''Schiavoni'' (Slavs) or ''Dalmati'' (Dalmatians) of Molise]] in Italy to be Serbs that were brought there by [[Skanderbeg]] during his [[Skanderbeg's Italian expedition|Italian expedition]] in 1460-1462 along with the [[Albanians]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Kova\u010di\u0107|first=Risto|authorlink=Risto Kova\u010di\u0107|title=Glasnik Srpskoga u\u010denog dru\u0161tva, Volume 62|year=1885|publisher=Serbian Learned Society|url=https://books.google.com/books?ei=pmQnTrvbIo6UOqalvK8K&ct=result&id=cQQbAAAAMAAJ&dq=%D1%81%D0%BA%D0%B5%D0%BD%D0%B4%D0%B5%D1%80%D0%B1%D0%B5%D0%B3+%D1%81%D1%80%D0%B1%D0%B8%D0%BD&q=%D0%BF%D1%80%D0%B2%D0%B8+%D0%A1%D1%80%D0%B1%D0%B8#search_anchor|accessdate=21 July 2011|pages=273\u2013340 [281] |chapter=Srpske Naseobine u Ju\u017enoj Italiji |chapterurl=https://books.google.rs/books?ei=pmQnTrvbIo6UOqalvK8K&ct=result&id=cQQbAAAAMAAJ&dq=%D1%81%D0%BA%D0%B5%D0%BD%D0%B4%D0%B5%D1%80%D0%B1%D0%B5%D0%B3+%D1%81%D1%80%D0%B1%D0%B8%D0%BD&q=%D0%BF%D1%80%D0%B2%D0%B8+%D0%A1%D1%80%D0%B1%D0%B8&redir_esc=y#search_anchor |quote=\u041f\u043e \u0433\u043e\u0441\u043f\u043e\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0443 \u0434\u0435 \u0420\u0443\u0431\u0435\u0440\u0442\u0438\u0441\u0443, \u0432\u0435\u043b\u0438 \u0433\u043e\u0441\u043f. \u0410\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0438 \u043e\u043d\u0434\u0458\u0435, \u043f\u0440\u0432\u0438 \u0421\u0440\u0431\u0438 \u2014 \u0438\u043b\u0438 \u043a\u0430\u043a\u043e \u0438\u0445 \u043e\u043d\u0430\u043c\u043e \u043e\u0431\u0438\u0447\u043d\u0438\u0458\u0435 \u0437\u043e\u0432\u0443 Schiavoni  \u0438\u043b\u0438 Dalmati \u2014 \u0434\u043e\u0448\u043b\u0438 \u0441\u0443 \u0443 \u041c\u043e\u043b\u0438\u0437\u0435 \u0437\u0430\u0435\u0434\u043d\u043e \u0441 \u0410\u0440\u0431\u0430\u043d\u0430\u0441\u0438\u043c\u0430 (\u0410\u043b\u0431\u0430\u043d\u0435\u0437\u0438) \u0448\u0442\u043e \u0438\u0445 \u0458\u0435 \u043e\u043d\u0430\u043c\u043e \u0434\u043e\u0432\u0435\u043e \u0421\u043a\u0435\u043d\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0435\u0433.}}</ref>\n\nIn 1497 Italian court poet Rogeri de Pacienza di Nardo wrote about a group of Serbian refugees who left the Despotate of [[\u0110ura\u0111 Brankovi\u0107]] to settle in the village of [[Gioia del Colle]] near [[Bari]], Italy. He describes how they sang and danced the [[kolo (dance)]] in honour of the Queen of Naples, [[Isabella del Balzo]]. The names of the singers that Pacienza wrote down are common Serbian names.<ref>{{cite book | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=dPBPHVf3kdoC&pg=PA98 | page = 98 | title = Oral Art Forms and Their Passage Into Writing | editor1-first = Else | editor1-last = Mundal | editor2-first = Jonas | editor2-last = Wellendorf | publisher = Museum Tusculanum Press | year = 2008 | isbn = 9788763505048}}</ref>\n\nIn 1782 the first Serbian school opened in [[Trieste]], and in the 19th century the Serbian Orthodox \"Saint Spyridon church\" in Trieste was built near the Ponte Rosso square.<ref name=NSK1>Sve Vesti, [http://www.svevesti.com/a199267-udru%C5%BEenje-srba-vuk-karad%C5%BEic-najstarije-u-italiji ''Udruzenje Srba \"Vuk Karadzic\" najstarija u Italiji'']</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\nSome 40,000 Serbs live in northern Italy. In [[Arzignano]] there are thousands of Serbs from all over former Yugoslavia.<ref>RTS.rs, [http://www.rts.rs/page/tv/sr/story/22/RTS+Satelit/645881/Srbi+u+severnoj+Italiji ''Srbi u severnoj Italiji'']</ref> In [[Trieste]], 10,000-15,000 Serbs live in the city.<ref name=Trieste>{{cite web |url=http://www.retecivica.trieste.it/new/default.asp?pagina=-&ids=51&id_sx=79&tipo=monoblocchi&tabella_padre=dx&id_padre=800  |title=Rete Civica Trieste |author= |date= |work= |accessdate=12 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n*{{nts|46,958}} (2013 census), \"Foreign citizens\" from Serbia (excl. Kosovo) <ref>{{cite web|title=Cittadini Stranieri|date=December 31, 2013|url=http://demo.istat.it/str2013/index.html|quote=Cittadini Stranieri. Popolazione residente per sesso e cittadinanza al 31 dicembre 2013 Italia - Europa}}</ref>\n\n==Triestine Serbs==\n\n'''Triestine Serbs''' ({{lang-sr-cyr|\u0422\u0440\u0448\u045b\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438 \u0421\u0440\u0431\u0438 /Tr\u0161\u0107anski Srbi}}; {{lang-it|Serbi Triestini}}) are the ethnic [[Serbs]] of [[Trieste]], present in the city since the 18th century.<ref name=\"Medakovic 1987\">{{cite book |last=Medakovic |first=Dejan |authorlink=Dejan Medakovic |year=1987 |title=Serbs in the history of Trieste}}</ref> \n\n===History===\nSerb merchants and ship-owners established a community in Trieste at the start of the 18th century, most primarily originating from [[Sarajevo]], [[Trebinje]], and the [[Bay of Kotor]].<ref name=\"Gorup 2006\">{{cite journal |last=Gorup |first=Radmila |date=Spring 2006 |title=Marija Mitrovi\u0107. Sul mare brillavano vasti silenzi: Imagini di Trieste nella letteratura Serba |journal=Serbian Studies |volume=20 |page=203}}</ref> In 1751 [[Maria Theresa]] of the Austro-Hungarian Empire proclaimed religious freedom in the city, and the Serbs and Greeks of Trieste built the [[Saint Spyridon Church, Trieste|Saint Spyridon church]] that same year.<ref name=\"peoplesaint\">{{cite web|url=http://www.culturaitalia.it/opencms/en/contenuti/eventi/event_1320.html?language=en|title=People of Saint Spiridione: the cultural and religious legacy of the Serbians of Trieste|accessdate=2014-06-11}}</ref> The most influential of the wealthy Serbian merchants of the time were<ref>{{Cite book|title=Kultura Srba u Trstu|last=Peri\u0161i\u0107|first=Miroslav|last2=Relji\u0107|first2=Jelica|publisher=Arhiv Srbije|year=2016|isbn=|location=Belgrade|pages=}}</ref> the Kurtovi\u0107, Gop\u010devi\u0107, Vojnovi\u0107, Vu\u010deti\u0107, Popovi\u0107, Nikoli\u0107 and Mileti\u0107 families, who owned most the structures and dock area of the \"Porto Vecchio\" (Old Port).<ref name=\"Medakovi\u0107 1987\">{{cite book |last=Medakovi\u0107 |first=Dejan |authorlink=Dejan Medakovi\u0107 |year=1987 |title=Serbs in the history of Trieste}}</ref> In 1766 Trieste's Serbs numbered 50, by 1780 they grew to 200.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Pavlowitch |first=Stevan K. |date=June 1961 |title= History of the Serbian Orthodox Church community of Trieste |journal=The Slavonic and East European Review |volume=39 |pages=541\u2013544}}</ref>\n\n===Serbian School===\nIn 1782 the Serbian community of Trieste began expressing its desire for a [[Serbian language|Serbian]]-language day school, a place for their children to be passed down Serbian culture and language. Jovan Miletic, a wealthy Serb merchant in Trieste, donated 24,000 florins to build a Serbian Elementary School in 1787. On July 1, 1792, the local government approved its opening and the \"Jovan Mileti\u0107\" private school began official operation, located in the city center, right beside the Saint Spyridon Church. A night school and reading room were opened in 1911.<ref name=\"Medakovic 1987\"/> In 1911 an asylum was added to the school, for Serbian political refugees, due to the constant warfare and bloodshed occurring between the [[Austro-Hungarian]] and [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] empires on the [[Balkan Peninsula]]. The school represented a pillar of the Serbian community of Trieste, where the children of the wealthy Serbian merchants went to school and integrated into the city's community. In 1973 the school was shut down due to lack of student enrollment and became a Sunday school for Serbian language and culture. Velimir Djerasimovi\u0107, the school's principal and teacher since 1927, retired in 1973. Djerasimovi\u0107 is the father of Italian film actors [[Ivan Rassimov]] and [[Rada Rassimov]].\n\n===Saint Spyridon Church===\n{{main|Saint Spyridon Church, Trieste}}\n[[File:Trieste Serb-orthodox church of San-Spiridione3.jpg|300px|thumbnail|right|The [[Saint Spyridon Church, Trieste|St. Spyridon Serbian Orthodox Church]]]]\nIn 1782 the [[Serbian Orthodox]] and [[Greek Orthodox]] communities of Trieste split due to major disagreements concerning church rituals and language-usage, at which point the Greek community built its own church, dedicated to [[Saint Nicholas]] in the [[Neoclassical architecture|neoclassical]] style, and the Serbs continued to use the original church of [[Saint Spyridon]]. In 1861 the Serb community demolished the original church, and rebuilt it in [[Serbo-Byzantine Revival]] style, in order to \"stamp their identity architecturally in the midst of a baroque Austro-Italian city\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neomagazine.com/2010_11_november/_hellenes.html|title=The Greeks of Trieste &#124; Neo Magazine|author=Alexander Billinis|accessdate=2014-06-11}}</ref> {{irrelevant citation|reason= Trieste is not a baroque city; article's author cites an unnamed person. |date=December 2014}} The church's construction was completed seven years later, in 1868. With the added capacity for 1600 worshippers, it was for a long time the second largest Serbian church in the world. {{citation needed|reason= This claim needs a reliable source by a historian of architecture.|date=December 2014}} The church is filled with liturgical masterpieces of the time, works in gold from the 17th and 18th centuries, antique Orthodox icons and handmade books, making it an important monument to Serbian history and culture.<ref name=\"peoplesaint\"/> The church was designed by Italian architect [[Carlo Maciachini]], featuring four cupolas and one large main dome adorned in an off-blue color. In the 1800s the Serbian population in Trieste numbered around 200 people.<ref name=\"Catalan 2011\">{{cite journal |last=Catalan |first=Tullia |date=October 2011 |title=The Ambivalence of a Port City: The Jews of Trieste from the 19th to the 20th century |journal=Quest. Issues in Contemporary Jewish History |url=http://www.quest-cdecjournal.it/focus.php?id=232}}</ref>\n\n===Under Fascist Rule===\nIn 1918, at the end of [[World War I]], Trieste became part of Italy and social life drastically changed for the Serbs and other minorities of Trieste. Due to the contentious national border with [[Slovenia]], Italian society became increasingly hostile towards all [[Slavs]] in Trieste including the Serbs, and anti-Slavic racism began to flourish in Italy.<ref name=\"Catalan 2011\"/> The anti-Slavic feelings in Trieste were present already before the War, embodied by the local Liberal-National Party, led by Giuseppe Cuzzi, whose aim was to make Trieste completely [[Catholic]] and Italian. The anti-Slavic propaganda focused on the idea that Slavic people were barbaric and could not integrate properly into a civilized society.<ref name=\"Catalan 2011\"/> Tensions came to a hilt in [[World War Two]], when the Germans, who had occupied Northern Italy in September 1943, built the only Nazi Extermination Camp in Italy, \"[[Risiera di San Sabba]]\", on the outskirts of Trieste. Three thousand Jews, Serbs and other Slavs were executed here in 1944 while thousands more were imprisoned awaiting transfer to other extermination camps.<ref>{{cite book |last=Poprzeczny|first=Joseph |authorlink=Joseph Poprzeczny|year=2004 |title=Odilo Globocnik Hitler's Man in the East}}</ref>\n\n===Monuments===\n[[File:Trieste-Canal Grande-DSCF1420.JPG|300px|thumbnail|right|The Palazzo Gopcevich]]\nBesides the Saint Spyridon Church and the Jovan Mileti\u0107 Serbian School, the Serbs of Trieste contributed to several other important landmarks of the city. The Gop\u010devi\u0107 family built the \"Palazzo Gopcevich\" on the Canal Grande, near the Serbian Church, in 1850 in commemoration to the heroes who fought for the [[Second Serbian Uprising|independence of Serbia from the Ottoman Empire]] (1814). Cristoforo Popovich owned many famous merchant ships in Trieste, some of the largest in the Adriatic: the \"Tartana\", \"Il Feroce Dalmata\", \"La Forza\" and the \"Ripatriato\", and was instrumental to the Russian-side in the Crimean War (1853-1856). Cristoforo Scuglievich (Skuljevic) built the Palazzo Scuglievich in the mid-1800s along the banks of the city, and donated the palace in his will to the Serbian community of Trieste; today it is owned by the Serb community.<ref name=\"Medakovi\u0107 1987\"/>\n\n===Serbian Writers===\nThe Serbian community of Trieste had a deep and long-lasting relationship with Serbian writers from the 18th century to today. Iconic [[Serbian literature|Serbian writers]] and linguists such as [[Vuk Karad\u017ei\u0107]], [[Dositej Obradovi\u0107]], [[Petar II Petrovi\u0107-Njego\u0161]], [[Zaharije Orfelin]] and [[Pavle Solari\u0107]] were inspired by Trieste and its developed Serbian community.<ref name=\"Gorup 2006\"/>  They wrote many works on Trieste's influence on Serbian \"pre-Romanticism\" and cultural development during a time when the Serbs lacked statehood and cultural expression. Serbian linguist and creator of the standardized Serbian language, [[Vuk Karad\u017ei\u0107]], kept in constant contact with Trieste's Serb community from his home in [[Vienna]]. In 1813 Vuk called upon the Triestan Serbs to subscribe to the Serbian-language newspaper, \"Novine Serbske\" promoting the newly standardized Serbian language, and more than sixty copies of the standard Serbian dictionary were bought in 1814.<ref name=\"Gorup 2006\"/> [[Lukijan Mu\u0161icki]] wrote an ode to Serbian merchants of Trieste in 1835, and revolutionary writer Dositej Obradovi\u0107 tutored the children of the wealthy Serb merchants.<ref name=\"Gorup 2006\"/> Many [[Serbian epic poetry|Serbian poets]] and folklorists {{Who|date=December 2014}} even worked in the Saint Spyridon Church for a time. An almost universal feeling of inspiration and admiration of Trieste's wealthy Serb community was shared by their Balkan-Serb contemporaries.{{Who|date=December 2014}}\n\n=== Modern Day ===\nToday, Serbian-born Serbs represent the largest foreign-born community in Trieste, numbering around 10,000, although some figures state anywhere up to 18,000.<ref name=\"ISTAT 2010\">http://www.demo.istat.it/str2010/index03_e.html</ref> The overwhelming majority of Serbs in Trieste today descend from the immigration wave following the [[Yugoslav Wars]] of the 90s. Recently the Serbian Orthodox Society in Trieste led by Bogoljub Stoji\u010devi\u0107 has called on the local government to grant the Serb Community of Trieste cultural autonomy and reinstate the [[Jovan Mileti\u0107]] Serbian school as a full-time school since it downgraded to a Sunday school due to inactivity in 1973.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.novosti.rs/vesti/planeta.301.html:312440-Trst-Srbi-traze-svoju-skolu|title=Serbs want their own school (In Serbian) |publisher=novosti.rs|accessdate=2014-06-10}}</ref> Since 2009 the Serbian community of Trieste, namely the Serbian Association \"Vuk Karadzic\", has been organizing an annual Balkan-style trumpet festival on the outskirts of Trieste called \"Guca na Krasu\" (Guca in [[Karst Plateau|Karst]]), modeled after the famous [[Gu\u010da Trumpet Festival]] in Serbia. Since its beginnings, the festival has managed to gain recognition and popularity, succeeding in getting famous musicians like [[Goran Bregovi\u0107]] and [[Boban Markovi\u0107]], as well as many popular Italian acts.<ref>{{cite book |last=Kunej |first=Drago |authorlink=Drago Kunej |year=2013 |title=Trapped in Folklore: Studies in Music and Dance Tradition and Their Contemporary Transformations|publisher=LIT Verlag}}</ref> The oldest active Serbian organization in Trieste is the soccer club \"Serbia Sport\",{{Dubious|reason= presumably, the oldest should be the Serbian Orthodox Community or Parish, not a football club from 1992|date=December 2014}} started in 1992, and since then has won a multitude of championships in the local Trieste soccer league, making it today one of the top soccer teams in the [[Province of Trieste]]. Together with the Serbian Association \"Vuk Karadzic\", Serbia Sport organizes an annual Serbian-Diaspora Soccer Tournament in Trieste on the Serbian holiday Spasovdan, which occurs 40 days after Easter.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radiobravo.net/home/42-vesti-radio-bravo/696-gua-na-krasu.html|title=Guca in Krast - Serbs, Slovenians and Italians in a Trance|author=Vasic, Slobodan|accessdate=2014-06-10}}</ref>\n\n==Organizations==\nThere are several community organizations of Serbs in Italy. The Association of Serbs of Italy was established in April 2015 by the combined organizations meeting in Trieste.<ref>{{cite web|title=Formiran Savez Srba Italije|work=Dijaspora|date=27 April 2015|publisher=Uprava za saradnju sa dijasporom i Srbima u regionu|url=http://www.dijaspora.gov.rs/lat/formiran-savez-srba-italije-2/}}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n\n; Nobility\n* [[Darinka Kveki\u0107]], wife of [[Danilo I, Prince of Montenegro]]\n* [[Natalija Konstantinovi\u0107]], wife of [[Prince Mirko of Montenegro]]\n\n;Artists\n*[[Marcello Dudovich]] was born in 1878 and died in 1962. He was one of the most acclaimed commercial artists of art, prints, and posters during his time.\n*[[Milan Zlokovi\u0107]], an architect born in Trieste\n\n;Writers\n*[[Ljudevit Vuli\u010devi\u0107]]\n*[[Dositej Obradovi\u0107]]\n*[[Aleksa \u0160anti\u0107]]\n*[[Petar II Petrovi\u0107-Njego\u0161]]\n*[[Stefano Zannowich]]\n*[[Tomo Medin]] \n\n;Printers\n*[[Bo\u017eidar Vukovi\u0107]]\n*[[Vi\u0107enco Vukovi\u0107]]\n\n;Business people\n*[[Spiridione Gopcevich]], a shipowner from Trieste\n*[[Jovo Kurtovi\u0107]], a shipowner from Trieste\n\n;Singers\n*[[Sara Jovanovi\u0107]] (born 1993), Serbian singer born in Rome that represented Serbia at Eurovision Song Contest 2008\n\n;Doctors\n*[[Dimitrije Fru\u0161i\u0107]]\n\n;Teachers\n*[[Dositej Obradovi\u0107]]\n\n;Scientists\n* [[Spiridon Gop\u010devi\u0107]]\n\n;TV and cinema\n*[[Nina Seni\u010dar]] (born 1985), model and actress, lives in Italy since 2006\n*[[Sasha Montenegro]] (born 1945), actress born in Bari as Aleksandra Acimovi\u0107 Popovi\u0107\n*[[Ivan Rassimov]] (1938\u20132003), late actor born in Trieste to Serbian parents as Ivan Djerasimovi\u0107; brother of [[Rada Rassimov]]. \n*[[Rada Rassimov]] (born 1941), actress born in Trieste to Serbian parents as Rada Djerasimovi\u0107; sister of [[Ivan Rassimov]].\n*[[Olga Bisera]], actress born Bisera [[Vukoti\u0107]]. \n\n;Sportspeople\n*[[Giovanni Raicevich]] was a famous Italian wrestler in the early 20th century. \n*[[Milo\u0161 Malivojevi\u0107]] (born 1993), active footballer born in Scandiano, [[Reggio Emilia]] \n*[[Marino Nicolich]] (born 1910), late footballer born in Monfalcone, whose name was italianized in \"Marino Nicoli\" by the Italian Fascist government.\n*[[Dragan Travica]] (born 1986), volleyball player born in Croatia, son of the Serbian coach [[Ljubomir Travica]]; plays for the Italian national team \n*[[Ljubomir Travica]] (born 1954), volleyball coach and retired player; has residence in Italy since he played for [[Modena]] in 1983. He is the father of [[Dragan Travica]]\n*[[Marko Stanojevic]] (born 1979), rugby union player born in Birmingham to a Serbian father and an Italian mother. He played for the Italian national team.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Serbian diaspora]]\n*[[Serbs]]\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite web|title=Svetionik (Srbi u Italiji)|url=http://www.svetionik.it/}} (Community page) {{in lang|sr|it}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110303004647/http://www.europeandevelopmentcentre.eu/ European Development centre] (Serbian Diaspora in Italy)\n*{{Citation |last=Mihajlovi\u0107 |first=Miodrag |script-title=sr:\u0421\u0440\u043f\u0441\u043a\u0430 \u043d\u0430\u0441\u0435\u0459\u0430 \u043d\u0430 \u0458\u0443\u0433\u0443 \u0418\u0442\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0458\u0435 \u2014 \u0421\u043a\u0430\u0432\u0443\u043d\u0438 \u0438 \u045a\u0438\u0445\u043e\u0432\u0435 \u0438\u0437\u0432\u043e\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0435 \u0432\u0438\u043b\u0435 |trans-title=Serbian settlements in Southern Italy \u2014 Schiavoni and their spring fairies |url= http://www.srpsko-nasledje.rs/sr-c/1998/03/article-17.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.srpsko-nasledje.rs%2Fsr-c%2F1998%2F03%2Farticle-17.html&date=2012-09-10 |archivedate= 10 September 2012 |accessdate= |edition= |series= Srpsko Nasle\u0111e, Istorijske sveske |volume=3 |date= March 1998|origyear= |publisher= Preduze\u0107e za novinsko izdava\u010dku delatnost glas |location= Belgrade |language= Serbian |isbn= |oclc=40132319 }}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{in lang|sr}} [http://www.svetionik.it/ Northern Italy's Serbian community website]\n* {{in lang|sr}} [http://italia.rastko.net/ Historical documents on the Serbs of Italy]\n\n{{Serbian diaspora}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Serbs In Italy}}\n[[Category:Italian people of Serbian descent]]\n[[Category:Serbian diaspora in Europe]]\n[[Category:Serbian Orthodox Church in Italy]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Italy]]\n", "name_user": "WorldlyVoice", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNotable people", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Serbs_in_Italy"}
{"title_page": "Amar pelos dois", "text_new": "{{short description|2017 song by Salvador Sobral}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name          = Amar pelos dois\n| cover         = Salvador Sobral - Amar pelos dois.jpg\n| alt           =\n| type          = single\n| artist        = [[Salvador Sobral]]\n| album         =\n| language      = Portuguese\n| English_title = \"To Love for the Both of Us\"\n| released      = {{start date|2017|3|10|df=yes}}\n| format        = {{hlist|[[CD single]]|[[Music download|digital download]]|[[Streaming media|streaming]]}}\n| recorded      =\n| studio        =\n| venue         =\n| genre         = {{hlist|[[Waltz_(music)#Jazz_waltzes|Jazz waltz]]|[[baroque pop]]|[[bossa nova]]}}\n| length        = 3:05\n| label         = Sons em Tr\u00e2nsito\n| writer        = {{Hlist|[[Lu\u00edsa Sobral]]}}\n| producer      = Lu\u00edsa Sobral\n| prev_title    = [[Nem Eu]]\n| prev_year     = 2016\n| next_title    = [[Mano a Mano (song)|Mano a Mano]]\n| next_year     = 2018\n| misc          = {{Infobox song contest entry\n| embed        = yes\n| song         = {{flagicon|Portugal}} \"Amar pelos dois\"\n| year         = 2017\n| country      = Portugal\n| artist       = [[Salvador Sobral]]\n| language     = Portuguese\n| composer     = [[Lu\u00edsa Sobral]]\n| lyricist     = Lu\u00edsa Sobral\n| place        = 1st\n| points       = 758\n| place_semi   = 1st\n| points_semi  = 370\n| prev         = H\u00e1 um mar que nos separa\n| prev_year    = 2015\n| prev_link    = H\u00e1 um mar que nos separa\n| next         = O jardim\n| next_year    = 2018\n| next_link    = O jardim\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Amar pelos dois'''\" ({{IPA-pt|\u0250\u02c8ma\u027e \u02c8p(\u0268)lu\u0283 \u02c8doj\u0283}}; English: To Love for the Both of Us) is a song performed by Portuguese singer [[Salvador Sobral]]. The track was written and produced by [[Lu\u00edsa Sobral]]. It premiered on 19 February 2017, when it was performed during the first semi-final of [[Festival da Can\u00e7\u00e3o|Festival da Can\u00e7\u00e3o 2017]], Portugal's national selection for the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2017]]. It was released as a [[Music download|digital download]] on 10 March 2017 by Sons em Tr\u00e2nsito. \n\n\"Amar pelos dois\" is a [[Waltz_(music)#Jazz_waltzes|jazz waltz]] with a lyrical theme of [[broken heart|heartbreak]] after a [[breakup]]. The track received praise from [[Music journalism|music critics]] \u2013 some reviewers considered it Portugal's all-time best Eurovision entry. The song earned the Sobral siblings various awards, including two [[Marcel Bezen\u00e7on Awards]]. It was included in the [[European Union]] Songbook as the all-time top Portuguese [[love song]], and was covered by several artists. The song achieved [[Record chart|commercial success]], particularly in [[Europe]].\n\n\"Amar pelos dois\" represented {{Esccnty|Portugal}} in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017 in [[Kiev]], Ukraine. The song gave Portugal its first ever win since their debut in {{Escyr|1964}}. It amassed 758 points, setting the record for the highest number of points in the history of the [[Eurovision Song Contest|competition]], and is the only entry to top both the televoting and jury voting in the second half of the [[2010s]]. Salvador Sobral performed alone on stage B, close to the audience, while the background [[LED display|LED screens]] displayed an [[enchanted forest]].\n\n== Background and release==\n{{Quote box|width=25%|align=left|bgcolor=#c6dbf7|quote=\"I wanted to write a song that represents me, that could be on a record of mine, a song that I could be proud of and that's what I did.\"<ref name=\"eurovision.tv\">{{cite web|url=https://eurovision.tv/story/salvador-sobral-has-love-enough-for-portugal-and-europe|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20171126203452/https://eurovision.tv/story/salvador-sobral-has-love-enough-for-portugal-and-europe|website=eurovision.tv|title=Salvador Sobral has love enough for Portugal and Europe|publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]]|last=M. Escudero|first=Victor|date=March 6, 2017|archivedate=November 26, 2017}}</ref>|source=\u2014Lu\u00edsa Sobral, composer of \"Amar pelos dois\"}}\n\"Amar pelos dois\" was one of sixteen songs commissioned by [[R\u00e1dio e Televis\u00e3o de Portugal|RTP]] for [[Festival da Can\u00e7\u00e3o|Festival da Can\u00e7\u00e3o 2017]], Portugal's national selection for the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2017]]. The composers both created the song and selected the performer for their entry. Lu\u00edsa Sobral composed \"Amar pelos dois\" specifically for her brother, Salvador Sobral: \"I never thought about singing this song myself because when I wrote it I already had my brother's voice in mind. I was very fond of seeing him playing my song, because I think he is an extraordinary singer and because it gives me great joy to see him at the song contest and also that it turned out to be a family thing\".<ref name=\"eurovision.tv\"/> Salvador Sobral stated that even though \"Amar pelos dois\" was created by his sister Lu\u00edsa, she gave him freedom to perform the song according to his artistic personality.<ref name=\"eurovision.tv\"/>\n\n\"Amar pelos dois\" premiered on 19 February 2017, when it was performed in [[Festival da Can\u00e7\u00e3o|Festival da Can\u00e7\u00e3o 2017]], Portugal's national selection for the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2017]]. The song became available through [[Music download|digital]] retailers and [[Streaming media|streaming]] services on 10 March 2017 via Sons em Tr\u00e2nsito.<ref name=\"iTunes\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/pt/album/amar-pelos-dois-single/id1213997535|title=Amar pelos dois - Single|website=[[iTunes Store]]|accessdate=10 March 2017}}</ref> On 16 June 2017, it was released on [[CD single|physical format]] via [[Sony Music]].<ref name=\"CD single\">{{cite web|url=http://media.rtp.pt/festivaldacancao/artigos/cd-single-amar-pelos-dois-lancado-16-junho/|title=CD Single \u201cAmar Pelos Dois\u201d \u00e9 lan\u00e7ado a 16 de junho|website=[[R\u00e1dio e Televis\u00e3o de Portugal|RTP]]|language=pt|accessdate=December 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Composition ==\n\"Amar pelos dois\" was written and produced by Lu\u00edsa Sobral, Salvador Sobral's sister. \"Amar pelos dois\" is a [[Waltz_(music)#Jazz_waltzes|jazz waltz]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.vaterland.li/kultur/news/Aus-fuer-die-Schweiz-am-Song-Contest;art106,268718|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170706234812/http://www.vaterland.li/kultur/news/Aus-fuer-die-Schweiz-am-Song-Contest;art106,268718|title=Aus f\u00fcr die Schweiz am Song Contest|work=[[Liechtensteiner Vaterland]]|publisher=Vaduzer Medienhaus AG|date=May 11, 2017|archivedate=July 6, 2017|language=de}}</ref> with a length of three minutes and five seconds (3:05)<ref name=\"iTunes\"/> that moves at a [[tempo]] of 92 beats per minute.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://escnation.com/news/?id=1240|title=Ballad or up-tempo? Let's take a look at the actual tempo of this year's entries|publisher=ESC Nation|author=Jonas|date=March 21, 2017}}</ref> The song is composed in the [[Key (music)|key]] of [[F major]] and is written in [[triple metre]], with Sobral's vocals spanning from D<sub>4</sub> to G<sub>5</sub>.<ref>{{cite web|last=Sobral|first=Salvador|title=Amar Pelos Dois By Salvador Sobral - Digital Sheet Music|url=http://www.musicnotes.com/sheetmusic/mtd.asp?ppn=MN0174501|website=Musicnotes.com|publisher=[[Sony/ATV Music Publishing]]|accessdate=June 16, 2017}}</ref> Without [[Backing vocalist|background vocals]], it has an [[Instrumentation (music)|instrumentation]] consisting of [[Violin family|strings]] and [[piano]]. Salvador Sobral stated that \"Amar pelos dois\" is \"influenced by those old songs from the [[Great American Songbook]], and it also has a touch of the beautiful [[bossa nova]] melodies\".<ref name=\"ESC Bubble\">{{cite web|url=http://escbubble.com/2017/02/salvador-sobral-amar-pelos-dois-love-song-sad-one/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170403215105/http://escbubble.com/2017/02/salvador-sobral-amar-pelos-dois-love-song-sad-one/ |title=Salvador Sobral: \"Amar pelos dois\" is a love song. A sad one. |publisher=ESC Bubble |author=Juh\u00e1sz, Ervin |date=February 16, 2017 |archivedate=April 3, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The song's lyrical theme is [[broken heart|heartbreak]] after a [[breakup]]:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wiwibloggs.com/2017/03/18/amar-pelos-dois-lyrics-salvador-sobral-portugal-eurovision-2017/181079/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170323164438/http://wiwibloggs.com/2017/03/18/amar-pelos-dois-lyrics-salvador-sobral-portugal-eurovision-2017/181079/ |title=\u201cAmar pelos dois\u201d lyrics \u2014 Salvador Sobral (Portugal, Eurovision 2017) |website=[[Wiwibloggs]] |date=March 18, 2017 |archivedate=March 23, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> \"Meu bem / Ouve as minhas preces / Pe\u00e7o que regresses / Que me voltes a querer\".{{refn|group=nb|In English translation: \"My love / Listen to my pleas / I beg you to come back / To want me again\".}} Sobral described it as \"a [[love song]]. A sad one\".<ref name=\"ESC Bubble\"/>\n\n== At Eurovision ==\n{{Main article|Portugal in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017}}\n=== National selection ===\nLu\u00edsa Sobral was announced as a participating songwriter in [[Festival da Can\u00e7\u00e3o|Festival da Can\u00e7\u00e3o 2017]], Portugal's national selection for the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2017]], on 5 December 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://esctoday.com/138971/portugal-three-shows-festival-da-cancao-2017-final-5-march|title=Portugal: Three shows for Festival da Can\u00e7\u00e3o 2017; final on 5 March|publisher=ESCToday|last=Jiandani|first=Sanjay|date=5 December 2016|accessdate=6 December 2016}}</ref> On 18 January 2017, her brother, Salvador Sobral, was announced to be performing her song, titled \"Amar pelos dois\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://media.rtp.pt/festivaldacancao/artigos/conheca-os-interpretes-da-1-semifinal-do-festival-da-cancao-2017/|title=Conhe\u00e7a os int\u00e9rpretes da 1.\u00aa Semifinal do Festival da Can\u00e7\u00e3o 2017|work=RTP.pt|accessdate=18 January 2017|language=pt|date=18 January 2017}}</ref> After being sent two songs by Lu\u00edsa Sobral, written for the competition, Salvador Sobral selected \"Amar pelos dois\" as the song he would like to perform. Lu\u00eds Figueiredo, who did the string arrangement, also chose \"Amar pelos dois\" as the song to go through the competition's various phases. Sobral competed in the first semi-final on February 19, placing second with 20 points after winning the jury vote and coming third in the televote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wiwibloggs.com/2017/02/19/portugal-festival-da-cancao-semi-final-qualifiers/175666/|title=PORTUGAL: VIVA LA DIVA AND FERNANDO DANIEL AMONG QUALIFIERS IN FIRST SEMI-FINAL OF FESTIVAL DA CAN\u00c7\u00c3O 2017|date=19 February 2017|publisher=Wiwibloggs|website=wiwibloggs.com|last=Fuster|first=Luis}}</ref> In the final, held on 5 March, he won the jury vote and came second in the televote, placing first with 22 points and thus representing Portugal at the Eurovision Song Contest 2017.<ref name=\"win\">{{cite web|url=http://wiwibloggs.com/2017/03/06/portugal-salvador-sobral-wins-festival-da-cancao-2017/179145/|title=Portugal: Salvador Sobral wins Festival da Can\u00e7\u00e3o 2017 with \"Amar pelos dois\"|last=Foster|first=Luis|date=6 March 2017|publisher=Wiwibloggs|website=wiwibloggs.com}}</ref><ref name=\"Mercereau\">{{cite news|last1=Mercereau|first1=Damien|title=Eurovision 2017 : le Portugal de retour avec Salvador Sobral|url=http://tvmag.lefigaro.fr/programme-tv/eurovision-2017-le-portugal-de-retour-avec-salvador-sobral_1cb2ee44-0259-11e7-aad0-d9371b2c396c/|accessdate=16 March 2017|newspaper=Le Figaro|date=6 March 2017|language=fr}}</ref>\n\n=== In Kiev ===\n[[File:Salvador Sobral (Eurovision 2017).jpg|thumb|Sobral performing \"Amar pelos dois\" during a dress rehearsal for the contest.]]\nThe [[Eurovision Song Contest 2017]] took place at the [[International Exhibition Centre]] in [[Kiev]], Ukraine and consisted of two semi-finals on 9 and 11 May, and the final on 13 May 2017. Portugal was drawn to compete in the first half of the first semi-final.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eurovision.tv/story/results-of-the-semi-final-allocation-draw |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170515142127/https://eurovision.tv/story/results-of-the-semi-final-allocation-draw |website=eurovision.tv |title=Results of the Semi-Final Allocation Draw |publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]] |last1=Jordan |first1=Paul |last2=Nilsson |first2=Helena |date=January 31, 2017 |archivedate=May 15, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The running order for the semi-finals was decided by the producers, in order to avoid similar songs being placed next to each other. Portugal was set to perform in position 9, following the entry from {{Esccnty|Azerbaijan|y=2017}} and before the entry from {{Esccnty|Greece|y=2017}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eurovision.tv/story/running-order-eurovision-2017-revealed |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170612000755/https://eurovision.tv/story/running-order-eurovision-2017-revealed |title=Semi-Final running order for Eurovision 2017 revealed |website=eurovision.tv |publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]] |last=Jordan |first=Paul |date=March 31, 2017 |archivedate=June 12, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> For the grand final, Portugal was drawn to compete in the first half. Portugal was subsequently placed to perform in position 11 by the producers, following the entry from {{Esccnty|Denmark|y=2017}} and before the entry from Azerbaijan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eurovision.tv/story/running-order-grand-final-2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170512103306/https://eurovision.tv/story/running-order-grand-final-2017 |title=EXCLUSIVE: Running order for the 2017 Grand Final released! |website=eurovision.tv |publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]] |last1=Jordan |first1=Paul |last2=Nilsson |first2=Helena |date=May 11, 2017 |archivedate=May 12, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Salvador Sobral was one of the favorites to win the contest according to [[Bookmaker|bookmakers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvi24.iol.pt/musica/festival-da-cancao/salvador-sobral-ja-e-primeiro-nas-apostas-para-ganhar-eurovisao|title=Salvador Sobral j\u00e1 \u00e9 primeiro nas apostas para ganhar Eurovis\u00e3o|website=[[TVI 24]]|date=May 12, 2017|language=pt}}</ref> With its tool The Eurosearch Song Contest, [[Google]] correctly predicted Sobral's victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://googletrends.github.io/eurosearch-song-contest/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180511013245/https://googletrends.github.io/eurosearch-song-contest/|title=The Eurosearch Song Contest|website=[[Google]]|archivedate=May 11, 2018}}</ref> For the winner's encore, siblings Salvador and Lu\u00edsa sang the song as a duet, just like they did in the national final.\n\nFor his performance, Salvador Sobral wore a black suit and performed alone on stage B, close to the audience. During the performance, the background [[LED display|LED screens]] displays an [[enchanted forest]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.escportugal.pt/2017/05/esc2017-as-reacoes-ao-segundo-ensaio-de.html|title=ESC2017: As rea\u00e7\u00f5es ao segundo ensaio de Portugal|website=ESC Portugal|date=May 4, 2017|language=pt}}</ref> \n\nSalvador Sobral's victory was hailed in Portugal by the [[Assembly of the Republic (Portugal)|Assembly of the Republic]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.escportugal.pt/2017/05/parlamento-de-pe-para-aplaudir-salvador.html|title=[V\u00cdDEO] Parlamento de p\u00e9 para aplaudir Salvador e Lu\u00edsa Sobral|website=ESC Portugal|date=May 19, 2017|language=pt}}</ref> [[Prime Minister of Portugal|Prime Minister]] [[Ant\u00f3nio Costa]],<ref>{{cite tweet|user=antoniocostapm|number=863525180861231104|date=May 13, 2017|title=Fez-se hist\u00f3ria em portugu\u00eas hoje na #Eurovis\u00e3o! Parab\u00e9ns Salvador! Parab\u00e9ns Portugal! #Eurovision}}</ref> [[Ministry of Culture (Portugal)|Minister of Culture]] [[Lu\u00eds Filipe Castro Mendes]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.escportugal.pt/2017/05/portugal-ministro-da-cultura-diz-que.html|title=Portugal: Ministro da Cultura diz que vit\u00f3ria na Eurovis\u00e3o \u00e9 prova da criatividade lusa |website=ESC Portugal|date=May 15, 2017|language=pt}}</ref> and [[President of Portugal|President]] [[Marcelo Rebelo de Sousa]] who distinguished the Sobral siblings with the [[Order of Merit (Portugal)|Order of Merit]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.publico.pt/2018/04/23/culturaipsilon/noticia/luisa-e-salvador-sobral-nomeados-comendadores-pelo-exito-singular-1811456|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180818140027/https://www.publico.pt/2018/04/23/culturaipsilon/noticia/luisa-e-salvador-sobral-nomeados-comendadores-pelo-exito-singular-1811456|title=Irm\u00e3os Sobral nomeados comendadores por \"\u00eaxito singular\"|work=[[P\u00fablico (Portugal)|P\u00fablico]]|date=April 23, 2018|archivedate=August 18, 2018|language=pt}}</ref>\n\n==== Record-breaking victory ====\nBy earning 758 points overall in the grand final, \"Amar pelos dois\" became the highest-scoring entry in the history of the [[Eurovision Song Contest]], overtaking {{Esccnty|Ukraine|y=2016}}'s \"[[1944 (song)|1944]]\" which had scored 534 points the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2016|year before]]. \"Amar pelos dois\" is the only entry to top both the televoting and jury voting in the second half of the [[2010s]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Eurovision 2017 Results: Voting & Points |url=http://eurovisionworld.com/?eurovision=2017 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20170616021651/http://eurovisionworld.com/?eurovision=2017 |website=Eurovision World |accessdate=June 16, 2017 |archivedate=June 16, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In the grand final, \"Amar pelos dois\" received at least five televote points from every participating country.<ref name=Scoreboard/> It is the first winning song entirely performed in a country's native language since {{Esccnty|Serbia|y=2007}}'s \"[[Molitva]]\" ({{Escyr|2007}}) and the first winning song written in [[triple metre]] since {{Esccnty|Ireland|y=1996}}'s \"[[The Voice (Eimear Quinn song)|The Voice]]\" ({{Escyr|1996}}). With 382 points awarded by the national juries, \"Amar pelos dois\" broke the record of most jury points ever, beating {{Esccnty|Sweden|y=2015}}'s \"[[Heroes (M\u00e5ns Zelmerl\u00f6w song)|Heroes]]\" which received 353 points from the juries in {{Escyr|2015}}.<ref name=\"Scoreboard\"/> Additionally, Portugal achieved the biggest winning margin of the decade and the second biggest of all time, scoring 143 more points than the [[Bulgaria in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|runners-up]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eurovision.tv/event/kyiv-2017/grand-final/participants |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170515092839/https://eurovision.tv/event/kyiv-2017/grand-final/participants |title=Grand Final Participants |website=eurovision.tv |publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]] |accessdate=June 12, 2017 |archivedate=May 15, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nUnder the [[Voting at the Eurovision Song Contest#Voting systems|previous voting system]], \"Amar pelos dois\" would have scored 417 points, surpassing {{Esccnty|Norway|y=2009}}'s \"[[Fairytale (Alexander Rybak song)|Fairytale]]\" which scored 387 points in {{Escyr|2009}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.escxtra.com/2017/05/14/eurovision-2017-old-voting/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170612015618/https://www.escxtra.com/2017/05/14/eurovision-2017-old-voting/ |title=An Alternate Universe: Eurovision 2017 Under the Old Voting System |website=escXtra |date=May 14, 2017 |archivedate=June 12, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Also under the previous voting system, \"Amar pelos dois\" would have received a record of twenty combined sets of 12 points (televote + jury vote), overcoming the eighteen maximum scores collected by {{Esccnty|Sweden|y=2012}}'s \"[[Euphoria (Loreen song)|Euphoria]]\" in {{Escyr|2012}}. Thus, from a combined vote perspective, Portugal received 12 points from Armenia, Austria, Belgium, Czech Republic, Estonia, Finland, France, Germany, Iceland, Israel, Lithuania, the Netherlands, Norway, San Marino, Slovenia, Spain, Sweden, Switzerland, Ukraine and the United Kingdom.<ref name=\"Classic voting\">{{cite web|url=https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1-sT2lLmqv-40THcOUbT6pFc7YZm8g9bAhzLx8kkyiCM/edit#gid=31282450|title=Eurovision 2017 Old Voting||publisher=escXtra|accessdate=June 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==== Points awarded to Portugal ====\n{{multiple image\n<!--image 1-->\n | image1            = ESC2017 Televote Portugal.svg\n | caption1          = Points awarded to Portugal by each national televote\n<!--image 2-->\n | image2            = ESC2017 Jury Portugal.svg\n | caption2          = Points awarded to Portugal by each national jury\n}}\nBelow is a breakdown of points awarded to Portugal in the first semi-final and grand final of the contest, and the breakdown of the televoting and jury voting conducted during the two shows. The country finished in first place on both occasions. In the semi-final, Portugal was ranked first with 370 points overall, garnering 197 from the televote and 173 from the jury vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eurovision.tv/story/exclusive-results-semi-finals-2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170522215347/https://eurovision.tv/story/exclusive-results-semi-finals-2017 |title=EXCLUSIVE: Here are the results of the Semi-Finals! |website=eurovision.tv |publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]] |last=Jordan |first=Paul |date=May 13, 2017 |archivedate=May 22, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Portugal received 12 points from the televoters in [[Albania in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Albania]], [[Belgium in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Belgium]], [[Finland in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Finland]], [[Iceland in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Iceland]], [[Latvia in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Latvia]], [[Poland in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Poland]], [[Slovenia in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Slovenia]], [[Spain in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Spain]] and [[Sweden in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Sweden]], and received 12 points from the juries of [[Azerbaijan in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Azerbaijan]], [[Georgia in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Georgia]], Iceland, Latvia, [[Moldova in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Moldova]], Poland and Spain.<ref>{{cite web|title=Portugal - First Semi-Final Scoreboard |url=https://eurovision.tv/event/kyiv-2017/first-semi-final/scoreboard/portugal |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170612001437/https://eurovision.tv/event/kyiv-2017/first-semi-final/scoreboard/portugal |website=eurovision.tv |publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]] |accessdate=June 12, 2017 |archivedate=June 12, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In the end, Portugal won the contest with 758 points overall; 376 from the televote and 382 from the jury vote. In the grand final, Portugal earned a total of thirty sets of 12 points. The country received maximum scores from the televoters in [[Austria in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Austria]], Belgium, Finland, [[France in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|France]], [[Germany in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Germany]], Iceland, [[Israel in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Israel]], [[Lithuania in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Lithuania]], the [[Netherlands in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Netherlands]], [[Norway in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Norway]], Spain and [[Switzerland in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Switzerland]], and received top marks from the juries of [[Armenia in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Armenia]], [[Czech Republic in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Czech Republic]], France, Georgia, [[Hungary in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Hungary]], Iceland, Israel, Latvia, Lithuania, the Netherlands, Poland, [[San Marino in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|San Marino]], [[Serbia in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Serbia]], Slovenia, Spain, Sweden, Switzerland and the [[United Kingdom in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|United Kingdom]].<ref name=Scoreboard>{{cite web|title=Portugal - 2017 Grand Final Scoreboard|url=https://eurovision.tv/event/kyiv-2017/grand-final/scoreboard/portugal |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20170612002917/https://eurovision.tv/event/kyiv-2017/grand-final/scoreboard/portugal |website=eurovision.tv |publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]] |accessdate=June 12, 2017 |archivedate=June 12, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed\"\n|-\n!colspan=\"5\"| Points awarded to Portugal (Semi-final 1)\n|-\n!colspan=\"5\"| Televote\n|-\n!width=20%|12 points\n!width=20%|10 points\n!width=20%|8 points\n!width=20%|7 points\n!width=20%|6 points\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*{{Esc|Albania|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Belgium|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Finland|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Iceland|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Latvia|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Poland|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Slovenia|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Spain|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Sweden|y=2017}}\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*{{Esc|Australia|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Greece|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Italy|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|United Kingdom|y=2017}}\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*{{Esc|Azerbaijan|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Georgia|y=2017}}\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*{{Esc|Armenia|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Czech Republic|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Montenegro|y=2017}}\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*{{Esc|Cyprus|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Moldova|y=2017}}\n|-\n!width=20%|5 points\n!width=20%|4 points\n!width=20%|3 points\n!width=20%|2 points\n!width=20%|1 point\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |\n| valign=\"top\" |\n| valign=\"top\" |\n| valign=\"top\" |\n| valign=\"top\" |\n|-\n!colspan=\"5\"| Jury\n|-\n!width=20%|12 points\n!width=20%|10 points\n!width=20%|8 points\n!width=20%|7 points\n!width=20%|6 points\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*{{Esc|Azerbaijan|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Georgia|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Iceland|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Latvia|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Moldova|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Poland|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Spain|y=2017}}\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*{{Esc|Cyprus|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Finland|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|United Kingdom|y=2017}}\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*{{Esc|Slovenia|y=2017}}\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*{{Esc|Armenia|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Belgium|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Czech Republic|y=2017}}\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*{{Esc|Albania|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Australia|y=2017}}\n|-\n!width=20%|5 points\n!width=20%|4 points\n!width=20%|3 points\n!width=20%|2 points\n!width=20%|1 point\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*{{Esc|Greece|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Sweden|y=2017}}\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*{{Esc|Italy|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Montenegro|y=2017}}\n| valign=\"top\" |\n| valign=\"top\" |\n| valign=\"top\" |\n|-\n!colspan=\"5\"| 50/50<ref name=\"Classic voting\"/>\n|-\n!width=20%|12 points\n!width=20%|10 points\n!width=20%|8 points\n!width=20%|7 points\n!width=20%|6 points\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |\n* {{Esc|Azerbaijan|y=2017}}\n* {{Esc|Belgium|y=2017}}\n* {{Esc|Finland|y=2017}}\n* {{Esc|Iceland|y=2017}}\n* {{Esc|Latvia|y=2017}}\n* {{Esc|Moldova|y=2017}}\n* {{Esc|Poland|y=2017}}\n* {{Esc|Slovenia|y=2017}}\n* {{Esc|Spain|y=2017}}\n* {{Esc|Sweden|y=2017}}\n* {{Esc|United Kingdom|y=2017}}\n| valign=\"top\" |\n* {{Esc|Albania|y=2017}}\n* {{Esc|Cyprus|y=2017}}\n* {{Esc|Georgia|y=2017}}\n| valign=\"top\" |\n* {{Esc|Australia|y=2017}}\n* {{Esc|Greece|y=2017}}\n* {{Esc|Italy|y=2017}}\n| valign=\"top\" |\n* {{Esc|Armenia|y=2017}}\n* {{Esc|Czech Republic|y=2017}}\n| valign=\"top\" |\n* {{Esc|Montenegro|y=2017}}\n|-\n!width=20%|5 points\n!width=20%|4 points\n!width=20%|3 points\n!width=20%|2 points\n!width=20%|1 point\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |\n| valign=\"top\" |\n| valign=\"top\" |\n| valign=\"top\" |\n| valign=\"top\" |\n|-\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed\"\n|-\n!colspan=\"5\"| Points awarded to Portugal (Final)\n|-\n!colspan=\"5\"| Televote\n|-\n!width=20%|12 points\n!width=20%|10 points\n!width=20%|8 points\n!width=20%|7 points\n!width=20%|6 points\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*{{Esc|Austria|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Belgium|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Finland|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|France|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Germany|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Iceland|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Israel|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Lithuania|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Netherlands|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Norway|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Spain|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Switzerland|y=2017}}\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*{{Esc|Armenia|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Croatia|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Estonia|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Ireland|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Latvia|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Poland|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Sweden|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Ukraine|y=2017}}\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*{{Esc|Albania|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Azerbaijan|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Czech Republic|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Georgia|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Greece|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Malta|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Montenegro|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Serbia|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Slovenia|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|United Kingdom|y=2017}}\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*{{Esc|Australia|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Belarus|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Bulgaria|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Cyprus|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Hungary|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Macedonia|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Romania|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|San Marino|y=2017}}\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*{{Esc|Moldova|y=2017}}\n|-\n!width=20%|5 points\n!width=20%|4 points\n!width=20%|3 points\n!width=20%|2 points\n!width=20%|1 point\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*{{Esc|Denmark|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Italy|y=2017}}\n| valign=\"top\" |\n| valign=\"top\" |\n| valign=\"top\" |\n| valign=\"top\" |\n|-\n!colspan=\"5\"| Jury\n|-\n!width=20%|12 points\n!width=20%|10 points\n!width=20%|8 points\n!width=20%|7 points\n!width=20%|6 points\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*{{Esc|Armenia|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Czech Republic|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|France|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Georgia|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Hungary|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Iceland|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Israel|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Latvia|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Lithuania|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Netherlands|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Poland|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|San Marino|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Serbia|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Slovenia|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Spain|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Sweden|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Switzerland|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|United Kingdom|y=2017}}\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*{{Esc|Belarus|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Denmark|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Germany|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Macedonia|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Malta|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Norway|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Ukraine|y=2017}}\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*{{Esc|Austria|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Azerbaijan|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Belgium|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Cyprus|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Estonia|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Finland|y=2017}}\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*{{Esc|Australia|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Croatia|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Moldova|y=2017}}\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*{{Esc|Albania|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Romania|y=2017}}\n|-\n!width=20%|5 points\n!width=20%|4 points\n!width=20%|3 points\n!width=20%|2 points\n!width=20%|1 point\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*{{Esc|Greece|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Ireland|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Italy|y=2017}}\n| valign=\"top\" |\n| valign=\"top\" |\n| valign=\"top\" |\n| valign=\"top\" |\n|-\n!colspan=\"5\"| 50/50<ref name=\"Classic voting\"/>\n|-\n!width=20%|12 points\n!width=20%|10 points\n!width=20%|8 points\n!width=20%|7 points\n!width=20%|6 points\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |\n* {{Esc|Armenia|y=2017}}\n* {{Esc|Austria|y=2017}}\n* {{Esc|Belgium|y=2017}}\n* {{Esc|Czech Republic|y=2017}}\n* {{Esc|Estonia|y=2017}}\n* {{Esc|Finland|y=2017}}\n* {{Esc|France|y=2017}}\n* {{Esc|Germany|y=2017}}\n* {{Esc|Iceland|y=2017}}\n* {{Esc|Israel|y=2017}}\n* {{Esc|Lithuania|y=2017}}\n* {{Esc|Netherlands|y=2017}}\n* {{Esc|Norway|y=2017}}\n* {{Esc|San Marino|y=2017}}\n* {{Esc|Slovenia|y=2017}}\n* {{Esc|Spain|y=2017}}\n* {{Esc|Sweden|y=2017}}\n* {{Esc|Switzerland|y=2017}}\n* {{Esc|Ukraine|y=2017}}\n* {{Esc|United Kingdom|y=2017}}\n| valign=\"top\" |\n* {{Esc|Australia|y=2017}}\n* {{Esc|Azerbaijan|y=2017}}\n* {{Esc|Belarus|y=2017}}\n* {{Esc|Denmark|y=2017}}\n* {{Esc|Georgia|y=2017}}\n* {{Esc|Greece|y=2017}}\n* {{Esc|Hungary|y=2017}}\n* {{Esc|Latvia|y=2017}}\n* {{Esc|Macedonia|y=2017}}\n* {{Esc|Poland|y=2017}}\n* {{Esc|Serbia|y=2017}}\n| valign=\"top\" |\n* {{Esc|Albania|y=2017}}\n* {{Esc|Croatia|y=2017}}\n* {{Esc|Italy|y=2017}}\n* {{Esc|Malta|y=2017}}\n* {{Esc|Romania|y=2017}}\n| valign=\"top\" |\n* {{Esc|Cyprus|y=2017}}\n* {{Esc|Ireland|y=2017}}\n* {{Esc|Moldova|y=2017}}\n| valign=\"top\" |\n* {{Esc|Montenegro|y=2017}}\n|-\n!width=20%|5 points\n!width=20%|4 points\n!width=20%|3 points\n!width=20%|2 points\n!width=20%|1 point\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |\n| valign=\"top\" |\n| valign=\"top\" |\n| valign=\"top\" |\n| valign=\"top\" |\n|-\n|}\n\n== Reception ==\n=== Critical response===\n\"Amar pelos dois\" received praise from [[Music journalism|music critics]]. Fabien Randanne of French newspaper ''[[20 minutes (France)|20 Minutes]]'' called \"Amar pelos dois\" a \"superb melancholic song\" and described it as a \"delightfully anachronistic sound\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.20minutes.fr/culture/2025335-20170306-video-eurovision-2017-portugal-fait-retour-superbe-chanson-melancolique |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170306195314/http://www.20minutes.fr/culture/2025335-20170306-video-eurovision-2017-portugal-fait-retour-superbe-chanson-melancolique |title=Eurovision 2017: Le Portugal fait son retour avec une superbe chanson m\u00e9lancolique |work=[[20 minutes (France)|20 Minutes]] |author=F.R. |date=March 6, 2017 |archivedate=March 6, 2017 |language=fr |url-status=dead }}</ref> Francisco Chac\u00f3n of Spanish newspaper ''[[ABC (newspaper)|ABC]]'' claimed that its jazz-pop tempo distinguished it from the \"outlandish proposals in the otherwise [[kitsch]] music scene\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.abc.es/cultura/eurovision/abci-eurovision-drama-humano-representante-portugal-eurovision-201703161856_noticia.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170316195738/http://www.abc.es/cultura/eurovision/abci-eurovision-drama-humano-representante-portugal-eurovision-201703161856_noticia.html |title=El drama humano del representante de Portugal en Eurovisi\u00f3n |work=[[ABC (newspaper)|ABC]] |publisher=[[Grupo Vocento]] |author=Chac\u00f3n, Francisco |date=March 16, 2017 |archivedate=March 16, 2017 |language=es |url-status=dead }}</ref> French magazine ''[[Paris Match]]'' declared it as one of their ten favourite entries of the year, and noted a \"great vocal mastery\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parismatch.com/Culture/Medias/Eurovision-2017-nos-10-candidats-favoris-1222139 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170329232135/http://www.parismatch.com/Culture/Medias/Eurovision-2017-nos-10-candidats-favoris-1222139 |title=Eurovision 2017 : nos 10 candidats favoris |work=[[Paris Match]] |publisher=Lagard\u00e8re Digital France |date=March 29, 2017 |archivedate=March 29, 2017 |language=fr |url-status=dead }}</ref> Chris Zeiher of Australian Eurovision broadcaster [[Special Broadcasting Service|SBS]] noted the \"simplicity\" of the song, adding that \"there's something refreshing and reflective\" in it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sbs.com.au/guide/article/2017/05/01/artists-eurovision-2017-salvador-sobral-amar-pelos-dois-portugal |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170504192628/http://www.sbs.com.au/guide/article/2017/05/01/artists-eurovision-2017-salvador-sobral-amar-pelos-dois-portugal |title=The artists of Eurovision 2017: Salvador Sobral \u2013 \"Amar pelos dois\" (Portugal) |work=[[Special Broadcasting Service|SBS]] |author=Zeiher, Chris |date=May 2, 2017 |archivedate=May 4, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Benny Royston of British newspaper ''[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]'' named it \"Portugal's best ever Eurovision entry\", and commented that \"sticking to [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]] maintains the charm and charisma of this song that pulls at the heartstrings through musical composition\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://metro.co.uk/2017/05/04/the-world-is-falling-in-love-with-portugals-best-ever-eurovision-entry-6615823/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170504212202/http://metro.co.uk/2017/05/04/the-world-is-falling-in-love-with-portugals-best-ever-eurovision-entry-6615823/ |title=The world is falling in love with Portugal\u2019s best ever Eurovision entry |work=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]] |publisher=[[DMG Media]] |author=Royston, Benny |date=May 4, 2017 |archivedate=May 4, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Christopher D. Shea of American newspaper ''[[The New York Times]]'' described it as an \"unexpectedly earnest ballad\" that \"has earned a loyal following for upending over-the-top Eurovision expectations\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/08/arts/music/eurovision-song-contest-2017-guide.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170509230251/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/08/arts/music/eurovision-song-contest-2017-guide.html|title=From Crimean Conflict to \u2018Yodel It!,\u2019 a Guide to Eurovision 2017|work=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|author=D. Shea, Christopher|date=May 8, 2017|archivedate=May 9, 2017|access-date=April 25, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Richard van de Crommert of Dutch newspaper ''[[De Telegraaf]]'' considered it Portugal's all-time best Eurovision entry.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.telegraaf.nl/prive/28130148/__Handleiding_voor_Kiev__.html |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170901223529/http://www.telegraaf.nl/prive/28130148/__Handleiding_voor_Kiev__.html |title=D\u00edt moet je weten voor de halve finale ESF |work=[[De Telegraaf]] |publisher=[[Telegraaf Media Groep]] |author=van de Crommert, Richard |date=May 9, 2017 |archivedate=2017-09-01 |language=nl |access-date=2017-09-01 |url-status=live }}</ref> Jens Maier of German magazine ''[[Stern (magazine)|Stern]]'' called the song a \"surprise\", adding that it \"enchanted\" the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2017|contest]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stern.de/kultur/musik/esc--ein-portugiese-verzaubert-kiew---so-lief-das-erste-semifinale-7446834.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170626233014/http://www.stern.de/kultur/musik/esc--ein-portugiese-verzaubert-kiew---so-lief-das-erste-semifinale-7446834.html |title=Ein Portugiese verzaubert den ESC \u2013 so lief das erste Semifinale |work=[[Stern (magazine)|Stern]] |publisher=[[Gruner + Jahr]] |author=Maier, Jens |date=May 10, 2017 |archivedate=June 26, 2017 |language=de |url-status=dead }}</ref> Charlotte Runcie of British newspaper ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' described it as an \"artistic, beautifully crafted\" and \"sophisticated\" song.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/tv/2017/05/09/eurovision-semi-final-one-live-results-running-order/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170511055313/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/tv/2017/05/09/eurovision-semi-final-one-live-results-running-order/ |title=Eurovision 2017, semi final 1 recap: let's all do the saxophone dance, and other highlights |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |publisher=[[Telegraph Media Group]] |author=Runcie, Charlotte |date=May 11, 2017 |archivedate=May 11, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n=== Commercial performance ===\n\"Amar pelos dois\" achieved [[Record chart|commercial success]], particularly in [[Europe]]. In Portugal, \"Amar pelos dois\" reached number 1 on the singles chart following its victory in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2017]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://portuguesecharts.com/archive.asp?todo=show&woche=20&jahr=2017&sparte=s|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170601003506/http://portuguesecharts.com/archive.asp?todo=show&woche=20&jahr=2017&sparte=s|title=Portuguese Charts: Singles|publisher=Hung Medien|archivedate=June 1, 2017}}</ref> On the Portuguese download chart, the song debuted at number 4, after winning the national final [[Festival da Can\u00e7\u00e3o]]. In the following week, it climbed to number 3,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/charts/2017-04-01/portugal |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170403231120/http://www.billboard.com/biz/charts/2017-04-01/portugal |title=Portugal Digital Song Sales |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=April 1, 2017 |archivedate=April 3, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and topped the chart eventually.<ref name=\"Billboard\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/charts/2017-05-27/portugal |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170519111334/http://www.billboard.com/biz/charts/2017-05-27/portugal |title=Portugal Digital Song Sales |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=May 27, 2017 |archivedate=May 19, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> It was certified gold by the [[Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Fonogr\u00e1fica Portuguesa]] (AFP), selling over 7,500 units.<ref name=\"Certification\">{{cite tweet|user=ESC_Portugal|number=872584241141473280|date=June 7, 2017|title=\"Amar pelos dois\" alcan\u00e7a disco de ouro|language=pt}}</ref> In Portugal, \"Amar pelos dois\" broke the record held by [[Ed Sheeran]]'s \"[[Shape of You]]\" for the most [[Streaming media|streams]] ever in a single day on [[Spotify]], with 75,373 daily streams, and became the only song to cross the 60,000 mark in a 24-hour period.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://spotifycharts.com/regional/pt/daily/2017-05-14|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170804222942/https://spotifycharts.com/regional/pt/daily/2017-05-14|title=Spotify Charts - Portugal|work=[[Spotify]]|date=May 14, 2017|archivedate=August 4, 2017}}</ref> Also on home ground, it achieved the second-biggest week ever for Spotify streams, with 366,423 weekly streams, and became one of only three songs to cross the 300,000 mark in a 7-day period.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://spotifycharts.com/regional/pt/weekly/2017-05-12--2017-05-19|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170804222306/https://spotifycharts.com/regional/pt/weekly/2017-05-12--2017-05-19|title=Spotify Charts - Portugal|work=[[Spotify]]|date=May 18, 2017|archivedate=August 4, 2017}}</ref> \n\nIn the rest of Europe, \"Amar pelos dois\" appeared on several download charts, reaching number 1 in Finland and the Netherlands, number 3 in Luxembourg, Norway and Sweden, number 4 in Denmark, number 5 in Greece, number 6 in Belgium, and number 31 in the [[UK Singles Downloads Chart|United Kingdom]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ifpi.fi/tilastot/virallinen-lista/artistit/Salvador+Sobral/Amar+pelos+dois |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170529185457/http://www.ifpi.fi/tilastot/virallinen-lista/artistit/Salvador%2BSobral/Amar%2Bpelos%2Bdois |title=Tilastot - Suomen virallinen lista - Artistit |publisher=[[Musiikkituottajat \u2013 IFPI Finland]] |archivedate=May 29, 2017 |language=fi |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"Billboard2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/search/charts?f[0]=ts_chart_artistname%3Asalvador%20sobral&f[1]=ss_bb_type%3Achart_item&type=2&artist=salvador%20sobral |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20170603121748/http://www.billboard.com/biz/search/charts?f%5B0%5D=ts_chart_artistname:salvador%20sobral&f%5B1%5D=ss_bb_type:chart_item&type=2&artist=salvador%20sobral |title=Chart Search |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |archivedate=June 3, 2017 |accessdate=May 19, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/charts/singles-downloads-chart/20170519/7000/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170529200504/http://www.officialcharts.com/charts/singles-downloads-chart/20170519/7000/ |title=Official Singles Downloads Chart Top 100 |publisher=[[Official Charts Company]] |archivedate=May 29, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> On other singles charts, the song peaked at number 1 in Iceland, number 6 in Switzerland, number 8 in Hungary, and number 22 in Austria.<ref name=\"Iceland\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ruv.is/lag/amar-pelos-dois |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20180821193145/http://www.ruv.is/lag/amar-pelos-dois |title=R\u00daV - Vins\u00e6ldalisti R\u00e1sar 2 |publisher=[[R\u00daV]] |archivedate=2018-08-21 |accessdate=May 20, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://hitparade.ch/charts/singles/21-05-2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170605211535/http://hitparade.ch/charts/singles/21-05-2017|title=Schweizer Hitparade - Singles Top 100|publisher=Hung Medien|date=May 21, 2017|archivedate=June 5, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://zene.slagerlistak.hu/single-track-top-40-lista/2017/20 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170529202440/http://zene.slagerlistak.hu/single-track-top-40-lista/2017/20 |title=Single (track) Top 40 lista |publisher=[[Association of Hungarian Record Companies|Magyar Hanglemezkiad\u00f3k Sz\u00f6vets\u00e9ge]] |archivedate=May 29, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://austriancharts.at/charts/singles/26-05-2017|title=Austria Top 40 - Singles|publisher=Hung Medien|date=May 26, 2017}}</ref> In France, it reached number 4, achieving the highest position for a [[Eurovision Song Contest]] winning entry since the {{Esccnty|United Kingdom|y=1976}}'s \"[[Save Your Kisses for Me]]\" in {{Escyr|1976}}.<ref name=\"France\">{{cite web|url=http://www.snepmusique.com/tops-semaine/top-singles-telecharges/?ye=2017&we=20|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170529191451/http://www.snepmusique.com/tops-semaine/top-singles-telecharges/?ye=2017&we=20|title=Le Top de la semaine : Top Singles T\u00e9l\u00e9charg\u00e9s|publisher=[[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique|SNEP]]|date=May 19, 2017|archivedate=May 29, 2017|access-date=May 19, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In Spain, \"Amar pelos dois\" debuted at number 1 and became the first Eurovision Song Contest winning entry to reach the top spot since {{Esccnty|Israel|y=1998}}'s \"[[Diva (Dana International song)|Diva]]\" in {{Escyr|1998}}.<ref name=\"Spain\">{{cite web|url=http://spanishcharts.com/weekchart.asp?cat=s3&year=2017&date=20170521|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180421190216/http://spanishcharts.com/weekchart.asp?cat=s3&year=2017&date=20170521|title=Physical/Digital Single Top 50|publisher=Hung Medien|date=May 21, 2017|archivedate=April 21, 2018}}</ref> In regard to streaming, the song achieved the third-biggest day ever on Spotify in Lithuania, with 5,704 daily streams.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://spotifycharts.com/regional/lt/daily/2017-05-14|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170901231929/https://spotifycharts.com/regional/lt/daily/2017-05-14|title=Spotify Charts - Lithuania|work=[[Spotify]]|date=May 14, 2017|archivedate=September 1, 2017}}</ref> \n\nIn the United States, \"Amar pelos dois\" peaked at number 7 on the [[Billboard_charts#International_charts|World Digital Songs]] chart, as one of the best-performing international digital singles.<ref name=\"Billboard2\"/>\n\nIn 2017, \"Amar pelos dois\" was listed at number 1 on the official [[Eurovision Song Contest]] year-end chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ouJYJWEx8l8|title=TOP 50: Most watched in 2017: 10 TO 1 - Eurovision Song Contest|website=[[YouTube]]|date=December 31, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Awards ===\n\"Amar pelos dois\" earned the Sobral siblings two [[Marcel Bezen\u00e7on Awards]]. Salvador Sobral received the Artistic Award, whereas Lu\u00edsa Sobral received the Composer Award.<ref name=\"Marcel Bezen\u00e7on Awards\">{{cite web|url=http://media.rtp.pt/festivaldacancao/artigos/marcel-bezencon-award-portugal-ganha-premio-artistico-e-premio-de-compositor-por-amar-pelos-dois/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170513191625/http://media.rtp.pt/festivaldacancao/artigos/marcel-bezencon-award-portugal-ganha-premio-artistico-e-premio-de-compositor-por-amar-pelos-dois/ |title=Marcel Bezen\u00e7on Award: Portugal ganha pr\u00e9mio art\u00edstico e pr\u00e9mio de compositor por \"Amar pelos dois\" |work=[[R\u00e1dio e Televis\u00e3o de Portugal|RTP]] |date=May 13, 2017 |archivedate=May 13, 2017 |language=pt |url-status=dead }}</ref> It marked the first time an entry was recognised with two of these awards since the {{Esccnty|Netherlands|y=2014}}' \"[[Calm After the Storm]]\" ({{Escyr|2014}}). \n\nAt the ESC Radio Awards, \"Amar pelos dois\" won Best Song. It marked the first time since {{Esccnty|Sweden|y=2012}}'s \"[[Euphoria (Loreen song)|Euphoria]]\" ({{Escyr|2012}}) that a Eurovision Song Contest winning entry also topped the ESC Radio Awards poll. Additionally, the song earned Salvador Sobral the Best Male Artist award.<ref name=\"ESC Radio Awards\">{{cite web|url=http://www.escradio.com/2017/06/esc-radio-awards-2017-the-winners/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170724231509/http://www.escradio.com/2017/06/esc-radio-awards-2017-the-winners/|title=ESC Radio Awards 2017 \u2013 The Winners|last=Mourinho|first=Daniel|website=ESC Radio|date=June 12, 2017|archivedate= July 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Award\n!Category\n!Result\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|2017\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Marcel Bezen\u00e7on Awards]]<ref name=\"Marcel Bezen\u00e7on Awards\"/>\n|Artistic Award\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|Composer Award\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|ESC Radio Awards<ref name=\"ESC Radio Awards\"/>\n|Best Song\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|Best Male Artist\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|2018\n|rowspan=\"1\"|SPA Awards<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spautores.pt/destaques/premio-autores-2018-vencedores|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20180321235646/https://www.spautores.pt/destaques/premio-autores-2018-vencedores|title=Pr\u00e9mio Autores 2018 / Vencedores|website=Sociedade Portuguesa de Autores|date=March 20, 2018|archivedate=March 21, 2018|language=pt}}</ref>\n|Best Song in Popular Music\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"|[[Golden Globes (Portugal)]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sic.sapo.pt/Programas/globosdeourosic/musica/2018-05-21-Amar-Pelos-Dois-e-a-Melhor-Musica-de-2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180523211455/http://sic.sapo.pt/Programas/globosdeourosic/musica/2018-05-21-Amar-Pelos-Dois-e-a-Melhor-Musica-de-2017|title=\u2018Amar Pelos Dois\u2019 \u00e9 a Melhor M\u00fasica de 2017|website=[[Sociedade Independente de Comunica\u00e7\u00e3o|SIC]]|date=May 21, 2018|archivedate=May 23, 2018|language=pt}}</ref>\n|Best Song \n|{{won}}\n|}\n\n==Live performances==\nSalvador Sobral and his sister Lu\u00edsa Sobral, composer of \"Amar pelos dois\", first appeared on the radio stations [[RFM (Portuguese radio station)|RFM]] (8 March 2017) and [[R\u00e1dio Comercial]] (14 March 2017).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lAwyAs8GVDM|title=AMAR PELOS DOIS - Salvador Sobral e Lu\u00edsa Sobral|website=[[YouTube]]|date=March 8, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vHqdXANF85c|title=R\u00e1dio Comercial / Salvador Sobral - Amar Pelos Dois|website=[[YouTube]]|date=March 14, 2017}}</ref> On 2 May 2017, Salvador Sobral's performance for ''Spain Calling International'' became available on [[RTVE]]'s website.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rtve.es/alacarta/videos/eurovision-2017/eurovision-2017-salvador-sobral-portugal-interpreta-directo-amar-pelos-dois/3998491/|title=Eurovisi\u00f3n 2017 - Salvador Sobral (Portugal) interpreta en directo \"Amar Pelos Dois\"|website=[[RTVE]]|date=May 2, 2017|language=es}}</ref> On 25 May 2017, the Sobral siblings performed on [[RTP1]]'s [[talk show]] ''Agora N\u00f3s''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://media.rtp.pt/festivaldacancao/videos/salvador-luisa-sobral-cantam-amar-pelos-dois-no-agora-nos/|title=Salvador e Lu\u00edsa Sobral cantam \u201cAmar Pelos Dois\u201d no Agora N\u00f3s|website=[[Radio and Television of Portugal|RTP]]|date=May 25, 2017|language=pt}}</ref> On 12 May 2018, Salvador Sobral performed alongside Brazilian singer [[Caetano Veloso]] at the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2018]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0aomcisD48I|title=Salvador Sobral performs with Caetano Veloso at the Grand Final of the 2018 Eurovision Song Contest|website=[[YouTube]]|date=May 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n===European Union Songbook===\n\"Amar pelos dois\" was included in the [[European Union]] Songbook as the all-time top Portuguese [[love song]]. \"Amar pelos dois\" was the most voted by the public in a field of ten songs pre-selected by music professionals, thus representing Portugal in the category Love.<ref name=\"EU Songbook\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eu-songbook.org/chosen-songs/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181114205114/http://www.eu-songbook.org/chosen-songs/|title=Chosen songs|website=European Union Songbook|archivedate=November 14, 2018|accessdate=November 14, 2018|}}</ref> \n\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#ccc;\"\n! Country\n! Category\n! Song\n! Result\n|- style=\"background:gold;\"\n| {{POR}}\n| [[Love song|Love]]\n| \"Amar pelos dois\"\n| 1st\n|}\n\n== Use in media ==\n\"Amar pelos dois\" is the opening theme song for the Brazilian [[telenovela]] ''[[Tempo de Amar]]'' on [[Rede Globo]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.movenoticias.com/2017/08/amar-pelos-dois-salvador-sobral-vai-tema-novela-da-globo/ |title='Amar pelos dois' de Salvador Sobral vai ser tema de novela da Globo|website=Move Not\u00edcias|date=August 1, 2017|language=pt}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IqlRVa42RmE|title=Tempo de Amar: veja a abertura|website=[[YouTube]]|date=September 26, 2017}}</ref> \"Amar pelos dois\" generated a two-part [[television documentary]] titled ''Sem Fazer Planos do Que Vir\u00e1 Depois'' and aired by Portuguese broadcaster [[R\u00e1dio e Televis\u00e3o de Portugal|RTP]]. As the central theme, \"Amar pelos dois\" is played and sung throughout the documentary.<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://media.rtp.pt/agoranos/artigos/sem-planos-do-vira-vitoria-salvador-sobral|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171231010052/http://media.rtp.pt/agoranos/artigos/sem-planos-do-vira-vitoria-salvador-sobral|title=\u201cSem fazer planos do que vir\u00e1 depois\u201d: a vit\u00f3ria de Salvador Sobral|website=[[R\u00e1dio e Televis\u00e3o de Portugal]]|archivedate=December 31, 2017|language=pt}}</ref> \n\n== Cover versions ==\n{{multiple image\n | footer = [[Eurovision Song Contest]] winners [[Marie Myriam]] (''left'') and [[Alexander Rybak]] (''right'') covered \"Amar pelos dois\".\n | image1 = MarieMyriam.jpg\n | image2 = Alexander Rybak i Skien (1).jpg\n | align  = right\n}}\n\n* [[Alexander Rybak]], [[Eurovision Song Contest 2009]] winner for {{Esccnty|Norway|y=2009}}, recorded an English-language version.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FNd3tyY7CcA|title=Alexander Rybak - ESC Winner 2017 Portugal - Tribute Cover (UNOFFICIAL English Lyrics)|website=[[YouTube]]|date=May 14, 2017}}</ref> \n* [[Nathan Trent]], {{Esccnty|Austria|y=2017}}'s representative in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2017]], did a rendition of the song with the Tiroler Symphonie Orchestra in his hometown, [[Innsbruck]].<ref>{{cite tweet|user=upTrent|number=882201872886530049|date=July 4, 2017|title=A snippet of yesterday's performance of \"Amar Pelos Dois\" with orchestra! I had so much fun! Hope you guys like it :)}}</ref> Trent performed it again at the Eurovision Live Concert 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=67UHSDnFB1k|title=Nathan Trent - Amar pelos dois|website=[[YouTube]]|date=September 9, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Selma Bj\u00f6rnsd\u00f3ttir]], {{Esccnty|Iceland}}'s representative in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1999]] and [[Eurovision Song Contest 2005|2005]], covered the song in English language at Eurobash 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mlQHb2-qmNg|title=Selma - Amar Pelos Dois - English version of Portugal 2017 - Eurovision|website=[[YouTube]]|date=September 14, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Lea Sirk]], {{Esccnty|Slovenia|y=2018}}'s representative in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2018]], performed the song on the [[talent show]] ''[[Your Face Sounds Familiar (Slovenian TV series)|Znan obraz ima svoj glas]]'', the Slovenian version of ''[[Your Face Sounds Familiar]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PvHCNhpTlM0|title=Your Face Sounds Familiar S4 E1 (SLOVENIA) - Salvador Sobral (Lea Sirk) - Amar Pelos Dois|website=[[YouTube]]|date=September 24, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Laura Groeseneken]], {{Esccnty|Belgium|y=2018}}'s representative in the Eurovision Song Contest 2018, covered the song in English language on the [[talk show]] ''Van Gils & gasten''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HE6RzSCDjgw|title=Laura Groeseneken met Love for Both - Cover version 'Amar Pelos Dois' by Salvador Sobral|website=[[YouTube]]|date=September 28, 2017}}</ref>\n* Dutch singer [[Jim van der Zee]], winner of the [[The Voice of Holland (season 8)|eighth season]] of singing competition ''[[The Voice of Holland]]'', covered the song in English language.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SAqOtZjEZRY|title=Jim van der Zee - Amar Pelos Dois / The voice of Holland / The Blind Auditions / Season 8|website=[[YouTube]]|date=October 20, 2017}}</ref>\n* Actor [[:es:Miquel Fern\u00e1ndez|Miquel Fern\u00e1ndez]] performed the song on the talent show ''[[:es:Tu cara me suena|Tu cara me suena]]'', the Spanish edition of ''Your Face Sounds Familiar''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=72Ve_V672LM|title=Miquel Fern\u00e1ndez imita a Salvador Sobral con 'Amar pelos dois' - Tu Cara Me Suena|website=[[YouTube]]|date=October 28, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Florin Cezar Ouatu|Cezar]], {{Esccnty|Romania|y=2013}}'s representative in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2013]], performed the song on the talent show ''[[Te cunosc de undeva!]]'', the Romanian version of ''Your Face Sounds Familiar''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PLnLU87vJ8w|title=Cezar Ouatu se transform\u0103 \u00een Salvador Sobral - Amar pelos dois|website=[[YouTube]]|date=November 4, 2017}}</ref> Cezar also covered the song in [[Selec\u021bia Na\u021bional\u0103]], [[Romania in the Eurovision Song Contest 2018|Romania]]'s national selection for the Eurovision Song Contest 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GaVzdDAnUZA|title=Cezar Ouatu - Amar pelos dois / Finala Eurovision Rom\u00e2nia 2018|website=[[YouTube]]|date=February 27, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Alfred Garc\u00eda]], {{Esccnty|Spain|y=2018}}'s representative in the Eurovision Song Contest 2018, performed the song in the [[Operaci\u00f3n Triunfo (series 9)|ninth season]] of Spanish [[reality television]] [[talent show]] ''[[Operaci\u00f3n Triunfo (Spanish TV series)|Operaci\u00f3n Triunfo]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-XswOUMP83g|title=\"Amar Pelos Dois\u201d - Alfred / Gala 4 / OT 2017|website=[[YouTube]]|date=November 20, 2017}}</ref>\n* Portuguese group Spell Choir recorded an [[a cappella]] version of the song.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vMnz--MG6_A|title=Spell Choir - Amar pelos Dois|website=[[YouTube]]|date=November 30, 2017}}</ref>\n* Yurcash, runners-up of the [[X Factor (Ukraine series 8)|eighth season]] of Ukraine's music competition ''[[X-Factor (Ukrainian TV series)|X-Factor]]'', did a Ukrainian-language cover of the song.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eVYbIXAKP5k|title=\u0413\u0440\u0443\u043f\u043f\u0430 Yurcash \u2013 Salvador Sobral \u2013 Amar Pelos Dois \u2013 \u0425-\u0424\u0430\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0440 8. \u0427\u0435\u0442\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0442\u044b\u0439 \u043f\u0440\u044f\u043c\u043e\u0439 \u044d\u0444\u0438\u0440|website=[[YouTube]]|date=December 2, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Marie Myriam]], [[Eurovision Song Contest 1977]] winner for {{Esccnty|France|y=1977}}, covered the song in Destination Eurovision, [[France in the Eurovision Song Contest 2018|France]]'s national selection for the Eurovision Song Contest 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bi423UtEYts|title=Medley jury + Marie Myriam - Amar Pelos Dois / Salvador Sobral|website=[[YouTube]]|date=January 20, 2018}}</ref>\n* Portuguese singer Ricardo Caria did a rendition of the song in Selec\u021bia Na\u021bional\u0103, Romania's national selection for the Eurovision Song Contest 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MBOWqow3aJ4|title=Ricardo Caria interpreta \"Amar Pelos Dois\" no Festival da Can\u00e7\u00e3o da Rom\u00e9nia|website=[[YouTube]]|date=January 28, 2018}}</ref>\n* Swiss-Portuguese singer Let\u00edcia Carvalho performed the song alongside Appenzeller S\u00e4ngerfreunde in Die Entscheidungsshow, [[Switzerland in the Eurovision Song Contest 2018|Switzerland]]'s national selection for the Eurovision Song Contest 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nmzRveCHLEQ|title=Leticia und Appenzeller S\u00e4ngerfreunde - Showact - \u00abAmar Pelos Dois\u00bb|website=[[YouTube]]|date=February 4, 2018}}</ref>\n* Sigr\u00ed\u00f0ur Thorlacius and Valdimar Gu\u00f0mundsson did an Icelandic-language cover of the song in [[Iceland_in_the_Eurovision_Song_Contest_2018#S%C3%B6ngvakeppnin_2018|S\u00f6ngvakeppnin]], Iceland's national selection for the Eurovision Song Contest 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hWR257jPutk|title=\u00c1st fyrir tvo (Amar Pelos Dois) \u2013 Sigr\u00ed\u00f0ur Thorlacius og Valdimar Gu\u00f0mundsson|website=[[YouTube]]|date=February 26, 2018}}</ref>\n* Ukrainian singer [[Tayanna]] covered the song in [[Eurovision National Selection (Ukraine)|Vidbir]], [[Ukraine in the Eurovision Song Contest 2018|Ukraine]]'s national selection for the Eurovision Song Contest 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xF4Wm7d5MNI|title=\u0424\u0456\u043d\u0430\u043b\u0456\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u0441\u043f\u0456\u0432\u0430\u044e\u0442\u044c \u043f\u043e\u043f\u0443\u0440\u0456 \u0445\u0456\u0442\u0456\u0432 \u0404\u0432\u0440\u043e\u0431\u0430\u0447\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044f|website=[[YouTube]]|date=February 24, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Ari \u00d3lafsson]], {{Esccnty|Iceland|y=2018}}'s representative in the Eurovision Song Contest 2018, did a bilingual English/Portuguese cover of the song.<ref>{{Facebook|ariolafsAIRmusic/posts/1675629242476484|name=Ari \u00d3lafsson}}</ref>\n* [[Madame Monsieur]], {{Esccnty|France|y=2018}}'s representatives in the Eurovision Song Contest 2018, did a French-language cover of the song.<ref>{{Facebook|MadameMonsieurMusic/videos/1687572838004302/|name=Madame Monsieur}}</ref>\n* [[Iriao]], {{Esccnty|Georgia|y=2018}}'s representatives in the Eurovision Song Contest 2018, did a rendition of the song.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2KUjxQfmOEY|title=\u201e\u10d8\u10e0\u10d8\u10d0\u10dd\u10e1\u201c \u10e1\u10d0\u10e9\u10e3\u10e5\u10d0\u10e0\u10d8 \u10d4\u10d5\u10e0\u10dd\u10de\u10d4\u10da \u10db\u10d0\u10e7\u10e3\u10e0\u10d4\u10d1\u10d4\u10da\u10e1! IRIAO - Amar Pelos Dois (Salvador Sobral)|website=[[YouTube]]|date=April 30, 2018}}</ref>\n* In a tribute at the Eurovision Song Contest 2018, several 2017 contestants sang the song: [[Svala]] ({{Esccnty|Iceland|y=2017}}), [[Manel Navarro]] ({{Esccnty|Spain|y=2017}}), [[Norma John]] ({{Esccnty|Finland|y=2017}}), [[Alma (French singer)|Alma]] ({{Esccnty|France|y=2017}}), [[Kristian Kostov]] ({{Esccnty|Bulgaria|y=2017}}), [[Martina B\u00e1rta]] ({{Esccnty|Czech Republic|y=2017}}), and [[Blanche (singer)|Blanche]] ({{Esccnty|Belgium|y=2017}}).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Kzwz36iITqw|title=Throwback to Salvador Sobral's Amar Pelos Dois in Kyiv|website=[[YouTube]]|date=May 8, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Michael Schulte (singer)|Michael Schulte]], {{Esccnty|Germany|y=2018}}'s representative in the Eurovision Song Contest 2018, covered the song in a reception held by the German embassy in [[Lisbon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=meRiqW4uZlY|title=Michael Schulte singt \"Amar Pelos Dois\" von Salvador Sobral / Eurovision Song Contest / NDR|website=[[YouTube]]|date=May 10, 2018}}</ref>\n* Brazilian singer [[:pt:Lilian Rodrigues|Lilian Rodrigues]] recorded a cover of the song.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CdYTqWmt3LQ|title=Amar Pelos Dois|website=[[YouTube]]|date=August 10, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Tiziana Tosca Donati]], winner of the [[Sanremo Music Festival 1996]], recorded an Italian-language version for her album ''Morabeza''.<ref>{{Facebook|TizianaToscaDonatiOfficial/videos/10156716253803896/|name=Tiziana Tosca Donati}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DMR7vP8vpNc|title=Per ogni oggi che verr\u00e0|website=[[YouTube]]|date=October 24, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[:cs:Jitka Zelenkov\u00e1|Jitka Zelenkov\u00e1]] recorded a Czech-language version for her album ''Intimity''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YYShNSaHgzk|title=L\u00e1ska za oba (Amar pelos dois)|website=[[YouTube]]|date=October 4, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Arisa]], winner of the [[Sanremo Music Festival 2014]], recorded an Italian-language version for her album ''Una nuova Rosalba in citt\u00e0''.<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://www.allmusicitalia.it/news/arisa-mi-sento-bene-sobral.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190111234340/http://www.allmusicitalia.it/news/arisa-mi-sento-bene-sobral.html|title=Arisa nel nuovo album anche una canzone di Salvador Sobral, vincitore dell\u2019Eurovision 2017|website=All Music Italia|date=January 5, 2019|archivedate=January 11, 2019|language=it}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=v7FdBQS-TwA|title=Amarsi in due|website=[[YouTube]]|date=February 25, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Jelena Toma\u0161evi\u0107]], {{Esccnty|Serbia|y=2008}}'s representative in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2008]], and Lea Sirk, Slovenia's representative in the Eurovision Song Contest 2018, covered the song in [[Beovizija]], Serbia's national selection for the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2019]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NNi-yFkivZY|title=Jelena Toma\u0161evi\u0107 i Lea Sirk - Amar pelos dois / Beovizija 2019|website=[[YouTube]]|date=March 1, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Jurijus Veklenko]], {{Esccnty|Lithuania|y=2019}}'s representative in the Eurovision Song Contest 2019, covered the song.<ref>{{Instagram|p/BvudnlngRJq|name=Jurijus Veklenko}}</ref>\n* Actor [[:el:\u0391\u03c1\u03b3\u03cd\u03c1\u03b7\u03c2 \u0391\u03b3\u03b3\u03ad\u03bb\u03bf\u03c5|Argyris Angelou]] performed the song on the [[Your Face Sounds Familiar (Greek TV series)|Greek version]] of talent show ''Your Face Sounds Familiar''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BunC_ok5MZ0|title=YFSF 5: 11\u03bf Live - \u0391\u03c1\u03b3\u03cd\u03c1\u03b7\u03c2 \u0391\u03b3\u03b3\u03ad\u03bb\u03bf\u03c5 (Salvador Sobral - Amar Pelos Dois) {7/4/2019}|website=[[YouTube]]|date=April 7, 2019}}</ref>\n* Spanish singer [[Pablo Albor\u00e1n]] did a rendition of the song during his concert in [[Lisbon]] in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.escportugal.pt/2019/06/video-pablo-alboran-canta-amar-pelos.html|title=Pablo Albor\u00e1n canta \"Amar Pelos Dois\" no Campo Pequeno|website=ESC Portugal|date=June 29, 2019|language=pt}}</ref>\n* [[Mar\u00eda Villal\u00f3n]], winner of the first season of music competition ''[[Factor X (Spanish TV series)|Factor X]]'' (Spanish version of ''[[The X Factor]]'') and the seventh season of talent show ''Tu cara me suena'' (Spanish edition of ''Your Face Sounds Familiar''), covered the song during her concert in [[:es:La Cueva de El Gato|La Cueva del Gato]], [[Province of M\u00e1laga|M\u00e1laga]] in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BAEHI__Kygs|title=Mar\u00eda Villal\u00f3n versiona \"Amar pelos dois\" en La Cueva del Gato (Benaoj\u00e1n-Espa\u00f1a)|website=[[YouTube]]|date=July 21, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Seraf\u00edn Zubiri]], {{Esccnty|Spain}}'s representative in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1992]] and [[Eurovision Song Contest 2000|2000]], covered the song at the 14th [[OGAE]] Spain convention.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OeLNbl5m3rA|title=Seraf\u00edn Zubiri - \u201cAmar Pelos Dois\u201d - XIV Congreso de OGAE Espa\u00f1a|website=[[YouTube]]|date=October 8, 2019}}</ref>\n* Estonian operatic tenor [[:et:Oliver Kuusik|Oliver Kuusik]] covered the song in [[Eesti Laul]], Estonia's national selection for the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2020]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-746ZiUCuQM|title=Oliver Kuusik - Amar Pelos Dois and Arcade (Eesti Laul 2020 II poolfinaal)|website=[[YouTube]]|date=March 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Track listings ==\n* '''Digital download'''<ref name=\"iTunes\"/>\n# \"Amar pelos dois\" \u2013 3:05\n\n* '''CD single'''<ref>{{cite AV media notes|title=Amar pelos dois (Liner Notes)|others=Salvador Sobral|date=June 16, 2017|type=Compact Disc|publisher=Sons em Tr\u00e2nsito}}</ref>\n# \"Amar pelos dois\" \u2013 3:05\n# \"Amar pelos dois\" (Instrumental) \u2013 2:56\n\n== Credits and personnel ==\n* Salvador Sobral \u2013 [[Lead vocalist|Vocals]]\n* Lu\u00edsa Sobral \u2013 [[Record producer|Production]], [[Songwriter|songwriting]]\n* Lu\u00eds Figueiredo \u2013 [[Arrangement|String arrangement]], [[piano]]<ref name=\"escportugal\">{{cite web|url=http://www.escportugal.pt/2017/01/entrevista-luisa-sobral-quis-fazer-uma.html|title=[ENTREVISTA] Lu\u00edsa Sobral: \"Quis fazer uma can\u00e7\u00e3o bonita para o Festival da Can\u00e7\u00e3o\"|website=ESC Portugal|date=January 18, 2017|language=pt}}</ref>\n* Quarteto Arabesco \u2013 [[Violin family|Strings]]<ref name=\"escportugal\"/>\n\nCredits adapted from the liner notes of \"Amar pelos dois\" promo single.<ref>{{cite AV media notes |title=Amar pelos dois (Liner Notes)|others=Salvador Sobral|year=2017|type=Compact Disc|work=MarteRecords promo|publisher=Sons em Tr\u00e2nsito}}</ref>\n\n== Charts ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2017)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br /> position\n|-\n{{single chart|Austria|22|artist=Salvador Sobral|song=Amar pelos dois|rowheader=true|accessdate=25 May 2017}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Flanders|30|artist=Salvador Sobral|song=Amar pelos dois|rowheader=true|accessdate=19 May 2017}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Wallonia Tip|8|artist=Salvador Sobral|song=Amar pelos dois|rowheader=true|accessdate=3 June 2017}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Belgium Digital Songs ([[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']])<ref name=\"Billboard2\"/>\n| 6\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Croatia ([[Croatian Radiotelevision|HRT]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://radio.hrt.hr/aod/arc-top-40/212079/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606232011/http://radio.hrt.hr/aod/arc-top-40/212079/ |title=ARC Top 40 |work=[[Croatian Radiotelevision|HRT]] |date=May 29, 2017 |archivedate=June 6, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| 19\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Denmark Digital Songs ([[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']])<ref name=\"Billboard2\"/>\n| 4\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Europe ([[Nielsen SoundScan|Euro Digital Songs]])<ref name=\"Billboard2\"/>\n| 13\n|-\n{{singlechart|Finnishdownload|1|artist=Salvador Sobral|song=Amar pelos dois|rowheader=true|accessdate=20 May 2017}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|France ([[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique|SNEP]])<ref name=\"France\"/>\n| 4\n|-\n{{singlechart|Germany2|43|songid=1641581|artist=Salvador Sobral|song=Amar pelos dois|rowheader=true|accessdate=19 May 2017}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Greece Digital Songs ([[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']])<ref name=\"Billboard2\"/>\n| 5\n|-\n{{single chart|Hungarysingle|8|year=2017|week=20|artist=Salvador Sobral|song=Amar pelos dois|rowheader=true|accessdate=26 May 2017}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Iceland ([[R\u00daV]])<ref name=\"Iceland\"/>\n| 1\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Luxembourg Digital Songs ([[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']])<ref name=\"Billboard2\"/>\n| 3\n|-\n{{single chart|Dutch100|35|artist=Salvador Sobral|song=Amar pelos dois|rowheader=true|accessdate=19 May 2017}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Netherlands Digital Songs ([[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/charts/2017-05-27/netherlands |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170602195828/http://www.billboard.com/biz/charts/2017-05-27/netherlands |title=Netherlands Digital Song Sales |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=May 27, 2017 |archivedate=June 2, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| 1\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Norway Digital Songs ([[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']])<ref name=\"Billboard2\"/>\n| 3\n|-\n{{single chart|Portugal|1|artist=Salvador Sobral|song=Amar pelos dois|rowheader=true|accessdate=23 March 2017}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Portugal Digital Songs ([[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']])<ref name=\"Billboard\"/>\n| 1\n|-\n{{singlechart|Scotland|37|date=2017-05-19|rowheader=true|accessdate=19 May 2017}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Spain ([[Productores de M\u00fasica de Espa\u00f1a|PROMUSICAE]])<ref name=\"Spain\"/>\n| 1\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|Sweden ([[Sverigetopplistan]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sverigetopplistan.se/|title=Sverigetopplistan - Sveriges Officiella Topplista|publisher=[[Sverigetopplistan]]|accessdate=19 May 2017}}</ref>\n| 33\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Sweden Digital Songs ([[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']])<ref name=\"Billboard2\"/>\n| 3\n|-\n{{singlechart|Switzerland|6|artist=Salvador Sobral|song=Amar pelos dois|rowheader=true|accessdate=22 May 2017}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|UK|97|date=2017-05-19|rowheader=true|accessdate=20 May 2017}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US [[Billboard_charts#International_charts|World Digital Songs]] ([[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']])<ref name=\"Billboard2\"/>\n| 7\n|}\n\n== Certifications ==\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Portugal ([[Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Fonogr\u00e1fica Portuguesa|AFP]])<ref name=\"Certification\"/>\n|Gold\n|7,500*\n|-\n{{Certification Table Bottom}}\n\n== Release history ==\n{|class=wikitable\n! Region\n! Date\n! Format\n! Label\n|-\n| Europe\n| 10 March 2017\n| [[Music download|Digital download]]\n| Sons em Tr\u00e2nsito\n|-\n| Portugal\n| 16 June 2017\n| [[CD single]]<ref name=\"CD single\"/>\n| [[Sony Music]]\n|-\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=nb}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{YouTube|id=ymFVfzu-2mw|title=Salvador Sobral - Amar pelos dois (Portugal) Eurovision 2017 - Official Music Video}}\n\n{{Salvador Sobral}}\n{{Portugal in the Eurovision Song Contest}}\n{{Eurovision Song Contest 2017}}\n{{List of Eurovision Song Contest winners}}\n\n[[Category:2017 singles]]\n[[Category:2017 songs]]\n[[Category:2010s ballads]]\n[[Category:Eurovision Song Contest winning songs]]\n[[Category:Eurovision songs of 2017]]\n[[Category:Eurovision songs of Portugal]]\n[[Category:Portuguese songs]]\n[[Category:Portuguese-language songs]]\n[[Category:Songs about heartache]]\n[[Category:Vocal jazz songs]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Iceland]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Portugal]]\n[[Category:Golden Globes (Portugal) winners]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2017 song by Salvador Sobral}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name          = Amar pelos dois\n| cover         = Salvador Sobral - Amar pelos dois.jpg\n| alt           =\n| type          = single\n| artist        = [[Salvador Sobral]]\n| album         =\n| language      = Portuguese\n| English_title = \"To Love for the Both of Us\"\n| released      = 10 March 2017\n| format        = {{hlist|[[CD single]]|[[Music download|digital download]]|[[Streaming media|streaming]]}}\n| recorded      =\n| studio        =\n| venue         =\n| genre         = {{hlist|[[Waltz_(music)#Jazz_waltzes|Jazz waltz]]|[[baroque pop]]|[[bossa nova]]}}\n| length        = 3:05\n| label         = Sons em Tr\u00e2nsito\n| writer        = {{Hlist|[[Lu\u00edsa Sobral]]}}\n| producer      = Lu\u00edsa Sobral\n| prev_title    = [[Nem Eu]]\n| prev_year     = 2016\n| next_title    = [[Mano a Mano (song)|Mano a Mano]]\n| next_year     = 2018\n| misc          = {{Infobox song contest entry\n| embed        = yes\n| song         = {{flagicon|Portugal}} \"Amar pelos dois\"\n| year         = 2017\n| country      = Portugal\n| artist       = [[Salvador Sobral]]\n| language     = Portuguese\n| composer     = [[Lu\u00edsa Sobral]]\n| lyricist     = Lu\u00edsa Sobral\n| place        = 1st\n| points       = 758\n| place_semi   = 1st\n| points_semi  = 370\n| prev         = H\u00e1 um mar que nos separa\n| prev_year    = 2015\n| prev_link    = H\u00e1 um mar que nos separa\n| next         = O jardim\n| next_year    = 2018\n| next_link    = O jardim\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Amar pelos dois'''\" ({{IPA-pt|\u0250\u02c8ma\u027e \u02c8p(\u0268)lu\u0283 \u02c8doj\u0283}}; English: To Love for the Both of Us) is a song performed by Portuguese singer [[Salvador Sobral]]. The track was written and produced by [[Lu\u00edsa Sobral]]. It premiered on 19 February 2017, when it was performed during the first semi-final of [[Festival da Can\u00e7\u00e3o|Festival da Can\u00e7\u00e3o 2017]], Portugal's national selection for the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2017]], and was released as a [[Music download|digital download]] on 10 March 2017 by Sons em Tr\u00e2nsito. \n\n\"Amar pelos dois\" is a [[Waltz_(music)#Jazz_waltzes|jazz waltz]] with a lyrical theme of [[broken heart|heartbreak]] after a [[breakup]]. The track received praise from [[Music journalism|music critics]] \u2013 some reviewers considered it Portugal's all-time best Eurovision entry. The song earned the Sobral siblings various awards, including two [[Marcel Bezen\u00e7on Awards]]. It was included in the [[European Union]] Songbook as the all-time top Portuguese [[love song]], and was covered by several artists. The song achieved [[Record chart|commercial success]], particularly in [[Europe]].\n\n\"Amar pelos dois\" represented {{Esccnty|Portugal}} in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017 in [[Kiev]], Ukraine. The song gave Portugal its first ever win since their debut in {{Escyr|1964}}. It amassed 758 points, setting the record for the highest number of points in the history of the [[Eurovision Song Contest|competition]], and is the only entry to top both the televoting and jury voting in the second half of the [[2010s]]. Salvador Sobral performed alone on stage B, close to the audience, while the background [[LED display|LED screens]] displayed an [[enchanted forest]].\n\n== Background and release==\n{{Quote box|width=25%|align=left|bgcolor=#c6dbf7|quote=\"I wanted to write a song that represents me, that could be on a record of mine, a song that I could be proud of and that's what I did.\"<ref name=\"eurovision.tv\">{{cite web|url=https://eurovision.tv/story/salvador-sobral-has-love-enough-for-portugal-and-europe|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20171126203452/https://eurovision.tv/story/salvador-sobral-has-love-enough-for-portugal-and-europe|website=eurovision.tv|title=Salvador Sobral has love enough for Portugal and Europe|publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]]|last=M. Escudero|first=Victor|date=March 6, 2017|archivedate=November 26, 2017}}</ref>|source=\u2014Lu\u00edsa Sobral, composer of \"Amar pelos dois\"}}\n\"Amar pelos dois\" was one of sixteen songs commissioned by [[R\u00e1dio e Televis\u00e3o de Portugal|RTP]] for [[Festival da Can\u00e7\u00e3o|Festival da Can\u00e7\u00e3o 2017]], Portugal's national selection for the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2017]]. The composers both created the song and selected the performer for their entry. Lu\u00edsa Sobral composed \"Amar pelos dois\" specifically for her brother, Salvador Sobral: \"I never thought about singing this song myself because when I wrote it I already had my brother's voice in mind. I was very fond of seeing him playing my song, because I think he is an extraordinary singer and because it gives me great joy to see him at the song contest and also that it turned out to be a family thing\".<ref name=\"eurovision.tv\"/> Salvador Sobral stated that even though \"Amar pelos dois\" was created by his sister Lu\u00edsa, she gave him freedom to perform the song according to his artistic personality.<ref name=\"eurovision.tv\"/>\n\n\"Amar pelos dois\" premiered on 19 February 2017, when it was performed in [[Festival da Can\u00e7\u00e3o|Festival da Can\u00e7\u00e3o 2017]], Portugal's national selection for the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2017]]. The song became available through [[Music download|digital]] retailers and [[Streaming media|streaming]] services on 10 March 2017 via Sons em Tr\u00e2nsito.<ref name=\"iTunes\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/pt/album/amar-pelos-dois-single/id1213997535|title=Amar pelos dois - Single|website=[[iTunes Store]]|accessdate=10 March 2017}}</ref> On 16 June 2017, it was released on [[CD single|physical format]] via [[Sony Music]].<ref name=\"CD single\">{{cite web|url=http://media.rtp.pt/festivaldacancao/artigos/cd-single-amar-pelos-dois-lancado-16-junho/|title=CD Single \u201cAmar Pelos Dois\u201d \u00e9 lan\u00e7ado a 16 de junho|website=[[R\u00e1dio e Televis\u00e3o de Portugal|RTP]]|language=pt|accessdate=December 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Composition ==\n\"Amar pelos dois\" was written and produced by Lu\u00edsa Sobral, Salvador Sobral's sister. \"Amar pelos dois\" is a [[Waltz_(music)#Jazz_waltzes|jazz waltz]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.vaterland.li/kultur/news/Aus-fuer-die-Schweiz-am-Song-Contest;art106,268718|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170706234812/http://www.vaterland.li/kultur/news/Aus-fuer-die-Schweiz-am-Song-Contest;art106,268718|title=Aus f\u00fcr die Schweiz am Song Contest|work=[[Liechtensteiner Vaterland]]|publisher=Vaduzer Medienhaus AG|date=May 11, 2017|archivedate=July 6, 2017|language=de}}</ref> with a length of three minutes and five seconds (3:05)<ref name=\"iTunes\"/> that moves at a [[tempo]] of 92 beats per minute.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://escnation.com/news/?id=1240|title=Ballad or up-tempo? Let's take a look at the actual tempo of this year's entries|publisher=ESC Nation|author=Jonas|date=March 21, 2017}}</ref> The song is composed in the [[Key (music)|key]] of [[F major]] and is written in [[triple metre]], with Sobral's vocals spanning from D<sub>4</sub> to G<sub>5</sub>.<ref>{{cite web|last=Sobral|first=Salvador|title=Amar Pelos Dois By Salvador Sobral - Digital Sheet Music|url=http://www.musicnotes.com/sheetmusic/mtd.asp?ppn=MN0174501|website=Musicnotes.com|publisher=[[Sony/ATV Music Publishing]]|accessdate=June 16, 2017}}</ref> Without [[Backing vocalist|background vocals]], it has an [[Instrumentation (music)|instrumentation]] consisting of [[Violin family|strings]] and [[piano]]. Salvador Sobral stated that \"Amar pelos dois\" is \"influenced by those old songs from the [[Great American Songbook]], and it also has a touch of the beautiful [[bossa nova]] melodies\".<ref name=\"ESC Bubble\">{{cite web|url=http://escbubble.com/2017/02/salvador-sobral-amar-pelos-dois-love-song-sad-one/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170403215105/http://escbubble.com/2017/02/salvador-sobral-amar-pelos-dois-love-song-sad-one/ |title=Salvador Sobral: \"Amar pelos dois\" is a love song. A sad one. |publisher=ESC Bubble |author=Juh\u00e1sz, Ervin |date=February 16, 2017 |archivedate=April 3, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The song's lyrical theme is [[broken heart|heartbreak]] after a [[breakup]]:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wiwibloggs.com/2017/03/18/amar-pelos-dois-lyrics-salvador-sobral-portugal-eurovision-2017/181079/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170323164438/http://wiwibloggs.com/2017/03/18/amar-pelos-dois-lyrics-salvador-sobral-portugal-eurovision-2017/181079/ |title=\u201cAmar pelos dois\u201d lyrics \u2014 Salvador Sobral (Portugal, Eurovision 2017) |website=[[Wiwibloggs]] |date=March 18, 2017 |archivedate=March 23, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> \"Meu bem / Ouve as minhas preces / Pe\u00e7o que regresses / Que me voltes a querer\".{{refn|group=nb|In English translation: \"My love / Listen to my pleas / I beg you to come back / To want me again\".}} Sobral described it as \"a [[love song]]. A sad one\".<ref name=\"ESC Bubble\"/>\n\n== At Eurovision ==\n{{Main article|Portugal in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017}}\n=== National selection ===\nLu\u00edsa Sobral was announced as a participating songwriter in [[Festival da Can\u00e7\u00e3o|Festival da Can\u00e7\u00e3o 2017]], Portugal's national selection for the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2017]], on 5 December 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://esctoday.com/138971/portugal-three-shows-festival-da-cancao-2017-final-5-march|title=Portugal: Three shows for Festival da Can\u00e7\u00e3o 2017; final on 5 March|publisher=ESCToday|last=Jiandani|first=Sanjay|date=5 December 2016|accessdate=6 December 2016}}</ref> On 18 January 2017, her brother, Salvador Sobral, was announced to be performing her song, titled \"Amar pelos dois\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://media.rtp.pt/festivaldacancao/artigos/conheca-os-interpretes-da-1-semifinal-do-festival-da-cancao-2017/|title=Conhe\u00e7a os int\u00e9rpretes da 1.\u00aa Semifinal do Festival da Can\u00e7\u00e3o 2017|work=RTP.pt|accessdate=18 January 2017|language=pt|date=18 January 2017}}</ref> After being sent two songs by Lu\u00edsa Sobral, written for the competition, Salvador Sobral selected \"Amar pelos dois\" as the song he would like to perform. Lu\u00eds Figueiredo, who did the string arrangement, also chose \"Amar pelos dois\" as the song to go through the competition's various phases. Sobral competed in the first semi-final on February 19, placing second with 20 points after winning the jury vote and coming third in the televote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wiwibloggs.com/2017/02/19/portugal-festival-da-cancao-semi-final-qualifiers/175666/|title=PORTUGAL: VIVA LA DIVA AND FERNANDO DANIEL AMONG QUALIFIERS IN FIRST SEMI-FINAL OF FESTIVAL DA CAN\u00c7\u00c3O 2017|date=19 February 2017|publisher=Wiwibloggs|website=wiwibloggs.com|last=Fuster|first=Luis}}</ref> In the final, held on 5 March, he won the jury vote and came second in the televote, placing first with 22 points and thus representing Portugal at the Eurovision Song Contest 2017.<ref name=\"win\">{{cite web|url=http://wiwibloggs.com/2017/03/06/portugal-salvador-sobral-wins-festival-da-cancao-2017/179145/|title=Portugal: Salvador Sobral wins Festival da Can\u00e7\u00e3o 2017 with \"Amar pelos dois\"|last=Foster|first=Luis|date=6 March 2017|publisher=Wiwibloggs|website=wiwibloggs.com}}</ref><ref name=\"Mercereau\">{{cite news|last1=Mercereau|first1=Damien|title=Eurovision 2017 : le Portugal de retour avec Salvador Sobral|url=http://tvmag.lefigaro.fr/programme-tv/eurovision-2017-le-portugal-de-retour-avec-salvador-sobral_1cb2ee44-0259-11e7-aad0-d9371b2c396c/|accessdate=16 March 2017|newspaper=Le Figaro|date=6 March 2017|language=fr}}</ref>\n\n=== In Kiev ===\n{{multiple image\n<!--image 1-->\n | image1            = ESC2017 Televote Portugal.svg\n | caption1          = Points awarded to Portugal by each national televote\n<!--image 2-->\n | image2            = ESC2017 Jury Portugal.svg\n | caption2          = Points awarded to Portugal by each national jury\n}}\nThe [[Eurovision Song Contest 2017]] took place at the [[International Exhibition Centre]] in [[Kiev]], Ukraine and consisted of two semi-finals on 9 and 11 May, and the final on 13 May 2017. Portugal was drawn to compete in the first half of the first semi-final.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eurovision.tv/story/results-of-the-semi-final-allocation-draw |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170515142127/https://eurovision.tv/story/results-of-the-semi-final-allocation-draw |website=eurovision.tv |title=Results of the Semi-Final Allocation Draw |publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]] |last1=Jordan |first1=Paul |last2=Nilsson |first2=Helena |date=January 31, 2017 |archivedate=May 15, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The running order for the semi-finals was decided by the producers, in order to avoid similar songs being placed next to each other. Portugal was set to perform in position 9, following the entry from {{Esccnty|Azerbaijan|y=2017}} and before the entry from {{Esccnty|Greece|y=2017}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eurovision.tv/story/running-order-eurovision-2017-revealed |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170612000755/https://eurovision.tv/story/running-order-eurovision-2017-revealed |title=Semi-Final running order for Eurovision 2017 revealed |website=eurovision.tv |publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]] |last=Jordan |first=Paul |date=March 31, 2017 |archivedate=June 12, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> For the grand final, Portugal was drawn to compete in the first half. Portugal was subsequently placed to perform in position 11 by the producers, following the entry from {{Esccnty|Denmark|y=2017}} and before the entry from Azerbaijan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eurovision.tv/story/running-order-grand-final-2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170512103306/https://eurovision.tv/story/running-order-grand-final-2017 |title=EXCLUSIVE: Running order for the 2017 Grand Final released! |website=eurovision.tv |publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]] |last1=Jordan |first1=Paul |last2=Nilsson |first2=Helena |date=May 11, 2017 |archivedate=May 12, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Salvador Sobral was one of the favorites to win the contest according to [[Bookmaker|bookmakers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvi24.iol.pt/musica/festival-da-cancao/salvador-sobral-ja-e-primeiro-nas-apostas-para-ganhar-eurovisao|title=Salvador Sobral j\u00e1 \u00e9 primeiro nas apostas para ganhar Eurovis\u00e3o|website=[[TVI 24]]|date=May 12, 2017|language=pt}}</ref> With its tool The Eurosearch Song Contest, [[Google]] correctly predicted Sobral's victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://googletrends.github.io/eurosearch-song-contest/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180511013245/https://googletrends.github.io/eurosearch-song-contest/|title=The Eurosearch Song Contest|website=[[Google]]|archivedate=May 11, 2018}}</ref> For the winner's encore, siblings Salvador and Lu\u00edsa sang the song as a duet, just like they did in the national final.\n\nFor his performance, Salvador Sobral wore a black suit and performed alone on stage B, close to the audience. During the performance, the background [[LED display|LED screens]] displays an [[enchanted forest]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.escportugal.pt/2017/05/esc2017-as-reacoes-ao-segundo-ensaio-de.html|title=ESC2017: As rea\u00e7\u00f5es ao segundo ensaio de Portugal|website=ESC Portugal|date=May 4, 2017|language=pt}}</ref> \n\nSalvador Sobral's victory was hailed in Portugal by the [[Assembly of the Republic (Portugal)|Assembly of the Republic]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.escportugal.pt/2017/05/parlamento-de-pe-para-aplaudir-salvador.html|title=[V\u00cdDEO] Parlamento de p\u00e9 para aplaudir Salvador e Lu\u00edsa Sobral|website=ESC Portugal|date=May 19, 2017|language=pt}}</ref> [[Prime Minister of Portugal|Prime Minister]] [[Ant\u00f3nio Costa]],<ref>{{cite tweet|user=antoniocostapm|number=863525180861231104|date=May 13, 2017|title=Fez-se hist\u00f3ria em portugu\u00eas hoje na #Eurovis\u00e3o! Parab\u00e9ns Salvador! Parab\u00e9ns Portugal! #Eurovision}}</ref> [[Ministry of Culture (Portugal)|Minister of Culture]] [[Lu\u00eds Filipe Castro Mendes]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.escportugal.pt/2017/05/portugal-ministro-da-cultura-diz-que.html|title=Portugal: Ministro da Cultura diz que vit\u00f3ria na Eurovis\u00e3o \u00e9 prova da criatividade lusa |website=ESC Portugal|date=May 15, 2017|language=pt}}</ref> and [[President of Portugal|President]] [[Marcelo Rebelo de Sousa]] who distinguished the Sobral siblings with the [[Order of Merit (Portugal)|Order of Merit]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.publico.pt/2018/04/23/culturaipsilon/noticia/luisa-e-salvador-sobral-nomeados-comendadores-pelo-exito-singular-1811456|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180818140027/https://www.publico.pt/2018/04/23/culturaipsilon/noticia/luisa-e-salvador-sobral-nomeados-comendadores-pelo-exito-singular-1811456|title=Irm\u00e3os Sobral nomeados comendadores por \"\u00eaxito singular\"|work=[[P\u00fablico (Portugal)|P\u00fablico]]|date=April 23, 2018|archivedate=August 18, 2018|language=pt}}</ref>\n\n==== Record-breaking victory ====\nBy earning 758 points overall in the grand final, \"Amar pelos dois\" became the highest-scoring entry in the history of the [[Eurovision Song Contest]], overtaking {{Esccnty|Ukraine|y=2016}}'s \"[[1944 (song)|1944]]\" which had scored 534 points the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2016|year before]]. \"Amar pelos dois\" is the only entry to top both the televoting and jury voting in the second half of the [[2010s]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Eurovision 2017 Results: Voting & Points |url=http://eurovisionworld.com/?eurovision=2017 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20170616021651/http://eurovisionworld.com/?eurovision=2017 |website=Eurovision World |accessdate=June 16, 2017 |archivedate=June 16, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In the grand final, \"Amar pelos dois\" received at least five televote points from every participating country.<ref name=Scoreboard/> It is the first winning song entirely performed in a country's native language since {{Esccnty|Serbia|y=2007}}'s \"[[Molitva]]\" ({{Escyr|2007}}) and the first winning song written in [[triple metre]] since {{Esccnty|Ireland|y=1996}}'s \"[[The Voice (Eimear Quinn song)|The Voice]]\" ({{Escyr|1996}}). With 382 points awarded by the national juries, \"Amar pelos dois\" broke the record of most jury points ever, beating {{Esccnty|Sweden|y=2015}}'s \"[[Heroes (M\u00e5ns Zelmerl\u00f6w song)|Heroes]]\" which received 353 points from the juries in {{Escyr|2015}}.<ref name=\"Scoreboard\"/> Additionally, Portugal achieved the biggest winning margin of the decade and the second biggest of all time, scoring 143 more points than the [[Bulgaria in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|runners-up]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eurovision.tv/event/kyiv-2017/grand-final/participants |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170515092839/https://eurovision.tv/event/kyiv-2017/grand-final/participants |title=Grand Final Participants |website=eurovision.tv |publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]] |accessdate=June 12, 2017 |archivedate=May 15, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nUnder the [[Voting at the Eurovision Song Contest#Voting systems|previous voting system]], \"Amar pelos dois\" would have scored 417 points, surpassing {{Esccnty|Norway|y=2009}}'s \"[[Fairytale (Alexander Rybak song)|Fairytale]]\" which scored 387 points in {{Escyr|2009}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.escxtra.com/2017/05/14/eurovision-2017-old-voting/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170612015618/https://www.escxtra.com/2017/05/14/eurovision-2017-old-voting/ |title=An Alternate Universe: Eurovision 2017 Under the Old Voting System |website=escXtra |date=May 14, 2017 |archivedate=June 12, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Also under the previous voting system, \"Amar pelos dois\" would have received a record of twenty combined sets of 12 points (televote + jury vote), overcoming the eighteen maximum scores collected by {{Esccnty|Sweden|y=2012}}'s \"[[Euphoria (Loreen song)|Euphoria]]\" in {{Escyr|2012}}. Thus, from a combined vote perspective, Portugal received 12 points from Armenia, Austria, Belgium, Czech Republic, Estonia, Finland, France, Germany, Iceland, Israel, Lithuania, the Netherlands, Norway, San Marino, Slovenia, Spain, Sweden, Switzerland, Ukraine and the United Kingdom.<ref name=\"Classic voting\">{{cite web|url=https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1-sT2lLmqv-40THcOUbT6pFc7YZm8g9bAhzLx8kkyiCM/edit#gid=31282450|title=Eurovision 2017 Old Voting||publisher=escXtra|accessdate=June 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==== Points awarded to Portugal ====\nBelow is a breakdown of points awarded to Portugal in the first semi-final and grand final of the contest, and the breakdown of the televoting and jury voting conducted during the two shows. The country finished in first place on both occasions. In the semi-final, Portugal was ranked first with 370 points overall, garnering 197 from the televote and 173 from the jury vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eurovision.tv/story/exclusive-results-semi-finals-2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170522215347/https://eurovision.tv/story/exclusive-results-semi-finals-2017 |title=EXCLUSIVE: Here are the results of the Semi-Finals! |website=eurovision.tv |publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]] |last=Jordan |first=Paul |date=May 13, 2017 |archivedate=May 22, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Portugal received 12 points from the televoters in [[Albania in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Albania]], [[Belgium in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Belgium]], [[Finland in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Finland]], [[Iceland in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Iceland]], [[Latvia in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Latvia]], [[Poland in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Poland]], [[Slovenia in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Slovenia]], [[Spain in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Spain]] and [[Sweden in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Sweden]], and received 12 points from the juries of [[Azerbaijan in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Azerbaijan]], [[Georgia in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Georgia]], Iceland, Latvia, [[Moldova in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Moldova]], Poland and Spain.<ref>{{cite web|title=Portugal - First Semi-Final Scoreboard |url=https://eurovision.tv/event/kyiv-2017/first-semi-final/scoreboard/portugal |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170612001437/https://eurovision.tv/event/kyiv-2017/first-semi-final/scoreboard/portugal |website=eurovision.tv |publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]] |accessdate=June 12, 2017 |archivedate=June 12, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In the end, Portugal won the contest with 758 points overall; 376 from the televote and 382 from the jury vote. In the grand final, Portugal earned a total of thirty sets of 12 points. The country received maximum scores from the televoters in [[Austria in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Austria]], Belgium, Finland, [[France in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|France]], [[Germany in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Germany]], Iceland, [[Israel in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Israel]], [[Lithuania in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Lithuania]], the [[Netherlands in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Netherlands]], [[Norway in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Norway]], Spain and [[Switzerland in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Switzerland]], and received top marks from the juries of [[Armenia in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Armenia]], [[Czech Republic in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Czech Republic]], France, Georgia, [[Hungary in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Hungary]], Iceland, Israel, Latvia, Lithuania, the Netherlands, Poland, [[San Marino in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|San Marino]], [[Serbia in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Serbia]], Slovenia, Spain, Sweden, Switzerland and the [[United Kingdom in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|United Kingdom]].<ref name=Scoreboard>{{cite web|title=Portugal - 2017 Grand Final Scoreboard|url=https://eurovision.tv/event/kyiv-2017/grand-final/scoreboard/portugal |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20170612002917/https://eurovision.tv/event/kyiv-2017/grand-final/scoreboard/portugal |website=eurovision.tv |publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]] |accessdate=June 12, 2017 |archivedate=June 12, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed\"\n|-\n!colspan=\"5\"| Points awarded to Portugal (Semi-final 1)\n|-\n!colspan=\"5\"| Televote\n|-\n!width=20%|12 points\n!width=20%|10 points\n!width=20%|8 points\n!width=20%|7 points\n!width=20%|6 points\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*{{Esc|Albania|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Belgium|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Finland|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Iceland|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Latvia|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Poland|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Slovenia|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Spain|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Sweden|y=2017}}\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*{{Esc|Australia|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Greece|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Italy|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|United Kingdom|y=2017}}\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*{{Esc|Azerbaijan|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Georgia|y=2017}}\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*{{Esc|Armenia|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Czech Republic|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Montenegro|y=2017}}\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*{{Esc|Cyprus|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Moldova|y=2017}}\n|-\n!width=20%|5 points\n!width=20%|4 points\n!width=20%|3 points\n!width=20%|2 points\n!width=20%|1 point\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |\n| valign=\"top\" |\n| valign=\"top\" |\n| valign=\"top\" |\n| valign=\"top\" |\