tugal) Eurovision 2017 - Official Music Video}}\n\n{{Salvador Sobral}}\n{{Portugal in the Eurovision Song Contest}}\n{{Eurovision Song Contest 2017}}\n{{List of Eurovision Song Contest winners}}\n\n[[Category:2017 singles]]\n[[Category:2017 songs]]\n[[Category:2010s ballads]]\n[[Category:Eurovision Song Contest winning songs]]\n[[Category:Eurovision songs of 2017]]\n[[Category:Eurovision songs of Portugal]]\n[[Category:Portuguese songs]]\n[[Category:Portuguese-language songs]]\n[[Category:Songs about heartache]]\n[[Category:Vocal jazz songs]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Iceland]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Portugal]]\n[[Category:Golden Globes (Portugal) winners]]\n", "name_user": "Grk1011", "label": "safe", "comment": "small fixes", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amar_pelos_dois"}
{"title_page": "Jerome Bettis", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|Jerrod Bettis}}\n{{short description|American football running back}}\n{{Use American English|date=December 2017}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n| name = Jerome Bettis\n| image = Jerome Bettis 2016.jpg\n| caption = Bettis in February 2016\n| number = 36\n| position = Fua\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1972|02|16|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Detroit|Detroit, Michigan]]\n| height_ft = 5\n| height_in = 11\n| weight_lbs = 255\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| high_school = [[Mackenzie High School (Michigan)|Detroit (MI) Mackenzie]]\n| college = [[Notre Dame Fighting Irish football|Notre Dame]]\n| draftyear = 1993\n| draftround = 1\n| draftpick = 10\n| pastteams =\n* [[Los Angeles Rams|Los Angeles / St. Louis Rams]] ([[1993 NFL season|1993]]\u2013[[1995 NFL season|1995]])\n* [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] ([[1996 NFL season|1996]]\u2013[[2005 NFL season|2005]])\n|highlights=\n* [[Super Bowl]] champion ([[Super Bowl XL|XL]])\n* 6\u00d7 [[Pro Bowl]] ([[1994 Pro Bowl|1993]], [[1995 Pro Bowl|1994]], [[1997 Pro Bowl|1996]], [[1998 Pro Bowl|1997]], [[2002 Pro Bowl|2001]], [[2005 Pro Bowl|2004]])\n* 2\u00d7 First-team [[All-Pro]] ([[1993 All-Pro Team|1993]], [[1996 All-Pro Team|1996]])\n* Second-team All-Pro ([[1997 All-Pro Team|1997]])\n* [[Walter Payton NFL Man of the Year]] (2001)\n* [[NFL Comeback Player of the Year]] (1996)\n* [[NFL Offensive Rookie of the Year]] (1993)\n* [[Pittsburgh Steelers All-Time Team]]\n| statlabel1 = Rushing yards\n| statvalue1 = 13,664\n| statlabel2 = Yards per carry\n| statvalue2 = 3.9\n| statlabel3 = Rushing touchdowns\n| statvalue3 = 91\n| statlabel4 = Receptions\n| statvalue4 = 200\n| statlabel5 = Receiving yards\n| statvalue5 = 1,457\n| statlabel6 = Receiving touchdowns\n| statvalue6 = 3\n| nfl = BET627285\n| pfr = B/BettJe00\n| HOF = jerome-bettis\n}}\n'''Jerome Abram Bettis Sr.''' (born February 24 1972), nicknamed '''The Bus''', is a former [[American football]] [[running back|halfback]] who played for the [[Los Angeles Rams|Los Angeles Rams/St. Louis Rams]] and [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL). Bettis is eighth on the [[List of National Football League rushing yards leaders|list of NFL rushing yards leaders]]. He retired in 2006 after he won [[Super Bowl XL]] with the Steelers in his native [[Detroit]], [[Michigan]], beating the [[Seattle Seahawks]]. Bettis was inducted into the [[Pro Football Hall of Fame]] in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jerome Bettis elected to Pro Football Hall of Fame|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/sports/steelers/2015/01/31/Steelers-champion-Jerome-Bettis-elected-to-Pro-Football-Hall-of-Fame/stories/201501310191|work=Ed Bouchette|publisher=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]|access-date=January 31, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nBettis was born February 16, 1972, in [[Detroit]], [[Michigan]]. He is the oldest of three children of Gladys Elizabeth (n\u00e9e Bougard) and Johnnie E. Bettis.<ref>Stated on ''[[Who Do You Think You Are? (U.S. TV series)|Who Do You Think You Are?]]'', March 9, 2012</ref> Bettis did not start playing football until high school, as his primary passion as a youth had been [[bowling]]. At age 14, he was diagnosed with asthma.<ref>{{cite web|title=Biography|url=http://www.webmd.com/jerome-bettis|work=Jerome Bettis|publisher=WebMD|access-date=November 25, 2012}}</ref> As a youth in Detroit, Bettis and his brother made ends meet by selling [[crack cocaine]].<ref name=crack>{{cite news|last1=Jahnke|first1=James|title=Jerome Bettis: I sold crack, shot at people in Detroit|url=http://www.freep.com/story/sports/nfl/2015/07/23/jerome-bettis-detroit/30566969/|access-date=July 24, 2015|work=[[Detroit Free Press]]|date=July 24, 2015}}</ref> He attended [[Mackenzie High School (Michigan)|Mackenzie High School]] in Detroit, where he was a standout running back and [[linebacker]]. As a senior, he was rated the top player in the state by the ''[[Detroit Free Press]]'', and was the [[Gatorade]] Circle of Champions Player of the Year award winner.\n\n==College career==\nAt the [[University of Notre Dame]], Bettis finished his career with 337 rushing attempts for 1,912 yards (5.7 yards per attempt), and made 32 receptions for 429 yards (13.4 yards per reception). In his last game as a junior, a 28-3 win by Notre Dame over Texas A&M in the [[1993 Cotton Bowl]], he rushed 20 times for 75 yards, ran for two touchdowns and caught a 26-yard touchdown pass. In his sophomore year, he set the Notre Dame touchdown record with 20 in one season, with 16 rushing, and 4 receiving (23 total touchdowns including the [[1992 Sugar Bowl]], a record which still stands).\n\n*1990: 15 carries for 115 yards and 1 touchdown.<ref>[http://www.totalfootballstats.com/PlayerRB.asp?id=316 Jerome Bettis College & Pro Football Statistics]. Totalfootballstats.com. Retrieved on July 23, 2013.</ref>\n*1991: 168 carries for 972 yards and 16 touchdowns. 17 catches for 190 yards and 4 touchdowns.\n*1992: 154 carries for 825 yards and 10 touchdowns. 15 catches for 239 yards and 6 touchdowns.\n\nBettis did not graduate from college.<ref name=\"nytimes.com\">Jenkins, Lee (February 4, 2006). [https://www.nytimes.com/2006/02/04/sports/football/04bettis.html?_r=0 \"With That Old College Retry, Bettis Revived His Career\"]. ''The New York Times''. Retrieved January 13, 2017.</ref> He skipped his senior year at [[University of Notre Dame|Notre Dame]] to enter the [[1993 NFL Draft]]. He returned to [[University of Notre Dame|Notre Dame]] in 1996 when he was having a dispute with the [[St. Louis Rams]] and was considering retirement. He took courses in \"history, philosophy, marketing and business\" totalling a heavy 18 credit class load.<ref name=\"nytimes.com\"/> He returned to the [[NFL]] shortly thereafter, and \"he has not returned to Notre Dame to finish the coursework for his degree.\"<ref name=\"nytimes.com\"/>\n\n==Professional career==\n===Los Angeles and St. Louis Rams===\nBettis was picked in the first round (10th overall) of the [[1993 NFL Draft]] by the [[Los Angeles Rams]]. On July 22, 1993, Bettis signed a three-year, $4.625 million contract with a signing bonus in excess of $2 million.<ref>[[T. J. Simers|Simers, J.T.]] (July 23, 1993). \"Rams Reach Agreement With Bettis Football: No. 1 pick expected to sign and practice today\".\n[https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/60346522.html?dids=60346522:60346522&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Jul+23%2C+1993&author=T.J.+SIMERS&pub=Los+Angeles+Times+(pre-1997+Fulltext)&desc=Rams+Reach+Agreement+With+Bettis+Football%3A+No.+1+pick+expected+to+sign+and+practice+today.+Trade+talks+involve+Cleveland+Gary.&pqatl=google Los Angeles Times] Retrieved September 10, 2010.</ref> As a rookie, he flourished under [[Chuck Knox]]'s ground-oriented offense.  He quickly earned the nickname \"The Battering Ram\" as he rushed for 1,429 yards (second in the NFL), drawing comparisons to [[Earl Campbell]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1993-12-08/sports/sp-65186_1_jerome-bettis|title=Bettis' Pounding Runs Haven't Rescued Rams :  NFL: Rookie running back is gaining yards and attention, but the offense remains ineffective because of a shoddy passing attack.|first=T. J.|last=SIMERS|date=December 8, 1993|publisher=|access-date=December 25, 2017|via=LA Times}}</ref> Bettis also had an NFL-best 79 rushing first downs and an NFL-best 38 runs of 10 or more yards, and tied for the league lead with seven 100-yard rushing games despite not becoming the full-time starter until the sixth game of the season. Bettis was named a First-Team [[1993 All-Pro Team|All-Pro]] (the only rookie named to the team) and Consensus [[NFL Rookie of the Year Award|NFL Offensive Rookie of the Year]]. He rushed for over 1,000 yards and was selected for the NFC's [[Pro Bowl]] team in each of his first two seasons with the Rams.\n\nThe Rams moved to [[St. Louis]] for the [[1995 NFL season|1995 season]]. New coach [[Rich Brooks]] instituted a more pass-oriented offense, a major reason why Bettis was limited to 637 yards,<ref>{{cite web|title=Pro Football Hall of Fame: Steelers' Jerome Bettis redefined big, quick RBs|url=http://www.cbssports.com/nfl/eye-on-football/25260852/nfl-hall-of-fame-steelers-jerome-bettis-redefined-big-quick-rbs|work=Ryan Wilson|publisher=[[CBSSports.com]]|accessdate=February 8, 2016}}</ref> a significant dropoff from his 1993 and 1994 totals. Brooks asked Bettis whether he wanted to move to fullback for the upcoming 1996 season or preferred to be traded. Bettis stated he thought he could still help an NFL team with his running.\n\nOn April 20, 1996, Bettis was traded to the Pittsburgh Steelers with a third-round pick in the [[1996 NFL Draft]], in exchange for the Steelers' second-round pick and their fourth-round pick in the [[1997 NFL Draft]].<ref>Clarochi, Paul (April 21, 1996), \"Steelers Bet on Bettis to Fill RB Void\".[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=wIkyAAAAIBAJ&sjid=TLYFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1859,4370381&dq=bettis+traded&hl=en Beaver County Times] Retrieved September 12, 2010.</ref> The Rams gave Bettis the option of which team he wanted to be traded to, and he chose the Steelers over their [[AFC North|AFC Central]] [[Steelers-Titans rivalry|rival]] [[Tennessee Titans|Houston Oilers]] (who would draft [[Eddie George]] that year instead) due to the Steelers more storied history.<ref>https://m.youtube.com/watch?feature=youtu.be&v=i8LfQvT0b-0</ref>\n\nIn exchange for Bettis, the Rams drafted [[Ernie Conwell]] (second round of 1996 draft) and also received the Steelers fourth-round pick in 1997.  In 1997, the Rams had multiple trade deals including moving up to the number 1 draft slot to draft [[Orlando Pace]]. The Rams traded their fourth-round pick from the Steelers to the Dolphins along with two sixth-round picks, in order to move up nine slots and draft offensive tackle [[Ryan Tucker]]. The Steelers drafted [[Steve Conley]] (third round of 1996 draft) with the draft selection they acquired from the Bettis trade with the Rams. Conley was traded to the Colts two seasons later for a fifth-round pick.\n\n===Pittsburgh Steelers===\nThe Steelers were in need of a running back because [[Bam Morris]], their power running back for the 1994 and 1995 seasons, was arrested in March 1996 for marijuana possession.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1996-03-27/sports/9603270102_1_drug-charges-assault-charge-morris.|title=Steelers' Morris Indicted On Drug Charges|date=March 27, 1996|website=ChicagoTribune.com|access-date=December 25, 2017}}</ref> The Steelers traded for Bettis on the day of the [[1996 NFL Draft]]. Morris eventually pleaded guilty to marijuana possession and was cut by the team in June 1996, leaving Bettis as the featured back. In his first season in Pittsburgh, Bettis rushed for a then career-high 1,431 yards and 11 touchdowns and was named to his second 1st team [[1996 All-Pro Team|All-Pro]] team. He also won the [[NFL Comeback Player of the Year]], NFL Alumni Running Back of the Year, was voted Steelers' team MVP and finished the 1996 season as the leader in [[Football Outsiders]] rushing [[Football Outsiders#DYAR|DYAR]] [[advanced metrics|metric]].<ref>[http://www.footballoutsiders.com/stats/rb1996] Footballoutsiders.com. Retrieved on September 13, 2017.</ref>\n\nBettis rushed for over 1,000 yards in each of his first six seasons with the Steelers between 1996 and 2001. Included in that run were three campaigns of over 1,300 yards. In 1997, Bettis rushed for a career-best 1,665 yards in the team's first 15 games. However, because the team had already wrapped up its playoff position, he was rested for the regular-season finale and finished 26 yards short of the team's single-season record. Bettis does hold the Steelers' franchise record for rushing yards in a single-season when including postseason play.<ref>[https://www.pro-football-reference.com/play-index/pgl_finder.cgi?request=1&match=single&year_min=1950&year_max=2017&season_start=1&season_end=-1&pos=0&game_type=E&team_id=pit&career_game_num_min=1&career_game_num_max=400&game_num_min=0&game_num_max=99&week_num_min=0&week_num_max=99&c5val=1.0&order_by=rush_yds] Pro-Football-Reference.com.</ref> Bettis was a second-team All-Pro choice in 1997 and set a then NFL record with two overtime touchdowns in the same season.\n\nBettis was leading the league with 1,072 rushing yards in 2001 when he suffered a serious hip and groin injury that sidelined him for the remainder of the regular season. Injuries would also cost him significant parts of the 2002 season and he then began the 2003 season as a backup to [[Amos Zereou\u00e9]]. Despite regaining his starting role midway through the 2003 season, Bettis again found himself a backup to start the 2004 season, this time to free-agent acquisition [[Duce Staley]]. But when an injury took Staley out of action midway through the year, Bettis stepped in and gained 100-plus yards in six of the next eight games, and in seven consecutive starts. The late season effort led to the sixth Pro-Bowl berth of his career.\n\nBettis spent the 2005 season as a short-yardage running back, but managed two notable games along the way: First, a 101-yard, two touchdown effort in a pivotal week 14 win over Chicago (his second-to-last game in Pittsburgh).  This game included a play in which he ran over Bears' safety [[Mike Green (defensive back)|Mike Green]] and the NFL's [[Associated Press NFL Defensive Player of the Year Award|Defensive Player of the Year]] linebacker [[Brian Urlacher]] on the goal line during a heavy snow squall. Secondly, he scored three touchdowns in a win over Detroit to clinch a playoff berth on the last day of the season, which was his last game in Pittsburgh. He finished the season and his career as the NFL's 5th leading all-time [[Rush (American football)|rusher]].\n\nBettis was also at the center of one of the most controversial calls in NFL history. During a Thanksgiving Day game with the [[Detroit Lions]] on November 26, 1998, Bettis was sent out as the Steelers representative for the overtime coin toss. Bettis appeared to call \"tails\" while the coin was in the air but referee [[Phil Luckett]] declared that Bettis called \"heads\" and awarded possession to Detroit, who would go on to win the game before Pittsburgh had the chance to have possession. After reviewing the incident, the NFL changed the rule and declared that the call of \"heads\" or \"tails\" would be made before the coin was tossed rather than during the coin toss and that at least two officials would be present during the coin toss. The readers of ESPN voted the incident as No. 8 on its list of the ten worst sports officiating calls of all time, even though later sound enhancements of the audio showed that Bettis said \"hea-tails\" and Bettis admitted starting to call \"heads\" before changing it to tails.<ref>[http://espn.go.com/page2/s/list/readers/worstcalls.html The Readers' List:Worst calls in history]. ESPN. August 27, 2001. Retrieved on 2013-07-23.</ref>  Immediately after the incident, however, Bettis commented \"I did not say 'heads-tails.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/11/27/sports/pro-football-heads-tails-referee-chooses-then-steelers-lose.html|title=PRO FOOTBALL; 'Heads'? 'Tails'? Referee Chooses, Then Steelers Lose|date=November 27, 1998|publisher=|access-date=December 25, 2017|work=New York Times|agency=Associated Press}}</ref> Bettis later put together one of the most bizarre single-game statistics in NFL history. In the 2004 season opener, he carried the ball five times for a total of only one yard, a 0.2 yards per carry average.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/nfl/boxscore?gameId=240912023.|title=NFL Football Scores - NFL Scoreboard - ESPN|date=September 12, 2004|website=ESPN.com|access-date=December 25, 2017}}</ref> However, he scored 18 points on those carries with three touchdowns.\n\nDuring that 2004 season, Bettis and [[New York Jets]] running back [[Curtis Martin]] dueled for position on the all-time rushing yards leaderboard. Bettis entered the season in 6th place all-time and 684 yards ahead of Martin in 9th place. Because Bettis was the backup in Pittsburgh for the start of the season, Martin was able to pass Bettis in week 13 until the Steelers played their game later in the day and Bettis retook the lead by 6 yards. When the Jets traveled to Martin's home town of Pittsburgh to play the Steelers the following week, both backs would cross the 13,000-yard mark, making this the first time two players crossed the 13,000 yard mark (or other similarly high yardage milestones) in the same game. Their combined career totals were also one of the biggest combined career totals for opposing running backs in history. At the end of the game, Martin would lead Bettis by 9 yards. Two weeks later in week 16, Bettis would again pass Martin and establish himself with a lead of 81 yards. In doing so, Bettis passed [[Eric Dickerson]] for 4th place on the all-time list. Bettis sat out the final week of the season, and when Martin rushed for 153 yards that week he passed Dickerson and Bettis for the final time.\n\nAfter the Steelers' defeat in the [[NFL playoffs, 2004\u201305|2004 AFC Championship Game]] on January 23, 2005, Bettis announced that he was considering retirement, but would not make a final decision for several months to prevent the sting of the defeat from clouding his judgment. Later, Bettis agreed to stay with the Steelers for another season. He stated he would love to play in the [[Super Bowl]] in 2006 since it was to be played in his hometown of Detroit. His wish came true as the Steelers played in, and won, [[Super Bowl XL]] (40) against the [[Seattle Seahawks]], 21\u201310, on February 5, 2006.\n\nBettis finished his 13 NFL seasons as the NFL's 5th all-time leading rusher with 13,662 yards and 91 touchdowns. He also caught 200 passes for 1,449 yards and 3 touchdowns and threw 3 career touchdown passes. He was named to the [[Pro Bowl]] in 1993, 1994, 1996, 1997, 2001, and 2004. Bettis won the [[NFL Comeback Player of the Year]] award in 1996, and in 2002 he was the recipient of the [[Walter Payton Man of the Year Award]]. While Bettis finished with 1,542 more yards than [[Franco Harris]] on the NFL's all-time rushing list, Harris remains the Steelers all-time leading rusher because 3,091 of those yards came while Bettis was with the Rams.\n\nRadio color commentator [[Myron Cope]] popularized the nickname \"'''The Bus'''\" after hearing a brother of a fellow Notre Dame alumni call Jerome \"Bussy\" in Green Bay.{{Citation needed|date=March 2012}} The nickname comes from his ability to carry multiple defenders on his back, like a bus ride, during his carries. It was during the Green Bay broadcast that Cope started using the nickname \"The Bus.\" Jerome credits the Notre Dame school newspaper with first using the nickname.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://old.post-gazette.com/steelers/20001221steele2.asp.|title=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|date=December 21, 2000|website=Post-Gazette.com|access-date=December 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAnother lesser known nickname for Bettis was \"'''The Closer'''.\" He was given this nickname by former Steeler head coach [[Bill Cowher]] because whenever Pittsburgh was ahead and was ready to close out the game, Cowher would send in Bettis to run out the clock. He did this because of Bettis's very low fumbling percentage and the fact that he was difficult to tackle.{{Citation needed|date=March 2012}}\n\n====Super Bowl XL====\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=March 2012}}\nShortly after the Steelers lost the 2004\u20132005 AFC Championship game to the eventual [[Super Bowl XXXIX]] champion [[New England Patriots]], [[Ben Roethlisberger]] approached Bettis. He promised Bettis that if he came back for one last season, he would get him to the Super Bowl. Apparently, it was this promise that got Jerome Bettis to play one last season.{{Citation needed|date=December 2017}} In 12 NFL seasons, Bettis had reached the playoffs five times, but had never been in the Super Bowl.\n\nIn week 17 of the 2005 NFL season, Bettis rushed for 41 yards and three touchdowns against the [[Detroit Lions]].<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/recap?gameId=260101023]. espn.go.com (January 1, 2006). Retrieved on August 20, 2015.</ref> The Steelers won, 35\u201321, and thanks to Bettis's three touchdowns, they clinched a playoff berth. When [[Bill Cowher]] pulled Bettis from the game late in the fourth quarter, he was given a standing ovation from the Steeler fans. This game would be the last home game (not including the neutral-site [[Super Bowl]]) for Jerome Bettis.\n\nBettis contributed 52 yards and a touchdown in the Steelers' wildcard playoff victory over the [[Cincinnati Bengals]] on January 8. After their wildcard win, Ben Roethlisberger revealed to the team that he promised to Bettis that he would get him to the Super Bowl, in order to get him to come back for the 2005 season.\n\nOn January 15, 2006, Bettis was the center of one of football's most memorable{{According to whom|date=December 2017}} endings in a divisional playoff game against the [[Indianapolis Colts]]. While the Steelers offensive attack was mostly pass driven during the game, Bettis ran well, taking in 46 yards on 17 rushes, including one touchdown. When the Steelers took possession of the ball on the Indianapolis 2-yard line with 1:20 remaining in the game, leading 21-18, the outcome seemed almost certain. The first play from scrimmage went to the surehanded Bettis, who had not fumbled once the entire year. As Bettis ran towards the end zone, Colts linebacker [[Gary Brackett]] popped the ball out of Jerome's hands, where, in seemingly another occurrence of the ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' \"cover jinx,\" it was picked up by cornerback [[Nick Harper (American football)|Nick Harper]], who was [[Pittsburgh sports lore#The Tackle|stopped from returning the fumble all the way for a touchdown]] by Steelers quarterback [[Ben Roethlisberger]]. Ultimately, however, Bettis's mistake did not result in a Steelers loss, as Colts kicker [[Mike Vanderjagt]] missed a 46-yard game-tying field goal, ending the game with a 21-18 Steelers victory.\n\nThe next week, the Steelers were set to face off against the [[Denver Broncos]] in the AFC Championship game. Bettis delivered a rousing speech to his teammates the day before the game, asking them to \"Just get me to Detroit\", his hometown, where [[Super Bowl XL]] was to be played.{{Citation needed|date=December 2017}} Bettis's wish was granted, as he and the Steelers advanced to [[Super Bowl XL]] with a 34\u201317 win over the Broncos, led by [[Ben Roethlisberger]]'s arm and Bettis's 39 yards on 15 carries, including a touchdown. After the game was over, Bettis found his parents in the crowd and mouthed the words \"We're going home\" to them.\n\n===NFL statistics===\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Team\n! colspan=\"2\"| Games \n! colspan=\"6\"| Rushing\n! colspan=\"2\"| Fumbles\n|- \n! G !! GS !! Att !! Yards !! Avg !! Long !! TD !! FD !! Fum !! Lost\n|- \n! [[1993 NFL season|1993]] !! [[1993 Los Angeles Rams season|LAR]] \n| 16 || 12 || 294 || 1,429 || '''4.9''' || '''71''' || 7 || 79 || 3 || 1\n|- \n! [[1994 NFL season|1994]] !! [[1993 Los Angeles Rams season|LAR]] \n| 16 || 16 || 319 || 1,025 || 3.2 || 19 || 3 || 53 || 5 || 3\n|- \n! [[1995 NFL season|1995]] !! [[1995 St. Louis Rams season|STL]] \n| 15 || 13 || 183 || 637 || 3.5 || 41 || 3 || 24 || 4 || 2\n|- \n! [[1996 NFL season|1996]] !! [[1996 Pittsburgh Steelers season|PIT]] \n| 16 || 12 || 320 || 1,431 || 4.5 || 50 || 11 || 76 || 6 || 4\n|- \n! [[1997 NFL season|1997]] !! [[1997 Pittsburgh Steelers season|PIT]] \n| 15 || 15 || '''375''' || '''1,665''' || 4.4 || 34 || 7 || '''94''' || '''6''' || '''6'''\n|- \n! [[1998 NFL season|1998]] !! [[1998 Pittsburgh Steelers season|PIT]] \n| 15 || 15 || 316 || 1,185 || 3.8 || 42 || 3 || 58 || 2 || 1\n|- \n! [[1999 NFL season|1999]] !! [[1999 Pittsburgh Steelers season|PIT]] \n| 16 || 16 || 299 || 1,091 || 3.6 || 35 || 7 || 64 || 2 || 1\n|- \n! [[2000 NFL season|2000]] !! [[2000 Pittsburgh Steelers season|PIT]] \n| 16 || 16 || 355 || 1,341 || 3.8 || 30 || 8 || 71 || 1 || 0\n|- \n! [[2001 NFL season|2001]] !! [[2001 Pittsburgh Steelers season|PIT]] \n| 11 || 11 || 225 || 1,072 || 4.8 || 48 || 4 || 46 || 3 || 0\n|- \n! [[2002 NFL season|2002]] !! [[2002 Pittsburgh Steelers season|PIT]] \n| 13 || 11 || 187 || 667 || 3.6 || 41 || 9 || 42 || 1 || 1\n|- \n! [[2003 NFL season|2003]] !! [[2003 Pittsburgh Steelers season|PIT]] \n| 16 || 10 || 246 || 811 || 3.3 || 21 || 7 || 43 || 4 || 4\n|- \n! [[2004 NFL season|2004]] !! [[2004 Pittsburgh Steelers season|PIT]] \n| 15 || 6 || 250 || 941 || 3.8 || 29 || '''13''' || 50 || 1 || 0\n|- \n! [[2005 NFL season|2005]] !! [[2005 Pittsburgh Steelers season|PIT]] \n| 12 || 0 || 110 || 368 || 3.3 || 39 || 9 || 30 || 0 || 0\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n! colspan=\"2\"| Career !! 192 !! 152 !! 3,479 !! 13,662 !! 3.9 !! 71 !! 91 !! 730 !! 38 !! 23\n|}<ref name=ESPN>{{cite web|title=Jerome Bettis Stats|url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/player/stats/_/id/389/jerome-bettis|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures|accessdate=March 3, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Retirement from football==\nAsked about the possibility of retirement, Bettis announced, \"I played this game  for a championship. I'm a champion, and I think the Bus' last stop is here in Detroit.\" Thus, Jerome Bettis officially announced his retirement standing on the champions' podium, holding the [[Vince Lombardi Trophy]]. [[Hines Ward]], the MVP of the game, said during the Super Bowl commercial, \"[[I'm Going to Disney World!|I'm going to Disney World]] and I'm taking '''''The Bus'''''!\"\n\nAlthough the Steelers have not officially retired Bettis' #36, they have not reissued it since his retirement and it is understood that no Steeler will ever wear it again. His number joins a list of other unofficially retired numbers such as those of [[Terry Bradshaw]], [[Franco Harris]], and [[Hines Ward]].\n\nOn January 31, 2006, [[List of mayors of Detroit|Detroit Mayor]] [[Kwame Kilpatrick]] and the City Council presented the [[key to the city]] to Bettis and declared the week \"Jerome Bettis Week\" for being \"a shining example of what a kid with a dream from Detroit can accomplish with hard work and determination.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=fWMyAAAAIBAJ&sjid=iLUFAAAAIBAJ&pg=6318%2C156178 |title=Officially, today is Jerome Bettis Day |work=Beaver County Times |date=February 1, 2006}}</ref> Jerome moved to [[Atlanta, Georgia]] at the end of his career and is currently living there.{{Citation needed|date=March 2012}}\n\nGovernor [[Jennifer M. Granholm]] of the State of [[Michigan]] declared February 1, 2006 to be Jerome Bettis Day.<ref>[http://www.michigan.gov/gov/0,1607,7-168-23442_25488-136253--,00.html Jerome Bettis Day] Proclamations, Michigan.gov</ref>\n\nOn May 21, 2006, Bettis received an honorary Doctoral degree from [[Lawrence Technological University]] in Southfield, Michigan.\n\nBefore the Steelers' home opener of the [[2006 NFL season]], a large school bus drove onto the field, and Bettis stepped out to a massive crowd ovation.  He was one of several Steelers players being honored as part of the celebration of their five Super Bowl victories; [[Lynn Swann]] and [[Franco Harris]] were also present.\n\n==Post-football career==\n[[File:Bettis 2011-02-19.jpg|thumb|Bettis speaking at a sports convention.]]\nIn February 2006, at the 2006 Winter Olympics, [[NBC Sports]] announced that Bettis had been signed as a studio commentator for NBC's new [[Football Night in America]] Sunday night pregame show where he was through the 2008 season.\n{{wikinews|Pittsburgh's Bettis to work as NBC studio analyst}}\n\nIn April 2006, Bettis and his parents teamed up with Don Barden, the head of PITG Gaming LLC, in a bid for a casino on Pittsburgh's [[Northside (Pittsburgh)|Northside]] to be called the Majestic Star. Their plan would aid the [[National Hockey League|NHL]]'s [[Pittsburgh Penguins]] with funding for a new ice arena.  Barden said that he would give $7.5 million a year for 30 years to help build a new arena.<ref>[https://www.tsn.ca/nhl/news_story/?ID=163073&hubname= Bettis joins bid for new Pittsburgh arena] Associated Press article at tsn.ca, April 18, 2006</ref>\n\nBettis opened a restaurant called \"Jerome Bettis' Grille 36\" on June 5, 2007 on Pittsburgh's Northside.<ref>[http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/07151/790197-46.stm Jerome Bettis Grille 36 opens Tuesday on N. Side] Pittsburgh Post-Gazette, Dining Guide, May 31, 2007</ref><ref>[http://www.postgazette.com/pg/06192/704864-66.stm Bettis' Grille 36 in the works] Pittsburgh Post-Gazette, Sports, July 11, 2007</ref>\n\nBettis makes a cameo as himself in the episode [[The Convention (The Office)|The Convention]] of season 3 of the NBC comedy series ''[[The Office (US TV series)|The Office]]''. Signing autographs at a paper convention, [[Michael Scott (The Office)|Michael Scott]] tries to invite him to a room party, which Bettis declines. Later, Michael claims Bettis is nicknamed \"The Bus\" because he is afraid of flying.\n\nIn 2010, Bettis joined [[School of the Legends]] (SOTL), an [[online community]] and partner of the [[NFLPA]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Veteran Running Backs Offer Rookies Advice in Exclusive School of the Legends Interview |publisher=Business Wire |date=June 3, 2011 |url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20110603005764/en/Veteran-Running-Backs-Offer-Rookies-Advice-Exclusive |accessdate=December 6, 2011 |archiveurl = http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20110603005764/en/Veteran-Running-Backs-Offer-Rookies-Advice-Exclusive |archivedate = December 6, 2011}}</ref> He was featured in an article on the D1 Training website in February 2011 and filmed training courses for SOTL that focused on his position as a running back.<ref>{{cite web |title=Jerome Bettis Stops by D1 |publisher=D1SportingTraining|date=February 21, 2011 |url=http://d1sportstraining.blogspot.com/2011/02/jerome-bettis-stops-by-d1.html }}</ref>\n\nBettis is currently the host of ''The Jerome Bettis Show'' on [[WPXI-TV]], filmed at [[Heinz Field]] in Pittsburgh, airing Saturdays at 7:00 PM and 1:00 AM. He was a commentator for the [[NFL Network]] and a former NBC studio analyst for ''[[Football Night in America]].''  Now he is an NFL analyst for different [[ESPN]] programs, such as [[SportsCenter]].\n\nThe Jerome Bettis Bus Stops Here Foundation and other agencies sponsor the Jerome Bettis Asthma and Sports Camp annually for children with asthma.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jerome Bettis Hosts Children's Asthma Sports Camp At Heinz Field|url=http://www.wpxi.com/news/entertainment/jerome-bettis-hosts-childrens-asthma-sports-camp-a/nGprt/|newspaper=WPXI|date=July 22, 2010}}</ref> Bettis has also delivered over 1000 pairs of cleats to children in the Detroit school system.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Evans |first1=Gavin |title=Where Are They Now? Your Favorite NFL Players of the '90s |url=https://www.complex.com/sports/2013/09/nfl-players-90s-where-are-they-now/jerome-bettis |website=Complex |accessdate=August 20, 2018 |date=September 11, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAfter falling short as a finalist in 2013,<ref>{{cite news|title=Parcells, Carter finally make Pro Football Hall of Fame|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/2013/02/02/nfl-hall-of-fame-announcement/1886453/|newspaper=USA Today|accessdate=February 2, 2013|first1=Jim|last1=Corbett|date=February 2, 2013}}</ref> on January 31, 2015, Bettis was voted into The [[Pro Football Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Pro Football Hall of Fame: Jerome Bettis among the 2015 class|url=http://www.cbssports.com/nfl/eye-on-football/25013699/pro-football-hall-of-fame-jerome-bettis-among-the-2015-class|work=CBSSports.com|accessdate=January 31, 2015|first1=Igor|last1=Mello|date=January 31, 2015}}</ref>  Bettis returned to NBC to help [[Bob Costas]] preside over the [[Vince Lombardi Trophy]] presentation at the end of [[Super Bowl XLIX]] on February 1, 2015.\n\nBettis starred in a Geico commercial in 2019, playing a running back in flag football that dominates the competition (49-0).\n\n==Personal life==\nBettis had made political donations to both [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] and [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] candidates; specifically the Congressional campaign of Democratic [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] [[Carolyn Cheeks Kilpatrick]], and the 2004 campaign of Republican [[President of the United States|President]] [[George W. Bush]].<ref name=BettisPoliticalDonations>[http://www.newsmeat.com/sports_political_donations/Jerome_Bettis.php Jerome Bettis] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080406013053/http://www.newsmeat.com/sports_political_donations/Jerome_Bettis.php |date=April 6, 2008 }}, Newsmeat.com, ''Accessed March 31, 2008.''</ref>  On March 29, 2008, Bettis accompanied [[Barack Obama]] on a campaign visit to the [[US Steel]] plant in Braddock, Pennsylvania.<ref>Michael David Smith, [http://sports.aol.com/fanhouse/2008/03/29/barack-obamas-pennsylvania-strategy-appear-with-franco-harris/ Barack Obama's Pennsylvania Strategy: Appear With Franco Harris, Jerome Bettis], ''Accessed March 31, 2008.''</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{Profootballhof|id=296|name=Jerome Bettis}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081011174133/http://www.wpxi.com/jeromebettisshow/ The Jerome Bettis Show on WPXI]\n* [http://www.thebus36.com/ The Bus Stops Here Foundation]\n* {{Footballstats |nfl=BET627285 |espn=389 |cbs= |yahoo=2354 |si=2354 |pfr=B/BettJe00 |rotoworld=699}}\n\n{{1993 NFL Draft}}\n{{RamsFirstPick}}\n{{Los Angeles Rams 1993 draft navbox}}\n{{AP Offensive Rookies of the Year}}\n{{NFL Comeback Players of the Year}}\n{{Walter Payton Man of the Year Award}}\n{{Super Bowl XL}}\n{{10,000 rushing yards club}}\n{{Pittsburgh Steelers All-Time Team}}\n{{Pittsburgh Steelers}}\n{{2015 Football HOF}}\n{{Pro Football Hall of Fame members}}\n{{Walter Camp Man of the Year}}\n{{Football Night in America}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bettis, Jerome}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American Conference Pro Bowl players]]\n[[Category:American drug traffickers]]\n[[Category:American football running backs]]\n[[Category:American ten-pin bowling players]]\n[[Category:Los Angeles Rams players]]\n[[Category:National Conference Pro Bowl players]]\n[[Category:National Football League announcers]]\n[[Category:National Football League Offensive Rookie of the Year Award winners]]\n[[Category:Notre Dame Fighting Irish football players]]\n[[Category:Pittsburgh Steelers players]]\n[[Category:People from Roswell, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Michigan]]\n[[Category:Pro Football Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Detroit]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Fulton County, Georgia]]\n[[Category:St. Louis Rams players]]\n[[Category:Super Bowl champions]]\n[[Category:Bowling broadcasters]]\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish|Jerrod Bettis}}\n{{short description|American football running back}}\n{{Use American English|date=December 2017}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n| name = Jerome Bettis\n| image = Jerome Bettis 2016.jpg\n| caption = Bettis in February 2016\n| number = 36\n| position = [[Running back]]\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1972|02|16|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Detroit|Detroit, Michigan]]\n| height_ft = 5\n| height_in = 11\n| weight_lbs = 255\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| high_school = [[Mackenzie High School (Michigan)|Detroit (MI) Mackenzie]]\n| college = [[Notre Dame Fighting Irish football|Notre Dame]]\n| draftyear = 1993\n| draftround = 1\n| draftpick = 10\n| pastteams =\n* [[Los Angeles Rams|Los Angeles / St. Louis Rams]] ([[1993 NFL season|1993]]\u2013[[1995 NFL season|1995]])\n* [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] ([[1996 NFL season|1996]]\u2013[[2005 NFL season|2005]])\n|highlights=\n* [[Super Bowl]] champion ([[Super Bowl XL|XL]])\n* 6\u00d7 [[Pro Bowl]] ([[1994 Pro Bowl|1993]], [[1995 Pro Bowl|1994]], [[1997 Pro Bowl|1996]], [[1998 Pro Bowl|1997]], [[2002 Pro Bowl|2001]], [[2005 Pro Bowl|2004]])\n* 2\u00d7 First-team [[All-Pro]] ([[1993 All-Pro Team|1993]], [[1996 All-Pro Team|1996]])\n* Second-team All-Pro ([[1997 All-Pro Team|1997]])\n* [[Walter Payton NFL Man of the Year]] (2001)\n* [[NFL Comeback Player of the Year]] (1996)\n* [[NFL Offensive Rookie of the Year]] (1993)\n* [[Pittsburgh Steelers All-Time Team]]\n| statlabel1 = Rushing yards\n| statvalue1 = 13,664\n| statlabel2 = Yards per carry\n| statvalue2 = 3.9\n| statlabel3 = Rushing touchdowns\n| statvalue3 = 91\n| statlabel4 = Receptions\n| statvalue4 = 200\n| statlabel5 = Receiving yards\n| statvalue5 = 1,457\n| statlabel6 = Receiving touchdowns\n| statvalue6 = 3\n| nfl = BET627285\n| pfr = B/BettJe00\n| HOF = jerome-bettis\n}}\n'''Jerome Abram Bettis Sr.''' (born February 24 1972), nicknamed '''The Bus''', is a former [[American football]] [[running back|halfback]] who played for the [[Los Angeles Rams|Los Angeles Rams/St. Louis Rams]] and [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL). Bettis is eighth on the [[List of National Football League rushing yards leaders|list of NFL rushing yards leaders]]. He retired in 2006 after he won [[Super Bowl XL]] with the Steelers in his native [[Detroit]], [[Michigan]], beating the [[Seattle Seahawks]]. Bettis was inducted into the [[Pro Football Hall of Fame]] in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jerome Bettis elected to Pro Football Hall of Fame|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/sports/steelers/2015/01/31/Steelers-champion-Jerome-Bettis-elected-to-Pro-Football-Hall-of-Fame/stories/201501310191|work=Ed Bouchette|publisher=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]|access-date=January 31, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nBettis was born February 16, 1972, in [[Detroit]], [[Michigan]]. He is the oldest of three children of Gladys Elizabeth (n\u00e9e Bougard) and Johnnie E. Bettis.<ref>Stated on ''[[Who Do You Think You Are? (U.S. TV series)|Who Do You Think You Are?]]'', March 9, 2012</ref> Bettis did not start playing football until high school, as his primary passion as a youth had been [[bowling]]. At age 14, he was diagnosed with asthma.<ref>{{cite web|title=Biography|url=http://www.webmd.com/jerome-bettis|work=Jerome Bettis|publisher=WebMD|access-date=November 25, 2012}}</ref> As a youth in Detroit, Bettis and his brother made ends meet by selling [[crack cocaine]].<ref name=crack>{{cite news|last1=Jahnke|first1=James|title=Jerome Bettis: I sold crack, shot at people in Detroit|url=http://www.freep.com/story/sports/nfl/2015/07/23/jerome-bettis-detroit/30566969/|access-date=July 24, 2015|work=[[Detroit Free Press]]|date=July 24, 2015}}</ref> He attended [[Mackenzie High School (Michigan)|Mackenzie High School]] in Detroit, where he was a standout running back and [[linebacker]]. As a senior, he was rated the top player in the state by the ''[[Detroit Free Press]]'', and was the [[Gatorade]] Circle of Champions Player of the Year award winner.\n\n==College career==\nAt the [[University of Notre Dame]], Bettis finished his career with 337 rushing attempts for 1,912 yards (5.7 yards per attempt), and made 32 receptions for 429 yards (13.4 yards per reception). In his last game as a junior, a 28-3 win by Notre Dame over Texas A&M in the [[1993 Cotton Bowl]], he rushed 20 times for 75 yards, ran for two touchdowns and caught a 26-yard touchdown pass. In his sophomore year, he set the Notre Dame touchdown record with 20 in one season, with 16 rushing, and 4 receiving (23 total touchdowns including the [[1992 Sugar Bowl]], a record which still stands).\n\n*1990: 15 carries for 115 yards and 1 touchdown.<ref>[http://www.totalfootballstats.com/PlayerRB.asp?id=316 Jerome Bettis College & Pro Football Statistics]. Totalfootballstats.com. Retrieved on July 23, 2013.</ref>\n*1991: 168 carries for 972 yards and 16 touchdowns. 17 catches for 190 yards and 4 touchdowns.\n*1992: 154 carries for 825 yards and 10 touchdowns. 15 catches for 239 yards and 6 touchdowns.\n\nBettis did not graduate from college.<ref name=\"nytimes.com\">Jenkins, Lee (February 4, 2006). [https://www.nytimes.com/2006/02/04/sports/football/04bettis.html?_r=0 \"With That Old College Retry, Bettis Revived His Career\"]. ''The New York Times''. Retrieved January 13, 2017.</ref> He skipped his senior year at [[University of Notre Dame|Notre Dame]] to enter the [[1993 NFL Draft]]. He returned to [[University of Notre Dame|Notre Dame]] in 1996 when he was having a dispute with the [[St. Louis Rams]] and was considering retirement. He took courses in \"history, philosophy, marketing and business\" totalling a heavy 18 credit class load.<ref name=\"nytimes.com\"/> He returned to the [[NFL]] shortly thereafter, and \"he has not returned to Notre Dame to finish the coursework for his degree.\"<ref name=\"nytimes.com\"/>\n\n==Professional career==\n===Los Angeles and St. Louis Rams===\nBettis was picked in the first round (10th overall) of the [[1993 NFL Draft]] by the [[Los Angeles Rams]]. On July 22, 1993, Bettis signed a three-year, $4.625 million contract with a signing bonus in excess of $2 million.<ref>[[T. J. Simers|Simers, J.T.]] (July 23, 1993). \"Rams Reach Agreement With Bettis Football: No. 1 pick expected to sign and practice today\".\n[https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/60346522.html?dids=60346522:60346522&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Jul+23%2C+1993&author=T.J.+SIMERS&pub=Los+Angeles+Times+(pre-1997+Fulltext)&desc=Rams+Reach+Agreement+With+Bettis+Football%3A+No.+1+pick+expected+to+sign+and+practice+today.+Trade+talks+involve+Cleveland+Gary.&pqatl=google Los Angeles Times] Retrieved September 10, 2010.</ref> As a rookie, he flourished under [[Chuck Knox]]'s ground-oriented offense.  He quickly earned the nickname \"The Battering Ram\" as he rushed for 1,429 yards (second in the NFL), drawing comparisons to [[Earl Campbell]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1993-12-08/sports/sp-65186_1_jerome-bettis|title=Bettis' Pounding Runs Haven't Rescued Rams :  NFL: Rookie running back is gaining yards and attention, but the offense remains ineffective because of a shoddy passing attack.|first=T. J.|last=SIMERS|date=December 8, 1993|publisher=|access-date=December 25, 2017|via=LA Times}}</ref> Bettis also had an NFL-best 79 rushing first downs and an NFL-best 38 runs of 10 or more yards, and tied for the league lead with seven 100-yard rushing games despite not becoming the full-time starter until the sixth game of the season. Bettis was named a First-Team [[1993 All-Pro Team|All-Pro]] (the only rookie named to the team) and Consensus [[NFL Rookie of the Year Award|NFL Offensive Rookie of the Year]]. He rushed for over 1,000 yards and was selected for the NFC's [[Pro Bowl]] team in each of his first two seasons with the Rams.\n\nThe Rams moved to [[St. Louis]] for the [[1995 NFL season|1995 season]]. New coach [[Rich Brooks]] instituted a more pass-oriented offense, a major reason why Bettis was limited to 637 yards,<ref>{{cite web|title=Pro Football Hall of Fame: Steelers' Jerome Bettis redefined big, quick RBs|url=http://www.cbssports.com/nfl/eye-on-football/25260852/nfl-hall-of-fame-steelers-jerome-bettis-redefined-big-quick-rbs|work=Ryan Wilson|publisher=[[CBSSports.com]]|accessdate=February 8, 2016}}</ref> a significant dropoff from his 1993 and 1994 totals. Brooks asked Bettis whether he wanted to move to fullback for the upcoming 1996 season or preferred to be traded. Bettis stated he thought he could still help an NFL team with his running.\n\nOn April 20, 1996, Bettis was traded to the Pittsburgh Steelers with a third-round pick in the [[1996 NFL Draft]], in exchange for the Steelers' second-round pick and their fourth-round pick in the [[1997 NFL Draft]].<ref>Clarochi, Paul (April 21, 1996), \"Steelers Bet on Bettis to Fill RB Void\".[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=wIkyAAAAIBAJ&sjid=TLYFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1859,4370381&dq=bettis+traded&hl=en Beaver County Times] Retrieved September 12, 2010.</ref> The Rams gave Bettis the option of which team he wanted to be traded to, and he chose the Steelers over their [[AFC North|AFC Central]] [[Steelers-Titans rivalry|rival]] [[Tennessee Titans|Houston Oilers]] (who would draft [[Eddie George]] that year instead) due to the Steelers more storied history.<ref>https://m.youtube.com/watch?feature=youtu.be&v=i8LfQvT0b-0</ref>\n\nIn exchange for Bettis, the Rams drafted [[Ernie Conwell]] (second round of 1996 draft) and also received the Steelers fourth-round pick in 1997.  In 1997, the Rams had multiple trade deals including moving up to the number 1 draft slot to draft [[Orlando Pace]]. The Rams traded their fourth-round pick from the Steelers to the Dolphins along with two sixth-round picks, in order to move up nine slots and draft offensive tackle [[Ryan Tucker]]. The Steelers drafted [[Steve Conley]] (third round of 1996 draft) with the draft selection they acquired from the Bettis trade with the Rams. Conley was traded to the Colts two seasons later for a fifth-round pick.\n\n===Pittsburgh Steelers===\nThe Steelers were in need of a running back because [[Bam Morris]], their power running back for the 1994 and 1995 seasons, was arrested in March 1996 for marijuana possession.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1996-03-27/sports/9603270102_1_drug-charges-assault-charge-morris.|title=Steelers' Morris Indicted On Drug Charges|date=March 27, 1996|website=ChicagoTribune.com|access-date=December 25, 2017}}</ref> The Steelers traded for Bettis on the day of the [[1996 NFL Draft]]. Morris eventually pleaded guilty to marijuana possession and was cut by the team in June 1996, leaving Bettis as the featured back. In his first season in Pittsburgh, Bettis rushed for a then career-high 1,431 yards and 11 touchdowns and was named to his second 1st team [[1996 All-Pro Team|All-Pro]] team. He also won the [[NFL Comeback Player of the Year]], NFL Alumni Running Back of the Year, was voted Steelers' team MVP and finished the 1996 season as the leader in [[Football Outsiders]] rushing [[Football Outsiders#DYAR|DYAR]] [[advanced metrics|metric]].<ref>[http://www.footballoutsiders.com/stats/rb1996] Footballoutsiders.com. Retrieved on September 13, 2017.</ref>\n\nBettis rushed for over 1,000 yards in each of his first six seasons with the Steelers between 1996 and 2001. Included in that run were three campaigns of over 1,300 yards. In 1997, Bettis rushed for a career-best 1,665 yards in the team's first 15 games. However, because the team had already wrapped up its playoff position, he was rested for the regular-season finale and finished 26 yards short of the team's single-season record. Bettis does hold the Steelers' franchise record for rushing yards in a single-season when including postseason play.<ref>[https://www.pro-football-reference.com/play-index/pgl_finder.cgi?request=1&match=single&year_min=1950&year_max=2017&season_start=1&season_end=-1&pos=0&game_type=E&team_id=pit&career_game_num_min=1&career_game_num_max=400&game_num_min=0&game_num_max=99&week_num_min=0&week_num_max=99&c5val=1.0&order_by=rush_yds] Pro-Football-Reference.com.</ref> Bettis was a second-team All-Pro choice in 1997 and set a then NFL record with two overtime touchdowns in the same season.\n\nBettis was leading the league with 1,072 rushing yards in 2001 when he suffered a serious hip and groin injury that sidelined him for the remainder of the regular season. Injuries would also cost him significant parts of the 2002 season and he then began the 2003 season as a backup to [[Amos Zereou\u00e9]]. Despite regaining his starting role midway through the 2003 season, Bettis again found himself a backup to start the 2004 season, this time to free-agent acquisition [[Duce Staley]]. But when an injury took Staley out of action midway through the year, Bettis stepped in and gained 100-plus yards in six of the next eight games, and in seven consecutive starts. The late season effort led to the sixth Pro-Bowl berth of his career.\n\nBettis spent the 2005 season as a short-yardage running back, but managed two notable games along the way: First, a 101-yard, two touchdown effort in a pivotal week 14 win over Chicago (his second-to-last game in Pittsburgh).  This game included a play in which he ran over Bears' safety [[Mike Green (defensive back)|Mike Green]] and the NFL's [[Associated Press NFL Defensive Player of the Year Award|Defensive Player of the Year]] linebacker [[Brian Urlacher]] on the goal line during a heavy snow squall. Secondly, he scored three touchdowns in a win over Detroit to clinch a playoff berth on the last day of the season, which was his last game in Pittsburgh. He finished the season and his career as the NFL's 5th leading all-time [[Rush (American football)|rusher]].\n\nBettis was also at the center of one of the most controversial calls in NFL history. During a Thanksgiving Day game with the [[Detroit Lions]] on November 26, 1998, Bettis was sent out as the Steelers representative for the overtime coin toss. Bettis appeared to call \"tails\" while the coin was in the air but referee [[Phil Luckett]] declared that Bettis called \"heads\" and awarded possession to Detroit, who would go on to win the game before Pittsburgh had the chance to have possession. After reviewing the incident, the NFL changed the rule and declared that the call of \"heads\" or \"tails\" would be made before the coin was tossed rather than during the coin toss and that at least two officials would be present during the coin toss. The readers of ESPN voted the incident as No. 8 on its list of the ten worst sports officiating calls of all time, even though later sound enhancements of the audio showed that Bettis said \"hea-tails\" and Bettis admitted starting to call \"heads\" before changing it to tails.<ref>[http://espn.go.com/page2/s/list/readers/worstcalls.html The Readers' List:Worst calls in history]. ESPN. August 27, 2001. Retrieved on 2013-07-23.</ref>  Immediately after the incident, however, Bettis commented \"I did not say 'heads-tails.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/11/27/sports/pro-football-heads-tails-referee-chooses-then-steelers-lose.html|title=PRO FOOTBALL; 'Heads'? 'Tails'? Referee Chooses, Then Steelers Lose|date=November 27, 1998|publisher=|access-date=December 25, 2017|work=New York Times|agency=Associated Press}}</ref> Bettis later put together one of the most bizarre single-game statistics in NFL history. In the 2004 season opener, he carried the ball five times for a total of only one yard, a 0.2 yards per carry average.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/nfl/boxscore?gameId=240912023.|title=NFL Football Scores - NFL Scoreboard - ESPN|date=September 12, 2004|website=ESPN.com|access-date=December 25, 2017}}</ref> However, he scored 18 points on those carries with three touchdowns.\n\nDuring that 2004 season, Bettis and [[New York Jets]] running back [[Curtis Martin]] dueled for position on the all-time rushing yards leaderboard. Bettis entered the season in 6th place all-time and 684 yards ahead of Martin in 9th place. Because Bettis was the backup in Pittsburgh for the start of the season, Martin was able to pass Bettis in week 13 until the Steelers played their game later in the day and Bettis retook the lead by 6 yards. When the Jets traveled to Martin's home town of Pittsburgh to play the Steelers the following week, both backs would cross the 13,000-yard mark, making this the first time two players crossed the 13,000 yard mark (or other similarly high yardage milestones) in the same game. Their combined career totals were also one of the biggest combined career totals for opposing running backs in history. At the end of the game, Martin would lead Bettis by 9 yards. Two weeks later in week 16, Bettis would again pass Martin and establish himself with a lead of 81 yards. In doing so, Bettis passed [[Eric Dickerson]] for 4th place on the all-time list. Bettis sat out the final week of the season, and when Martin rushed for 153 yards that week he passed Dickerson and Bettis for the final time.\n\nAfter the Steelers' defeat in the [[NFL playoffs, 2004\u201305|2004 AFC Championship Game]] on January 23, 2005, Bettis announced that he was considering retirement, but would not make a final decision for several months to prevent the sting of the defeat from clouding his judgment. Later, Bettis agreed to stay with the Steelers for another season. He stated he would love to play in the [[Super Bowl]] in 2006 since it was to be played in his hometown of Detroit. His wish came true as the Steelers played in, and won, [[Super Bowl XL]] (40) against the [[Seattle Seahawks]], 21\u201310, on February 5, 2006.\n\nBettis finished his 13 NFL seasons as the NFL's 5th all-time leading rusher with 13,662 yards and 91 touchdowns. He also caught 200 passes for 1,449 yards and 3 touchdowns and threw 3 career touchdown passes. He was named to the [[Pro Bowl]] in 1993, 1994, 1996, 1997, 2001, and 2004. Bettis won the [[NFL Comeback Player of the Year]] award in 1996, and in 2002 he was the recipient of the [[Walter Payton Man of the Year Award]]. While Bettis finished with 1,542 more yards than [[Franco Harris]] on the NFL's all-time rushing list, Harris remains the Steelers all-time leading rusher because 3,091 of those yards came while Bettis was with the Rams.\n\nRadio color commentator [[Myron Cope]] popularized the nickname \"'''The Bus'''\" after hearing a brother of a fellow Notre Dame alumni call Jerome \"Bussy\" in Green Bay.{{Citation needed|date=March 2012}} The nickname comes from his ability to carry multiple defenders on his back, like a bus ride, during his carries. It was during the Green Bay broadcast that Cope started using the nickname \"The Bus.\" Jerome credits the Notre Dame school newspaper with first using the nickname.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://old.post-gazette.com/steelers/20001221steele2.asp.|title=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|date=December 21, 2000|website=Post-Gazette.com|access-date=December 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAnother lesser known nickname for Bettis was \"'''The Closer'''.\" He was given this nickname by former Steeler head coach [[Bill Cowher]] because whenever Pittsburgh was ahead and was ready to close out the game, Cowher would send in Bettis to run out the clock. He did this because of Bettis's very low fumbling percentage and the fact that he was difficult to tackle.{{Citation needed|date=March 2012}}\n\n====Super Bowl XL====\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=March 2012}}\nShortly after the Steelers lost the 2004\u20132005 AFC Championship game to the eventual [[Super Bowl XXXIX]] champion [[New England Patriots]], [[Ben Roethlisberger]] approached Bettis. He promised Bettis that if he came back for one last season, he would get him to the Super Bowl. Apparently, it was this promise that got Jerome Bettis to play one last season.{{Citation needed|date=December 2017}} In 12 NFL seasons, Bettis had reached the playoffs five times, but had never been in the Super Bowl.\n\nIn week 17 of the 2005 NFL season, Bettis rushed for 41 yards and three touchdowns against the [[Detroit Lions]].<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/recap?gameId=260101023]. espn.go.com (January 1, 2006). Retrieved on August 20, 2015.</ref> The Steelers won, 35\u201321, and thanks to Bettis's three touchdowns, they clinched a playoff berth. When [[Bill Cowher]] pulled Bettis from the game late in the fourth quarter, he was given a standing ovation from the Steeler fans. This game would be the last home game (not including the neutral-site [[Super Bowl]]) for Jerome Bettis.\n\nBettis contributed 52 yards and a touchdown in the Steelers' wildcard playoff victory over the [[Cincinnati Bengals]] on January 8. After their wildcard win, Ben Roethlisberger revealed to the team that he promised to Bettis that he would get him to the Super Bowl, in order to get him to come back for the 2005 season.\n\nOn January 15, 2006, Bettis was the center of one of football's most memorable{{According to whom|date=December 2017}} endings in a divisional playoff game against the [[Indianapolis Colts]]. While the Steelers offensive attack was mostly pass driven during the game, Bettis ran well, taking in 46 yards on 17 rushes, including one touchdown. When the Steelers took possession of the ball on the Indianapolis 2-yard line with 1:20 remaining in the game, leading 21-18, the outcome seemed almost certain. The first play from scrimmage went to the surehanded Bettis, who had not fumbled once the entire year. As Bettis ran towards the end zone, Colts linebacker [[Gary Brackett]] popped the ball out of Jerome's hands, where, in seemingly another occurrence of the ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' \"cover jinx,\" it was picked up by cornerback [[Nick Harper (American football)|Nick Harper]], who was [[Pittsburgh sports lore#The Tackle|stopped from returning the fumble all the way for a touchdown]] by Steelers quarterback [[Ben Roethlisberger]]. Ultimately, however, Bettis's mistake did not result in a Steelers loss, as Colts kicker [[Mike Vanderjagt]] missed a 46-yard game-tying field goal, ending the game with a 21-18 Steelers victory.\n\nThe next week, the Steelers were set to face off against the [[Denver Broncos]] in the AFC Championship game. Bettis delivered a rousing speech to his teammates the day before the game, asking them to \"Just get me to Detroit\", his hometown, where [[Super Bowl XL]] was to be played.{{Citation needed|date=December 2017}} Bettis's wish was granted, as he and the Steelers advanced to [[Super Bowl XL]] with a 34\u201317 win over the Broncos, led by [[Ben Roethlisberger]]'s arm and Bettis's 39 yards on 15 carries, including a touchdown. After the game was over, Bettis found his parents in the crowd and mouthed the words \"We're going home\" to them.\n\n===NFL statistics===\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Team\n! colspan=\"2\"| Games \n! colspan=\"6\"| Rushing\n! colspan=\"2\"| Fumbles\n|- \n! G !! GS !! Att !! Yards !! Avg !! Long !! TD !! FD !! Fum !! Lost\n|- \n! [[1993 NFL season|1993]] !! [[1993 Los Angeles Rams season|LAR]] \n| 16 || 12 || 294 || 1,429 || '''4.9''' || '''71''' || 7 || 79 || 3 || 1\n|- \n! [[1994 NFL season|1994]] !! [[1993 Los Angeles Rams season|LAR]] \n| 16 || 16 || 319 || 1,025 || 3.2 || 19 || 3 || 53 || 5 || 3\n|- \n! [[1995 NFL season|1995]] !! [[1995 St. Louis Rams season|STL]] \n| 15 || 13 || 183 || 637 || 3.5 || 41 || 3 || 24 || 4 || 2\n|- \n! [[1996 NFL season|1996]] !! [[1996 Pittsburgh Steelers season|PIT]] \n| 16 || 12 || 320 || 1,431 || 4.5 || 50 || 11 || 76 || 6 || 4\n|- \n! [[1997 NFL season|1997]] !! [[1997 Pittsburgh Steelers season|PIT]] \n| 15 || 15 || '''375''' || '''1,665''' || 4.4 || 34 || 7 || '''94''' || '''6''' || '''6'''\n|- \n! [[1998 NFL season|1998]] !! [[1998 Pittsburgh Steelers season|PIT]] \n| 15 || 15 || 316 || 1,185 || 3.8 || 42 || 3 || 58 || 2 || 1\n|- \n! [[1999 NFL season|1999]] !! [[1999 Pittsburgh Steelers season|PIT]] \n| 16 || 16 || 299 || 1,091 || 3.6 || 35 || 7 || 64 || 2 || 1\n|- \n! [[2000 NFL season|2000]] !! [[2000 Pittsburgh Steelers season|PIT]] \n| 16 || 16 || 355 || 1,341 || 3.8 || 30 || 8 || 71 || 1 || 0\n|- \n! [[2001 NFL season|2001]] !! [[2001 Pittsburgh Steelers season|PIT]] \n| 11 || 11 || 225 || 1,072 || 4.8 || 48 || 4 || 46 || 3 || 0\n|- \n! [[2002 NFL season|2002]] !! [[2002 Pittsburgh Steelers season|PIT]] \n| 13 || 11 || 187 || 667 || 3.6 || 41 || 9 || 42 || 1 || 1\n|- \n! [[2003 NFL season|2003]] !! [[2003 Pittsburgh Steelers season|PIT]] \n| 16 || 10 || 246 || 811 || 3.3 || 21 || 7 || 43 || 4 || 4\n|- \n! [[2004 NFL season|2004]] !! [[2004 Pittsburgh Steelers season|PIT]] \n| 15 || 6 || 250 || 941 || 3.8 || 29 || '''13''' || 50 || 1 || 0\n|- \n! [[2005 NFL season|2005]] !! [[2005 Pittsburgh Steelers season|PIT]] \n| 12 || 0 || 110 || 368 || 3.3 || 39 || 9 || 30 || 0 || 0\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n! colspan=\"2\"| Career !! 192 !! 152 !! 3,479 !! 13,662 !! 3.9 !! 71 !! 91 !! 730 !! 38 !! 23\n|}<ref name=ESPN>{{cite web|title=Jerome Bettis Stats|url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/player/stats/_/id/389/jerome-bettis|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures|accessdate=March 3, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Retirement from football==\nAsked about the possibility of retirement, Bettis announced, \"I played this game  for a championship. I'm a champion, and I think the Bus' last stop is here in Detroit.\" Thus, Jerome Bettis officially announced his retirement standing on the champions' podium, holding the [[Vince Lombardi Trophy]]. [[Hines Ward]], the MVP of the game, said during the Super Bowl commercial, \"[[I'm Going to Disney World!|I'm going to Disney World]] and I'm taking '''''The Bus'''''!\"\n\nAlthough the Steelers have not officially retired Bettis' #36, they have not reissued it since his retirement and it is understood that no Steeler will ever wear it again. His number joins a list of other unofficially retired numbers such as those of [[Terry Bradshaw]], [[Franco Harris]], and [[Hines Ward]].\n\nOn January 31, 2006, [[List of mayors of Detroit|Detroit Mayor]] [[Kwame Kilpatrick]] and the City Council presented the [[key to the city]] to Bettis and declared the week \"Jerome Bettis Week\" for being \"a shining example of what a kid with a dream from Detroit can accomplish with hard work and determination.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=fWMyAAAAIBAJ&sjid=iLUFAAAAIBAJ&pg=6318%2C156178 |title=Officially, today is Jerome Bettis Day |work=Beaver County Times |date=February 1, 2006}}</ref> Jerome moved to [[Atlanta, Georgia]] at the end of his career and is currently living there.{{Citation needed|date=March 2012}}\n\nGovernor [[Jennifer M. Granholm]] of the State of [[Michigan]] declared February 1, 2006 to be Jerome Bettis Day.<ref>[http://www.michigan.gov/gov/0,1607,7-168-23442_25488-136253--,00.html Jerome Bettis Day] Proclamations, Michigan.gov</ref>\n\nOn May 21, 2006, Bettis received an honorary Doctoral degree from [[Lawrence Technological University]] in Southfield, Michigan.\n\nBefore the Steelers' home opener of the [[2006 NFL season]], a large school bus drove onto the field, and Bettis stepped out to a massive crowd ovation.  He was one of several Steelers players being honored as part of the celebration of their five Super Bowl victories; [[Lynn Swann]] and [[Franco Harris]] were also present.\n\n==Post-football career==\n[[File:Bettis 2011-02-19.jpg|thumb|Bettis speaking at a sports convention.]]\nIn February 2006, at the 2006 Winter Olympics, [[NBC Sports]] announced that Bettis had been signed as a studio commentator for NBC's new [[Football Night in America]] Sunday night pregame show where he was through the 2008 season.\n{{wikinews|Pittsburgh's Bettis to work as NBC studio analyst}}\n\nIn April 2006, Bettis and his parents teamed up with Don Barden, the head of PITG Gaming LLC, in a bid for a casino on Pittsburgh's [[Northside (Pittsburgh)|Northside]] to be called the Majestic Star. Their plan would aid the [[National Hockey League|NHL]]'s [[Pittsburgh Penguins]] with funding for a new ice arena.  Barden said that he would give $7.5 million a year for 30 years to help build a new arena.<ref>[https://www.tsn.ca/nhl/news_story/?ID=163073&hubname= Bettis joins bid for new Pittsburgh arena] Associated Press article at tsn.ca, April 18, 2006</ref>\n\nBettis opened a restaurant called \"Jerome Bettis' Grille 36\" on June 5, 2007 on Pittsburgh's Northside.<ref>[http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/07151/790197-46.stm Jerome Bettis Grille 36 opens Tuesday on N. Side] Pittsburgh Post-Gazette, Dining Guide, May 31, 2007</ref><ref>[http://www.postgazette.com/pg/06192/704864-66.stm Bettis' Grille 36 in the works] Pittsburgh Post-Gazette, Sports, July 11, 2007</ref>\n\nBettis makes a cameo as himself in the episode [[The Convention (The Office)|The Convention]] of season 3 of the NBC comedy series ''[[The Office (US TV series)|The Office]]''. Signing autographs at a paper convention, [[Michael Scott (The Office)|Michael Scott]] tries to invite him to a room party, which Bettis declines. Later, Michael claims Bettis is nicknamed \"The Bus\" because he is afraid of flying.\n\nIn 2010, Bettis joined [[School of the Legends]] (SOTL), an [[online community]] and partner of the [[NFLPA]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Veteran Running Backs Offer Rookies Advice in Exclusive School of the Legends Interview |publisher=Business Wire |date=June 3, 2011 |url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20110603005764/en/Veteran-Running-Backs-Offer-Rookies-Advice-Exclusive |accessdate=December 6, 2011 |archiveurl = http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20110603005764/en/Veteran-Running-Backs-Offer-Rookies-Advice-Exclusive |archivedate = December 6, 2011}}</ref> He was featured in an article on the D1 Training website in February 2011 and filmed training courses for SOTL that focused on his position as a running back.<ref>{{cite web |title=Jerome Bettis Stops by D1 |publisher=D1SportingTraining|date=February 21, 2011 |url=http://d1sportstraining.blogspot.com/2011/02/jerome-bettis-stops-by-d1.html }}</ref>\n\nBettis is currently the host of ''The Jerome Bettis Show'' on [[WPXI-TV]], filmed at [[Heinz Field]] in Pittsburgh, airing Saturdays at 7:00 PM and 1:00 AM. He was a commentator for the [[NFL Network]] and a former NBC studio analyst for ''[[Football Night in America]].''  Now he is an NFL analyst for different [[ESPN]] programs, such as [[SportsCenter]].\n\nThe Jerome Bettis Bus Stops Here Foundation and other agencies sponsor the Jerome Bettis Asthma and Sports Camp annually for children with asthma.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jerome Bettis Hosts Children's Asthma Sports Camp At Heinz Field|url=http://www.wpxi.com/news/entertainment/jerome-bettis-hosts-childrens-asthma-sports-camp-a/nGprt/|newspaper=WPXI|date=July 22, 2010}}</ref> Bettis has also delivered over 1000 pairs of cleats to children in the Detroit school system.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Evans |first1=Gavin |title=Where Are They Now? Your Favorite NFL Players of the '90s |url=https://www.complex.com/sports/2013/09/nfl-players-90s-where-are-they-now/jerome-bettis |website=Complex |accessdate=August 20, 2018 |date=September 11, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAfter falling short as a finalist in 2013,<ref>{{cite news|title=Parcells, Carter finally make Pro Football Hall of Fame|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/2013/02/02/nfl-hall-of-fame-announcement/1886453/|newspaper=USA Today|accessdate=February 2, 2013|first1=Jim|last1=Corbett|date=February 2, 2013}}</ref> on January 31, 2015, Bettis was voted into The [[Pro Football Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Pro Football Hall of Fame: Jerome Bettis among the 2015 class|url=http://www.cbssports.com/nfl/eye-on-football/25013699/pro-football-hall-of-fame-jerome-bettis-among-the-2015-class|work=CBSSports.com|accessdate=January 31, 2015|first1=Igor|last1=Mello|date=January 31, 2015}}</ref>  Bettis returned to NBC to help [[Bob Costas]] preside over the [[Vince Lombardi Trophy]] presentation at the end of [[Super Bowl XLIX]] on February 1, 2015.\n\nBettis starred in a Geico commercial in 2019, playing a running back in flag football that dominates the competition (49-0).\n\n==Personal life==\nBettis had made political donations to both [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] and [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] candidates; specifically the Congressional campaign of Democratic [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] [[Carolyn Cheeks Kilpatrick]], and the 2004 campaign of Republican [[President of the United States|President]] [[George W. Bush]].<ref name=BettisPoliticalDonations>[http://www.newsmeat.com/sports_political_donations/Jerome_Bettis.php Jerome Bettis] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080406013053/http://www.newsmeat.com/sports_political_donations/Jerome_Bettis.php |date=April 6, 2008 }}, Newsmeat.com, ''Accessed March 31, 2008.''</ref>  On March 29, 2008, Bettis accompanied [[Barack Obama]] on a campaign visit to the [[US Steel]] plant in Braddock, Pennsylvania.<ref>Michael David Smith, [http://sports.aol.com/fanhouse/2008/03/29/barack-obamas-pennsylvania-strategy-appear-with-franco-harris/ Barack Obama's Pennsylvania Strategy: Appear With Franco Harris, Jerome Bettis], ''Accessed March 31, 2008.''</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{Profootballhof|id=296|name=Jerome Bettis}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081011174133/http://www.wpxi.com/jeromebettisshow/ The Jerome Bettis Show on WPXI]\n* [http://www.thebus36.com/ The Bus Stops Here Foundation]\n* {{Footballstats |nfl=BET627285 |espn=389 |cbs= |yahoo=2354 |si=2354 |pfr=B/BettJe00 |rotoworld=699}}\n\n{{1993 NFL Draft}}\n{{RamsFirstPick}}\n{{Los Angeles Rams 1993 draft navbox}}\n{{AP Offensive Rookies of the Year}}\n{{NFL Comeback Players of the Year}}\n{{Walter Payton Man of the Year Award}}\n{{Super Bowl XL}}\n{{10,000 rushing yards club}}\n{{Pittsburgh Steelers All-Time Team}}\n{{Pittsburgh Steelers}}\n{{2015 Football HOF}}\n{{Pro Football Hall of Fame members}}\n{{Walter Camp Man of the Year}}\n{{Football Night in America}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bettis, Jerome}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American Conference Pro Bowl players]]\n[[Category:American drug traffickers]]\n[[Category:American football running backs]]\n[[Category:American ten-pin bowling players]]\n[[Category:Los Angeles Rams players]]\n[[Category:National Conference Pro Bowl players]]\n[[Category:National Football League announcers]]\n[[Category:National Football League Offensive Rookie of the Year Award winners]]\n[[Category:Notre Dame Fighting Irish football players]]\n[[Category:Pittsburgh Steelers players]]\n[[Category:People from Roswell, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Michigan]]\n[[Category:Pro Football Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Detroit]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Fulton County, Georgia]]\n[[Category:St. Louis Rams players]]\n[[Category:Super Bowl champions]]\n[[Category:Bowling broadcasters]]\n", "name_user": "120.22.48.126", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jerome_Bettis"}
{"title_page": "K\u00e4rstin Ehrnlund", "text_new": "{{short description|Swedish golfer}}\n{{Infobox golfer\n| name              = K\u00e4rstin Ehrnlund\n| image             = \n| imagesize         = <!-- Optional, default is 200px -->\n| caption           = \n| fullname          =K\u00e4rstin Helena Ehrnlund Strand \t\n| nickname          = \n| birth_date        = {{birth date and age|1959|2|10|df=y}}\n| birth_place       = [[Karlstad]], [[Sweden]]\n| death_date        = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|1959|2|10|df=y}} -->\n| death_place       = \n| height            = \n| weight            = \n| nationality       = {{SWE}}\n| residence         = Ytterby, [[Kung\u00e4lv]], [[Sweden]]\n| spouse            =Erik Strand \n| partner           = \n| children          = \n| college           = \n| yearpro           = 1979\n| retired           =1986 \n| tour              = \n| extour            = [[Ladies European Tour]]\n| prowins           = 2\n| letwins           = 2\n| otherwins         = \n| majorwins         = <!-- Number of Major Championship wins -->\n| nabisco           = \n| lpga              = \n| wusopen           = \n| wbritopen         = \n| evian             = \n| wghofid           = <!-- World Golf Hall of Fame member ID -->\n| wghofyear         = <!-- World Golf Hall of Fame year inducted -->\n| award1            = <!-- Achievement or award details -->\n| year1             = <!-- Year(s) of achievement or award -->\n| award2            = \n| year2             = \n| awardssection     = <!-- location of awards page or section -->\n}}\n'''K\u00e4rstin Ehrnlund''' (born 10 February 1959 in [[Karlstad]]) is a [[List of Swedish professional golfers|Swedish professional golfer]]. She was the first Swedish woman to join a [[professional golf tours|professional golf tour]] and the first Swede to record a victory on an international tour.\n\n==Early years==\nHer father Sven-Erik was a well-known coach for the local [[bandy]] team, Surte, in the 70s, playing at the highest level in [[Sweden]]. Living in [[Bohusl\u00e4n|Bohus]], Sweden,  the family started playing golf at nearby Lyseg\u00e5rden Golf Club, but soon switched to Gullbringa Golf & Country Club, the same club as six years younger [[Helen Alfredsson]] started her career. Ehrnlund found more interest in horse riding at young ages, but allergy against horses forced her to golf instead. At 15 years of age, she moved to Palm Springs, California, to practice for [[Johnny Revolta]] and stayed for two years.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Amateur career==\nStill at junior age, she dominated Swedish amateur golf, winning the Swedish Match-play Championship in 1977 and 1978, as well as the open amateur championships of Sweden, Germany and Austria in 1978. At the end of  the 1978 season and her amateur career, she represented Sweden, together with [[Liv Wollin]] and Charlotte Mongomery, in the [[Espirito Santo Trophy]] in Pacific Harbour, [[Fiji|Fidji]], were the Swedish team finished 8th.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Professional career==\nIn 1979, she turned professional on the nascent Women's Professional Golf Association (WPGA) Tour, later renamed [[Ladies European Tour]]. In August 1980 Ehrnlund played the Welsh Classic at [[Whitchurch Golf Club]] in [[Cardiff]], Wales. She was in the lead after two rounds with 68\u201374, and after the last round was cancelled due to rain she was declared the winner. Four years later she won another Ladies European Tour title, the United Friendly Tournament at two-time [[Ryder Cup]]-venue [[Southport and Ainsdale Golf Club]] near [[Liverpool]], England.<ref>[http://svenskagolfmuseet.se/golfens-profiler/ Golf Profiles], Swedish Golf Museum, accessed 17 November 2016 {{in lang|sv}}</ref>\n\nSix years after Ehrnlunds first victory on the ladies tour, [[Ove Sellberg]] became the first Swede to record a victory on the [[European Tour]] in 1986.\n\n==Private life==\nSince 1991, Ehrnlund, together with her husband Erik, runs her own 9-hole golf course, Bollestad Golf Club, between [[Marstrand]] and Kung\u00e4lv, Sweden.\n\n==Amateur wins==\n*1977 Swedish Match-play Championship\n*1978 Swedish Junior Match-play Championship, Swedish Match-play Championship, Swedish International Stroke-play Championship, German Open Amateur Championship, Austrian Open Amateur Championship\n\nSources:<ref>[http://www.svenskgolf.se/artiklar/folja/20120816/har-ar-alla-vinnare-i-sm-match SM Match Winners], Swedish Golf, accessed 17 November 2016 {{in lang|sv}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.expressen.se/gt/sport/golf/pionjaren-som-domdes-ut-bodde-i-husvagn-/ |title=Pionj\u00e4ren som d\u00f6mdes ut - bodde i husvagn |newspaper=Expressen |location=Stockholm, Sweden |date=April 26, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Professional wins (2)==\n===Ladies European Tour (2)===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:95%;\"\n!No.\n!Date\n!Tournament\n!Winning score\n!Margin of<br>victory\n!Runner(s)-up\n|-\n|1\n|28 Aug 1980\n|McEwans Lager Welsh Classic\n|\u22122 (68-74=142)\n|2 strokes\n|{{flagicon|ENG}} Jane Chapman\n|-\n|2\n|5 Aug 1984\n|United Friendly Tournament\n|\u22124 (75-75-72-69=288)\n|4 strokes\n|{{flagicon|ENG}} Jane Forrest {{flagicon|SCO}} [[Dale Reid]]\n|}\n\nSource:<ref>[http://www.golf.se/globalassets/tavling/blagula-segrar/alla-svenska-segrar.pdf Swedish Professional Tour Victories], Swedish Golf Association, accessed 17 November 2016 {{in lang|sv}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.e-magin.se/paper/7m49qpt6/popup/1? |title=K\u00e4rstin skrev golfhistoria |trans-title=K\u00e4rstin wrote history |magazine=Svensk Golf |date=July 1980 |page=5}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.e-magin.se/paper/dv6ftvf8/popup/1? |title=K\u00e4rstin - \u00c4ntligen fick hon en 72-h\u00e5lsseger |trans-title=K\u00e4rstin - Finally she got a 72-hole victory |magazine=Svensk Golf |date=September 1984 |page=7, 64}}</ref>\n\n==Team appearances==\n'''Amateur'''\n*[[Espirito Santo Trophy]] (representing Sweden): 1978<ref name=\":0\">{{citeweb |url=http://www.e-magin.se/paper/1pfc350j/popup/1? |title=Golf - Den Stora Sporten' |language=Swedish |trans-title=Golf - the Great Sport |publisher=Swedish Golf Federation 100 Years |pages=184, 209, 220, 221}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Golfdata|11175}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ehrnlund, Karstin}}\n[[Category:Swedish female golfers]]\n[[Category:Ladies European Tour golfers]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Karlstad]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Gothenburg]]\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Swedish golfer}}\n{{Infobox golfer\n| name              = K\u00e4rstin Ehrnlund\n| image             = \n| imagesize         = <!-- Optional, default is 200px -->\n| caption           = \n| fullname          =K\u00e4rstin Helena Ehrnlund Strand \t\n| nickname          = \n| birth_date        = {{birth date and age|1959|2|10|df=y}}\n| birth_place       = [[Karlstad]], [[Sweden]]\n| death_date        = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|1959|2|10|df=y}} -->\n| death_place       = \n| height            = \n| weight            = \n| nationality       = {{SWE}}\n| residence         = Ytterby, [[Kung\u00e4lv]], [[Sweden]]\n| spouse            =Erik Strand \n| partner           = \n| children          = \n| college           = \n| yearpro           = 1979\n| retired           =1986 \n| tour              = \n| extour            = [[Ladies European Tour]]\n| prowins           = 2\n| letwins           = 2\n| otherwins         = \n| majorwins         = <!-- Number of Major Championship wins -->\n| nabisco           = \n| lpga              = \n| wusopen           = \n| wbritopen         = \n| evian             = \n| wghofid           = <!-- World Golf Hall of Fame member ID -->\n| wghofyear         = <!-- World Golf Hall of Fame year inducted -->\n| award1            = <!-- Achievement or award details -->\n| year1             = <!-- Year(s) of achievement or award -->\n| award2            = \n| year2             = \n| awardssection     = <!-- location of awards page or section -->\n}}\n'''K\u00e4rstin Ehrnlund''' (born 10 February 1959 in [[Karlstad]]) is a [[List of Swedish professional golfers|Swedish professional golfer]]. She was the first Swedish woman to join a [[professional golf tours|professional golf tour]] and the first Swede to record a victory on an international tour.\n\n==Early years==\nHer father Sven-Erik was a well-known coach for the local [[bandy]] team, Surte, in the 70s, playing at the highest level in [[Sweden]]. Living in [[Bohusl\u00e4n|Bohus]], Sweden,  the family started playing golf at nearby Lyseg\u00e5rden Golf Club, but soon switched to Gullbringa Golf & Country Club, the same club as six years younger [[Helen Alfredsson]] started her career. Ehrnlund found more interest in horse riding at young ages, but allergy against horses forced her to golf instead. At 15 years of age, she moved to Palm Springs, California, to practice for [[Johnny Revolta]] and stayed for two years.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Amateur career==\nStill at junior age, she dominated Swedish amateur golf, winning the Swedish Match-play Championship in 1977 and 1978, as well as the open amateur championships of Sweden, Germany and Austria in 1978. At the end of  the 1978 season and her amateur career, she represented Sweden, together with [[Liv Wollin]] and Charlotte Mongomery, in the [[Espirito Santo Trophy]] in Pacific Harbour, [[Fiji|Fidji]], were the Swedish team finished 8th.\n\n==Professional career==\nIn 1979, she turned professional on the nascent Women's Professional Golf Association (WPGA) Tour, later renamed [[Ladies European Tour]]. In August 1980 Ehrnlund played the Welsh Classic at [[Whitchurch Golf Club]] in [[Cardiff]], Wales. She was in the lead after two rounds with 68\u201374, and after the last round was cancelled due to rain she was declared the winner. Four years later she won another Ladies European Tour title, the United Friendly Tournament at two-time [[Ryder Cup]]-venue [[Southport and Ainsdale Golf Club]] near [[Liverpool]], England.<ref>[http://svenskagolfmuseet.se/golfens-profiler/ Golf Profiles], Swedish Golf Museum, accessed 17 November 2016 {{in lang|sv}}</ref>\n\nSix years after Ehrnlunds first victory on the ladies tour, [[Ove Sellberg]] became the first Swede to record a victory on the [[European Tour]] in 1986.\n\n==Private life==\nSince 1991, Ehrnlund, together with her husband Erik, runs her own 9-hole golf course, Bollestad Golf Club, between [[Marstrand]] and Kung\u00e4lv, Sweden.\n\n==Amateur wins==\n*1977 Swedish Match-play Championship\n*1978 Swedish Junior Match-play Championship, Swedish Match-play Championship, Swedish International Stroke-play Championship, German Open Amateur Championship, Austrian Open Amateur Championship\n\nSources:<ref>[http://www.svenskgolf.se/artiklar/folja/20120816/har-ar-alla-vinnare-i-sm-match SM Match Winners], Swedish Golf, accessed 17 November 2016 {{in lang|sv}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.expressen.se/gt/sport/golf/pionjaren-som-domdes-ut-bodde-i-husvagn-/ |title=Pionj\u00e4ren som d\u00f6mdes ut - bodde i husvagn |newspaper=Expressen |location=Stockholm, Sweden |date=April 26, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Professional wins (2)==\n===Ladies European Tour (2)===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:95%;\"\n!No.\n!Date\n!Tournament\n!Winning score\n!Margin of<br>victory\n!Runner(s)-up\n|-\n|1\n|28 Aug 1980\n|McEwans Lager Welsh Classic\n|\u22122 (68-74=142)\n|2 strokes\n|{{flagicon|ENG}} Jane Chapman\n|-\n|2\n|5 Aug 1984\n|United Friendly Tournament\n|\u22124 (75-75-72-69=288)\n|4 strokes\n|{{flagicon|ENG}} Jane Forrest {{flagicon|SCO}} [[Dale Reid]]\n|}\n\nSource:<ref>[http://www.golf.se/globalassets/tavling/blagula-segrar/alla-svenska-segrar.pdf Swedish Professional Tour Victories], Swedish Golf Association, accessed 17 November 2016 {{in lang|sv}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.e-magin.se/paper/7m49qpt6/popup/1? |title=K\u00e4rstin skrev golfhistoria |trans-title=K\u00e4rstin wrote history |magazine=Svensk Golf |date=July 1980 |page=5}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.e-magin.se/paper/dv6ftvf8/popup/1? |title=K\u00e4rstin - \u00c4ntligen fick hon en 72-h\u00e5lsseger |trans-title=K\u00e4rstin - Finally she got a 72-hole victory |magazine=Svensk Golf |date=September 1984 |page=7, 64}}</ref>\n\n==Team appearances==\n'''Amateur'''\n*[[Espirito Santo Trophy]] (representing Sweden): 1978<ref name=\":0\">{{citeweb |url=http://www.e-magin.se/paper/1pfc350j/popup/1? |title=Golf - Den Stora Sporten' |language=Swedish |trans-title=Golf - the Great Sport |publisher=Swedish Golf Federation 100 Years |pages=184, 209, 220, 221}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Golfdata|11175}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ehrnlund, Karstin}}\n[[Category:Swedish female golfers]]\n[[Category:Ladies European Tour golfers]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Karlstad]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Gothenburg]]\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "EEJB", "label": "safe", "comment": "Source", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/K%C3%A4rstin_Ehrnlund"}
{"title_page": "M (Big Bang single album)", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = M\n| cover      = BigBang - M (Single Album).jpg\n| alt        =\n| border     = yes\n| type       = Single Album\n| artist     = [[Big Bang (South Korean band)|Big Bang]]\n| released   = {{Start date|2015|05|01}}\n| format     =\n| recorded   = 2014\u20132015\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Dance-pop]]|[[PBR&B]]|[[Hip hop music|hip hop]]}}\n| length     = 6:28 (Digital) <br> 12:56 (Physical)\n| label      = {{hlist|[[YG Entertainment|YG]]|[[KT Music]]}}\n| composer   =\n| lyricist   =\n| producer   = \n* [[Yang Hyun-suk]] ([[Executive producer|exec.]])\n* [[Teddy Park|Teddy]]\n* [[G-Dragon]]\n| prev_title = [[Monster (Big Bang song)|Monster]]\n| prev_year  = 2012\n| next_title = [[A (Big Bang single album)|A]]\n| next_year  = 2015\n| misc       = {{Extra album cover\n | header  = \"M\" Version (Black)\n | type    = single album\n | cover   = M cover Bigbang.jpg\n | border  =\n | alt     =\n | caption =\n}}\n{{Extra album cover\n | header  = \"m\" Version (White)\n | type    = single album\n | cover   = BigBang - M (White Version).jpg\n | border  =\n | alt     =\n | caption =\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''M''''' is the fourth [[single album]] by South Korean band [[Big Bang (South Korean band)|Big Bang]], and the first from their ''Made Series''. It marks the first comeback for them after a three-year absence, which is also their first single album in nine years.\n\n==Background==\n\nOn April 17,  [[YG Entertainment]] revealed the first teaser picture.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sbs.com.au/popasia/blog/2015/04/01/bigbang-2015-comeback-confirmed-finally|title=BIGBANG 2015 comeback confirmed - new teaser photo|accessdate=April 17, 2015|work=sbs.com.au|author=SBS PopAsia HQ}}</ref> Later, trailer for Big Bang's [[Made World Tour]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VwV2I5tH4no|title=BIGBANG - 'MADE' TOUR TRAILER |publisher=BIGBANG Youtube Channel |date=April 16, 2015|accessdate=April 20, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sbs.com.au/popasia/blog/2015/04/17/bigbang-drop-theatrical-trailer-new-album-made|title=BIGBANG drop theatrical trailer for new album & tour \"MADE\" |publisher=sbs.com.au |date=April 16, 2015|accessdate=April 20, 2015}}</ref> was unveiled. YG Entertainment announced the title tracks of Big Bang's \"MADE Series: M\" in the third teaser.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yg-life.com/archives/50119|title=BIGBANG \u2013 MADE SERIES [M]|accessdate=April 25, 2015|work=YGLife}}</ref> Two of the four teasers for D-1 to D-4 consist of the song info, including who was responsible for the tracks' composition.\n\n[[G-Dragon]] revealed during the second concert of Made World Tour that he had a hard time making the album, since there are a big expectations for Big Bang's comeback, he said, \"In all honesty, I was in a slump that wasn't a normal slump. I worried a lot. The group has grown due to all the fans, so I unknowingly felt a heavy burden because it's been a long time since we released an album. I worried a lot because of this, but we worked well, as we continued.\" He added, \"I thought to myself that I just need to work. We got together frequently and worked.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sbs.com.au/popasia/blog/2015/04/28/g-dragon-reveals-he-fell-deep-slump-last-year|title=G-Dragon reveals he fell into a deep slump last year|publisher=sbs.com.au |date=April 29, 2015|accessdate=May 1, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreaboo.com/comebacks/g-dragon-reveals-felt-heavy-emotional-slump-solo-album/|title=G-Dragon reveals why he had a heavy emotional slump after his solo album|publisher=koreaboo.com|date=April 28, 2015|accessdate=May 1, 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Release ==\nThe album opened for pre-order on 24 to 30 April consisting of two singles which are both title tracks and is released worldwide through [[iTunes Store|iTunes]], [[Melon (online music service)|Melon]] and other online music portals on May 1. There are two different versions of the album; M (black) and m (white). One contains only CD and Booklet (24p) while the other one contains CD, Booklet (24p) + Special kit (Puzzle ticket, 5 photo cards and 1 limited photo card) + Poster.\n\n==Commercial performance==\n''M'' charted at number one on the [[Gaon Album Chart]] selling 130,130 copies in just two days, peaking at number two in April.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/album.gaon?nationGbn=T&serviceGbn=&targetTime=04&hitYear=2015&termGbn=month|title=Gaon Album Chart - April|accessdate=July 10, 2015|work=[[Gaon Music Chart]]}}</ref> The album sold 137,261 copies in the first half of 2015.<ref name=\"Gaon\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/article/view.gaon?idx=9835&sgenre=opinion|title=Gaon Comprehensive Sales 2015 First Half (6/2015)|publisher=[[Gaon Chart|Gaon]]|language=Korean}}</ref> In China, ''M'' sold over 500,000 digital copies, making the album one of the [[List of best-selling albums in China|best-selling digital albums in Chinese history]].<ref name=\"y.qq.com\">{{cite web| url=http://y.qq.com/live/bigbang/index.html?sid=&g_f=yqqjiaodian| title=BigBang\u300aM\u300b\uff085.1\uff09\u6570\u5b57\u4e13\u8f91 QQ\u97f3\u4e50\u72ec\u5bb6\u9996\u53d1 - QQ\u97f3\u4e50| work=QQ music| publisher=y.qq.com| date=1 May 2015| accessdate=22 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe group debuted on Billboard's 'World Digital Songs' chart<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allkpop.com/article/2015/05/big-bangs-loser-bae-bae-debut-at-1-2-on-billboards-world-digital-songs-chart|title=Big Bang's 'Loser' & 'Bae Bae' debut at No. 1 & 2 on Billboard's 'World Digital Songs' chart|accessdate=May 7, 2015|work=Allkpop]]}}</ref> with \"Loser\" charting 1st place and \"Bae Bae\" charting 2nd place on May 7. The music videos were also ranked 3rd and 4th most viewed K-pop M/V videos in the U.S. (April) according to Billboard.\n\n==Promotion==\nAfter performing both songs during their Made Tour, Big Bang held their first comeback stage on [[Inkigayo]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ent.hankyung.com/news/app/newsview.php?aid=2015050364354|title='\ucef4\ubc31' \ube45\ubc45, '\uc778\uae30\uac00\uc694' \ucd9c\uaca9 \"\uc9c0\ub204\uc158-\uc774\uc218\ud604 \ud53c\ucc98\ub9c1\"|accessdate=May 3, 2015|work=Hankyung|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518070848/http://ent.hankyung.com/news/app/newsview.php?aid=2015050364354|archivedate=May 18, 2015}}</ref> on May 3, 2015. On May 6, YG Entertainment announced the release of special clips for \"Bae Bae\" on 6 to 10 May.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreaboo.com/photo/yg-entertainment-release-sticky-rice-cake-clips-bigbangs-bae-bae/|title=\"sticky rice cake\" clips for BIGBANG's \"Bae Bae\"|accessdate=May 6, 2015|work=KoreaBoo}}</ref> Big Bang had their second comeback on May 7 installment of [[M Countdown|MNET's M Countdown]]. On the May 10 episode on Inkigayo, Big Bang made their third comeback.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soompi.com/2015/05/10/bigbang-takes-2nd-music-show-win-on-inkigayo/|title=BIGBANG Takes 2nd Music Show Win on \"Inkigayo\"|accessdate=May 10, 2015|work=Soompi}}</ref> Big Bang also appeared on KBS' \"Happy Together\" on May 20, the first time featuring all of the members in a variety show.\n\nIn May 2015, Big Bang started a cover contest, the contestant can upload any type of cover for \"Loser\" and \"Bae Bae\". The winners will win album, get featured on the playlist of Big Bang's official YouTube Channel and get the chance to audition at [[YG Entertainment]]. The submission started on May 18 till May 29, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://facebook.ygfamily.com/ygperm/BIGBANG/madeMcover/m_madeMcover_eng.php|title=BIGBANG MADE [M] COVER CONTEST|accessdate=July 10, 2015|work=YG Family Facebook}}</ref> a total of 404 videos were submitted, the winners were announced on June 19.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/BIGBANG/app_805613112858202|title=MADE [M] COVER|accessdate=July 10, 2015|work=YG Family Facebook}}</ref>\n\n== Track listing ==\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed       = no\n| headline        = ''M'' - Single \n| extra_column    = Arrangement\n| total_length    = 6:28\n\n| all_writing     = \n| all_lyrics      =\n| all_music       =\n\n| title1          = [[Loser (Big Bang song)|Loser]]\n| note1           =\n| writer1         = \n| lyrics1         = [[Teddy Park|Teddy]], [[T.O.P (rapper)|T.O.P]], G-Dragon\n| music1          = Teddy, [[Taeyang]]\n| extra1          = Teddy\n| length1         = 3:39\n\n| title2          = [[Bae Bae]]\n| note2           = \n| writer2         = \n| lyrics2         = G-Dragon, Teddy, T.O.P\n| music2          = Teddy, G-Dragon, T.O.P\n| extra2          = Teddy\n| length2         = 2:49\n}}\n\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed       = no\n| headline        = ''M'' - CD<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yesasia.com/big-bang-made-series-m-random-version-m-or-m/1039396498-0-0-0-en/info.html|title=Big Bang Made Series - M (Random Version - M or m)|publisher=[[yesasia]]|access-date=November 15, 2016}}</ref>\n| extra_column    = Arrangement\n| total_length    = 12:56\t\n\n| all_writing     = \n| all_lyrics      = \n| all_music       =\n\n| title1          = Loser\n| note1           =\n| writer1         = \n| lyrics1         = Teddy, T.O.P, G-Dragon\n| music1          = Teddy, Taeyang\n| extra1          = Teddy\n| length1         = 3:39\n\n| title2          = Bae Bae\n| note2           = \n| writer2         = \n| lyrics2         = G-Dragon, Teddy, T.O.P\n| music2          = Teddy, G-Dragon, T.O.P\n| extra2          = Tedd\n| length2         = 2:49\n\n| title3          = Loser\n| note3           = [[instrumental]]\n| writer3         =\n| lyrics3         = \n| music3          = Teddy, Taeyang\n| extra3          = Teddy\n| length3         = 3:39\n\n| title4          = Bae Bae\n| note4           = Instrumental\n| writer4         = \n| lyrics4         = \n| music4          = Teddy, G-Dragon, T.O.P \n| extra4    