ril 2020}}</ref>\n**138th Chemical Company (Georgia NG)<ref>{{cite web|url=  https://www.dvidshub.net/news/136078/mariettas-138th-chem-company-no-1-national-guard|title=YYYY|website=dvids.net|date=11 July 2014|author=Will Cox|accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n**140th Chemical Company (California NG)<ref>{{cite web|url=  https://cdp.dhs.gov/news-media/article/140th-chemical-company-to-train-this-week\n|title=140th Chemical Company to Train this Week|website=cdp.dhs.gov|date= |author=Richard Hildreth|accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n**222nd Chemical Company (New York NG)<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.nationalguard.mil/News/Article/1099823/technology-helps-new-york-national-guard-prepare-for-chemical-and-radiological/\n|title=Technology helps New York National Guard prepare for chemical and radiological threats|website=nationalguard.mil|date=2 March 2017|author=Yolanda Arrington|accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n**229th Chemical Company (Virginia NG)<ref>{{cite web|url= https://vaguard.dodlive.mil/2014/10/22/6215/\n|title=229th Chemical Company completes NTC rotation|website=vanguard.dodlive.mil|date=22 October 2014|author=Terra C.Gatti|accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n**231st Chemical Company (Maryland NG)<ref>{{cite web|url=  https://www.nationalguard.mil/News/Article/575532/in-a-first-marylands-231st-chemical-company-joins-with-air-guard-in-hazmat-trai/\n|title=In a first, Maryland's 231st Chemical Company joins with Air Guard in HAZMAT training|website=nationalguard.mil|date=19 February 2014|author=Thaddesus Harrington|accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n**272nd Chemical Company (Massachusetts NG)<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.researchgate.net/figure/Massachusetts-National-Guard-272-nd-Chemical-Company-CBRN-Response-Teams-effluent_fig4_306307888\n|title=Massachusetts National Guard 272 nd Chemical Company CBRN Response Team's effluent collection blivets.|website=researchgate.net|date= |author= |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n**434th Chemical Company (Minnesota NG)<ref>{{cite web|url= https://minnesotanationalguard.ng.mil/434th/\n|title=434th Chemical Company|website=minnesotanationalguard.ng.mil|date= |author= |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n**436th Chemical Company (Texas NG)<ref>{{cite web|url= https://tmd.texas.gov/chemical-soldiers-train-for-dual-mission|title=Chemical soldiers train for dual mission|website=tmd.texas.gov|date=9 December 2017|author=Matthew Verdugo|accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n**438th Chemical Company (Indiana NG)<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.in.ng.mil/About/Organization/81st-Troop-Command/\n|title=81st Troop Command - Units|website=in.ng.mil|date= |author= |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n**457th Chemical Company (Wisconsin NG)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dma.wi.gov/DMA/news/2016news/16015|title=Wisconsin Guard chemical company fields new Stryker reconnaissance vehicles|website=dma.wi.gov|date=25 February 2016|author=Joe Trovato|accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n**460th Chemical Company (Michigan NG)<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.minationalguard.com/460th-chemical-company/\n|title=460th Chemical Company|website=minationalguard.com|date=18 May 2015|author=Denice Rankin|accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n**482nd Chemical Company (Puerto Rico NG)<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.ang.af.mil/Media/Article-Display/Article/2052177/puerto-rico-national-guard-helps-respond-to-earthquakes/\n|title=Puerto Rico National Guard helps respond to earthquakes|website=ang.af.mil|date= |author= |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n**631st Chemical Company (Montana NG)<ref>{{cite web|url= https://nbcmontana.com/news/local/national-guard-called-in-to-assist-with-lolo-peak-fire\n|title=National Guard called in to assist with Lolo Peak Fire|website=nbcmontana.com|date=19 August 2017|author= |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n**704th Chemical Company (Minnesota NG)<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.army.mil/article/132159/vibrant_response_trains_chemical_soldiers_to_respond_to_potential_disaster\n|title=Vibrant Response trains chemical Soldiers to respond to potential disaster|website=army.mil|date=20 August 2014|author= |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n[[United States Marine Corps|Marines]]\n* [[Chemical Biological Incident Response Force]]<ref>{{cite web|url=  https://www.cbirf.marines.mil/\n|title= Chemical Biological Incident Response Force |website=cbirf.marines.mil|date= |author= |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Uruguay==\n* Chemical, Biological, Radiological and Nuclear Group (''Grupo Quimico, Biologico, Radiologico y Nuclear'') <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lr21.com.uy/politica/202402-el-ejercito-entrena-una-unidad-especial-en-prevencion-de-ataques-con-quimicos|title=El Ej\u00e9rcito entrena una unidad especial en prevenci\u00f3n de ataques con qu\u00edmicos|website=lr21.com.uy|date=11 February 2006|accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of paratrooper forces]]\n* [[List of marines and naval infantry forces]]\n* [[List of mountain warfare forces]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of military units and formations]]\n[[Category:Chemical, biological, radiological and nuclear defense]]\n", "name_user": "Arturolorioli", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eUnited States of America", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_CBRN_warfare_forces"}
{"title_page": "Elsevier", "text_new": "{{short description|Dutch publishing and analytics company}}\n{{other uses}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2016}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Elsevier\n| logo = \n| logo_caption = \n| image = Elsevier logo 2019.svg\n| image_size = 200px\n| image_caption = \n| trading_name = <!-- d/b/a/, doing business as - if different from legal name above -->\n| native_name = <!-- Company's name in home country language -->\n| native_name_lang = <!-- Use ISO 639-1 code, e.g. \"fr\" for French. If there is more than one native name, in different languages, enter those names using {{tl|lang}}, instead. -->\n| romanized_name = \n| former_name = \n| type = \n| traded_as = \n| industry = Publishing\n| genre = <!-- Only used with media and publishing companies -->\n| fate = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| foundation = {{start date and age|df=yes|1880}}\n| founder = \n| defunct = <!-- {{End date|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| location_city = [[Amsterdam]], [[Netherlands]]\n| location_country = \n| locations = <!-- Number of locations, stores, offices, etc. -->\n| area_served = \n| key_people = \n| products = \n| brands = \n| production = \n| services = \n| revenue = \u00a32.54 billion (2018)<ref name=\"RELX 2018 Report\"/>\n| operating_income = \n| net_income = <!-- Removed due to lack of verifiability -->\n| aum = <!-- Only used with financial services companies -->\n| assets = \n| equity = \n| owner = \n| num_employees = \n| parent = [[RELX]]\n| divisions = \n| subsid = \n| website = {{URL|https://www.elsevier.com/}}\n| footnotes = \n| intl = \n}}\n\n'''Elsevier''' ({{IPA-nl|\u02c8\u025blz\u0259vi\u02d0r|lang}}) is a [[Netherlands|Dutch]] [[publishing]] and [[analytics]] company specializing in scientific, technical, and medical content. It is a part of the [[RELX Group]], known until 2015 as Reed Elsevier.  Its products include journals such as ''[[The Lancet]]'' and ''[[Cell (journal)|Cell]]'', the [[ScienceDirect]] collection of electronic journals, the ''[[Trends (journals)|Trends]]'' and ''[[Current Opinion (Elsevier)|Current Opinion]]'' series of journals, the online citation database [[Scopus]], and the [[ClinicalKey]] search engine for clinicians. Elsevier's products also include digital tools for data-management, instruction, and assessment.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://scholarlykitchen.sspnet.org/2017/02/02/plum-goes-orange-elsevier-acquires-plum-analytics/|title = Plum Goes Orange \u2013 Elsevier Acquires Plum Analytics |date = 2017-02-02 }}</ref>\n\nElsevier publishes more than 470,000 articles annually in 2,500 journals.<ref name=\"RELX 2018 Report\">{{Cite web |url = https://www.relx.com/~/media/Files/R/RELX-Group/documents/reports/annual-reports/2018-annual-report.pdf |title = 2018 RELX Group Annual Report |date = March 2019 |accessdate =  |website = RELX Company Reports |publisher = RELX}}</ref> Its archives contain over 16 million documents and 30,000 e-books. Total yearly downloads amount to more than 1 billion.<ref name = \"RELX 2018 Report\" />\n\nElsevier's high operating profit margins (37% in 2018) and 950 million pounds in profits, often on publicly funded research works<ref name=\"RELX 2018 Report\" /><ref name=\"relx-results-press-release-2018\">\n{{cite press release\n | author = RELX\n | title = RELX \u2014 Results for the year to December 2018\n | date = 21 February 2019\n | publisher = RELX Group\n | location = London, United Kingdom and Amsterdam, The Netherlands\n | url = https://www.relx.com/~/media/Files/R/RELX-Group/documents/press-releases/2019/relx-results-2018-pressrelease.pdf\n | access-date = 2019-03-27\n}}  Adjusted operating margin for 2017 for the publishing division is 36.8% (p6).\n</ref> \nand its [[Copyright policies of academic publishers|copyright practices]] have subjected it to criticism by researchers.<ref name=boyc >{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/02/14/science/researchers-boycott-elsevier-journal-publisher.html|title=Mathematicians Organize Boycott of a Publisher | work=The New York Times | first=Thomas|last=Lin|date=13 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n==History==\n\n[[File:Elsevier.svg|200px|right|thumb|The original seal of the Elsevier family, used by Elsevier company as logo until 2019.]]\nElsevier was founded in 1880{{sfn|Groen|2007|p=217}} and adopted the name and logo from the Dutch publishing house [[House of Elzevir|Elzevir]] that was an inspiration and has no connection to the contemporary Elsevier.{{sfn|Groen|2007|p=217}} The Elzevir family operated as booksellers and publishers in the [[Netherlands]]; the founder, [[Lodewijk Elzevir]] (1542\u20131617), lived in [[Leiden]] and established the business in 1580. As company logo, Elsevier used the Elzevir family's printer's mark, a tree entwined with a vine and the words ''Non Solus'', which is Latin for \"not alone.\"<ref name=\"AT 2019-03\" /> Elsevier suggests that this logo represents \"the symbiotic relationship between publisher and scholar\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.facebook.com/notes/elsevier-india/interesting-fact-history-of-the-elsevier-logo/295913917111368/ |title=Interesting Fact - History of the Elsevier Logo |website=[[Facebook]] |access-date=2019-06-12}}</ref>\n\nThe expansion of Elsevier in the scientific field after 1945 was funded with the profits of the newsweekly ''[[Elsevier (magazine)|Elsevier]]'', which published its first issue on 27 October 1945. The weekly was an instant success and earned lots of money.<ref>Gerry van der List, ''Meer dan een weekblad. De geschiedenis van Elsevier''</ref> The weekly was a continuation, as is stated in its first issue, of the monthly Elsevier, which was founded in 1891 to promote the name of the publishing house and had to stop publication in December 1940 because of the [[Netherlands in World War II|Nazi occupation of the Netherlands]].\n\nIn 1947, Elsevier began publishing its first English-language journal, ''[[Biochimica et Biophysica Acta]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Reed Elsevier Timeline |url=http://www.ulib.niu.edu/publishers/ReedElsevier.htm |website=www.ulib.niu.edu |accessdate=13 September 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151030233859/http://www.ulib.niu.edu/publishers/ReedElsevier.htm |archivedate=30 October 2015 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Elsevier acquired [[Mendeley]], a UK company making software for managing and sharing research papers. Mendeley, previously an open platform for sharing of research, was greatly criticized for the acquisition, which users saw as acceding to the \"[[paywall]]\" approach to research literature. Mendeley's previously open sharing system now allows exchange of paywalled resources only within private groups.<ref name=fast>{{cite web |last1=Amirtha |first1=Tina |title=THE OPEN PUBLISHING REVOLUTION, NOW BEHIND A BILLION-DOLLAR PAYWALL |url=http://www.fastcompany.com/3042443/mendeley-elsevier-and-the-future-of-scholarly-publishing |website=Fast Company |accessdate=26 January 2016 |date=2015-04-17}}</ref> ''[[The New Yorker]]'' described Elsevier's reasons for buying Mendeley as two-fold: to acquire its user data, and to \"destroy or co\u00f6pt an [[Open science|open-science]] icon that threatens its [[business model]]\".<ref name=\"NewYorker\">{{cite magazine |url=https://www.newyorker.com/online/blogs/elements/2013/04/elsevier-mendeley-journals-science-software.html |title=When the Rebel Alliance Sells Out |first=David |last=Dobbs |magazine=[[The New Yorker]] |date=12 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn the first half of 2019, RELX reported the first slowdown in revenue growth for Elsevier in several years: 1% vs. an expectation of 2% and a typical growth of at least 4% in the previous 5 years.<ref>{{cite news|title=Relx falls short of growth expectations|newspaper=Financial Times|author=Patricia Nilsson|date=2019-07-25|via=[https://finance.yahoo.com/m/c84c5326-55c5-3f81-b51d-9d1f4b7806e7/relx-falls-short-of-growth.html Yahoo Finance]}}</ref>\n\n== Company statistics ==\n{{as of | 2018 | alt = During 2018}}, researchers submitted over 1.8 million [[research papers]] to Elsevier-based publications. Over 20,000 editors managed the peer review and selection of these papers, resulting in the publication of more than 470,000 articles in over 2,500 journals.<ref name=\"RELX 2018 Report\" /> Editors are generally unpaid volunteers who perform their duties alongside a full-time job in academic institutions,<ref>{{cite journal|first1=James A.|last1=Coleman|title=How to get published in English: Advice from the outgoing Editor-in-Chief |url= |journal=System |date=2014-01-03 |issn=0346-251X |pages=404\u2013411 |volume=42 |doi=10.1016/j.system.2014.01.004|quote=Remember that editors and reviewers are unpaid, and are undertaking their tasks voluntarily, in addition to a full-time job}}</ref> although exceptions have been reported.\n\nIn 2013, the five editorial groups Elsevier, [[Springer Science+Business Media|Springer]], [[Wiley-Blackwell]], [[Taylor & Francis]], and [[SAGE Publications]] published more than half of all academic papers in the peer-reviewed literature.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vocativ.com/culture/science/five-corporations-control-academic-publishing/|title=These Five Corporations Control Academic Publishing|date=10 June 2015|website=Vocativ.com|accessdate=31 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=The Oligopoly of Academic Publishers in the Digital Era|author1=Vincent Larivi\u00e8re |author2=Stefanie Haustein |author3=Philippe Mongeon |journal=PLoS ONE|volume=10|issue=6|year=2015|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0127502 |pmid=26061978 |pmc=4465327 |pages=e0127502|bibcode=2015PLoSO..1027502L}}</ref> At that time, Elsevier accounted for 16% of the world market in science, technology, and medical publishing.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Elsevier leads the business the internet could not kill |url = https://www.ft.com/content/93138f3e-87d6-11e5-90de-f44762bf9896|website = www.ft.com|accessdate = 7 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nElsevier breaks down its revenue sources by format and by geographic region. Approximately 44% of revenue by geography in 2018 derived from North America, 24% from Europe and the remaining 32% from the rest of the world. Approximately 83% of revenue by format came from electronic usage and 17% came from print.<ref name=\"RELX 2018 Report\" />\n\nElsevier employs more than 7,800 people in over 70 offices across 24 countries. Following the integration of its Science & Technology and Health Sciences divisions in 2012, Elsevier has operated under a traditional business structure with a single [[chief executive officer]] (CEO).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.infotoday.com/it/mar13/Brynko--Mobed--Elseviers-Next-Steps.shtml|title=Elsevier Next Steps|publisher=Information Today|accessdate=7 November 2016}}</ref> The CEO is Kumsal Bayazit,<ref name=\"ataglance\">{{cite web |url= https://www.elsevier.com/about/management/kumsal-bayazit |title=Kumsal Bayazit |website=Elsevier.com |accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref> who was appointed on 15 February 2019.\n\nIn 2018, Elsevier accounted for 34% of the revenues of RELX group (\u20a42.538 billion of \u20a47.492 billion). In [[Earnings before interest and taxes|operating profits]], it represented 40% (\u20a4942 million of \u20a42,346 million). Adjusted operating profits (with constant currency) rose by 2% from 2017 to 2018<ref name=\"RELX 2018 Report\" />. Profits grew further from 2018 to 2019, to a total of \u00a3982 million<ref>\"RELX Annual Report and Financial Statements 2019\", https://www.relx.com/investors/annual-reports/2019</ref>.\n\nIn 2018, Elsevier reported a mean 2017 [[gender pay gap]] of 29.1% for its UK workforce, while the median was 40.4%, more than twice the UK average and by far the worst figure recorded by any academic publisher in UK. Elsevier attributed the result to the under-representation of women in its senior ranks and the prevalence of men in its technical workforce.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2019-08-11|title=Elsevier reports 40% gender pay gap|url=https://www.thebookseller.com/news/elsevier-reports-40-gender-pay-gap-759606|website=www.thebookseller.com}}</ref>\n\n==Market model==\n\n===Products and services===\n\nProducts and services include electronic and print versions of journals, textbooks and [[reference work]]s, and cover the [[healthcare science|health]], life, physical and [[social science]]s.\n\nThe target markets are academic and government research institutions, corporate research labs, booksellers, librarians, scientific researchers, authors, editors, physicians, nurses, allied health professionals, medical and nursing students and schools, medical researchers, [[Pharmaceutical company|pharmaceutical companies]], hospitals, and research establishments. It publishes in 13 languages including English, German, French, Spanish, Italian, Portuguese, Polish, Japanese, Hindi, and Chinese.\n\nFlagship products and services include VirtualE, [[ScienceDirect]], [[Scopus]], [[Scirus]], [[EMBASE]], Engineering Village, [[Compendex]], [[Cell (journal)|Cell]], SciVal, Pure, and Analytical Services, The Consult series (FirstCONSULT, PathCONSULT, NursingCONSULT, MDConsult, StudentCONSULT), Virtual Clinical Excursions, and major reference works such as ''[[Gray's Anatomy]]'', ''Nelson Pediatrics'', ''[[Dorland's Illustrated Medical Dictionary]]'', ''[[Frank H. Netter|Netter]]'s Atlas of Human Anatomy'', and online versions of many journals<ref>[http://www.journals.elsevierhealth.com/ Health Advance]. Elsevier.</ref> including ''[[The Lancet]]''.\n\nScienceDirect is Elsevier's platform for online electronic access to its journals and over 6,000 e-books, reference works, book series, and handbooks. The articles are grouped in four main sections: ''Physical Sciences and Engineering'', ''Life Sciences'', ''Health Sciences'', and ''Social Sciences and Humanities''. For most articles on the website, abstracts are freely available; access to the full text of the article (in PDF, and also HTML for newer publications) often requires a subscription or pay-per-view purchase.\n\n===Research and information ecosystem===\n\n[[RELX Group]] has been [[RELX Group#Significant acquisitions|active]] in [[mergers and acquisitions]]. Elsevier has been joined by businesses which were either complementing or competing in the field of research and publishing and which reinforce its [[market power]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.techdirt.com/articles/20170804/05454537924/elsevier-continues-to-build-monopoly-solution-all-aspects-scholarly-communication.shtml|title=Elsevier Continues To Build Its Monopoly Solution For All Aspects Of Scholarly Communication|last=|first=|date=2017-08-04|work=Techdirt|access-date=2018-10-17|author=Glyn Moody|author-link=Glyn Moody}}</ref> such as [[Mendeley]] (after the closure of [[2collab]]), [[SSRN]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.techdirt.com/articles/20160517/13513134465/disappointing-elsevier-buys-open-access-academic-pre-publisher-ssrn.shtml|title=Disappointing: Elsevier Buys Open Access Academic Pre-Publisher SSRN|last=|first=|date=2016-05-17|work=Techdirt|access-date=2018-10-17|author=Mike Masnick|author-link=Mike Masnick}}</ref> [[bepress]]/[[Digital Commons (Elsevier)|Digital Commons]], [[PlumX]], Hivebench, Newsflo.<ref name=Herb2019/> These integrations are seen as a way to exert additional power on the research process.<ref name=Herb2019>{{cite journal |last1=Herb |first1=Ulrich|date=2019|title=Steering science through Output Indicators & Data Capitalism|doi=10.5281/zenodo.3333395|doi-access=free}}</ref> The group contains additional information and analytics companies, particularly [[LexisNexis]] and [[ThreatMetrix]].\n\n=== Conferences ===\nElsevier conducts conferences, exhibitions and workshops around the world, with over 50 conferences a year covering life sciences, physical sciences and engineering, social sciences, and health sciences.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.elsevier.com/events/conferences |title=Conferences |work=elsevier.com}}</ref>\n\n===Pricing===\n\nIn the 21st century, the subscription rates charged by the company for its journals have been criticized; some very large journals (with more than 5,000 articles) charge subscription prices as high as \u00a39,634, far above average,<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2011/aug/29/academic-publishers-murdoch-socialist|journal=Guardian|last=Monbiot|first=George|date=29 August 2011|title=Academic publishers make Murdoch look like a socialist}}</ref> and many British universities pay more than a million pounds to Elsevier annually.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://gowers.wordpress.com/2014/04/24/elsevier-journals-some-facts/ |title=Elsevier journals \u2014 some facts |work=Gowers's Weblog |date=24 April 2014 |accessdate=27 July 2014}}</ref> The company has been criticized not only by advocates of a switch to the [[Open access (publishing)|open-access]] publication model, but also by universities whose library budgets make it difficult for them to afford current journal prices.\n\nFor example, a resolution by [[Stanford University]]'s senate singled out Elsevier's journals as being \"disproportionately expensive compared to their educational and research value\", which librarians should consider dropping, and encouraged its faculty \"not to contribute articles or editorial or review efforts to publishers and journals that engage in exploitive or exorbitant pricing\".<ref>''[http://news-service.stanford.edu/news/2004/february25/minutes-225.html Faculty Senate minutes February 19 meeting]'' Stanford Report, 25 February 2004</ref> Similar guidelines and criticism of Elsevier's pricing policies have been passed by the [[University of California]], [[Harvard University]], and [[Duke University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.stanforddaily.com/?p=1013953 |title=Fac Sen addresses costly journals |work=The Stanford Daily |date=20 February 2004 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105040316/http://archive.stanforddaily.com/?p=1013953 |archivedate=5 November 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nIn July 2015, the [[Association of Universities in the Netherlands]] (VSNU) announced a plan to start boycotting Elsevier, which refused to negotiate on any [[Open Access]] policy for Dutch universities.<ref>Danny Kingsley [https://unlockingresearch.blog.lib.cam.ac.uk/?p=192 ''Dutch boycott of Elsevier \u2013 a game changer?''], University of Cambridge Office of Scholarly Communication</ref> In December 2016, [[Nature Publishing Group]] reported that academics in Germany, Peru and Taiwan are to lose access to Elsevier journals as negotiations had broken down with the publisher.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Schiermeier|first=Quirin|last2=Mega|first2=Emiliano Rodr\u00edguez|title=Scientists in Germany, Peru and Taiwan to lose access to Elsevier journals|journal=Nature|doi=10.1038/nature.2016.21223|pmid=28054621|volume=541|issue=7635|page=13|year=2016|bibcode=2017Natur.541...13S|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\nA complaint about Elsevier/RELX was made to the UK [[Competition and Markets Authority]] in December 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.martineve.com/2016/12/03/referring-elsevierrelx-to-the-competition-and-markets-authority/|title=Referring Elsevier/RELX to the Competition and Markets Authority|author=Martin Paul Eve|language=en-US|date=2016-12-14|author-link=Martin Paul Eve}}</ref> In October 2018, a competition complaint against Elsevier was filed with the European Commission, alleging anti-competitive practices stemming from Elsevier's confidential subscription agreements and market dominance.<ref name=\"competition_plaint\">{{cite news |last1=Kelly |first1=\u00c9anna |title=Researchers complain to Brussels over 'dominant position' of RELX Group in scientific publishing |url=https://sciencebusiness.net/framework-programmes/news/researchers-complain-brussels-over-dominant-position-relx-group |accessdate=16 January 2019 |work=sciencebusiness.net |date=2 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Shill review offer ===\n\nAccording to the [[BBC]], \"the firm [Elsevier] offered a \u00a317.25 Amazon voucher to academics who contributed to the textbook ''Clinical Psychology'' if they would go on [[Amazon.com]] and [[Barnes & Noble]] (a large US books retailer) and give it five stars.\" Elsevier said that \"encouraging interested parties to post book reviews isn't outside the norm in scholarly publishing, nor is it wrong to offer to nominally compensate people for their time. But in all instances the request should be unbiased, with no incentives for a positive review, and that's where this particular e-mail went too far\", and that it was a mistake by a marketing employee.<ref>Finlo Rohrer, \"[http://news.bbc.co.uk/go/pr/fr/-/2/hi/uk_news/magazine/8118577.stm The perils of five-star reviews]\", ''BBC News Magazine'', 25 June 2009.</ref>\n\n=== Blocking text mining research ===\nElsevier seeks to regulate [[text and data mining]] with private licenses,<ref name=nature527413f/> claiming that reading requires extra permission if automated and that the publisher holds copyright on [[threshold of originality|output of automated processes]]. The conflict on research and copyright policy has often resulted in researchers being blocked from their work.<ref>{{cite journal|first1=Richard|last1=Van Noorden|title=Elsevier opens its papers to text-mining|journal=Nature|date=2014-02-03|issn=0028-0836|pages=17|volume=506|issue=7486|doi=10.1038/506017a|pmid=24499898|doi-access=free|quote=\u201cIt was a legitimate criticism, that people sent text-mining requests in to publishers and they bounced around for a time without any response,\u201d admits Chris Shillum, vice-president of product management for platform and content at Elsevier.|bibcode=2014Natur.506...17V}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2015, Elsevier blocked a scientist from performing [[text mining]] research at scale on Elsevier papers, even though his institution already pays for access to Elsevier journal content.<ref name=nature527413f>{{cite journal|last1=Bloudoff-Indelicato|first1=Mollie|title=Text-mining block prompts online response|journal=Nature|date=20 November 2015|volume=527|issue=7579|pages=413|doi=10.1038/527413f|bibcode=2015Natur.527..413B}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Moody|first1=Glyn|title=Elsevier Says Downloading And Content-Mining Licensed Copies Of Research Papers 'Could Be Considered' Stealing|url=https://www.techdirt.com/articles/20151117/09383132839/elsevier-says-downloading-content-mining-licensed-copies-research-papers-could-be-considered-stealing.shtml|website=TechDirt|accessdate=21 November 2015}}</ref> The data were collected via parsing of downloaded PDF and HTML files,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Nuijten|first1=Mich\u00e8le B.|last2=Hartgerink|first2=Chris H. J.|last3=van Assen|first3=Marcel A. L. M.|last4=Epskamp|first4=Sacha|last5=Wicherts|first5=Jelte M.|title=The prevalence of statistical reporting errors in psychology (1985\u20132013)|journal=Behavior Research Methods|date=23 October 2015|volume=48|issue=4|pages=1205\u20131226|doi=10.3758/s13428-015-0664-2|pmid=26497820|pmc=5101263}}</ref> although Elsevier claimed that the method used was [[screenscraping]].<ref>A. Wise, 2015-11-17, [http://onsnetwork.org/chartgerink/2015/11/16/elsevier-stopped-me-doing-my-research/#comment-11 Elsevier stopped me doing my research - Comment by Dr Alicia Wise]</ref>\n\n== Academic practices ==\n\n=== \"Who's Afraid of Peer Review\" ===\n{{main|Who's Afraid of Peer Review?}}\n\nOne of Elsevier's journals was caught in the sting set up by [[John Bohannon]], published in [[Science (journal)|''Science'']], called \"Who's Afraid of Peer Review?\"<ref name=\"Bohannon2013\">{{Cite journal | last1 = Bohannon | first1 = John| authorlink1 = John Bohannon| title = Who's Afraid of Peer Review? | doi = 10.1126/science.342.6154.60 | journal = Science | volume = 342 | issue = 6154 | pages = 60\u201365 | year = 2013 | pmid =  24092725| pmc = |bibcode = 2013Sci...342...60B | doi-access = free }}</ref> The journal ''Drug Invention Today'' accepted an obviously bogus paper made up by Bohannon that should have been rejected by any good [[peer review]] system.<ref>{{cite news|author=Claire Shaw |url=https://www.theguardian.com/higher-education-network/2013/oct/04/open-access-journals-fake-paper |title=Hundreds of open access journals accept fake science paper |publisher=Theguardian.com |accessdate=26 December 2013|newspaper=The Guardian |date=2013-10-04 }}</ref> Instead, ''Drug Invention Today'' was among many [[open access]] journals that accepted the fake paper for publication. As of 2014, this journal had been transferred to a different publisher.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/journal/09757619|title=Drug Invention Today|work=sciencedirect.com}}</ref>\n\n=== Fake journals ===<!-- See talk section \"Elsevier published 6 fake journals\" for discussion of this heading\" -->\n{{further|Australasian Journal of Bone & Joint Medicine}}\n\nAt a 2009 court case in Australia where [[Merck & Co.]] was being sued by a user of [[Vioxx]], the plaintiff alleged that Merck had paid Elsevier to publish the ''[[Australasian Journal of Bone and Joint Medicine]]'', which had the appearance of being a [[peer-review]]ed [[academic journal]] but in fact contained only articles favourable to Merck drugs.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/story/0,25197,25311725-5013871,00.html |title=Doctors signed Merck's Vioxx studies |last=Rout |first=Milanda |date=9 April 2009 |work=[[The Australian]] |accessdate=4 May 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090506064629/http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/story/0,25197,25311725-5013871,00.html |archive-date=6 May 2009 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://classic.the-scientist.com/blog/display/55671/ |title=Merck published fake journal |last=Grant |first=Bob |date=30 April 2009 |work=[[The Scientist (magazine)|The Scientist]] |accessdate=4 May 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.theage.com.au/national/merck-accused-of-ghost-writing-medical-article-20090422-afdk.html?page=-1 |title=Merck accused of 'ghost writing' medical article |last=Hagan |first=Kate |date=23 April 2009 |work=[[The Age]] |accessdate=4 May 2009}}</ref><ref>Ben Goldacre, [https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2009/may/09/bad-science-medical-journals-companies \"The danger of drugs \u2026 and data\"], ''The Guardian'', 9 May 2009</ref> Merck described the journal as a \"complimentary publication,\" denied claims that articles within it were [[ghost writer|ghost written]] by Merck, and stated that the articles were all reprinted from peer-reviewed medical journals.<ref>{{cite press release|title=Merck Responds to Questions about the Australasian Journal of Bone and Joint Medicine Journal |date=30 April 2009 |url=http://www.merck.com/newsroom/vioxx/pdf/statement_20090430.pdf |publisher=[[Merck & Co.]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091231104929/http://merck.com/newsroom/vioxx/pdf/statement_20090430.pdf |archivedate=31 December 2009 |df=dmy }}</ref> In May 2009, Elsevier Health Sciences CEO Hansen released a statement regarding Australia-based sponsored journals, conceding that they were \"sponsored article compilation publications, on behalf of pharmaceutical clients, that were made to look like journals and lacked the proper disclosures.\" The statement acknowledged that it \"was an unacceptable practice.\"<ref>{{cite press release |title=Statement from Michael Hansen, CEO Of Elsevier's Health Sciences Division, regarding Australia based sponsored journal practices between 2000 and 2005 |url= http://www.elsevier.com/wps/find/authored_newsitem.cws_home/companynews05_01203 |publisher=Elsevier}}</ref> ''[[The Scientist (magazine)|The Scientist]]'' reported that, according to an Elsevier spokesperson, six sponsored publications \"were put out by their Australia office and bore the [[Excerpta Medica]] imprint from 2000 to 2005,\" namely the ''Australasian Journal of Bone and Joint Medicine'' (''Australas. J. Bone Joint Med.''), the ''Australasian Journal of General Practice'' (''Australas. J. Gen. Pract.''), the ''Australasian Journal of Neurology'' (''Australas. J. Neurol.''), the ''Australasian Journal of Cardiology'' (''Australas. J. Cardiol.''), the ''Australasian Journal of Clinical Pharmacy'' (''Australas. J. Clin. Pharm.''), and the ''Australasian Journal of Cardiovascular Medicine'' (''Australas. J. Cardiovasc. Med.'').<ref>{{cite news|first=Bob|last=Grant|title=Elsevier published 6 fake journals |url=http://www.the-scientist.com/blog/display/55679/ |date=7 May 2009 |work=[[The Scientist (magazine)|The Scientist]]}}</ref> Excerpta Medica was a \"strategic medical communications agency\" run by Elsevier, according to the imprint's web page.<ref>{{cite web|title=\"Excerpta Medica\", official webpage |url=http://www.excerptamedica.com/ |publisher=Elsevier}}</ref> In October 2010, Excerpta Medica was acquired by Adelphi Worldwide.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Excerpta Medica Joins Adelphi Worldwide\", press release |url= http://www.excerptamedica.com/?page=newsroom&item=301 |publisher=Elsevier}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Chaos, Solitons & Fractals'' ===\n\nThere was speculation<ref>{{cite journal |title=Self-publishing editor set to retire |doi=10.1038/456432a | volume=456 |issue=7221 | journal=Nature |pages=432 |pmid=19037282 | last1 = Schiermeier | first1 = Q|year=2008 |doi-access=free }}</ref> that the editor-in-chief of Elsevier journal ''Chaos, Solitons & Fractals'', [[Mohamed El Naschie]], misused his power to publish his own work without appropriate peer review. The journal had published 322 papers with El Naschie as author since 1993. The last issue of December 2008 featured five of his papers.<ref>''Chaos, Solitons & Fractals'' '''38'''(5), pp. 1229\u20131534 (December 2008)</ref> The controversy was covered extensively in blogs.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://scholarlykitchen.sspnet.org/?s=el+naschie| title= The Scholarly Kitchen}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://elnaschiewatch.blogspot.com/ |title= El Naschie Watch Blog |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101015195449/http://elnaschiewatch.blogspot.com/ |archivedate= 15 October 2010 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> The publisher announced in January 2009 that El Naschie had retired as editor-in-chief.<ref>{{Cite journal| doi = 10.1016/S0960-0779(09)00060-5| title = Publisher's note| year = 2009| journal = Chaos, Solitons & Fractals| volume = 39| pages = v\u2013|bibcode = 2009CSF....39D...5. }}</ref> {{As of|2011|11}} the co-Editors-in-Chief of the journal were Maurice Courbage and Paolo Grigolini.<ref>{{cite book |url= http://www.journals.elsevier.com/chaos-solitons-and-fractals/ |title= Chaos, Solitons and Fractals |date=November 2011}}</ref> In June 2011, El Naschie sued the journal ''[[Nature (journal)|Nature]]'' for libel, claiming that his reputation had been damaged by their November 2008 article about his retirement, which included statements that ''Nature'' had been unable to verify his claimed affiliations with certain international institutions.<ref name=\"BBC-CSF-libel\">{{cite news | title = Nature journal libel case begins | work = BBC News | last1 = Ghosh | first1 = Pallab | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-15697636 | accessdate = 11 November 2011 | date=11 November 2011}}</ref> The suit came to trial in November 2011 and was dismissed in July 2012, with the judge ruling that the article was \"substantially true\", contained \"honest comment\" and was \"the product of responsible journalism\". The judgement noted that El Naschie, who represented himself in court, had failed to provide any documentary evidence that his papers had been peer-reviewed.<ref name=\"Guardian2\">[https://www.theguardian.com/science/2012/jul/06/nature-libel-peer-review?newsfeed=true \"Nature libel verdict 'a victory for free speech'\"],''The Guardian'' 6 July 2012</ref> Judge [[Victoria Sharp]] also found \"reasonable and serious grounds\" for suspecting that El Naschie used a range of false names to defend his editorial practice in communications with ''Nature'', and described this behavior as \"curious\" and \"bizarre.\" <ref>{{cite journal\n| last       = Aron\n| first       = Jacob\n| date        = 6 July 2012\n| title       = Nature Publishing Group wins libel trial\n| journal     = New Scientist\n| issue       = 2873\n| url         = https://www.newscientist.com/article/dn22026-nature-publishing-group-wins-libel-trial.html\n| accessdate  = 14 July 2012\n}}</ref>\n\n===Plagiarism===\nSome Elsevier journals automatically screen submissions for plagiarism,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.elsevier.com/editors/perk/plagiarism-complaints/plagiarism-detection |title=Plagiarism detection |publisher=Elsevier}}</ref> but not all.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://retractionwatch.com/2018/08/23/elsevier-investigating-paper-on-solar-cells-that-appears-to-plagiarize-a-nature-journal/ |title=UPDATED: Elsevier retracts a paper on solar cells that appears to plagiarize a Nature journal. But the reason is\u2026odd |author=Ivan Oransky|date=2018-08-23}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Elsevier journal ''[[Procedia]]'' was reported to have published plagiarism by an Albanian politician in 2012.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://exit.al/en/2018/12/25/massive-plagiarism-scandal-hits-albanian-officials/ |title= Massive Plagiarism Scandal Hits Albanian Officials without Consequences |date=2018-12-25}}</ref>\n\n== Control of journals ==\n\n=== Resignation of editorial boards ===\nIn November 1999 the entire editorial board (50 persons) of the ''[[Journal of Logic Programming]]'' (founded in 1984 by [[John Alan Robinson|Alan Robinson]]) collectively resigned after 16 months of unsuccessful negotiations with Elsevier Press about the price of library subscriptions.<ref name=birman>[[Joan Birman]]. \"[http://www.ams.org/notices/200007/forum-birman.pdf Scientific publishing: a mathematician\u2019s viewpoint]\". ''[[Notices of the AMS]]''. Vol. 47, No. 7, August 2000</ref> The personnel created a new journal, ''Theory and Practice of Logic Programming'', with [[Cambridge University Press]] at a much lower price,<ref name=birman/> while Elsevier continued publication with a new editorial board and a slightly different name (the ''[[Journal of Logic and Algebraic Programming]]'').\n\nIn 2002, dissatisfaction at Elsevier's pricing policies caused the [[European Economic Association]] to terminate an agreement with Elsevier designating Elsevier's ''[[European Economic Review]]'' as the official journal of the association. The EEA launched a new journal, the ''[[Journal of the European Economic Association]]''.<ref>{{cite web|author=EffeDesign |url=http://www.eeassoc.org/index.php?page=14 |title=The EEA's journal: a brief history |publisher=Eeassoc.org |accessdate=26 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, the entire editorial board of the ''Journal of Algorithms'' resigned to start ''[[ACM Transactions on Algorithms]]'' with a different, lower-priced, not-for-profit publisher,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cs.colorado.edu/~hal/s.pdf |title=Changes at the Journal of Algorithms |accessdate=26 December 2013}}</ref> at the suggestion of ''Journal of Algorithms'' founder [[Donald Knuth]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www-cs-faculty.stanford.edu/~knuth/joalet.pdf | author=Donald Knuth| date=25 October 2003 | title=Letter to the editorial board of the Journal of Algorithms| accessdate=18 February 2008}}</ref> The ''Journal of Algorithms'' continued under Elsevier with a new editorial board until October 2009, when it was discontinued.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/journal/01966774 |title=Journal of Algorithms page at ScienceDirect |publisher=Sciencedirect.com |accessdate=26 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe same happened in 2005 to the ''International Journal of Solids and Structures'', whose editors resigned to start the ''[[Journal of Mechanics of Materials and Structures]]''. However, a new editorial board was quickly established and the journal continues in apparently unaltered form with editors D.A. Hills ([[Oxford University]]) and Stelios Kyriakides ([[University of Texas at Austin]]).<ref>{{cite web |title=Journal declarations of independence |url=http://oad.simmons.edu/oadwiki/Journal_declarations_of_independence#2005 |work=Open Access Directory |publisher=Simmons College |accessdate=23 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Kyriakides|first=Stelios|author2=Hills, David A.|title=Editorial|journal=International Journal of Solids and Structures|date=1 January 2006|volume=43|issue=1|page=1|doi=10.1016/j.ijsolstr.2005.11.001|accessdate=|quote=Charles R. Steele succeeded Herrmann as editor in chief in 1985 and served in that capacity until June 2005. During his 20-year tenure the journal grew both in size and in reputation, becoming one of the premier journals in the field. We have accepted an invitation to serve as editors of the journal as of October 1, 2005, being cognizant of the immense contributions, leadership, and high standards exercised by our two predecessors on the way to making IJSS the forum it is today.}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2006, the entire editorial board of the distinguished [[mathematical journal]] ''[[Topology (journal)|Topology]]'' handed in their resignation, again because of stalled negotiations with Elsevier to lower the subscription price.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://math.ucr.edu/home/baez/topology-letter.pdf | date=10 August 2006 | title=Resignation letter from the editors of Topology | accessdate=18 February 2008}}</ref> This board then launched the new ''[[Journal of Topology]]'' at a far lower price, under the auspices of the [[London Mathematical Society]].<ref>[http://www.lms.ac.uk/publications/jtop.html Journal of Topology] (pub. London Mathematical Society) {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070207123258/http://www.lms.ac.uk/publications/jtop.html |date=7 February 2007 }}</ref> After this mass resignation, ''[[Topology (journal)|Topology]]'' remained in circulation under a new editorial board until 2009, when the last issue was published.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://www.journals.elsevier.com/topology/|title=Topology|publisher=elsevier.com|accessdate=13 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/journal/00409383/48/2-4 |title=Topology page at ScienceDirect |publisher=Sciencedirect.com |accessdate=26 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe French [[\u00c9cole Normale Sup\u00e9rieure]] has stopped having Elsevier publish the journal ''[[Annales Scientifiques de l'\u00c9cole Normale Sup\u00e9rieure]]''<ref>[[John Baez]]: ''[http://math.ucr.edu/home/baez/journals.html What We Can Do About Science Journals]'' 13 August 2007</ref> (as of 2008).<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.elsevier.com/wps/find/journaldescription.cws_home/600714/description | title=Publisher's description of Annales Scientifiques de l'\u00c9cole Normale Sup\u00e9rieure | publisher=Elsevier | accessdate=18 February 2008 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080412014908/http://www.elsevier.com/wps/find/journaldescription.cws_home/600714/description | archivedate=12 April 2008 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe elevated pricing of field journals in economics, most of which are published by Elsevier, was one of the motivations that moved the [[American Economic Association]] to launch the ''[[American Economic Journal]]'' in 2009.<ref>David Glenn. \"American Economic Association Plans 4 New Journals\". '' The Chronicle of Higher Education''. 25 January 2008. Available online at [http://chronicle.com/article/American-Economic-Association/440 Chronicle.com]</ref>\n\nIn May 2015, [[Stephen Leeder]] was removed from his role as editor of the ''[[Medical Journal of Australia]]'' after its publisher decided to outsource the journal's production to Elsevier. As a consequence, all but one of the journal's editorial advisory committee members co-signed a letter of resignation.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/medical-journal-editor-sacked-and-editorial-committee-resigns-20150503-1myr8q.html | title=Medical journal editor sacked and editorial committee resigns | accessdate=18 May 2015| date=2015-05-03 }}</ref>\n\nIn October 2015, the entire editorial staff of the [[general linguistics]] journal ''[[Lingua (journal)|Lingua]]'' resigned in protest of Elsevier's unwillingness to agree to their terms of [[Fair Access to Science and Technology Research Act|Fair Open Access]]. Editor in Chief Johan Rooryck also announced that the Lingua staff would establish a new journal, ''[[Glossa (journal)|Glossa]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2015/11/02/editors-and-editorial-board-quit-top-linguistics-journal-protest-subscription-fees|title=Language of Protest|last=Jaschik|first=Scott|date=2 November 2015|work=Inside Higher Ed|access-date=18 January 2017|via=}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2019, the entire editorial board of Elsevier's ''[[Journal of Informetrics]]'' resigned over the open-access policies of its publisher and founded open-access journal called Quantitative Science Studies.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2019/01/14/elsevier-journal-editors-resign-start-rival-open-access-journal|title=Elsevier journal editors resign, start rival open-access journal}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2019/01/14/elsevier-journal-editors-resign-start-rival-open-access-journal|title=Elsevier journal editors resign, start rival open-access journal|website=www.insidehighered.com|language=en|access-date=2019-01-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Chawla|first=Dalmeet Singh|date=2019-01-14|title=Open-access row prompts editorial board of Elsevier journal to resign|url=http://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-019-00135-8|journal=Nature|language=EN|doi=10.1038/d41586-019-00135-8}}</ref>\n\n===\"The Cost of Knowledge\" boycott===\n{{Main|The Cost of Knowledge}}\n\nIn 2003 various university librarians began coordinating with each other to complain about Elsevier's \"[[Subscription business model|big deal]]\" journal bundling packages, in which the company offered a group of journal subscriptions to libraries at a certain rate, but in which librarians claimed there was no economical option to subscribe to only the popular journals at a rate comparable to the bundled rate.{{sfn|Groen|2007|p=177}} Librarians continued to discuss the implications of the pricing schemes, many feeling pressured into buying the Elsevier packages without other options.{{sfn|Groen|2007|p=180}}\n\nOn 21 January 2012, mathematician [[Timothy Gowers]] publicly announced he would boycott Elsevier, noting that others in the field have been doing so privately. The three reasons for the [[boycott]] are high subscription prices for individual journals, bundling subscriptions to journals of different value and importance, and Elsevier's support for [[Stop Online Piracy Act|SOPA]], [[PROTECT IP Act|PIPA]], and the [[Research Works Act]].<ref name=Guardian>{{cite news|last=Flood |first=Alison |url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2012/feb/02/academics-boycott-publisher-elsevier |title=Scientists sign petition to boycott academic publisher Elsevier |newspaper=The Guardian |date=2 February 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/65VHiGo2Z?url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/science/2012/feb/02/academics-boycott-publisher-elsevier |archivedate=16 February 2012 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref><ref name=Chronicle>{{cite news|last=Fischman |first=Josh |url=http://chronicle.com/blogs/wiredcampus/elsevier-publishing-boycott-gathers-steam-among-academics/35216 |title=Elsevier Publishing Boycott Gathers Steam Among Academics |newspaper=The Chronicle of Higher Education |date=30 January 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/65VIHYC2S?url=http://chronicle.com/blogs/wiredcampus/elsevier-publishing-boycott-gathers-steam-among-academics/35216 |archivedate=16 February 2012 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref><ref name=Economist>{{cite news|url=http://www.economist.com/node/21545974 |title=Scientific publishing: The price of information |work=The Economist |date=4 February 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/65VHxfKJ9?url=http://www.economist.com/node/21545974 |archivedate=16 February 2012 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nFollowing this, a petition advocating non-cooperation with Elsevier (that is, not submitting papers to Elsevier journals, not [[peer review|refereeing]] articles in Elsevier journals, and not participating in journal editorial boards), appeared on the site \"The Cost of Knowledge\". By February 2012 this petition had been signed by over 5,000 academics,<ref name=Guardian/><ref name=Chronicle/> growing to over 17,000 by November 2018.<ref>{{cite web|title=thecostofknowledge.com|url=http://thecostofknowledge.com/|accessdate=12 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nElsevier disputed the claims, claiming that their prices are below the industry average, and stating that bundling is only one of several different options available to buy access to Elsevier journals.<ref name=Guardian/> The company also claimed that its profit margins are \"simply a consequence of the firm's efficient operation\".<ref name=Economist/> The academics replied that their work was funded by public money and thus should be freely available.\n\nOn 27 February 2012, Elsevier issued a statement on its website that declared that it has withdrawn support from the Research Works Act.<ref>{{cite web|title=Elsevier Backs Down as Boycott Grows|url=http://www.elsevier.com/about/issues-and-information/newmessagerwa|accessdate=25 August 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140911222130/http://www.elsevier.com/about/issues-and-information/newmessagerwa|archivedate=11 September 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Although the Cost of Knowledge movement was not mentioned, the statement indicated the hope that the move would \"help create a less heated and more productive climate\" for ongoing discussions with research funders. Hours after Elsevier's statement, the sponsors of the bill, [[United States House of Representatives|US House Representatives]] [[Darrell Issa]] and [[Carolyn Maloney]], issued a joint statement saying that they would not push the bill in Congress.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sponsors and Supporters Back Away from Research Works Act|url=http://www.sparc.arl.org/news/sponsors-and-supporters-back-away-research-works-act|accessdate=25 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Plan S===\nThe [[Plan S]] open-access initiative, which began in Europe and has since spread to some US research funding agencies would force researchers receiving some grants to publish in open access journals by 2020.<ref name=\"US_funders\">{{cite journal |last1=Noorden |first1=Richard Van |title=Wellcome and Gates join bold European open-access plan |journal=Nature |date=5 November 2018 |doi=10.1038/d41586-018-07300-5 |url=https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-018-07300-5 |accessdate=16 January 2019 |language=EN}}</ref> A spokesman for Elsevier said \"If you think that information should be free of charge, go to Wikipedia\".<ref>{{cite news |title=11 EU-landen besluiten: vanaf 2020 moet alle wetenschappelijke literatuur gratis beschikbaar zijn |first=Maarten |last=Keulemans |url= https://www.volkskrant.nl/nieuws-achtergrond/11-eu-landen-besluiten-vanaf-2020-moet-alle-wetenschappelijke-literatuur-gratis-beschikbaar-zijn~be002c39/ |newspaper=De Volkskrant |date=4 September 2018 |accessdate=25 September 2018 |language=Dutch |quote=Als je vindt dat informatie gratis moet zijn: ga naar Wikipedia.}}</ref> In September 2018 [[UBS]] advised to sell Elsevier (RELX) stocks, noting that Plan S could affect 5-10% of scientific funding and may force Elsevier to reduce pricing.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Elder |first1=Bryce |title=Stocks to watch: SSE, BAT, Gal\u00e1pagos, RELX, Telef\u00f3nica, RBS |url=https://www.ft.com/content/2a2064e2-b669-11e8-bbc3-ccd7de085ffe |accessdate=14 October 2018 |work=[[Financial Times]] |date=12 September 2018 }}</ref>\n\n== Relationship with academic institutions ==\n\n=== Finland ===\nIn 2015 Finnish research organizations paid a total of 27 million euros in subscription fees. Over one third of the total costs went to Elsevier. The information was revealed after successful court appeal following a denied request on the subscription fees, due to confidentiality clauses in contracts with the publishers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ropengov.github.io/r/2016/06/10/FOI/|title=Scientific journal subscription costs in Finland 2010-2015: a preliminary analysis|website=rOpenGov|access-date=2017-10-15}}</ref> Establishing of this fact lead to creation of tiedonhinta.fi petition demanding more reasonable pricing and open access to content signed by more than 2800 members of the research community.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://tiedonhinta.fi/en/english/|title=Tiedonhinta.fi|website=tiedonhinta.fi|language=en-GB|access-date=2017-10-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171015203433/http://tiedonhinta.fi/en/english/|archive-date=15 October 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> While deals with other publishers have been made, this was not the case for Elsevier, leading to the nodealnoreview.org boycott of the publisher signed more than 600 times.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nodealnoreview.org/|title=No deal, no review \u2013 #nodealnoreview|website=Nodealnoreview.org|language=en-US|access-date=2017-10-15}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2018, it was confirmed that a deal had been reached between those concerned.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kansalliskirjasto.fi/en/news/finelib-and-elsevier-reach-agreement-for-subscription-access-and-open-access-publishing|title=FinELib and Elsevier Reach Agreement for Subscription Access and Open Access Publishing|last=Kukkonen|first=Suvi|date=2018-01-17|website=National Library|language=en|access-date=2018-01-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mostlyphysics.net/blog/2018/1/25/finland-takes-a-step-back-in-the-openness-of-academic-journal-pricing|title=Finland takes steps in the openness of academic journal pricing|author=Toma Susi|date=2018-01-25|newspaper=Mostly Physics|accessdate=2018-05-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite publication|author=Marie Farge|accessdate=2018-05-01|title=Transition vers l'Acc\u00e8s Libre: le pi\u00e8ge des accords globaux avec les \u00e9diteurs|url=https://blogs.mediapart.fr/edition/au-coeur-de-la-recherche/article/130418/transition-vers-l-acces-libre-le-piege-des-accords-globaux-avec-les-editeur|newspaper=Matematika|publisher=Club de Mediapart|language=fr}}</ref>\n\n=== France ===\nThe French [[Couperin (consortium)|Couperin consortium]] agreed in 2019 to a 4-year contract with Elsevier,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aefinfo.fr/assets/medias/documents/4/8/482545.pdf|title=Communiqu\u00e9 sur la n\u00e9gociation Elsevier|last=Consortium Couperin|date=2019-06-11}}</ref> despite criticism from the scientific community.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.lemonde.fr/sciences/article/2019/05/13/embrouilles-a-propos-de-l-acces-aux-revues-scientifiques_5461530_1650684.html|title=Embrouilles \u00e0 propos de l'acc\u00e8s aux revues scientifiques|date=2019-05-13|access-date=2019-08-26|language=fr}}</ref>\n\n===Germany===\nAlmost no academic institution in Germany is subscribed to Elsevier.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.projekt-deal.de/vertragskundigungen-elsevier-2018/|title=Vertragsk\u00fcndigungen Elsevier 2018|last=Haufe|first=Gottfried|date=20 November 2018|website=www.projekt-deal.de|access-date=6 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-019-00492-4|title=Thousands of scientists run up against Elsevier's paywall|last=Else|first=Holly|date=5 February 2019|journal=Nature|access-date=6 March 2019|doi=10.1038/d41586-019-00492-4}}</ref>\n\nGermany's DEAL project ([[Projekt DEAL]]) which includes over 60 major research institutions<!--consortium of state-funded universities and research organizations-->, has announced that all of its members are cancelling their contracts with Elsevier, effective 1 January 2017. The boycott is in response to Elsevier's refusal to adopt \"transparent business models\" to \"make publications more openly accessible\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Doctorow|first1=Cory|title=Germany-wide consortium of research libraries announce boycott of Elsevier journals over open access|url=https://boingboing.net/2016/12/15/germany-wide-consortium-of-res.html|publisher=Boing Boing|accessdate=27 December 2016|date=15 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=No full-text access to Elsevier journals to be expected from 1 January 2017 on|url=https://www.sub.uni-goettingen.de/en/news/details/voraussichtlich-keine-volltexte-von-zeitschriften-des-elsevier-verlags-ab-dem-112017/|publisher=G\u00f6ttingen State and University Library|accessdate=27 December 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161227132101/https://www.sub.uni-goettingen.de/en/news/details/voraussichtlich-keine-volltexte-von-zeitschriften-des-elsevier-verlags-ab-dem-112017/|archivedate=27 December 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=nature1/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lrk-bw.de/index.php/pressemitteilungen|title=Pressemitteilungen|website=Lrk-bw.de|language=de-de|access-date=2017-07-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.the-scientist.com/?articles.view/articleNo/49906/title/Major-German-Universities-Cancel-Elsevier-Contracts/|title=Major German Universities Cancel Elsevier Contracts|website=The Scientist|access-date=2017-07-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://www.sciencemag.org/news/2017/08/bold-open-access-push-germany-could-change-future-academic-publishing|title=A bold open-access push in Germany could change the future of academic publishing|date=2017-08-23|journal=Science|access-date=2017-08-24|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hrk.de/press/press-releases/press-release/meldung/researchers-resign-editorship-of-elsevier-journals-4237/|title=Researchers resign editorship of Elsevier journals|last=Conference|first=German Rectors'|access-date=2017-10-16|language=en}}</ref> Horst Hippler, spokesperson for the DEAL consortium states that \"taxpayers have a right to read what they are paying for\" and that \"publishers must understand that the route to open-access publishing at an affordable price is irreversible\".<ref name=nature1/> In July 2017, another 13 institutions announced that they would also be cancelling their subscriptions to Elsevier journals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.booksandpublishing.com.au/articles/2017/07/26/93682/german-universities-to-let-elsevier-contracts-lapse/|title=German universities to let Elsevier contracts lapse {{!}} Books+Publishing|website=Booksandpublishing.com.au|language=en-AU|access-date=2017-07-29}}</ref> In August 2017, at least 185 German institutions had cancelled their contracts with Elsevier.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.projekt-deal.de/vertragskundigungen-elsevier-2017/|title=Vertragsk\u00fcndigungen Elsevier 2017 \u2013 Projekt DEAL|website=Projekt-deal.de|language=en-US|access-date=2017-09-12}}</ref> In 2018, whilst negotiations were ongoing, around 200 German universities who cancelled their subscriptions to Elsevier journals were granted complimentary open access to them until this ended in July of the year.<ref name=\"matthews-2018\">{{cite news\n | last1 = Matthews | first1 = David\n | title = Elsevier maintains German access despite failure to strike deal\n | date = 4 January 2018\n | work = Times Higher Education (THE)\n | location = London, United Kingdom\n | issn = 0049-3929\n | url = https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/elsevier-maintains-german-access-despite-failure-strike-deal\n | access-date = 2018-01-05\n}}</ref><ref>[https://www.the-scientist.com/news-opinion/universities-in-germany-and-sweden-lose-access-to-elsevier-journals--64522 Universities in Germany and Sweden Lose Access to Elsevier Journals], DIANA KWON, The Scientist, July 19, 2018</ref><ref name=\"schiermeier-2018\">\n{{cite journal\n | last1 = Schiermeier | first1 = Quirin\n | title = Germany vs Elsevier: universities win temporary journal access after refusing to pay fees\n | date = 4 January 2018\n | journal = Nature News\n | volume =553\n | issue =7687\n | page =137\n | issn = 1476-4687\n | doi=10.1038/d41586-018-00093-7\n| pmid = 29323311\n | bibcode =2018Natur.553..137S\n | doi-access = free\n }}</ref>\n\nOn 19 December 2018 the [[Max Planck Society]] (MPS) announced that the existing subscription agreement with Elsevier would not be renewed after the expiration date of 31 December 2018. The Max Planck Society counts 14.000 scientists in 84 research institutes, publishing 12.000 articles each year.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mpdl.mpg.de/en/505|title=Max Planck Society discontinues agreement with Elsevier; stands firm with Projekt DEAL negotiations - MPDL}}</ref><ref name=\"mps20181219\">{{cite news |first1=Gary |last1=Price |url=https://www.infodocket.com/2018/12/19/max-planck-society-discontinues-agreement-with-elsevier-affirms-support-for-projekt-deal/ |title=Max Planck Society Discontinues Agreement with Elsevier. Affirms Support for Projekt Deal | work=infodocket.com Library Journal |date=19 December 2018 |accessdate=19 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Hungary===\nIn March 2018, the Hungarian ''Electronic Information Service National Programme'' entered negotiations on its 2019 Elsevier subscriptions, asking for a read-and-publish deal.<ref name=\"hungary_terminates\">{{cite web |first1= |title=Hungarian Consortium terminates negotiations with Elsevier |url=http://eisz.mtak.hu/index.php/en/283-hungarian-consortium-terminates-negotiations-with-elsevier.html |website=eisz.mtak.hu |accessdate=16 January 2019}}</ref> Negotiations were ended by the Hungarian consortium in December 2018, and the subscription was not renewed.<ref>{{cite news |last1=McKenzie |first1=Lindsay |title=Elsevier journal editors resign, start rival open-access journal |url=http://www.insidehighered.com/news/2019/01/14/elsevier-journal-editors-resign-start-rival-open-access-journal |accessdate=16 January 2019 |work=www.insidehighered.com |date=14 January 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Iran===\n\nIn 2013, Elsevier changed its policies in response to sanctions announced by the US [[Office of Foreign Assets Control]] that year. This included a request that all Elsevier journals avoid publishing papers by Iranian nationals which are employed by the Iranian government.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.issuesinmedicalethics.org/articles/scientific-sanctions-a-catastrophe-for-the-civilised-world/?galley=print|title=Scientific sanctions: A catastrophe for the civilized world|first=Behnam|last=Baghianimoghadam|publisher=Indian Journal of Medical Ethics|date=2014-02-09|accessdate=2018-12-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.farsnews.com/print.aspx?nn=13920814000991|title=Taylor & Francis group bans publication of articles by Iranian authors|publisher=Fars News|date=2013-11-05|accessdate=2018-12-25}}</ref> Elsevier executive Mark Seeley expressed regret on behalf of the company but did not announce an intention to challenge this interpretation of the law.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/trade-sanctions-against-iran-affect-publishers|first=Mark|last=Seeley|title=Trade sanctions against Iran affect publishers|publisher=Elsevier|date=2013-05-09|accessdate=2018-12-25}}</ref>\n\n=== Italy ===\n\nCRUI (association of Italian universities) sealed a 5-year-long deal for 2018\u20132022,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.crui.it/archivio-notizie/i-ricercatori-italiani-potranno-beneficiare-dell%E2%80%99accesso-continuo-al-database-sciencedirect-di-elsevie.html|title=I ricercatori italiani potranno beneficiare dell'accesso continuo al database ScienceDirect di Elsevier - CRUI - Conferenza dei Rettori delle Universit\u00e0 italiane}}</ref> despite protests from the scientific community, protests focused on aspects such as the lack of prevention of cost increases by means of the [[Double dipping (publishing)|double dipping]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.roars.it/online/svezia-italia-1-0-berlino-2018-italia-fanalino-di-coda-nellopen-science/|title=Svezia-Italia 1-0. Berlino 2018: Italia fanalino di coda nell'Open Science|date=2018-12-10|author=Paola Galimberti|newspaper=Roars: Returns on Academic Research}}</ref>\n\n===Netherlands===\nIn 2015 a consortium of all of Netherlands' 14 universities threatened to boycott Elsevier if it could not agree that articles by Dutch authors would be made open access and settled with the compromise of 30% of its Dutch papers becoming open access by 2018. Gerard Meijer, president of [[Radboud University]] in [[Nijmegen]] and lead negotiator on the Dutch side notes that \"it's not the 100% that I hoped for\".<ref name=nature1>{{cite journal|last1=Schiermeier|first1=Quirin|last2=Mega|first2=Emiliano Rodr\u00edguez|title=Scientists in Germany, Peru and Taiwan to lose access to Elsevier journals|journal=Nature|volume=541|issue=7635|pages=13|doi=10.1038/nature.2016.21223|pmid=28054621|bibcode=2017Natur.541...13S|year=2016|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Bohannon|first1=John|title=In unique deal, Elsevier agrees to make some papers by Dutch authors free|url=http://www.sciencemag.org/news/2015/12/unique-deal-elsevier-agrees-make-some-papers-dutch-authors-free|journal=Science|accessdate=27 December 2016|date=11 December 2015|doi=10.1126/science.aad7565|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Dutch Universities and Elsevier reach agreement in principle - Library UvA - University of Amsterdam|url=http://uba.uva.nl/en/news/news/content/2015/12/elsevier-deal.html|publisher=Universiteit van Amsterdam|accessdate=27 December 2016|date=12 October 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161227130822/http://uba.uva.nl/en/news/news/content/2015/12/elsevier-deal.html|archivedate=27 December 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/@SiccodeKnecht/how-elsevier-plans-to-sabotage-open-access-76fbd46593ae|title=How Elsevier plans to sabotage Open Access|date=2017-03-25|website=Medium|access-date=2017-03-26}}</ref>\n\n===Norway===\nIn March 2019, the Norwegian government on behalf of 44 institutions &mdash; universities, university colleges, research institutes and hospitals &mdash; decided to break negotiations on renewal of their subscription deal with Elsevier, because of disagreement regarding open access policy and Elsevier's unwillingness to reduce the cost of reading access.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.mynewsdesk.com/no/unit/pressreleases/norwegian-research-institutions-have-decided-not-to-renew-their-agreement-with-elsevier-2846284|title=Norwegian research institutions have decided not to renew their agreement with Elsevier|date=2019-03-12|website=UNIT|access-date=2019-03-12}}</ref>\n\n=== South Korea ===\nIn 2017, over 70 university libraries confirmed a \"contract boycott\" movement involving three publishers including Elsevier. As of January 2018, whilst negotiations remain underway, a decision will be made as to whether or not continue the participating libraries will continue the boycott.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.unn.net/news/articleView.html?idxno=183521|title=70\uc5ec\uac1c \ub300\ud559 \ub3c4\uc11c\uad00, \uc0c8\ud574 \uccab \ub0a0\ubd80\ud130 \uc77c\ubd80 \ub17c\ubb38 \ubabb \ubd10 - \ud55c\uad6d\ub300\ud559\uc2e0\ubb38|date=2017-12-29|access-date=2018-01-05|language=ko-KR}}</ref> It was subsequently confirmed that an agreement had been reached.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://www.sciencemag.org/news/2018/01/south-korean-universities-reach-agreement-elsevier-after-long-standoff|title=South Korean universities reach agreement with Elsevier after long standoff|date=2018-01-15|journal=Science|access-date=2018-01-16|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Sweden ===\nIn May 2018, the [[Bibsam Consortium]], which negotiates license agreements on behalf of all Swedish universities and research institutes, decided not to renew their contract with Elsevier,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/sweden-cancels-elsevier-contract-open-access-dispute-spreads|title=Sweden cancels Elsevier contract as open-access dispute spreads|date=16 May 2018|website=www.timeshighereducation.com}}</ref><ref name=sparc>{{citation |url=https://sparcopen.org/our-work/big-deal-cancellation-tracking/ |title=Big Deal Cancellation Tracking |work=Sparcopen.org |publisher=[[Scholarly Publishing and Academic Resources Coalition]] |location=US |accessdate= 30 June 2018 }}</ref> alleging that the publisher does not meet the demands of transition towards a more open access model, and referring to the rapidly increasing costs for publishing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kb.se/bibliotek/centrala-avtal/|title=Bibsamkonsortiet - Kungliga biblioteket|last=annwen|website=www.kb.se|language=SV|access-date=2018-05-31}}</ref> Swedish universities will still have access to articles published before 30 June 2018. Astrid S\u00f6derbergh Widding, Chairman of the Bibsam Consortium, said that \"the current system for scholarly communication must change and our only option is to cancel deals when they don't meet our demands for a sustainable transition to open access\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://openaccess.blogg.kb.se/2018/05/16/sweden-stands-up-for-open-access-cancels-agreement-with-elsevier/|title=Sweden stands up for open access \u2013 cancels agreement with Elsevier|date=2018-05-16|work=OpenAccess.se|access-date=2018-05-30|language=sv-SE}}</ref>\n\nSweden has a goal of open access by 2026.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://openaccess.blogg.kb.se/2018/05/16/sweden-stands-up-for-open-access-cancels-agreement-with-elsevier/|title=Sweden stands up for open access \u2013 cancels agreement with Elsevier|last=Wentzel|first=Annica|date=16 May 2018|website=openaccess.blogg.kb.se|access-date=6 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Taiwan===\nIn Taiwan more than 75% of universities, including the region's top 11 institutions, have joined a collective boycott against Elsevier. On 7 December 2016, the Taiwanese consortium, CONCERT, which represents more than 140 institutions, announced it would not renew its contract with Elsevier.<ref name=nature1/><ref>{{cite web|title=\u95dc\u65bcElsevier\u8cc7\u6599\u5eab\u5408\u7d04\u8ac7\u5224 CONCERT\u8072\u660e|url=https://concert.stpi.narl.org.tw/news/249|accessdate=27 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Taiwan Tech to Discontinue Subscription to Elsevier ScienceDirect Starting 2017 - NTUST Library|url=http://library.ntust.edu.tw/files/14-1025-58346,r1-1.php?Lang=en|accessdate=27 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/asia-advances-open-access-research_us_58dd0e6de4b0fa4c09598679|title=Asia Advances Open Access Research|last=Schmitt|first=Jason|date=2017-03-30|website=Huffington Post|language=en-US|access-date=2017-04-29}}</ref>\n\n===United States===\nIn March 2018, [[Florida State University]]'s faculty elected to cancel its $2 million subscription to a bundle of several journals. Starting in 2019 it will instead buy access to titles \u00e0 la carte.<ref name=sparc />\n\nIn February 2019, the [[University of California]] said it would terminate subscriptions \"in push for open access to publicly funded research.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.universityofcalifornia.edu/press-room/uc-terminates-subscriptions-worlds-largest-scientific-publisher-push-open-access-publicly|title=UC terminates subscriptions with world's largest scientific publisher in push for open access to publicly funded research|date=28 February 2019|website=www.universityofcalifornia.edu|access-date=6 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://phys.org/news/2019-03-university-california-terminates-subscriptions-elsevier.html|title=University of California terminates subscriptions to Elsevier|last=Yirka|first=Bob|date=4 March 2019|website=phys.org|access-date=6 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"AT 2019-03\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2019/03/uc-elsevier-publisher/583909/|title=The Real Cost of Knowledge|last=Zhang|first=Sarah|date=4 March 2019|work=[[The Atlantic]]|access-date=6 March 2019|language=en-US}}</ref> After months of negotiations over open access to research by UC researchers and prices for subscriptions to Elsevier journals, a press release by the UC Office of the President issued Thursday, 28 February 2019 stated \"Under Elsevier\u2019s proposed terms, the publisher would have charged UC authors large publishing fees on top of the university\u2019s multi-million dollar subscription, resulting in much greater cost to the university and much higher profits for Elsevier.\"<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.universityofcalifornia.edu/news/why-uc-split-publishing-giant-elsevier|title=Why UC split with publishing giant Elsevier|last=Kell|first=Gretchen|last2=Berkeley|first2=U. C.|date=2019-03-06|website=University of California|language=en|access-date=2019-06-12}}</ref> On July 10, 2019 Elsevier began restricting access to all new paywalled articles and approximately 5% of paywalled articles published before 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statnews.com/2019/07/10/university-of-california-loses-access-to-new-journal-articles-published-by-elsevier-after-research-access-fight|title=University of California loses access to new journal articles published by Elsevier after research access fight|website=statnews.com|language=en|access-date=2019-07-10|date=10 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2020, the [[University of North Carolina]] elected not to renew its bundled Elsevier package citing a failure \"to provide an affordable path\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Upcoming Elsevier Cancellations |url=https://library.unc.edu/2020/04/upcoming-elsevier-cancellations |publisher=University of North Carolina |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>. Rather than extend the license which was stated to cost $2.6 million annually, the university decided to continue subscribing to a smaller set of individual journals. The [[State University of New York]] Libraries Consortium also announced similar outcome,<ref>{{Cite news|publisher=Inside Highered|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/quicktakes/2020/04/13/suny-cancels-big-deal-elsevier|title=SUNY Cancels Big Deal With Elsevier|date=April 13, 2020|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|publisher=SUNY Libraries Consortium (SLC)|title=State University of New York Steps Away From the \u201cBig Deal\u201d with Elsevier|url=http://slcny.libguides.com/slc/elsevier2020update|date=April 7, 2020|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref> with the help of estimates from [[Unpaywall Journals]].<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2020-04-18|title=SUNY Negotiates New, Modified Agreement with Elsevier - Libraries News Center University at Buffalo Libraries|url=https://library.buffalo.edu/news/2020/04/07/suny-negotiates-new-modified-agreement-with-elsevier/|website=library.buffalo.edu}}</ref>\n\n== Dissemination of research ==\n\n=== Lobbying efforts against open access ===\nElsevier have been known to be involved in lobbying against [[open access]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.opensecrets.org/lobby/clientsum.php?id=D000067394&year=2017|title=Lobbying Spending Database - RELX Group, 2017|website=Opensecrets.org|language=en|access-date=2017-08-30}}</ref> These have included the likes of:\n* The [[Federal Research Public Access Act]] (FRPPA)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.taxpayeraccess.org/issues/frpaa/index.shtml|title=Federal Research Public Access Act (Alliance for Taxpayer Access)|website=Taxpayeraccess.org|language=en|access-date=2017-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.chronicle.com/article/Legislation-to-Bar/130949/|title=Legislation to Bar Public-Access Requirement on Federal Research Is Dead|date=2012-02-27|work=The Chronicle of Higher Education|access-date=2017-03-25}}</ref> \n* The [[Research Works Act]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thinkprogress.org/how-corporations-score-big-profits-by-limiting-access-to-publicly-funded-academic-research-fcee09671b22#.joxfvmi94|title=How Corporations Score Big Profits By Limiting Access To Publicly Funded Academic Research|date=2013-03-03|work=ThinkProgress|access-date=2017-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2012/02/15/the-dangerous-research-works-act/|title=The Dangerous \"Research Works Act\"|last=Contributor|website=TechCrunch|access-date=2017-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2016/01/elsevier-academic-publishing-petition/427059/|title=Academics Want You to Read Their Work for Free|last=Hu|first=Jane C.|work=The Atlantic|access-date=2017-03-25|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elsevier.com/about/company-information/policies/message-on-the-research-works-act|title=Message on the Research Works Act|last=Elsevier|website=Elsevier.com|language=en|access-date=2017-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/future_tense/2012/02/28/research_works_act_elsevier_and_politicians_back_down_from_open_access_threat_.html|title=Scientists' Victory Over the Research Works Act Is Like the SOPA Defeat|last=Kakaes|first=Konstantin|date=2012-02-28|work=Slate|access-date=2017-03-25|language=en-US|issn=1091-2339}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://boingboing.net/2012/02/28/elsevier-withdraws-support-fro.html|title=Elsevier withdraws support from Research Works Act, bill collapses|date=2012-02-28|website=Boing Boing|access-date=2017-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2012/jan/16/academic-publishers-enemies-science|title=Academic publishers have become the enemies of science|date=2012-01-16|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-03-26|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> \n* PRISM.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://scienceblogs.com/transcript/2007/01/27/elsevier-wiley-are-getting-pr/|title=Elsevier, Wiley are getting PR advice from Eric Dezenhall|work=Transcription and Translation|access-date=2017-03-25|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dyer|first=Owen|date=2007-02-03|title=Publishers hire PR heavyweight to defend themselves against open access|journal=BMJ: British Medical Journal|volume=334|issue=7587|pages=227|doi=10.1136/bmj.39112.439051.DB|issn=0959-8138|pmc=1790741|pmid=17272546}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://www.sciencemag.org/news/2013/06/scientific-publishers-offer-solution-white-houses-public-access-mandate|title=Scientific Publishers Offer Solution to White House's Public Access Mandate|date=2013-06-04|journal=Science|access-date=2017-03-25|language=en}}</ref> In the case of PRISM, the [[Association of American Publishers]] hired [[Eric Dezenhall]], the so-called \"Pit Bull Of Public Relations\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2006-04-16/the-pit-bull-of-public-relations|title=\"The Pit Bull Of Public Relations\" - Bloomberg|date=2006-04-17|work=Bloomberg.com|access-date=2017-03-25}}</ref>\n* [[Horizon 2020]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/muscle-from-brussels-as-open-access-gets-an-80bn-boost/419949.article|title=Muscle from Brussels as open access gets an \u20ac80bn boost|date=2012-05-17|work=Times Higher Education (THE)|access-date=2017-03-26|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gowers.wordpress.com/2012/05/17/horizon-2020-to-promote-open-access/|title=Horizon 2020 to promote open access|date=2012-05-17|website=Gowers's Weblog|access-date=2017-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://www.sciencemag.org/news/2012/05/horizon-2020-80-billion-battlefield-open-access|title=Horizon 2020: A \u20ac80 Billion Battlefield for Open Access|date=2012-05-24|journal=Science|access-date=2017-03-26|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2012/05/17/european-union-links-research-grants-open-access|title=European Union links research grants to open access|access-date=2017-03-26}}</ref>\n* [[Office of Science and Technology Policy]] (OSTP)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/inside-higher-ed-big-push-for-open-access/2002057.article|title=Inside Higher Ed: Big push for open access|date=2013-02-26|work=Times Higher Education (THE)|access-date=2017-03-26|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/elsevier-distances-itself-from-open-access-article/2004055.article|title=Elsevier distances itself from open-access article|date=2013-05-22|work=Times Higher Education (THE)|access-date=2017-03-26|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thinkprogress.org/how-corporations-score-big-profits-by-limiting-access-to-publicly-funded-academic-research-fcee09671b22#.u06x7x9zu|title=How Corporations Score Big Profits By Limiting Access To Publicly Funded Academic Research|date=2013-03-03|work=ThinkProgress|access-date=2017-03-26}}</ref>\n* The [[European Union]]'s [[Open science|Open Science]] Monitor was criticised after Elsevier were confirmed as a subcontractor.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.techdirt.com/articles/20180402/09131239544/hated-science-publisher-elsevier-to-help-eu-monitor-open-science-including-open-access.shtml|title=Hated Science Publisher Elsevier To Help EU Monitor Open Science - Including Open Access|work=Techdirt.|access-date=2018-04-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Lykkja|first1=P\u00e5l Magnus|last2=Myklebust|first2=Jan Petter|title=Open science in the EU \u2013 Will the astroturfers take over?|url=http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=20180317044918836|website=University World News|accessdate=2018-04-13|date=17 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Selling open access articles ===\nIn 2014, 2015, 2016 and 2017,<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=2018-04-30|title=Hybrid open access is unreliable|url=http://rossmounce.co.uk/2017/02/20/hybrid-open-access-is-unreliable/|author=Ross Mounce|date=2017-02-20}}</ref> Elsevier was found to be selling some articles which should have been open access, but had been put behind a paywall.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/news/elsevier-bumps-on-road-to-open-access/2012238.article |title=Elsevier: bumps on road to open access |work=[[Times Higher Education]] |date=27 March 2014 |accessdate=9 March 2015 |last1=Jump |first1=Paul}}</ref> A related case occurred in 2015, when Elsevier charged for downloading an open access article from a journal published by [[John Wiley & Sons]]. However, it was not clear whether Elsevier was in violation of the license under which the article was made available on their website.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://creativecommons.org/weblog/entry/45175 |title=Are commercial publishers wrongly selling access to openly licensed scholarly articles? |work=Creative Commons News|date=13 March 2015 |accessdate=14 March 2015 |last1=Vollmer |first1=Timothy}}</ref>\n\n===Action against academics posting their own articles online===\n\nIn 2013, [[Digimarc]], a company representing Elsevier, told the [[University of Calgary]] to remove articles published by faculty authors on university web pages; although such [[self-archiving]] of academic articles may be legal under the [[fair dealing]] provisions in Canadian [[copyright law]],<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=2018-05-01|title=Elsevier Ramps Up Its War On Access To Knowledge|url=https://www.techdirt.com/articles/20131218/00393725601/elsevier-ramps-up-its-war-access-to-knowledge.shtml|newspaper=[[Techdirt]]|author= Mike Masnick}}</ref> the university complied. [[Harvard University]] and the [[University of California, Irvine]] also received [[Notice and take down|takedown notices]] for self-archived academic articles, a first for Harvard, according to [[Peter Suber]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Peterson|first1=Andrea|title=How one publisher is stopping academics from sharing their research|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/the-switch/wp/2013/12/19/how-one-publisher-is-stopping-academics-from-sharing-their-research/|accessdate=6 January 2015|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=19 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Masnick|first1=Mike|title=Elsevier Ramps Up Its War On Access To Knowledge|url=https://www.techdirt.com/articles/20131218/00393725601/elsevier-ramps-up-its-war-access-to-knowledge.shtml|accessdate=6 January 2015|work=[[Techdirt]]|date=20 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-switch/wp/2013/12/19/how-one-publisher-is-stopping-academics-from-sharing-their-research/|title=How one publisher is stopping academics from sharing their research|website=Washington Post|access-date=2017-03-26}}</ref>\n\nMonths after its acquisition of [[Academia.edu]] rival [[Mendeley]], Elsevier sent thousands of [[takedown notice]]s to Academia.edu, a practice that has since ceased following widespread complaint by academics, according to Academia.edu founder and chief executive Richard Price.<ref name=\"Parr2014\">{{cite journal|last1=Parr|first1=Chris|title=Sharing is a way of life for millions on Academia.edu|journal=Times Higher Education|date=12 June 2014|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/news/sharing-is-a-way-of-life-for-millions-on-academiaedu/2013839.article?nopaging=1 |accessdate=14 September 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Howard2013\">{{cite journal|last1=Howard|first1=Jennifer|title=Posting Your Latest Article? You Might Have to Take It Down|journal=The Chronicle of Higher Education|date=6 December 2013|url=http://chronicle.com/blogs/wiredcampus/posting-your-latest-article-you-might-have-to-take-it-down/48865|accessdate=14 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter Elsevier acquired the repository [[SSRN]] in May 2016 academics started complaining that some of their work has been removed without notice. The action was explained as a technical error.<ref>Mike Masnick [https://www.techdirt.com/articles/20160718/02211935003/just-as-open-competitor-to-elseviers-ssrn-launches-ssrn-accused-copyright-crackdown.shtml ''SSRN accused of copyright crackdown''], Techdirt.</ref>\n\n===Sci-Hub and LibGen lawsuit===\n\nIn 2015 Elsevier filed a lawsuit against the sites [[Sci-Hub]] and [[Library Genesis|LibGen]], which make copyright protected articles available for free. Elsevier also claimed illegal access to institutional accounts.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.stephenmclaughlin.net/2016/03/18/elsevier-v-sci-hub-on-the-docket/ |title=Elsevier v. Sci-Hub on the docket |first=Stephen Reid |last=McLaughlin |date=18 March 2016 |access-date=2016-06-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/simba-information-five-professional-publishing-news-events-of-2015-signal-times-are-a-changin-300194611.html|title = Simba Information: Five Professional Publishing News Events of 2015 Signal Times Are A-Changin'|date =17 December 2015 |accessdate = 28 June 2016 |website = PR Newswire }}</ref>\n\n===Rejection of the Initiative for Open Citations===\nAmong the major academic publishers, Elsevier alone declined to join the [[Initiative for Open Citations]]. In the context of the resignation of the ''[[Journal of Informetrics]]''' editorial board, Elsevier stated:<ref name=\"Elsevier\">{{cite web|url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/about-the-resignation-of-the-journal-of-informetrics-editorial-board|title=About the resignation of the Journal of Informetrics Editorial Board|date=15 January 2019|last = Reller|first = Tom|work=Elsevier Connect|accessdate=15 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote|Elsevier invests significantly in citation extraction technology. While these are made available to those who wish to license this data, Elsevier cannot make such a large corpus of data, to which it has added significant value, available for free.}}\n\n==Imprints==\n\nElsevier uses its [[Imprint (trade name)|imprint]]s (that is, [[Brand|brand names]] used in publishing) to market to different consumer segments. Many of the imprints have previously been the names of publishing companies that were purchased by Reed Elsevier.\n\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* [[Academic Press]]\n* Bailli\u00e8re Tindall\n* BC Decker\n* [[Butterworth\u2013Heinemann]]\n* CMP\n* [[Cell Press]]\n* [[Churchill Livingstone]]\n* Digital Press\n* Elsevier\n* [[Gulf Professional Publishing]]\n* GW Medical Publishing\n* Hanley & Belfus\n* [[Masson (publisher)|Masson]]\n* [[Medicine Publishing]]\n* [[Morgan Kaufmann Publishers]]\n* [[Mosby (publisher)|Mosby]]\n* Newnes\n* North-Holland Publishing Company\n* [[Pergamon Press]]\n* Pergamon Flexible Learning\n* [[Saunders (publisher)|Saunders]]\n* Syngress\n* Urban & Fischer\n* [[William Andrew (publisher)|William Andrew]]\n* [[Woodhead Publishing]] (including Chandos and Horwood)\n}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Netherlands|Companies|Books}}\n* [[List of Elsevier periodicals]]\n* [[2collab]], a free researcher collaboration tool launched by Elsevier in 2007 and discontinued in 2011\n* [[Sci-Hub]], a website providing free access to otherwise paywalled academic papers on a massive scale that is involved in a legal case with Elsevier\n{{clear}}\n\n== References ==\n=== Citations ===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n=== Sources ===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |ref = harv |last = Groen |first = Frances K. |title = Access to medical knowledge : libraries, digitization, and the public good |year = 2007 |publisher = Scarecrow Press |location = Lanham, Mar. |isbn = 978-0-8108-52723 |page = 217 }}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Elsevier}}\n*{{Official website}}\n*[http://www.caat.org.uk/issues/arms-fairs/reed-elsevier/ Campaign success: Reed Elsevier sells international arms fairs]\n*{{cite web |title=Reed Elsevier Timeline |url=http://www.ulib.niu.edu/publishers/index.htm |work=The Academic Publishing Industry: A Story of Merger and Acquisition |author=Mary H. Munroe |year=2004 |via=Northern Illinois University |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141020153836/http://www.ulib.niu.edu/publishers/Holtzbrinck.htm |archivedate=20 October 2014 |df=dmy-all}}\n\n{{Reed Elsevier|state=collapsed}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Elsevier| ]]\n[[Category:1880 establishments in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Academic publishing companies]]\n[[Category:Bibliographic database providers]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Amsterdam]]\n[[Category:Multinational companies headquartered in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Publishing companies established in 1880]]\n[[Category:Publishing companies of the Netherlands]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Dutch publishing and analytics company}}\n{{other uses}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2016}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Elsevier\n| logo = \n| logo_caption = \n| image = Elsevier logo 2019.svg\n| image_size = 200px\n| image_caption = \n| trading_name = <!-- d/b/a/, doing business as - if different from legal name above -->\n| native_name = <!-- Company's name in home country language -->\n| native_name_lang = <!-- Use ISO 639-1 code, e.g. \"fr\" for French. If there is more than one native name, in different languages, enter those names using {{tl|lang}}, instead. -->\n| romanized_name = \n| former_name = \n| type = \n| traded_as = \n| industry = Publishing\n| genre = <!-- Only used with media and publishing companies -->\n| fate = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| foundation = {{start date and age|df=yes|1880}}\n| founder = \n| defunct = <!-- {{End date|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| location_city = [[Amsterdam]], [[Netherlands]]\n| location_country = \n| locations = <!-- Number of locations, stores, offices, etc. -->\n| area_served = \n| key_people = \n| products = \n| brands = \n| production = \n| services = \n| revenue = \u00a32.54 billion (2018)<ref name=\"RELX 2018 Report\"/>\n| operating_income = \n| net_income = <!-- Removed due to lack of verifiability -->\n| aum = <!-- Only used with financial services companies -->\n| assets = \n| equity = \n| owner = \n| num_employees = \n| parent = [[RELX]]\n| divisions = \n| subsid = \n| website = {{URL|https://www.elsevier.com/}}\n| footnotes = \n| intl = \n}}\n\n'''Elsevier''' ({{IPA-nl|\u02c8\u025blz\u0259vi\u02d0r|lang}}) is a [[Netherlands|Dutch]] [[publishing]] and [[analytics]] company specializing in scientific, technical, and medical content. It is a part of the [[RELX Group]], known until 2015 as Reed Elsevier.  Its products include journals such as ''[[The Lancet]]'' and ''[[Cell (journal)|Cell]]'', the [[ScienceDirect]] collection of electronic journals, the ''[[Trends (journals)|Trends]]'' and ''[[Current Opinion (Elsevier)|Current Opinion]]'' series of journals, the online citation database [[Scopus]], and the [[ClinicalKey]] search engine for clinicians. Elsevier's products also include digital tools for data-management, instruction, and assessment.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://scholarlykitchen.sspnet.org/2017/02/02/plum-goes-orange-elsevier-acquires-plum-analytics/|title = Plum Goes Orange \u2013 Elsevier Acquires Plum Analytics |date = 2017-02-02 }}</ref>\n\nElsevier publishes more than 470,000 articles annually in 2,500 journals.<ref name=\"RELX 2018 Report\">{{Cite web |url = https://www.relx.com/~/media/Files/R/RELX-Group/documents/reports/annual-reports/2018-annual-report.pdf |title = 2018 RELX Group Annual Report |date = March 2019 |accessdate =  |website = RELX Company Reports |publisher = RELX}}</ref> Its archives contain over 16 million documents and 30,000 e-books. Total yearly downloads amount to more than 1 billion.<ref name = \"RELX 2018 Report\" />\n\nElsevier's high operating profit margins (37% in 2018) and 950 million pounds in profits, often on publicly funded research works<ref name=\"RELX 2018 Report\" /><ref name=\"relx-results-press-release-2018\">\n{{cite press release\n | author = RELX\n | title = RELX \u2014 Results for the year to December 2018\n | date = 21 February 2019\n | publisher = RELX Group\n | location = London, United Kingdom and Amsterdam, The Netherlands\n | url = https://www.relx.com/~/media/Files/R/RELX-Group/documents/press-releases/2019/relx-results-2018-pressrelease.pdf\n | access-date = 2019-03-27\n}}  Adjusted operating margin for 2017 for the publishing division is 36.8% (p6).\n</ref> \nand its [[Copyright policies of academic publishers|copyright practices]] have subjected it to criticism by researchers.<ref name=boyc >{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/02/14/science/researchers-boycott-elsevier-journal-publisher.html|title=Mathematicians Organize Boycott of a Publisher | work=The New York Times | first=Thomas|last=Lin|date=13 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n==History==\n\n[[File:Elsevier.svg|200px|right|thumb|The original seal of the Elsevier family, used by Elsevier company as logo until 2019.]]\nElsevier was founded in 1880{{sfn|Groen|2007|p=217}} and adopted the name and logo from the Dutch publishing house [[House of Elzevir|Elzevir]] that was an inspiration and has no connection to the contemporary Elsevier.{{sfn|Groen|2007|p=217}} The Elzevir family operated as booksellers and publishers in the [[Netherlands]]; the founder, [[Lodewijk Elzevir]] (1542\u20131617), lived in [[Leiden]] and established the business in 1580. As company logo, Elsevier used the Elzevir family's printer's mark, a tree entwined with a vine and the words ''Non Solus'', which is Latin for \"not alone.\"<ref name=\"AT 2019-03\" /> Elsevier suggests that this logo represents \"the symbiotic relationship between publisher and scholar\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.facebook.com/notes/elsevier-india/interesting-fact-history-of-the-elsevier-logo/295913917111368/ |title=Interesting Fact - History of the Elsevier Logo |website=[[Facebook]] |access-date=2019-06-12}}</ref>\n\nThe expansion of Elsevier in the scientific field after 1945 was funded with the profits of the newsweekly ''[[Elsevier (magazine)|Elsevier]]'', which published its first issue on 27 October 1945. The weekly was an instant success and earned lots of money.<ref>Gerry van der List, ''Meer dan een weekblad. De geschiedenis van Elsevier''</ref> The weekly was a continuation, as is stated in its first issue, of the monthly Elsevier, which was founded in 1891 to promote the name of the publishing house and had to stop publication in December 1940 because of the [[Netherlands in World War II|Nazi occupation of the Netherlands]].\n\nIn 1947, Elsevier began publishing its first English-language journal, ''[[Biochimica et Biophysica Acta]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Reed Elsevier Timeline |url=http://www.ulib.niu.edu/publishers/ReedElsevier.htm |website=www.ulib.niu.edu |accessdate=13 September 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151030233859/http://www.ulib.niu.edu/publishers/ReedElsevier.htm |archivedate=30 October 2015 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Elsevier acquired [[Mendeley]], a UK company making software for managing and sharing research papers. Mendeley, previously an open platform for sharing of research, was greatly criticized for the acquisition, which users saw as acceding to the \"[[paywall]]\" approach to research literature. Mendeley's previously open sharing system now allows exchange of paywalled resources only within private groups.<ref name=fast>{{cite web |last1=Amirtha |first1=Tina |title=THE OPEN PUBLISHING REVOLUTION, NOW BEHIND A BILLION-DOLLAR PAYWALL |url=http://www.fastcompany.com/3042443/mendeley-elsevier-and-the-future-of-scholarly-publishing |website=Fast Company |accessdate=26 January 2016 |date=2015-04-17}}</ref> ''[[The New Yorker]]'' described Elsevier's reasons for buying Mendeley as two-fold: to acquire its user data, and to \"destroy or co\u00f6pt an [[Open science|open-science]] icon that threatens its [[business model]]\".<ref name=\"NewYorker\">{{cite magazine |url=https://www.newyorker.com/online/blogs/elements/2013/04/elsevier-mendeley-journals-science-software.html |title=When the Rebel Alliance Sells Out |first=David |last=Dobbs |magazine=[[The New Yorker]] |date=12 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn the first half of 2019, RELX reported the first slowdown in revenue growth for Elsevier in several years: 1% vs. an expectation of 2% and a typical growth of at least 4% in the previous 5 years.<ref>{{cite news|title=Relx falls short of growth expectations|newspaper=Financial Times|author=Patricia Nilsson|date=2019-07-25|via=[https://finance.yahoo.com/m/c84c5326-55c5-3f81-b51d-9d1f4b7806e7/relx-falls-short-of-growth.html Yahoo Finance]}}</ref>\n\n== Company statistics ==\n{{as of | 2018 | alt = During 2018}}, researchers submitted over 1.8 million [[research papers]] to Elsevier-based publications. Over 20,000 editors managed the peer review and selection of these papers, resulting in the publication of more than 470,000 articles in over 2,500 journals.<ref name=\"RELX 2018 Report\" /> Editors are generally unpaid volunteers who perform their duties alongside a full-time job in academic institutions,<ref>{{cite journal|first1=James A.|last1=Coleman|title=How to get published in English: Advice from the outgoing Editor-in-Chief |url= |journal=System |date=2014-01-03 |issn=0346-251X |pages=404\u2013411 |volume=42 |doi=10.1016/j.system.2014.01.004|quote=Remember that editors and reviewers are unpaid, and are undertaking their tasks voluntarily, in addition to a full-time job}}</ref> although exceptions have been reported.\n\nIn 2013, the five editorial groups Elsevier, [[Springer Science+Business Media|Springer]], [[Wiley-Blackwell]], [[Taylor & Francis]], and [[SAGE Publications]] published more than half of all academic papers in the peer-reviewed literature.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vocativ.com/culture/science/five-corporations-control-academic-publishing/|title=These Five Corporations Control Academic Publishing|date=10 June 2015|website=Vocativ.com|accessdate=31 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=The Oligopoly of Academic Publishers in the Digital Era|author1=Vincent Larivi\u00e8re |author2=Stefanie Haustein |author3=Philippe Mongeon |journal=PLoS ONE|volume=10|issue=6|year=2015|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0127502 |pmid=26061978 |pmc=4465327 |pages=e0127502|bibcode=2015PLoSO..1027502L}}</ref> At that time, Elsevier accounted for 16% of the world market in science, technology, and medical publishing.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Elsevier leads the business the internet could not kill |url = https://www.ft.com/content/93138f3e-87d6-11e5-90de-f44762bf9896|website = www.ft.com|accessdate = 7 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nElsevier breaks down its revenue sources by format and by geographic region. Approximately 44% of revenue by geography in 2018 derived from North America, 24% from Europe and the remaining 32% from the rest of the world. Approximately 83% of revenue by format came from electronic usage and 17% came from print.<ref name=\"RELX 2018 Report\" />\n\nElsevier employs more than 7,800 people in over 70 offices across 24 countries. Following the integration of its Science & Technology and Health Sciences divisions in 2012, Elsevier has operated under a traditional business structure with a single [[chief executive officer]] (CEO).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.infotoday.com/it/mar13/Brynko--Mobed--Elseviers-Next-Steps.shtml|title=Elsevier Next Steps|publisher=Information Today|accessdate=7 November 2016}}</ref> The CEO is Kumsal Bayazit,<ref name=\"ataglance\">{{cite web |url= https://www.elsevier.com/about/management/kumsal-bayazit |title=Kumsal Bayazit |website=Elsevier.com |accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref> who was appointed on 15 February 2019.\n\nIn 2018, Elsevier accounted for 34% of the revenues of RELX group (\u20a42.538 billion of \u20a47.492 billion). In [[Earnings before interest and taxes|operating profits]], it represented 40% (\u20a4942 million of \u20a42,346 million). Adjusted operating profits (with constant currency) rose by 2% from 2017 to 2018.<ref name=\"RELX 2018 Report\" />\n\nIn 2018, Elsevier reported a mean 2017 [[gender pay gap]] of 29.1% for its UK workforce, while the median was 40.4%, more than twice the UK average and by far the worst figure recorded by any academic publisher in UK. Elsevier attributed the result to the under-representation of women in its senior ranks and the prevalence of men in its technical workforce.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2019-08-11|title=Elsevier reports 40% gender pay gap|url=https://www.thebookseller.com/news/elsevier-reports-40-gender-pay-gap-759606|website=www.thebookseller.com}}</ref>\n\n==Market model==\n\n===Products and services===\n\nProducts and services include electronic and print versions of journals, textbooks and [[reference work]]s, and cover the [[healthcare science|health]], life, physical and [[social science]]s.\n\nThe target markets are academic and government research institutions, corporate research labs, booksellers, librarians, scientific researchers, authors, editors, physicians, nurses, allied health professionals, medical and nursing students and schools, medical researchers, [[Pharmaceutical company|pharmaceutical companies]], hospitals, and research establishments. It publishes in 13 languages including English, German, French, Spanish, Italian, Portuguese, Polish, Japanese, Hindi, and Chinese.\n\nFlagship products and services include VirtualE, [[ScienceDirect]], [[Scopus]], [[Scirus]], [[EMBASE]], Engineering Village, [[Compendex]], [[Cell (journal)|Cell]], SciVal, Pure, and Analytical Services, The Consult series (FirstCONSULT, PathCONSULT, NursingCONSULT, MDConsult, StudentCONSULT), Virtual Clinical Excursions, and major reference works such as ''[[Gray's Anatomy]]'', ''Nelson Pediatrics'', ''[[Dorland's Illustrated Medical Dictionary]]'', ''[[Frank H. Netter|Netter]]'s Atlas of Human Anatomy'', and online versions of many journals<ref>[http://www.journals.elsevierhealth.com/ Health Advance]. Elsevier.</ref> including ''[[The Lancet]]''.\n\nScienceDirect is Elsevier's platform for online electronic access to its journals and over 6,000 e-books, reference works, book series, and handbooks. The articles are grouped in four main sections: ''Physical Sciences and Engineering'', ''Life Sciences'', ''Health Sciences'', and ''Social Sciences and Humanities''. For most articles on the website, abstracts are freely available; access to the full text of the article (in PDF, and also HTML for newer publications) often requires a subscription or pay-per-view purchase.\n\n===Research and information ecosystem===\n\n[[RELX Group]] has been [[RELX Group#Significant acquisitions|active]] in [[mergers and acquisitions]]. Elsevier has been joined by businesses which were either complementing or competing in the field of research and publishing and which reinforce its [[market power]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.techdirt.com/articles/20170804/05454537924/elsevier-continues-to-build-monopoly-solution-all-aspects-scholarly-communication.shtml|title=Elsevier Continues To Build Its Monopoly Solution For All Aspects Of Scholarly Communication|last=|first=|date=2017-08-04|work=Techdirt|access-date=2018-10-17|author=Glyn Moody|author-link=Glyn Moody}}</ref> such as [[Mendeley]] (after the closure of [[2collab]]), [[SSRN]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.techdirt.com/articles/20160517/13513134465/disappointing-elsevier-buys-open-access-academic-pre-publisher-ssrn.shtml|title=Disappointing: Elsevier Buys Open Access Academic Pre-Publisher SSRN|last=|first=|date=2016-05-17|work=Techdirt|access-date=2018-10-17|author=Mike Masnick|author-link=Mike Masnick}}</ref> [[bepress]]/[[Digital Commons (Elsevier)|Digital Commons]], [[PlumX]], Hivebench, Newsflo.<ref name=Herb2019/> These integrations are seen as a way to exert additional power on the research process.<ref name=Herb2019>{{cite journal |last1=Herb |first1=Ulrich|date=2019|title=Steering science through Output Indicators & Data Capitalism|doi=10.5281/zenodo.3333395|doi-access=free}}</ref> The group contains additional information and analytics companies, particularly [[LexisNexis]] and [[ThreatMetrix]].\n\n=== Conferences ===\nElsevier conducts conferences, exhibitions and workshops around the world, with over 50 conferences a year covering life sciences, physical sciences and engineering, social sciences, and health sciences.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.elsevier.com/events/conferences |title=Conferences |work=elsevier.com}}</ref>\n\n===Pricing===\n\nIn the 21st century, the subscription rates charged by the company for its journals have been criticized; some very large journals (with more than 5,000 articles) charge subscription prices as high as \u00a39,634, far above average,<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2011/aug/29/academic-publishers-murdoch-socialist|journal=Guardian|last=Monbiot|first=George|date=29 August 2011|title=Academic publishers make Murdoch look like a socialist}}</ref> and many British universities pay more than a million pounds to Elsevier annually.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://gowers.wordpress.com/2014/04/24/elsevier-journals-some-facts/ |title=Elsevier journals \u2014 some facts |work=Gowers's Weblog |date=24 April 2014 |accessdate=27 July 2014}}</ref> The company has been criticized not only by advocates of a switch to the [[Open access (publishing)|open-access]] publication model, but also by universities whose library budgets make it difficult for them to afford current journal prices.\n\nFor example, a resolution by [[Stanford University]]'s senate singled out Elsevier's journals as being \"disproportionately expensive compared to their educational and research value\", which librarians should consider dropping, and encouraged its faculty \"not to contribute articles or editorial or review efforts to publishers and journals that engage in exploitive or exorbitant pricing\".<ref>''[http://news-service.stanford.edu/news/2004/february25/minutes-225.html Faculty Senate minutes February 19 meeting]'' Stanford Report, 25 February 2004</ref> Similar guidelines and criticism of Elsevier's pricing policies have been passed by the [[University of California]], [[Harvard University]], and [[Duke University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.stanforddaily.com/?p=1013953 |title=Fac Sen addresses costly journals |work=The Stanford Daily |date=20 February 2004 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105040316/http://archive.stanforddaily.com/?p=1013953 |archivedate=5 November 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nIn July 2015, the [[Association of Universities in the Netherlands]] (VSNU) announced a plan to start boycotting Elsevier, which refused to negotiate on any [[Open Access]] policy for Dutch universities.<ref>Danny Kingsley [https://unlockingresearch.blog.lib.cam.ac.uk/?p=192 ''Dutch boycott of Elsevier \u2013 a game changer?''], University of Cambridge Office of Scholarly Communication</ref> In December 2016, [[Nature Publishing Group]] reported that academics in Germany, Peru and Taiwan are to lose access to Elsevier journals as negotiations had broken down with the publisher.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Schiermeier|first=Quirin|last2=Mega|first2=Emiliano Rodr\u00edguez|title=Scientists in Germany, Peru and Taiwan to lose access to Elsevier journals|journal=Nature|doi=10.1038/nature.2016.21223|pmid=28054621|volume=541|issue=7635|page=13|year=2016|bibcode=2017Natur.541...13S|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\nA complaint about Elsevier/RELX was made to the UK [[Competition and Markets Authority]] in December 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.martineve.com/2016/12/03/referring-elsevierrelx-to-the-competition-and-markets-authority/|title=Referring Elsevier/RELX to the Competition and Markets Authority|author=Martin Paul Eve|language=en-US|date=2016-12-14|author-link=Martin Paul Eve}}</ref> In October 2018, a competition complaint against Elsevier was filed with the European Commission, alleging anti-competitive practices stemming from Elsevier's confidential subscription agreements and market dominance.<ref name=\"competition_plaint\">{{cite news |last1=Kelly |first1=\u00c9anna |title=Researchers complain to Brussels over 'dominant position' of RELX Group in scientific publishing |url=https://sciencebusiness.net/framework-programmes/news/researchers-complain-brussels-over-dominant-position-relx-group |accessdate=16 January 2019 |work=sciencebusiness.net |date=2 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Shill review offer ===\n\nAccording to the [[BBC]], \"the firm [Elsevier] offered a \u00a317.25 Amazon voucher to academics who contributed to the textbook ''Clinical Psychology'' if they would go on [[Amazon.com]] and [[Barnes & Noble]] (a large US books retailer) and give it five stars.\" Elsevier said that \"encouraging interested parties to post book reviews isn't outside the norm in scholarly publishing, nor is it wrong to offer to nominally compensate people for their time. But in all instances the request should be unbiased, with no incentives for a positive review, and that's where this particular e-mail went too far\", and that it was a mistake by a marketing employee.<ref>Finlo Rohrer, \"[http://news.bbc.co.uk/go/pr/fr/-/2/hi/uk_news/magazine/8118577.stm The perils of five-star reviews]\", ''BBC News Magazine'', 25 June 2009.</ref>\n\n=== Blocking text mining research ===\nElsevier seeks to regulate [[text and data mining]] with private licenses,<ref name=nature527413f/> claiming that reading requires extra permission if automated and that the publisher holds copyright on [[threshold of originality|output of automated processes]]. The conflict on research and copyright policy has often resulted in researchers being blocked from their work.<ref>{{cite journal|first1=Richard|last1=Van Noorden|title=Elsevier opens its papers to text-mining|journal=Nature|date=2014-02-03|issn=0028-0836|pages=17|volume=506|issue=7486|doi=10.1038/506017a|pmid=24499898|doi-access=free|quote=\u201cIt was a legitimate criticism, that people sent text-mining requests in to publishers and they bounced around for a time without any response,\u201d admits Chris Shillum, vice-president of product management for platform and content at Elsevier.|bibcode=2014Natur.506...17V}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2015, Elsevier blocked a scientist from performing [[text mining]] research at scale on Elsevier papers, even though his institution already pays for access to Elsevier journal content.<ref name=nature527413f>{{cite journal|last1=Bloudoff-Indelicato|first1=Mollie|title=Text-mining block prompts online response|journal=Nature|date=20 November 2015|volume=527|issue=7579|pages=413|doi=10.1038/527413f|bibcode=2015Natur.527..413B}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Moody|first1=Glyn|title=Elsevier Says Downloading And Content-Mining Licensed Copies Of Research Papers 'Could Be Considered' Stealing|url=https://www.techdirt.com/articles/20151117/09383132839/elsevier-says-downloading-content-mining-licensed-copies-research-papers-could-be-considered-stealing.shtml|website=TechDirt|accessdate=21 November 2015}}</ref> The data were collected via parsing of downloaded PDF and HTML files,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Nuijten|first1=Mich\u00e8le B.|last2=Hartgerink|first2=Chris H. J.|last3=van Assen|first3=Marcel A. L. M.|last4=Epskamp|first4=Sacha|last5=Wicherts|first5=Jelte M.|title=The prevalence of statistical reporting errors in psychology (1985\u20132013)|journal=Behavior Research Methods|date=23 October 2015|volume=48|issue=4|pages=1205\u20131226|doi=10.3758/s13428-015-0664-2|pmid=26497820|pmc=5101263}}</ref> although Elsevier claimed that the method used was [[screenscraping]].<ref>A. Wise, 2015-11-17, [http://onsnetwork.org/chartgerink/2015/11/16/elsevier-stopped-me-doing-my-research/#comment-11 Elsevier stopped me doing my research - Comment by Dr Alicia Wise]</ref>\n\n== Academic practices ==\n\n=== \"Who's Afraid of Peer Review\" ===\n{{main|Who's Afraid of Peer Review?}}\n\nOne of Elsevier's journals was caught in the sting set up by [[John Bohannon]], published in [[Science (journal)|''Science'']], called \"Who's Afraid of Peer Review?\"<ref name=\"Bohannon2013\">{{Cite journal | last1 = Bohannon | first1 = John| authorlink1 = John Bohannon| title = Who's Afraid of Peer Review? | doi = 10.1126/science.342.6154.60 | journal = Science | volume = 342 | issue = 6154 | pages = 60\u201365 | year = 2013 | pmid =  24092725| pmc = |bibcode = 2013Sci...342...60B | doi-access = free }}</ref> The journal ''Drug Invention Today'' accepted an obviously bogus paper made up by Bohannon that should have been rejected by any good [[peer review]] system.<ref>{{cite news|author=Claire Shaw |url=https://www.theguardian.com/higher-education-network/2013/oct/04/open-access-journals-fake-paper |title=Hundreds of open access journals accept fake science paper |publisher=Theguardian.com |accessdate=26 December 2013|newspaper=The Guardian |date=2013-10-04 }}</ref> Instead, ''Drug Invention Today'' was among many [[open access]] journals that accepted the fake paper for publication. As of 2014, this journal had been transferred to a different publisher.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/journal/09757619|title=Drug Invention Today|work=sciencedirect.com}}</ref>\n\n=== Fake journals ===<!-- See talk section \"Elsevier published 6 fake journals\" for discussion of this heading\" -->\n{{further|Australasian Journal of Bone & Joint Medicine}}\n\nAt a 2009 court case in Australia where [[Merck & Co.]] was being sued by a user of [[Vioxx]], the plaintiff alleged that Merck had paid Elsevier to publish the ''[[Australasian Journal of Bone and Joint Medicine]]'', which had the appearance of being a [[peer-review]]ed [[academic journal]] but in fact contained only articles favourable to Merck drugs.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/story/0,25197,25311725-5013871,00.html |title=Doctors signed Merck's Vioxx studies |last=Rout |first=Milanda |date=9 April 2009 |work=[[The Australian]] |accessdate=4 May 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090506064629/http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/story/0,25197,25311725-5013871,00.html |archive-date=6 May 2009 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://classic.the-scientist.com/blog/display/55671/ |title=Merck published fake journal |last=Grant |first=Bob |date=30 April 2009 |work=[[The Scientist (magazine)|The Scientist]] |accessdate=4 May 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.theage.com.au/national/merck-accused-of-ghost-writing-medical-article-20090422-afdk.html?page=-1 |title=Merck accused of 'ghost writing' medical article |last=Hagan |first=Kate |date=23 April 2009 |work=[[The Age]] |accessdate=4 May 2009}}</ref><ref>Ben Goldacre, [https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2009/may/09/bad-science-medical-journals-companies \"The danger of drugs \u2026 and data\"], ''The Guardian'', 9 May 2009</ref> Merck described the journal as a \"complimentary publication,\" denied claims that articles within it were [[ghost writer|ghost written]] by Merck, and stated that the articles were all reprinted from peer-reviewed medical journals.<ref>{{cite press release|title=Merck Responds to Questions about the Australasian Journal of Bone and Joint Medicine Journal |date=30 April 2009 |url=http://www.merck.com/newsroom/vioxx/pdf/statement_20090430.pdf |publisher=[[Merck & Co.]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091231104929/http://merck.com/newsroom/vioxx/pdf/statement_20090430.pdf |archivedate=31 December 2009 |df=dmy }}</ref> In May 2009, Elsevier Health Sciences CEO Hansen released a statement regarding Australia-based sponsored journals, conceding that they were \"sponsored article compilation publications, on behalf of pharmaceutical clients, that were made to look like journals and lacked the proper disclosures.\" The statement acknowledged that it \"was an unacceptable practice.\"<ref>{{cite press release |title=Statement from Michael Hansen, CEO Of Elsevier's Health Sciences Division, regarding Australia based sponsored journal practices between 2000 and 2005 |url= http://www.elsevier.com/wps/find/authored_newsitem.cws_home/companynews05_01203 |publisher=Elsevier}}</ref> ''[[The Scientist (magazine)|The Scientist]]'' reported that, according to an Elsevier spokesperson, six sponsored publications \"were put out by their Australia office and bore the [[Excerpta Medica]] imprint from 2000 to 2005,\" namely the ''Australasian Journal of Bone and Joint Medicine'' (''Australas. J. Bone Joint Med.''), the ''Australasian Journal of General Practice'' (''Australas. J. Gen. Pract.''), the ''Australasian Journal of Neurology'' (''Australas. J. Neurol.''), the ''Australasian Journal of Cardiology'' (''Australas. J. Cardiol.''), the ''Australasian Journal of Clinical Pharmacy'' (''Australas. J. Clin. Pharm.''), and the ''Australasian Journal of Cardiovascular Medicine'' (''Australas. J. Cardiovasc. Med.'').<ref>{{cite news|first=Bob|last=Grant|title=Elsevier published 6 fake journals |url=http://www.the-scientist.com/blog/display/55679/ |date=7 May 2009 |work=[[The Scientist (magazine)|The Scientist]]}}</ref> Excerpta Medica was a \"strategic medical communications agency\" run by Elsevier, according to the imprint's web page.<ref>{{cite web|title=\"Excerpta Medica\", official webpage |url=http://www.excerptamedica.com/ |publisher=Elsevier}}</ref> In October 2010, Excerpta Medica was acquired by Adelphi Worldwide.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Excerpta Medica Joins Adelphi Worldwide\", press release |url= http://www.excerptamedica.com/?page=newsroom&item=301 |publisher=Elsevier}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Chaos, Solitons & Fractals'' ===\n\nThere was speculation<ref>{{cite journal |title=Self-publishing editor set to retire |doi=10.1038/456432a | volume=456 |issue=7221 | journal=Nature |pages=432 |pmid=19037282 | last1 = Schiermeier | first1 = Q|year=2008 |doi-access=free }}</ref> that the editor-in-chief of Elsevier journal ''Chaos, Solitons & Fractals'', [[Mohamed El Naschie]], misused his power to publish his own work without appropriate peer review. The journal had published 322 papers with El Naschie as author since 1993. The last issue of December 2008 featured five of his papers.<ref>''Chaos, Solitons & Fractals'' '''38'''(5), pp. 1229\u20131534 (December 2008)</ref> The controversy was covered extensively in blogs.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://scholarlykitchen.sspnet.org/?s=el+naschie| title= The Scholarly Kitchen}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://elnaschiewatch.blogspot.com/ |title= El Naschie Watch Blog |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101015195449/http://elnaschiewatch.blogspot.com/ |archivedate= 15 October 2010 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> The publisher announced in January 2009 that El Naschie had retired as editor-in-chief.<ref>{{Cite journal| doi = 10.1016/S0960-0779(09)00060-5| title = Publisher's note| year = 2009| journal = Chaos, Solitons & Fractals| volume = 39| pages = v\u2013|bibcode = 2009CSF....39D...5. }}</ref> {{As of|2011|11}} the co-Editors-in-Chief of the journal were Maurice Courbage and Paolo Grigolini.<ref>{{cite book |url= http://www.journals.elsevier.com/chaos-solitons-and-fractals/ |title= Chaos, Solitons and Fractals |date=November 2011}}</ref> In June 2011, El Naschie sued the journal ''[[Nature (journal)|Nature]]'' for libel, claiming that his reputation had been damaged by their November 2008 article about his retirement, which included statements that ''Nature'' had been unable to verify his claimed affiliations with certain international institutions.<ref name=\"BBC-CSF-libel\">{{cite news | title = Nature journal libel case begins | work = BBC News | last1 = Ghosh | first1 = Pallab | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-15697636 | accessdate = 11 November 2011 | date=11 November 2011}}</ref> The suit came to trial in November 2011 and was dismissed in July 2012, with the judge ruling that the article was \"substantially true\", contained \"honest comment\" and was \"the product of responsible journalism\". The judgement noted that El Naschie, who represented himself in court, had failed to provide any documentary evidence that his papers had been peer-reviewed.<ref name=\"Guardian2\">[https://www.theguardian.com/science/2012/jul/06/nature-libel-peer-review?newsfeed=true \"Nature libel verdict 'a victory for free speech'\"],''The Guardian'' 6 July 2012</ref> Judge [[Victoria Sharp]] also found \"reasonable and serious grounds\" for suspecting that El Naschie used a range of false names to defend his editorial practice in communications with ''Nature'', and described this behavior as \"curious\" and \"bizarre.\" <ref>{{cite journal\n| last       = Aron\n| first       = Jacob\n| date        = 6 July 2012\n| title       = Nature Publishing Group wins libel trial\n| journal     = New Scientist\n| issue       = 2873\n| url         = https://www.newscientist.com/article/dn22026-nature-publishing-group-wins-libel-trial.html\n| accessdate  = 14 July 2012\n}}</ref>\n\n===Plagiarism===\nSome Elsevier journals automatically screen submissions for plagiarism,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.elsevier.com/editors/perk/plagiarism-complaints/plagiarism-detection |title=Plagiarism detection |publisher=Elsevier}}</ref> but not all.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://retractionwatch.com/2018/08/23/elsevier-investigating-paper-on-solar-cells-that-appears-to-plagiarize-a-nature-journal/ |title=UPDATED: Elsevier retracts a paper on solar cells that appears to plagiarize a Nature journal. But the reason is\u2026odd |author=Ivan Oransky|date=2018-08-23}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Elsevier journal ''[[Procedia]]'' was reported to have published plagiarism by an Albanian politician in 2012.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://exit.al/en/2018/12/25/massive-plagiarism-scandal-hits-albanian-officials/ |title= Massive Plagiarism Scandal Hits Albanian Officials without Consequences |date=2018-12-25}}</ref>\n\n== Control of journals ==\n\n=== Resignation of editorial boards ===\nIn November 1999 the entire editorial board (50 persons) of the ''[[Journal of Logic Programming]]'' (founded in 1984 by [[John Alan Robinson|Alan Robinson]]) collectively resigned after 16 months of unsuccessful negotiations with Elsevier Press about the price of library subscriptions.<ref name=birman>[[Joan Birman]]. \"[http://www.ams.org/notices/200007/forum-birman.pdf Scientific publishing: a mathematician\u2019s viewpoint]\". ''[[Notices of the AMS]]''. Vol. 47, No. 7, August 2000</ref> The personnel created a new journal, ''Theory and Practice of Logic Programming'', with [[Cambridge University Press]] at a much lower price,<ref name=birman/> while Elsevier continued publication with a new editorial board and a slightly different name (the ''[[Journal of Logic and Algebraic Programming]]'').\n\nIn 2002, dissatisfaction at Elsevier's pricing policies caused the [[European Economic Association]] to terminate an agreement with Elsevier designating Elsevier's ''[[European Economic Review]]'' as the official journal of the association. The EEA launched a new journal, the ''[[Journal of the European Economic Association]]''.<ref>{{cite web|author=EffeDesign |url=http://www.eeassoc.org/index.php?page=14 |title=The EEA's journal: a brief history |publisher=Eeassoc.org |accessdate=26 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, the entire editorial board of the ''Journal of Algorithms'' resigned to start ''[[ACM Transactions on Algorithms]]'' with a different, lower-priced, not-for-profit publisher,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cs.colorado.edu/~hal/s.pdf |title=Changes at the Journal of Algorithms |accessdate=26 December 2013}}</ref> at the suggestion of ''Journal of Algorithms'' founder [[Donald Knuth]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www-cs-faculty.stanford.edu/~knuth/joalet.pdf | author=Donald Knuth| date=25 October 2003 | title=Letter to the editorial board of the Journal of Algorithms| accessdate=18 February 2008}}</ref> The ''Journal of Algorithms'' continued under Elsevier with a new editorial board until October 2009, when it was discontinued.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/journal/01966774 |title=Journal of Algorithms page at ScienceDirect |publisher=Sciencedirect.com |accessdate=26 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe same happened in 2005 to the ''International Journal of Solids and Structures'', whose editors resigned to start the ''[[Journal of Mechanics of Materials and Structures]]''. However, a new editorial board was quickly established and the journal continues in apparently unaltered form with editors D.A. Hills ([[Oxford University]]) and Stelios Kyriakides ([[University of Texas at Austin]]).<ref>{{cite web |title=Journal declarations of independence |url=http://oad.simmons.edu/oadwiki/Journal_declarations_of_independence#2005 |work=Open Access Directory |publisher=Simmons College |accessdate=23 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Kyriakides|first=Stelios|author2=Hills, David A.|title=Editorial|journal=International Journal of Solids and Structures|date=1 January 2006|volume=43|issue=1|page=1|doi=10.1016/j.ijsolstr.2005.11.001|accessdate=|quote=Charles R. Steele succeeded Herrmann as editor in chief in 1985 and served in that capacity until June 2005. During his 20-year tenure the journal grew both in size and in reputation, becoming one of the premier journals in the field. We have accepted an invitation to serve as editors of the journal as of October 1, 2005, being cognizant of the immense contributions, leadership, and high standards exercised by our two predecessors on the way to making IJSS the forum it is today.}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2006, the entire editorial board of the distinguished [[mathematical journal]] ''[[Topology (journal)|Topology]]'' handed in their resignation, again because of stalled negotiations with Elsevier to lower the subscription price.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://math.ucr.edu/home/baez/topology-letter.pdf | date=10 August 2006 | title=Resignation letter from the editors of Topology | accessdate=18 February 2008}}</ref> This board then launched the new ''[[Journal of Topology]]'' at a far lower price, under the auspices of the [[London Mathematical Society]].<ref>[http://www.lms.ac.uk/publications/jtop.html Journal of Topology] (pub. London Mathematical Society) {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070207123258/http://www.lms.ac.uk/publications/jtop.html |date=7 February 2007 }}</ref> After this mass resignation, ''[[Topology (journal)|Topology]]'' remained in circulation under a new editorial board until 2009, when the last issue was published.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://www.journals.elsevier.com/topology/|title=Topology|publisher=elsevier.com|accessdate=13 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/journal/00409383/48/2-4 |title=Topology page at ScienceDirect |publisher=Sciencedirect.com |accessdate=26 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe French [[\u00c9cole Normale Sup\u00e9rieure]] has stopped having Elsevier publish the journal ''[[Annales Scientifiques de l'\u00c9cole Normale Sup\u00e9rieure]]''<ref>[[John Baez]]: ''[http://math.ucr.edu/home/baez/journals.html What We Can Do About Science Journals]'' 13 August 2007</ref> (as of 2008).<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.elsevier.com/wps/find/journaldescription.cws_home/600714/description | title=Publisher's description of Annales Scientifiques de l'\u00c9cole Normale Sup\u00e9rieure | publisher=Elsevier | accessdate=18 February 2008 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080412014908/http://www.elsevier.com/wps/find/journaldescription.cws_home/600714/description | archivedate=12 April 2008 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe elevated pricing of field journals in economics, most of which are published by Elsevier, was one of the motivations that moved the [[American Economic Association]] to launch the ''[[American Economic Journal]]'' in 2009.<ref>David Glenn. \"American Economic Association Plans 4 New Journals\". '' The Chronicle of Higher Education''. 25 January 2008. Available online at [http://chronicle.com/article/American-Economic-Association/440 Chronicle.com]</ref>\n\nIn May 2015, [[Stephen Leeder]] was removed from his role as editor of the ''[[Medical Journal of Australia]]'' after its publisher decided to outsource the journal's production to Elsevier. As a consequence, all but one of the journal's editorial advisory committee members co-signed a letter of resignation.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/medical-journal-editor-sacked-and-editorial-committee-resigns-20150503-1myr8q.html | title=Medical journal editor sacked and editorial committee resigns | accessdate=18 May 2015| date=2015-05-03 }}</ref>\n\nIn October 2015, the entire editorial staff of the [[general linguistics]] journal ''[[Lingua (journal)|Lingua]]'' resigned in protest of Elsevier's unwillingness to agree to their terms of [[Fair Access to Science and Technology Research Act|Fair Open Access]]. Editor in Chief Johan Rooryck also announced that the Lingua staff would establish a new journal, ''[[Glossa (journal)|Glossa]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2015/11/02/editors-and-editorial-board-quit-top-linguistics-journal-protest-subscription-fees|title=Language of Protest|last=Jaschik|first=Scott|date=2 November 2015|work=Inside Higher Ed|access-date=18 January 2017|via=}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2019, the entire editorial board of Elsevier's ''[[Journal of Informetrics]]'' resigned over the open-access policies of its publisher and founded open-access journal called Quantitative Science Studies.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2019/01/14/elsevier-journal-editors-resign-start-rival-open-access-journal|title=Elsevier journal editors resign, start rival open-access journal}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2019/01/14/elsevier-journal-editors-resign-start-rival-open-access-journal|title=Elsevier journal editors resign, start rival open-access journal|website=www.insidehighered.com|language=en|access-date=2019-01-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Chawla|first=Dalmeet Singh|date=2019-01-14|title=Open-access row prompts editorial board of Elsevier journal to resign|url=http://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-019-00135-8|journal=Nature|language=EN|doi=10.1038/d41586-019-00135-8}}</ref>\n\n===\"The Cost of Knowledge\" boycott===\n{{Main|The Cost of Knowledge}}\n\nIn 2003 various university librarians began coordinating with each other to complain about Elsevier's \"[[Subscription business model|big deal]]\" journal bundling packages, in which the company offered a group of journal subscriptions to libraries at a certain rate, but in which librarians claimed there was no economical option to subscribe to only the popular journals at a rate comparable to the bundled rate.{{sfn|Groen|2007|p=177}} Librarians continued to discuss the implications of the pricing schemes, many feeling pressured into buying the Elsevier packages without other options.{{sfn|Groen|2007|p=180}}\n\nOn 21 January 2012, mathematician [[Timothy Gowers]] publicly announced he would boycott Elsevier, noting that others in the field have been doing so privately. The three reasons for the [[boycott]] are high subscription prices for individual journals, bundling subscriptions to journals of different value and importance, and Elsevier's support for [[Stop Online Piracy Act|SOPA]], [[PROTECT IP Act|PIPA]], and the [[Research Works Act]].<ref name=Guardian>{{cite news|last=Flood |first=Alison |url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2012/feb/02/academics-boycott-publisher-elsevier |title=Scientists sign petition to boycott academic publisher Elsevier |newspaper=The Guardian |date=2 February 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/65VHiGo2Z?url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/science/2012/feb/02/academics-boycott-publisher-elsevier |archivedate=16 February 2012 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref><ref name=Chronicle>{{cite news|last=Fischman |first=Josh |url=http://chronicle.com/blogs/wiredcampus/elsevier-publishing-boycott-gathers-steam-among-academics/35216 |title=Elsevier Publishing Boycott Gathers Steam Among Academics |newspaper=The Chronicle of Higher Education |date=30 January 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/65VIHYC2S?url=http://chronicle.com/blogs/wiredcampus/elsevier-publishing-boycott-gathers-steam-among-academics/35216 |archivedate=16 February 2012 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref><ref name=Economist>{{cite news|url=http://www.economist.com/node/21545974 |title=Scientific publishing: The price of information |work=The Economist |date=4 February 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/65VHxfKJ9?url=http://www.economist.com/node/21545974 |archivedate=16 February 2012 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nFollowing this, a petition advocating non-cooperation with Elsevier (that is, not submitting papers to Elsevier journals, not [[peer review|refereeing]] articles in Elsevier journals, and not participating in journal editorial boards), appeared on the site \"The Cost of Knowledge\". By February 2012 this petition had been signed by over 5,000 academics,<ref name=Guardian/><ref name=Chronicle/> growing to over 17,000 by November 2018.<ref>{{cite web|title=thecostofknowledge.com|url=http://thecostofknowledge.com/|accessdate=12 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nElsevier disputed the claims, claiming that their prices are below the industry average, and stating that bundling is only one of several different options available to buy access to Elsevier journals.<ref name=Guardian/> The company also claimed that its profit margins are \"simply a consequence of the firm's efficient operation\".<ref name=Economist/> The academics replied that their work was funded by public money and thus should be freely available.\n\nOn 27 February 2012, Elsevier issued a statement on its website that declared that it has withdrawn support from the Research Works Act.<ref>{{cite web|title=Elsevier Backs Down as Boycott Grows|url=http://www.elsevier.com/about/issues-and-information/newmessagerwa|accessdate=25 August 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140911222130/http://www.elsevier.com/about/issues-and-information/newmessagerwa|archivedate=11 September 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Although the Cost of Knowledge movement was not mentioned, the statement indicated the hope that the move would \"help create a less heated and more productive climate\" for ongoing discussions with research funders. Hours after Elsevier's statement, the sponsors of the bill, [[United States House of Representatives|US House Representatives]] [[Darrell Issa]] and [[Carolyn Maloney]], issued a joint statement saying that they would not push the bill in Congress.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sponsors and Supporters Back Away from Research Works Act|url=http://www.sparc.arl.org/news/sponsors-and-supporters-back-away-research-works-act|accessdate=25 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Plan S===\nThe [[Plan S]] open-access initiative, which began in Europe and has since spread to some US research funding agencies would force researchers receiving some grants to publish in open access journals by 2020.<ref name=\"US_funders\">{{cite journal |last1=Noorden |first1=Richard Van |title=Wellcome and Gates join bold European open-access plan |journal=Nature |date=5 November 2018 |doi=10.1038/d41586-018-07300-5 |url=https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-018-07300-5 |accessdate=16 January 2019 |language=EN}}</ref> A spokesman for Elsevier said \"If you think that information should be free of charge, go to Wikipedia\".<ref>{{cite news |title=11 EU-landen besluiten: vanaf 2020 moet alle wetenschappelijke literatuur gratis beschikbaar zijn |first=Maarten |last=Keulemans |url= https://www.volkskrant.nl/nieuws-achtergrond/11-eu-landen-besluiten-vanaf-2020-moet-alle-wetenschappelijke-literatuur-gratis-beschikbaar-zijn~be002c39/ |newspaper=De Volkskrant |date=4 September 2018 |accessdate=25 September 2018 |language=Dutch |quote=Als je vindt dat informatie gratis moet zijn: ga naar Wikipedia.}}</ref> In September 2018 [[UBS]] advised to sell Elsevier (RELX) stocks, noting that Plan S could affect 5-10% of scientific funding and may force Elsevier to reduce pricing.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Elder |first1=Bryce |title=Stocks to watch: SSE, BAT, Gal\u00e1pagos, RELX, Telef\u00f3nica, RBS |url=https://www.ft.com/content/2a2064e2-b669-11e8-bbc3-ccd7de085ffe |accessdate=14 October 2018 |work=[[Financial Times]] |date=12 September 2018 }}</ref>\n\n== Relationship with academic institutions ==\n\n=== Finland ===\nIn 2015 Finnish research organizations paid a total of 27 million euros in subscription fees. Over one third of the total costs went to Elsevier. The information was revealed after successful court appeal following a denied request on the subscription fees, due to confidentiality clauses in contracts with the publishers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ropengov.github.io/r/2016/06/10/FOI/|title=Scientific journal subscription costs in Finland 2010-2015: a preliminary analysis|website=rOpenGov|access-date=2017-10-15}}</ref> Establishing of this fact lead to creation of tiedonhinta.fi petition demanding more reasonable pricing and open access to content signed by more than 2800 members of the research community.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://tiedonhinta.fi/en/english/|title=Tiedonhinta.fi|website=tiedonhinta.fi|language=en-GB|access-date=2017-10-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171015203433/http://tiedonhinta.fi/en/english/|archive-date=15 October 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> While deals with other publishers have been made, this was not the case for Elsevier, leading to the nodealnoreview.org boycott of the publisher signed more than 600 times.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nodealnoreview.org/|title=No deal, no review \u2013 #nodealnoreview|website=Nodealnoreview.org|language=en-US|access-date=2017-10-15}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2018, it was confirmed that a deal had been reached between those concerned.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kansalliskirjasto.fi/en/news/finelib-and-elsevier-reach-agreement-for-subscription-access-and-open-access-publishing|title=FinELib and Elsevier Reach Agreement for Subscription Access and Open Access Publishing|last=Kukkonen|first=Suvi|date=2018-01-17|website=National Library|language=en|access-date=2018-01-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mostlyphysics.net/blog/2018/1/25/finland-takes-a-step-back-in-the-openness-of-academic-journal-pricing|title=Finland takes steps in the openness of academic journal pricing|author=Toma Susi|date=2018-01-25|newspaper=Mostly Physics|accessdate=2018-05-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite publication|author=Marie Farge|accessdate=2018-05-01|title=Transition vers l'Acc\u00e8s Libre: le pi\u00e8ge des accords globaux avec les \u00e9diteurs|url=https://blogs.mediapart.fr/edition/au-coeur-de-la-recherche/article/130418/transition-vers-l-acces-libre-le-piege-des-accords-globaux-avec-les-editeur|newspaper=Matematika|publisher=Club de Mediapart|language=fr}}</ref>\n\n=== France ===\nThe French [[Couperin (consortium)|Couperin consortium]] agreed in 2019 to a 4-year contract with Elsevier,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aefinfo.fr/assets/medias/documents/4/8/482545.pdf|title=Communiqu\u00e9 sur la n\u00e9gociation Elsevier|last=Consortium Couperin|date=2019-06-11}}</ref> despite criticism from the scientific community.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.lemonde.fr/sciences/article/2019/05/13/embrouilles-a-propos-de-l-acces-aux-revues-scientifiques_5461530_1650684.html|title=Embrouilles \u00e0 propos de l'acc\u00e8s aux revues scientifiques|date=2019-05-13|access-date=2019-08-26|language=fr}}</ref>\n\n===Germany===\nAlmost no academic institution in Germany is subscribed to Elsevier.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.projekt-deal.de/vertragskundigungen-elsevier-2018/|title=Vertragsk\u00fcndigungen Elsevier 2018|last=Haufe|first=Gottfried|date=20 November 2018|website=www.projekt-deal.de|access-date=6 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-019-00492-4|title=Thousands of scientists run up against Elsevier's paywall|last=Else|first=Holly|date=5 February 2019|journal=Nature|access-date=6 March 2019|doi=10.1038/d41586-019-00492-4}}</ref>\n\nGermany's DEAL project ([[Projekt DEAL]]) which includes over 60 major research institutions<!--consortium of state-funded universities and research organizations-->, has announced that all of its members are cancelling their contracts with Elsevier, effective 1 January 2017. The boycott is in response to Elsevier's refusal to adopt \"transparent business models\" to \"make publications more openly accessible\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Doctorow|first1=Cory|title=Germany-wide consortium of research libraries announce boycott of Elsevier journals over open access|url=https://boingboing.net/2016/12/15/germany-wide-consortium-of-res.html|publisher=Boing Boing|accessdate=27 December 2016|date=15 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=No full-text access to Elsevier journals to be expected from 1 January 2017 on|url=https://www.sub.uni-goettingen.de/en/news/details/voraussichtlich-keine-volltexte-von-zeitschriften-des-elsevier-verlags-ab-dem-112017/|publisher=G\u00f6ttingen State and University Library|accessdate=27 December 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161227132101/https://www.sub.uni-goettingen.de/en/news/details/voraussichtlich-keine-volltexte-von-zeitschriften-des-elsevier-verlags-ab-dem-112017/|archivedate=27 December 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=nature1/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lrk-bw.de/index.php/pressemitteilungen|title=Pressemitteilungen|website=Lrk-bw.de|language=de-de|access-date=2017-07-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.the-scientist.com/?articles.view/articleNo/49906/title/Major-German-Universities-Cancel-Elsevier-Contracts/|title=Major German Universities Cancel Elsevier Contracts|website=The Scientist|access-date=2017-07-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://www.sciencemag.org/news/2017/08/bold-open-access-push-germany-could-change-future-academic-publishing|title=A bold open-access push in Germany could change the future of academic publishing|date=2017-08-23|journal=Science|access-date=2017-08-24|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hrk.de/press/press-releases/press-release/meldung/researchers-resign-editorship-of-elsevier-journals-4237/|title=Researchers resign editorship of Elsevier journals|last=Conference|first=German Rectors'|access-date=2017-10-16|language=en}}</ref> Horst Hippler, spokesperson for the DEAL consortium states that \"taxpayers have a right to read what they are paying for\" and that \"publishers must understand that the route to open-access publishing at an affordable price is irreversible\".<ref name=nature1/> In July 2017, another 13 institutions announced that they would also be cancelling their subscriptions to Elsevier journals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.booksandpublishing.com.au/articles/2017/07/26/93682/german-universities-to-let-elsevier-contracts-lapse/|title=German universities to let Elsevier contracts lapse {{!}} Books+Publishing|website=Booksandpublishing.com.au|language=en-AU|access-date=2017-07-29}}</ref> In August 2017, at least 185 German institutions had cancelled their contracts with Elsevier.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.projekt-deal.de/vertragskundigungen-elsevier-2017/|title=Vertragsk\u00fcndigungen Elsevier 2017 \u2013 Projekt DEAL|website=Projekt-deal.de|language=en-US|access-date=2017-09-12}}</ref> In 2018, whilst negotiations were ongoing, around 200 German universities who cancelled their subscriptions to Elsevier journals were granted complimentary open access to them until this ended in July of the year.<ref name=\"matthews-2018\">{{cite news\n | last1 = Matthews | first1 = David\n | title = Elsevier maintains German access despite failure to strike deal\n | date = 4 January 2018\n | work = Times Higher Education (THE)\n | location = London, United Kingdom\n | issn = 0049-3929\n | url = https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/elsevier-maintains-german-access-despite-failure-strike-deal\n | access-date = 2018-01-05\n}}</ref><ref>[https://www.the-scientist.com/news-opinion/universities-in-germany-and-sweden-lose-access-to-elsevier-journals--64522 Universities in Germany and Sweden Lose Access to Elsevier Journals], DIANA KWON, The Scientist, July 19, 2018</ref><ref name=\"schiermeier-2018\">\n{{cite journal\n | last1 = Schiermeier | first1 = Quirin\n | title = Germany vs Elsevier: universities win temporary journal access after refusing to pay fees\n | date = 4 January 2018\n | journal = Nature News\n | volume =553\n | issue =7687\n | page =137\n | issn = 1476-4687\n | doi=10.1038/d41586-018-00093-7\n| pmid = 29323311\n | bibcode =2018Natur.553..137S\n | doi-access = free\n }}</ref>\n\nOn 19 December 2018 the [[Max Planck Society]] (MPS) announced that the existing subscription agreement with Elsevier would not be renewed after the expiration date of 31 December 2018. The Max Planck Society counts 14.000 scientists in 84 research institutes, publishing 12.000 articles each year.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mpdl.mpg.de/en/505|title=Max Planck Society discontinues agreement with Elsevier; stands firm with Projekt DEAL negotiations - MPDL}}</ref><ref name=\"mps20181219\">{{cite news |first1=Gary |last1=Price |url=https://www.infodocket.com/2018/12/19/max-planck-society-discontinues-agreement-with-elsevier-affirms-support-for-projekt-deal/ |title=Max Planck Society Discontinues Agreement with Elsevier. Affirms Support for Projekt Deal | work=infodocket.com Library Journal |date=19 December 2018 |accessdate=19 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Hungary===\nIn March 2018, the Hungarian ''Electronic Information Service National Programme'' entered negotiations on its 2019 Elsevier subscriptions, asking for a read-and-publish deal.<ref name=\"hungary_terminates\">{{cite web |first1= |title=Hungarian Consortium terminates negotiations with Elsevier |url=http://eisz.mtak.hu/index.php/en/283-hungarian-consortium-terminates-negotiations-with-elsevier.html |website=eisz.mtak.hu |accessdate=16 January 2019}}</ref> Negotiations were ended by the Hungarian consortium in December 2018, and the subscription was not renewed.<ref>{{cite news |last1=McKenzie |first1=Lindsay |title=Elsevier journal editors resign, start rival open-access journal |url=http://www.insidehighered.com/news/2019/01/14/elsevier-journal-editors-resign-start-rival-open-access-journal |accessdate=16 January 2019 |work=www.insidehighered.com |date=14 January 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Iran===\n\nIn 2013, Elsevier changed its policies in response to sanctions announced by the US [[Office of Foreign Assets Control]] that year. This included a request that all Elsevier journals avoid publishing papers by Iranian nationals which are employed by the Iranian government.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.issuesinmedicalethics.org/articles/scientific-sanctions-a-catastrophe-for-the-civilised-world/?galley=print|title=Scientific sanctions: A catastrophe for the civilized world|first=Behnam|last=Baghianimoghadam|publisher=Indian Journal of Medical Ethics|date=2014-02-09|accessdate=2018-12-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.farsnews.com/print.aspx?nn=13920814000991|title=Taylor & Francis group bans publication of articles by Iranian authors|publisher=Fars News|date=2013-11-05|accessdate=2018-12-25}}</ref> Elsevier executive Mark Seeley expressed regret on behalf of the company but did not announce an intention to challenge this interpretation of the law.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/trade-sanctions-against-iran-affect-publishers|first=Mark|last=Seeley|title=Trade sanctions against Iran affect publishers|publisher=Elsevier|date=2013-05-09|accessdate=2018-12-25}}</ref>\n\n=== Italy ===\n\nCRUI (association of Italian universities) sealed a 5-year-long deal for 2018\u20132022,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.crui.it/archivio-notizie/i-ricercatori-italiani-potranno-beneficiare-dell%E2%80%99accesso-continuo-al-database-sciencedirect-di-elsevie.html|title=I ricercatori italiani potranno beneficiare dell'accesso continuo al database ScienceDirect di Elsevier - CRUI - Conferenza dei Rettori delle Universit\u00e0 italiane}}</ref> despite protests from the scientific community, protests focused on aspects such as the lack of prevention of cost increases by means of the [[Double dipping (publishing)|double dipping]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.roars.it/online/svezia-italia-1-0-berlino-2018-italia-fanalino-di-coda-nellopen-science/|title=Svezia-Italia 1-0. Berlino 2018: Italia fanalino di coda nell'Open Science|date=2018-12-10|author=Paola Galimberti|newspaper=Roars: Returns on Academic Research}}</ref>\n\n===Netherlands===\nIn 2015 a consortium of all of Netherlands' 14 universities threatened to boycott Elsevier if it could not agree that articles by Dutch authors would be made open access and settled with the compromise of 30% of its Dutch papers becoming open access by 2018. Gerard Meijer, president of [[Radboud University]] in [[Nijmegen]] and lead negotiator on the Dutch side notes that \"it's not the 100% that I hoped for\".<ref name=nature1>{{cite journal|last1=Schiermeier|first1=Quirin|last2=Mega|first2=Emiliano Rodr\u00edguez|title=Scientists in Germany, Peru and Taiwan to lose access to Elsevier journals|journal=Nature|volume=541|issue=7635|pages=13|doi=10.1038/nature.2016.21223|pmid=28054621|bibcode=2017Natur.541...13S|year=2016|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Bohannon|first1=John|title=In unique deal, Elsevier agrees to make some papers by Dutch authors free|url=http://www.sciencemag.org/news/2015/12/unique-deal-elsevier-agrees-make-some-papers-dutch-authors-free|journal=Science|accessdate=27 December 2016|date=11 December 2015|doi=10.1126/science.aad7565|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Dutch Universities and Elsevier reach agreement in principle - Library UvA - University of Amsterdam|url=http://uba.uva.nl/en/news/news/content/2015/12/elsevier-deal.html|publisher=Universiteit van Amsterdam|accessdate=27 December 2016|date=12 October 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161227130822/http://uba.uva.nl/en/news/news/content/2015/12/elsevier-deal.html|archivedate=27 December 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/@SiccodeKnecht/how-elsevier-plans-to-sabotage-open-access-76fbd46593ae|title=How Elsevier plans to sabotage Open Access|date=2017-03-25|website=Medium|access-date=2017-03-26}}</ref>\n\n===Norway===\nIn March 2019, the Norwegian government on behalf of 44 institutions &mdash; universities, university colleges, research institutes and hospitals &mdash; decided to break negotiations on renewal of their subscription deal with Elsevier, because of disagreement regarding open access policy and Elsevier's unwillingness to reduce the cost of reading access.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.mynewsdesk.com/no/unit/pressreleases/norwegian-research-institutions-have-decided-not-to-renew-their-agreement-with-elsevier-2846284|title=Norwegian research institutions have decided not to renew their agreement with Elsevier|date=2019-03-12|website=UNIT|access-date=2019-03-12}}</ref>\n\n=== South Korea ===\nIn 2017, over 70 university libraries confirmed a \"contract boycott\" movement involving three publishers including Elsevier. As of January 2018, whilst negotiations remain underway, a decision will be made as to whether or not continue the participating libraries will continue the boycott.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.unn.net/news/articleView.html?idxno=183521|title=70\uc5ec\uac1c \ub300\ud559 \ub3c4\uc11c\uad00, \uc0c8\ud574 \uccab \ub0a0\ubd80\ud130 \uc77c\ubd80 \ub17c\ubb38 \ubabb \ubd10 - \ud55c\uad6d\ub300\ud559\uc2e0\ubb38|date=2017-12-29|access-date=2018-01-05|language=ko-KR}}</ref> It was subsequently confirmed that an agreement had been reached.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://www.sciencemag.org/news/2018/01/south-korean-universities-reach-agreement-elsevier-after-long-standoff|title=South Korean universities reach agreement with Elsevier after long standoff|date=2018-01-15|journal=Science|access-date=2018-01-16|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Sweden ===\nIn May 2018, the [[Bibsam Consortium]], which negotiates license agreements on behalf of all Swedish universities and research institutes, decided not to renew their contract with Elsevier,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/sweden-cancels-elsevier-contract-open-access-dispute-spreads|title=Sweden cancels Elsevier contract as open-access dispute spreads|date=16 May 2018|website=www.timeshighereducation.com}}</ref><ref name=sparc>{{citation |url=https://sparcopen.org/our-work/big-deal-cancellation-tracking/ |title=Big Deal Cancellation Tracking |work=Sparcopen.org |publisher=[[Scholarly Publishing and Academic Resources Coalition]] |location=US |accessdate= 30 June 2018 }}</ref> alleging that the publisher does not meet the demands of transition towards a more open access model, and referring to the rapidly increasing costs for publishing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kb.se/bibliotek/centrala-avtal/|title=Bibsamkonsortiet - Kungliga biblioteket|last=annwen|website=www.kb.se|language=SV|access-date=2018-05-31}}</ref> Swedish universities will still have access to articles published before 30 June 2018. Astrid S\u00f6derbergh Widding, Chairman of the Bibsam Consortium, said that \"the current system for scholarly communication must change and our only option is to cancel deals when they don't meet our demands for a sustainable transition to open access\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://openaccess.blogg.kb.se/2018/05/16/sweden-stands-up-for-open-access-cancels-agreement-with-elsevier/|title=Sweden stands up for open access \u2013 cancels agreement with Elsevier|date=2018-05-16|work=OpenAccess.se|access-date=2018-05-30|language=sv-SE}}</ref>\n\nSweden has a goal of open access by 2026.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://openaccess.blogg.kb.se/2018/05/16/sweden-stands-up-for-open-access-cancels-agreement-with-elsevier/|title=Sweden stands up for open access \u2013 cancels agreement with Elsevier|last=Wentzel|first=Annica|date=16 May 2018|website=openaccess.blogg.kb.se|access-date=6 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Taiwan===\nIn Taiwan more than 75% of universities, including the region's top 11 institutions, have joined a collective boycott against Elsevier. On 7 December 2016, the Taiwanese consortium, CONCERT, which represents more than 140 institutions, announced it would not renew its contract with Elsevier.<ref name=nature1/><ref>{{cite web|title=\u95dc\u65bcElsevier\u8cc7\u6599\u5eab\u5408\u7d04\u8ac7\u5224 CONCERT\u8072\u660e|url=https://concert.stpi.narl.org.tw/news/249|accessdate=27 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Taiwan Tech to Discontinue Subscription to Elsevier ScienceDirect Starting 2017 - NTUST Library|url=http://library.ntust.edu.tw/files/14-1025-58346,r1-1.php?Lang=en|accessdate=27 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/asia-advances-open-access-research_us_58dd0e6de4b0fa4c09598679|title=Asia Advances Open Access Research|last=Schmitt|first=Jason|date=2017-03-30|website=Huffington Post|language=en-US|access-date=2017-04-29}}</ref>\n\n===United States===\nIn March 2018, [[Florida State University]]'s faculty elected to cancel its $2 million subscription to a bundle of several journals. Starting in 2019 it will instead buy access to titles \u00e0 la carte.<ref name=sparc />\n\nIn February 2019, the [[University of California]] said it would terminate subscriptions \"in push for open access to publicly funded research.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.universityofcalifornia.edu/press-room/uc-terminates-subscriptions-worlds-largest-scientific-publisher-push-open-access-publicly|title=UC terminates subscriptions with world's largest scientific publisher in push for open access to publicly funded research|date=28 February 2019|website=www.universityofcalifornia.edu|access-date=6 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://phys.org/news/2019-03-university-california-terminates-subscriptions-elsevier.html|title=University of California terminates subscriptions to Elsevier|last=Yirka|first=Bob|date=4 March 2019|website=phys.org|access-date=6 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"AT 2019-03\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2019/03/uc-elsevier-publisher/583909/|title=The Real Cost of Knowledge|last=Zhang|first=Sarah|date=4 March 2019|work=[[The Atlantic]]|access-date=6 March 2019|language=en-US}}</ref> After months of negotiations over open access to research by UC researchers and prices for subscriptions to Elsevier journals, a press release by the UC Office of the President issued Thursday, 28 February 2019 stated \"Under Elsevier\u2019s proposed terms, the publisher would have charged UC authors large publishing fees on top of the university\u2019s multi-million dollar subscription, resulting in much greater cost to the university and much higher profits for Elsevier.\"<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.universityofcalifornia.edu/news/why-uc-split-publishing-giant-elsevier|title=Why UC split with publishing giant Elsevier|last=Kell|first=Gretchen|last2=Berkeley|first2=U. C.|date=2019-03-06|website=University of California|language=en|access-date=2019-06-12}}</ref> On July 10, 2019 Elsevier began restricting access to all new paywalled articles and approximately 5% of paywalled articles published before 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statnews.com/2019/07/10/university-of-california-loses-access-to-new-journal-articles-published-by-elsevier-after-research-access-fight|title=University of California loses access to new journal articles published by Elsevier after research access fight|website=statnews.com|language=en|access-date=2019-07-10|date=10 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2020, the [[University of North Carolina]] elected not to renew its bundled Elsevier package citing a failure \"to provide an affordable path\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Upcoming Elsevier Cancellations |url=https://library.unc.edu/2020/04/upcoming-elsevier-cancellations |publisher=University of North Carolina |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>. Rather than extend the license which was stated to cost $2.6 million annually, the university decided to continue subscribing to a smaller set of individual journals. The [[State University of New York]] Libraries Consortium also announced similar outcome,<ref>{{Cite news|publisher=Inside Highered|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/quicktakes/2020/04/13/suny-cancels-big-deal-elsevier|title=SUNY Cancels Big Deal With Elsevier|date=April 13, 2020|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|publisher=SUNY Libraries Consortium (SLC)|title=State University of New York Steps Away From the \u201cBig Deal\u201d with Elsevier|url=http://slcny.libguides.com/slc/elsevier2020update|date=April 7, 2020|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref> with the help of estimates from [[Unpaywall Journals]].<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2020-04-18|title=SUNY Negotiates New, Modified Agreement with Elsevier - Libraries News Center University at Buffalo Libraries|url=https://library.buffalo.edu/news/2020/04/07/suny-negotiates-new-modified-agreement-with-elsevier/|website=library.buffalo.edu}}</ref>\n\n== Dissemination of research ==\n\n=== Lobbying efforts against open access ===\nElsevier have been known to be involved in lobbying against [[open access]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.opensecrets.org/lobby/clientsum.php?id=D000067394&year=2017|title=Lobbying Spending Database - RELX Group, 2017|website=Opensecrets.org|language=en|access-date=2017-08-30}}</ref> These have included the likes of:\n* The [[Federal Research Public Access Act]] (FRPPA)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.taxpayeraccess.org/issues/frpaa/index.shtml|title=Federal Research Public Access Act (Alliance for Taxpayer Access)|website=Taxpayeraccess.org|language=en|access-date=2017-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.chronicle.com/article/Legislation-to-Bar/130949/|title=Legislation to Bar Public-Access Requirement on Federal Research Is Dead|date=2012-02-27|work=The Chronicle of Higher Education|access-date=2017-03-25}}</ref> \n* The [[Research Works Act]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thinkprogress.org/how-corporations-score-big-profits-by-limiting-access-to-publicly-funded-academic-research-fcee09671b22#.joxfvmi94|title=How Corporations Score Big Profits By Limiting Access To Publicly Funded Academic Research|date=2013-03-03|work=ThinkProgress|access-date=2017-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2012/02/15/the-dangerous-research-works-act/|title=The Dangerous \"Research Works Act\"|last=Contributor|website=TechCrunch|access-date=2017-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2016/01/elsevier-academic-publishing-petition/427059/|title=Academics Want You to Read Their Work for Free|last=Hu|first=Jane C.|work=The Atlantic|access-date=2017-03-25|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elsevier.com/about/company-information/policies/message-on-the-research-works-act|title=Message on the Research Works Act|last=Elsevier|website=Elsevier.com|language=en|access-date=2017-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/future_tense/2012/02/28/research_works_act_elsevier_and_politicians_back_down_from_open_access_threat_.html|title=Scientists' Victory Over the Research Works Act Is Like the SOPA Defeat|last=Kakaes|first=Konstantin|date=2012-02-28|work=Slate|access-date=2017-03-25|language=en-US|issn=1091-2339}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://boingboing.net/2012/02/28/elsevier-withdraws-support-fro.html|title=Elsevier withdraws support from Research Works Act, bill collapses|date=2012-02-28|website=Boing Boing|access-date=2017-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2012/jan/16/academic-publishers-enemies-science|title=Academic publishers have become the enemies of science|date=2012-01-16|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-03-26|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> \n* PRISM.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://scienceblogs.com/transcript/2007/01/27/elsevier-wiley-are-getting-pr/|title=Elsevier, Wiley are getting PR advice from Eric Dezenhall|work=Transcription and Translation|access-date=2017-03-25|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dyer|first=Owen|date=2007-02-03|title=Publishers hire PR heavyweight to defend themselves against open access|journal=BMJ: British Medical Journal|volume=334|issue=7587|pages=227|doi=10.1136/bmj.39112.439051.DB|issn=0959-8138|pmc=1790741|pmid=17272546}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://www.sciencemag.org/news/2013/06/scientific-publishers-offer-solution-white-houses-public-access-mandate|title=Scientific Publishers Offer Solution to White House's Public Access Mandate|date=2013-06-04|journal=Science|access-date=2017-03-25|language=en}}</ref> In the case of PRISM, the [[Association of American Publishers]] hired [[Eric Dezenhall]], the so-called \"Pit Bull Of Public Relations\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2006-04-16/the-pit-bull-of-public-relations|title=\"The Pit Bull Of Public Relations\" - Bloomberg|date=2006-04-17|work=Bloomberg.com|access-date=2017-03-25}}</ref>\n* [[Horizon 2020]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/muscle-from-brussels-as-open-access-gets-an-80bn-boost/419949.article|title=Muscle from Brussels as open access gets an \u20ac80bn boost|date=2012-05-17|work=Times Higher Education (THE)|access-date=2017-03-26|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gowers.wordpress.com/2012/05/17/horizon-2020-to-promote-open-access/|title=Horizon 2020 to promote open access|date=2012-05-17|website=Gowers's Weblog|access-date=2017-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://www.sciencemag.org/news/2012/05/horizon-2020-80-billion-battlefield-open-access|title=Horizon 2020: A \u20ac80 Billion Battlefield for Open Access|date=2012-05-24|journal=Science|access-date=2017-03-26|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2012/05/17/european-union-links-research-grants-open-access|title=European Union links research grants to open access|access-date=2017-03-26}}</ref>\n* [[Office of Science and Technology Policy]] (OSTP)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/inside-higher-ed-big-push-for-open-access/2002057.article|title=Inside Higher Ed: Big push for open access|date=2013-02-26|work=Times Higher Education (THE)|access-date=2017-03-26|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/elsevier-distances-itself-from-open-access-article/2004055.article|title=Elsevier distances itself from open-access article|date=2013-05-22|work=Times Higher Education (THE)|access-date=2017-03-26|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thinkprogress.org/how-corporations-score-big-profits-by-limiting-access-to-publicly-funded-academic-research-fcee09671b22#.u06x7x9zu|title=How Corporations Score Big Profits By Limiting Access To Publicly Funded Academic Research|date=2013-03-03|work=ThinkProgress|access-date=2017-03-26}}</ref>\n* The [[European Union]]'s [[Open science|Open Science]] Monitor was criticised after Elsevier were confirmed as a subcontractor.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.techdirt.com/articles/20180402/09131239544/hated-science-publisher-elsevier-to-help-eu-monitor-open-science-including-open-access.shtml|title=Hated Science Publisher Elsevier To Help EU Monitor Open Science - Including Open Access|work=Techdirt.|access-date=2018-04-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Lykkja|first1=P\u00e5l Magnus|last2=Myklebust|first2=Jan Petter|title=Open science in the EU \u2013 Will the astroturfers take over?|url=http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=20180317044918836|website=University World News|accessdate=2018-04-13|date=17 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Selling open access articles ===\nIn 2014, 2015, 2016 and 2017,<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=2018-04-30|title=Hybrid open access is unreliable|url=http://rossmounce.co.uk/2017/02/20/hybrid-open-access-is-unreliable/|author=Ross Mounce|date=2017-02-20}}</ref> Elsevier was found to be selling some articles which should have been open access, but had been put behind a paywall.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/news/elsevier-bumps-on-road-to-open-access/2012238.article |title=Elsevier: bumps on road to open access |work=[[Times Higher Education]] |date=27 March 2014 |accessdate=9 March 2015 |last1=Jump |first1=Paul}}</ref> A related case occurred in 2015, when Elsevier charged for downloading an open access article from a journal published by [[John Wiley & Sons]]. However, it was not clear whether Elsevier was in violation of the license under which the article was made available on their website.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://creativecommons.org/weblog/entry/45175 |title=Are commercial publishers wrongly selling access to openly licensed scholarly articles? |work=Creative Commons News|date=13 March 2015 |accessdate=14 March 2015 |last1=Vollmer |first1=Timothy}}</ref>\n\n===Action against academics posting their own articles online===\n\nIn 2013, [[Digimarc]], a company representing Elsevier, told the [[University of Calgary]] to remove articles published by faculty authors on university web pages; although such [[self-archiving]] of academic articles may be legal under the [[fair dealing]] provisions in Canadian [[copyright law]],<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=2018-05-01|title=Elsevier Ramps Up Its War On Access To Knowledge|url=https://www.techdirt.com/articles/20131218/00393725601/elsevier-ramps-up-its-war-access-to-knowledge.shtml|newspaper=[[Techdirt]]|author= Mike Masnick}}</ref> the university complied. [[Harvard University]] and the [[University of California, Irvine]] also received [[Notice and take down|takedown notices]] for self-archived academic articles, a first for Harvard, according to [[Peter Suber]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Peterson|first1=Andrea|title=How one publisher is stopping academics from sharing their research|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/the-switch/wp/2013/12/19/how-one-publisher-is-stopping-academics-from-sharing-their-research/|accessdate=6 January 2015|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=19 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Masnick|first1=Mike|title=Elsevier Ramps Up Its War On Access To Knowledge|url=https://www.techdirt.com/articles/20131218/00393725601/elsevier-ramps-up-its-war-access-to-knowledge.shtml|accessdate=6 January 2015|work=[[Techdirt]]|date=20 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-switch/wp/2013/12/19/how-one-publisher-is-stopping-academics-from-sharing-their-research/|title=How one publisher is stopping academics from sharing their research|website=Washington Post|access-date=2017-03-26}}</ref>\n\nMonths after its acquisition of [[Academia.edu]] rival [[Mendeley]], Elsevier sent thousands of [[takedown notice]]s to Academia.edu, a practice that has since ceased following widespread complaint by academics, according to Academia.edu founder and chief executive Richard Price.<ref name=\"Parr2014\">{{cite journal|last1=Parr|first1=Chris|title=Sharing is a way of life for millions on Academia.edu|journal=Times Higher Education|date=12 June 2014|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/news/sharing-is-a-way-of-life-for-millions-on-academiaedu/2013839.article?nopaging=1 |accessdate=14 September 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Howard2013\">{{cite journal|last1=Howard|first1=Jennifer|title=Posting Your Latest Article? You Might Have to Take It Down|journal=The Chronicle of Higher Education|date=6 December 2013|url=http://chronicle.com/blogs/wiredcampus/posting-your-latest-article-you-might-have-to-take-it-down/48865|accessdate=14 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter Elsevier acquired the repository [[SSRN]] in May 2016 academics started complaining that some of their work has been removed without notice. The action was explained as a technical error.<ref>Mike Masnick [https://www.techdirt.com/articles/20160718/02211935003/just-as-open-competitor-to-elseviers-ssrn-launches-ssrn-accused-copyright-crackdown.shtml ''SSRN accused of copyright crackdown''], Techdirt.</ref>\n\n===Sci-Hub and LibGen lawsuit===\n\nIn 2015 Elsevier filed a lawsuit against the sites [[Sci-Hub]] and [[Library Genesis|LibGen]], which make copyright protected articles available for free. Elsevier also claimed illegal access to institutional accounts.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.stephenmclaughlin.net/2016/03/18/elsevier-v-sci-hub-on-the-docket/ |title=Elsevier v. Sci-Hub on the docket |first=Stephen Reid |last=McLaughlin |date=18 March 2016 |access-date=2016-06-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/simba-information-five-professional-publishing-news-events-of-2015-signal-times-are-a-changin-300194611.html|title = Simba Information: Five Professional Publishing News Events of 2015 Signal Times Are A-Changin'|date =17 December 2015 |accessdate = 28 June 2016 |website = PR Newswire }}</ref>\n\n===Rejection of the Initiative for Open Citations===\nAmong the major academic publishers, Elsevier alone declined to join the [[Initiative for Open Citations]]. In the context of the resignation of the ''[[Journal of Informetrics]]''' editorial board, Elsevier stated:<ref name=\"Elsevier\">{{cite web|url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/about-the-resignation-of-the-journal-of-informetrics-editorial-board|title=About the resignation of the Journal of Informetrics Editorial Board|date=15 January 2019|last = Reller|first = Tom|work=Elsevier Connect|accessdate=15 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote|Elsevier invests significantly in citation extraction technology. While these are made available to those who wish to license this data, Elsevier cannot make such a large corpus of data, to which it has added significant value, available for free.}}\n\n==Imprints==\n\nElsevier uses its [[Imprint (trade name)|imprint]]s (that is, [[Brand|brand names]] used in publishing) to market to different consumer segments. Many of the imprints have previously been the names of publishing companies that were purchased by Reed Elsevier.\n\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* [[Academic Press]]\n* Bailli\u00e8re Tindall\n* BC Decker\n* [[Butterworth\u2013Heinemann]]\n* CMP\n* [[Cell Press]]\n* [[Churchill Livingstone]]\n* Digital Press\n* Elsevier\n* [[Gulf Professional Publishing]]\n* GW Medical Publishing\n* Hanley & Belfus\n* [[Masson (publisher)|Masson]]\n* [[Medicine Publishing]]\n* [[Morgan Kaufmann Publishers]]\n* [[Mosby (publisher)|Mosby]]\n* Newnes\n* North-Holland Publishing Company\n* [[Pergamon Press]]\n* Pergamon Flexible Learning\n* [[Saunders (publisher)|Saunders]]\n* Syngress\n* Urban & Fischer\n* [[William Andrew (publisher)|William Andrew]]\n* [[Woodhead Publishing]] (including Chandos and Horwood)\n}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Netherlands|Companies|Books}}\n* [[List of Elsevier periodicals]]\n* [[2collab]], a free researcher collaboration tool launched by Elsevier in 2007 and discontinued in 2011\n* [[Sci-Hub]], a website providing free access to otherwise paywalled academic papers on a massive scale that is involved in a legal case with Elsevier\n{{clear}}\n\n== References ==\n=== Citations ===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n=== Sources ===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |ref = harv |last = Groen |first = Frances K. |title = Access to medical knowledge : libraries, digitization, and the public good |year = 2007 |publisher = Scarecrow Press |location = Lanham, Mar. |isbn = 978-0-8108-52723 |page = 217 }}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Elsevier}}\n*{{Official website}}\n*[http://www.caat.org.uk/issues/arms-fairs/reed-elsevier/ Campaign success: Reed Elsevier 